<SLUG> BC-WHOA-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHOA-JACK!': COHEN UPDATES BUCHNER'S `WOYZECK'  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(rk) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was inevitable that one day Jeff Cohen would come
to Georg Buchner. In the last couple of years Cohen has updated two
Chekhov plays and a Greek tragedy to punch holes in the
self-satisfaction of the '90s. Buchner's ``Woyzeck,'' a play about
a soldier driven by personal abuse and social corruption to kill
his mistress, which Buchner wrote as a protest against injustice,
must have been irresistible to Cohen _ even more so, perhaps,
because it is so fragmentary that Buchner's friends assumed it was
unfinished when he died in 1837. It waited 76 years to find its
first producer.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Whoa-Jack!'' Cohen turns it into a drama about a black
American soldier at an Army base in Alabama in 1960 who is slightly
unhinged by the Ku Klux Klan mentality of the era and is pushed
over the edge by a white major who has an affair with the soldier's
girlfriend, the mother of his infant son. The racial themes fit
Buchner's plot naturally. That the German playwright was also a
brilliant anatomist who put some medical experimentation into his
play lets Cohen conjure up the infamous Tuskegee syphilis
experiments on unsuspecting black men.
</P>
<P>
   For the Worth Street Theater company's production, Cohen, who
directs, has assembled a good cast, with strong performances from
actors in the four key roles: Michael D. Brown as the soldier,
Private Jackson; Genie Sloan as his lover, Mary; Phyllis Johnson as
Mary's friend, the only person in the play who can foresee the
tragedy unfolding; and Roy Barnitt as the camp commandant, who
represents weakness and bigotry among whites but who really
believes, as he says, thatrucial final minutes not even Bargonetti's
incomparable guitar and Esther's magnificent rendition of ``Strange
Fruit' can lift one from the feeling of letdown, although his
strings and her voice are surely the best memories one takes aay
from this performance. ``Whoa-Jack!'' has been extended through
Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHOA-JACK!'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Jeff Cohen; adapted from Georg Buchner's
``Woyzeck''; sets by Patrice Andrew Davidson; assistant set
designer, Tavon Felix; lighting by Genny Wynn; costumes by Susan L.
Soetaert; music by Steve Bargonetti and Diane Gioia; associate
producers, Dan Dzindzihashvili and Sarah Yorra; production stage
manager, Stacy Waring. Presented by the Worth Street Theater
Company, Carol R. Fineman, producer. At the TriBeCa Playhouse, 111
Reade Street.
</P>
<P>
   With: Queen Esther (jazz singer), Michael D. Brown (Private
Jackson), Marcuis W. Harris (Andy), Genie Sloan (Mary), Phyllis
Johnson (Margaret), Peter Shaw (Major), Matthew Gorrek (Sergeant)
and Roy Barnitt (Colonel).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
