<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     01-30 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ Lawrence Taylor did it his way, for which he offers not a
whiff of an apology.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's way produced a rap sheet full of bad things. Lots of
them, including failure to pay child support. Even now, he has drug
charges hanging over his head, yet he refuses to hang his head in
shame.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a man you want in your Pro Football Hall of Fame? Do you
want to take your kid to the shrine in Canton, Ohio, and show him
Lawrence Taylor's bronze bust? Should L.T., a bust of a human
being, be officially certified as an immortal?
</P>
<P>
   No two ways about it, he is a lousy role model.
</P>
<P>
   But he was an amazingly gifted football player.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hall of Fame, invented to honor the latter, already
includes plenty of the former.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally accepted, albeit not altogether accurately, that
Taylor reinvented his position, that of outside linebacker.
Actually, the Oilers' Robert Brazile, who started a string of Pro
Bowl seasons as a rookie in 1975, was L.T. before L.T. became L.T.
But Dr. Doom lost his hard edge prematurely, and Taylor, performing
at a remarkable level in the New York media spotlight, eclipsed
Brazile completely.
</P>
<P>
   His ``A'' game lasted more than a decade, and he contributed
significantly to two world-championship Giants teams. For those who
hadn't paid Brazile much mind, Taylor was an entirely new breed of
cat, too quick and agile to be as big as he was. Were it not for
his considerable non-football liabilities, his assets would
guarantee him election to the Hall in this, his first year of
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, however, there will be much acrimonious debate _
possibly an unprecedented level _ when the selection committee
convenes today to decide whether to Cantonize L.T. If the full
complement of 36 is present, it will take eight ``no'' votes to
block his entry, and recent polls suggest a sufficient number of
thumbs-down may be lurking.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Hall's bylaws contain nothing in the way of
a ``morals'' clause. By all accounts, Taylor is supposed to be
judged solely on the basis of what he contributed to football, not
on how many times he has stumbled elsewhere. Even the commish, Paul
Tagliabue, won't dispute that point.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Blood McNally was a member of Canton's original class of
inductees despite his well-documented legacy as an unrepentant
hell-raiser. Paul Hornung made it, too, and he was banished for a
season for wagering on games.
</P>
<P>
   And O.J. Simpson is permanently ensconced as well, although
obviously he was elected long before he came to be seen by many
Americans as a heinous double murderer who stiff-armed the system.
</P>
<P>
   OK, there is one conspicuous _ although clearly not correct _
precedent for Taylor's exclusion. Bob Hayes, once the world's
fastest human, averaged 20 yards per catch as a Dallas Cowboy and
was basically responsible for the invention of the zone defense.
Yet because he did time in the pen at Huntsville for a drug
conviction, you won't find Bullet Bob's likeness anywhere near
Canton.
</P>
<P>
   Older sportswriters who own a vote seem unanimously inclined to
veto Taylor's bid, at least this year. Those who heard him speak on
his own behalf during an occasionally testy conference call Monday
were further put off by his stubborn unwillingness to show the
least bit of remorse for the stupid choices he has made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't apologize for anything,'' L.T. said. ``I live my life
like I live my life. All of us have things we'd like to change.
Unfortunately, we can't do that. I try to do the best I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get in (the Hall), I don't get in. That's a part of
life. I'll leave my fate up to the voters. That's for you guys to
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   And it should be a simple decision. L.T. was the best of the
best, and he stayed on top for a long time despite a
self-destructive bent that could have short-circuited his career on
numerous occasions. Given the criteria as presently spelled out, he
has to be a first-ballot Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the argument is wrongly centered. Perhaps the Hall
should re-examine its framework for membership. Should public
deportment be a factor? Need only model citizens apply? It's a
defendable position, considering how impressionable our kids can
be.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, we ask football players to behave in an antisocial
fashion. Almost everything that happens on the field would be at
least a misdemeanor if committed on the street. This is not a sport
that fosters ``good'' behavior. It demands anything but civility.
</P>
<P>
   L.T. played this violent, dangerous, reckless game as violently,
dangerously and recklessly as anyone ever has. That he has opted to
live his life similarly shouldn't be all that surprising or,
frankly, repellent. To expect complete conformity and normalcy
outside the white lines is a tad unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Hypocritical, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
