<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GEEGERVIN-HNS &LR;      01-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GEEGERVIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Make no mistake about it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I am the Iceman _ Ice,'' Basketball Hall of Famer George
Gervin Sr. declared. ``Gee is the Ice Cube.''
</P>
<P>
   George Gervin Jr., or Gee as he prefers to be called, is trying
to make his own name as the Houston Cougars continue their arduous
journey with first-year coach Clyde Drexler tonight when they meet
South Florida at Hofheinz Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, the Conference USA scoring leader at 21.5 points per game,
is growing along with the Cougars. He carries a heavy burden for
his team on his skinny 6-2, 175-pound frame, averaging 33 minutes
per game and taking on most of the playmaking role and much of the
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strain,'' Gervin said, ``but I'm trying to use it to my
advantage, learning what to do against these funky defenses some
teams are using, standing up to the physical demands, doing
whatever I can to help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   C-USA wins have been scarce for the Cougars (7-11, 2-6 in
conference). The Bulls, gifted with some of the best young players
in Division I, also are 2-6 (9-8 for the year) after their sixth
straight loss, 65-58 to DePaul on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gervins Sr. and Jr. take issue with those who want to compare
them. George, voted one of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players, scored
20,708 points in his 10 NBA seasons with the San Antonio Spurs
(1977-86), led the league in scoring four times with his assortment
of finger rolls and acrobatic shots and four times was selected to
the All-NBA first team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 6-8, and he's 6-2,'' Gervin said of Gee. ``The only
comparison is, he's my son. He can't do some of the things I was
able to do, and I can't do some of the things he can do. He and I
understand people will say that (making the comparison). I told
him, `I'm the Iceman; you're the Ice Cube.' I know he can be as
good as he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin is 17th nationally in scoring, and he is second in C-USA
in 3-point accuracy (44.7 percent), first in 3-pointers per game
(2.56), sixth in free-throw accuracy (81.9 percent), 10th in
assists (3.33 per game) and 12th in steals (1.7). The figures that
disturb him: 43.3-percent shooting overall and a 68-to-60
turnover/assist ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to learn to make better decisions with the ball and not
try to force things that aren't there,'' he said. ``I'm hard on
myself. I want to win so bad, sometimes I try to take it on my own
hands. It's not that I'm being selfish; it's about trying to help
my team win. I can't think of myself as a great player until I win
some games.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-year junior, Gervin played last season for San Jacinto
College, following just after Omar Sneed and Steve Francis, who are
starring this season at Memphis and Maryland, respectively. Until
his last game for San Jac, a loss to Tyler in the state
junior-college tournament in Waco last year, Gervin thought he
would play for South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   George Gervin met South Florida head coach Seth Greenberg on a
plane trip and mentioned that Gee might be a prospect for him.
Assistant David Zimroth watched Gee with San Jacinto several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking it might be a good place for me,'' Gee said.
``I guess coach Greenberg wasn't quite pleased with that last game,
and I never heard from them again. I've been waiting for this game
since last summer.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when Gervin and his friends from San Jac would come to
Hofheinz Pavilion to play pickup games against several of his
current UH teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We smacked those guys,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   His San Jac buddies included Calvin Bowman, now at West
Virginia, Alex Scales (Oregon) and Roy de la Cruz (redshirting at
TCU). Drexler had been hired recently as Cougars coach. Gervin, who
wasn't being heavily recruited at that time, talked to Drexler and
assistant Reid Gettys to set up an official visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was thrilled when Clyde got the job, but he left it up
to me,'' Gee said. ``He trusted me to make the right decision. I
felt it was an honor to play for Clyde Drexler. I ate that up.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gee was growing up, tennis was his favorite game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get him off the court,'' his dad said.
</P>
<P>
   During his freshman year at San Antonio's John Marshall High
School, he tried out for basketball but was left on the junior
varsity because he was so small. Gee and his father began their
regimen of working on his game together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven hundred, 800 shots a day from all around the court,''
George Gervin said. ``You can do it in an hour and a half, two
hours, with somebody chasing the ball for you. I drilled him in the
summers. I told him to discipline himself, develop a passion for
practice and take it to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stressed getting to every class on time, getting to every
practice on time, and get your education. Without an education, no
matter how talented you are, you can't be a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for Clyde (a former NBA opponent). He has
a good sense for life and this game. These boys don't know how
lucky they are. These guys should bust their tails off to play and
learn from him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
