A5013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREGARDIEN-MUSIC-REVI     01-30 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGARDIEN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPH PREGARDIEN: A LIEDER SINGER WHO MATTERS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Germany )   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &UR;  &LR; _ The German tenor Christoph Pregardien, who has
become one of the most essential of today's Lieder singers, was not
in his best voice for his recital on Sunday at Alice Tully Hall.
There was a little constriction in his mid-to-upper range, which
resulted in some overly forceful singing.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a testimony to Pregardien's artistry that his
less-than-top-notch vocal condition hardly mattered. The essential
sound of his voice is beguiling: a plaintive, flexible lyric tenor
with choirboy-clear high notes and surprisingly robust chest tones.
This is communicative, literate and affecting singing.
</P>
<P>
   His accompanist was his countryman Michael Gees, a remarkable
pianist, who was Pregardien's partner on his Lincoln Center recital
last season. Clearly, these two sympathetic artists bring out the
best in each other. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pregardien's program was typically intelligent. The first half
offered songs by Schumann, Beethoven, Schubert, Wolf, and the
under-appreciated 19th-century Viennese composer Karl Loewe _ all
settings of poems by Goethe. The second half was devoted to
Schumann's seldom-heard songs to texts by the medical doctor and
poet Justinus Kerner, impassioned Romantic meditations on loss and
unrequited love.
</P>
<P>
   The Loewe songs were particularly special. The composer's
version of Goethe's ``Erlkoenig'' is, in its way, as ingenious as
Schubert's famous setting of the same text. Instead of the
insistently repeated octaves in Schubert's piano part, which evoke
the galloping horse, carrying the reassuring father and his young
son, terrified by the voice of the Erl-king, through the dark,
stormy forest, Loewe conveys the scene with trembling chords and
ominous low trills in the piano, and vocal lines of haunting power
and narrative vividness. Pregardien framed this song with
``Wanderers Nachtlied I and II,'' music of meditative beauty and
ineffable sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the recital, Gees' playing technically was
accomplished and musically exquisite. He is quite a presence at the
keyboard. Though 45, the trim pianist with his boyish face and long
curly hair looks no more than 25. His playing is reflective of his
appearance, combining youthful exuberance and mature insight. He
should come back to New York to give a recital some time. Surely,
he would do an elegant performance of a Schubert sonata.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three of Schumann's Kerner songs, music of
meditative stillness, the performers had the audience transfixed.
Naturally, encores followed, including, to put Loewe's
``Erlkoenig'' in context, a demonic performance of Schubert's
version. These satisfying musicians wanted to send you home with
something to think about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
