<HEADER>
A5017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLES-NYT &LR;      01-30 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(rk) 
 By   TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y._ Bill Stewart has been successful everywhere he
has coached because of one constant: defense.
</P>
<P>
   For teams with limited talent, the trap is not only the best
strategy, it is the only strategy. It works for the Ottawa
Senators, and now it's working for the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since taking over behind the Islanders'
bench, Stewart's system was apparent Friday night against the
Phoenix Coyotes as the Islanders twice rallied from two-goal
deficits to earn a hard-fought 4-4 tie at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' aggressive forechecking, which created turnovers
in every zone, helped them to overcome a 4-2 deficit late in the
third period on goals by Zdeno Chara and Robert Reichel, who scored
with 1:52 left to send the game to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who are 2-0-1 under Stewart, outshot the Coyotes
3-0 in overtime and nearly came away with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   They turned up the pressure in the third period, first slicing
the Coyotes' lead to 3-2 on a goal by Trevor Linden at 5:56 and
later to 4-3 on Chara's first NHL goal.
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers, forced by the Islanders' smothering forechecking,
were key , providing several prime opportunities to tie the score
against Coyotes' goalie Jim Waite.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Adams scored the Coyotes' fourth goal on a soft wrist shot
from the middle of the right circle to give the Coyotes 4-2 lead.
It was the second straight questionable goal allowed by Tommy Salo,
who started in the Islander goal again , ahead of Felix Potvin.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Corkum's second goal of the game gave the Coyotes a 3-1 lead
at 14:00 of the third period. On a 2-on-1 rush, Corkum beat Salo
through the pads from the top of the right circle.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Islanders' goalie controversy settled, at least for
now. Salo has started three straight games and is expected to stay
in that role. But because Stewart has refused to commit on a No. 1,
that could change. Potvin has not played since Stewart replaced
Mike Milbury as coach eight days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Salo was excellent despite allowing a couple of
first period goals. Both were scored off rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Briere notched the game's first goal at 9:49. He was
standing at the right post when the puck squirted off Salo's stick
and onto his.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum put Phoenix ahead 2-0 at 12:41, whipping a wrist shot
past Salo, who was sprawled on the ice after stopping Juha Ylonen's
shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' hard work finally paid off in the second period
when Barry Richter finished off a 4-on-2 rush with a goal, cutting
the Phoenix lead to 2-1. Sergei Nemchinov led the Islanders' attack
down ice, dishing the puck to Richter in the slot. Richter, a
defenseman, banked the shot off the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The Nemchinov-Claude Lapointe-Mark Lawrence line was the
Islanders' most productive of the night.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   MARIUSZ CZERKAWSKI &UR;  &LR; was benched for Tuesday's game against the
Boston Bruins because he arrived two minutes late for a 9:45
meeting, which violated one of Bill Stewart's rules of conduct:
don't be late. Czerkawski arrived at 9:20 this morning... . While
FELIX POTVIN, the goalie who has struggled since arriving from the
Toronto Maple Leafs in the Bryan Berard deal, sat on the Islanders'
bench for the third straight game, fans chanted, ``Heave-ho, Felix
must go!'' ... . ZDENO CHARA, the Islanders' defenseman who nearly
lost an eye last Tuesday when his face was cut by the skate blade
of an opposing player, played with a visor on his helmet... .
DALLAS DRAKE of the Coyotes left midway through the first period
with what appeared to be a shoulder injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
