<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COP-CAMERAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD'S PATROL-CAR CAMERA PROGRAM LOSING FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Touted as a deterrent to police brutality after
the videotaped beating of Rodney King, the police Department's
program to install its own video cameras in every police car began
with great promise but now lies in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, only 25 to 30 cameras of the 36 installed in
1993 are even working. And most beat officers don't know how to use
them because there are so few, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There's still no official policy on use and storage. The program
also has a long history of being ignored, critics assert.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, patrol officers like John Smith feel the
frustration, as on one recent afternoon as he struggled to get his
camera to work in suburban North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   He played with the lens, fiddled with wires, tried to adjust the
camera's mount and tapped on a small video monitor. Still, it
wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are all falling apart, and the program has been
tied up in red tape for years,'' said Smith, who was instrumental
in getting the pilot program started. ``I hope the department does
something about this soon. We're losing out on a great way to
protect officers and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Recommended by the Christopher Commission after the March 1991
beating of King -- captured on videotape by a bystander -- the
cameras were touted as a cure-all for police misconduct because
they could help collect evidence, keep officers honest and resolve
conflicts between officers and residents. They also would save
millions of dollars in court costs, litigation and officer
misconduct claims, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the surviving cameras from the pilot program have proved
their value, recording incriminating comments from suspects inside
police cars and sending people to jail who made false accusations
of police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   But as far back as 1996, Los Angeles Police Department officials
reported to the Police Commission that the program was not meeting
its goals. Many cameras were broken and weren't being used
effectively, according to the report filed that year.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the manufacturer went out of business, so
replacement parts were difficult to find.
</P>
<P>
   The commission at that time ordered LAPD brass to take immediate
steps to get the program back on track. Nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our take is that the administration has instituted all of the
negative Christopher Commission recommendations against officers
and none of the positive stuff that would help them,'' said
Detective Gary Fullerton, a director of the Los Angeles Police
Protective League.
</P>
<P>
   Top police administrators concede the cameras have not been a
priority, but they say the push has been renewed under Police Chief
Bernard C. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program should have been pursued much more aggressively
in the past,'' said LAPD Capt. Dan Koenig. ``Our responsibility now
is to do this and ensure that tax dollars are used wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chief Parks has made the program a high priority, and he wants
them to be installed in units as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a new $7 million plan, the entire 1,170-car fleet will be
equipped by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD officials say cameras will be standard equipment in all new
police cars, and they could employ compact-disc technology instead
of videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go quickly, we're looking at a June rollout date,''
Koenig said. ``If we decide to go with CD technology, it could take
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say they aren't optimistic, especially if the
department's 1993 pilot program is any indication of what's to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration didn't make this a priority in the past,
and it should have been done a long time ago,'' Fullerton said.
`I'm very disappointed the department didn't go forward with this
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent high-profile case, the cameras helped convict
a North Hollywood apartment manager of manslaughter in 1997 after
he shot and killed a fleeing burglary suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The camera didn't record the shooting, but when Smith arrived in
his video-equipped patrol car he recorded the gunman, showing him
``visibly excited and highly agitated,'' a judge said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem for any police agency is getting at the
truth. If there's a dozen people at a scene, everyone has a
different story about what happened,'' Koenig said. ``It could be
differences in perception or their stories could be self-serving.
But the tape doesn't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The cameras also have captured officers' inappropriate behavior.
In 1994, Smith used his patrol car to nudge the bicycle of a drug
dealer who was refusing to stop.
</P>
<P>
   He thought the tactic was reasonable, but a supervisor saw the
tape and gave him a verbal reprimand. Smith accepted his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened, and I accepted the reprimand,'' he said. ``The
point is that if an officer -- and there are some bad ones out
there -- is being taped, he'll probably think twice before doing
something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's supervisor, Capt. Richard Wahler, said there has been a
misconception in the past that officers are concerned the cameras
will catch them in misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is the officers would love this technology,'' Wahler
said. ``They'll welcome any new technology that will help protect
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Police union leaders insist the lack of video cameras and
failure of the program is by design. It took no time for the LAPD
to create a system to track officer discipline history, Fullerton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the Christopher Commission's 120 recommendations
that would benefit officers, like periodic psychological
evaluations and the video cameras, have yet to see the light of
day.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig said the LAPD is now closer to action than it has ever
been. But there's still a catch.
</P>
<P>
   If the city decides to stick with video, it will send out bids
and start installing cameras in new squad cars by June, Koenig
said. At that rate, the entire fleet will have them by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But if the city decides to explore compact-disc technology, it
will have to ask companies to send proposals for different system
configurations -- taking the red tape back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to weigh the wait vs. the benefit,'' Koenig said.
``But if CD technology would be far greater than video, it might be
worth the wait.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
