<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T TELL THE NETS THIS ONE DIDN'T COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It will not count in the standings, and
in a few days no one will remember that it happened. But the Nets
will not belittle their 92-90 exhibition victory Friday night over
the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   While they were not celebrating festively after the game, the
Nets were smiling and feeling good about themselves. To them, it
meant something. Not bragging rights until they meet for real, but
something.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Gill, who scored 14 points and sank a huge 3-pointer
from 25 feet in the fourth quarter, talked about the game as if it
were a midseason battle that had playoff repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the real thing,'' Gill said. ``You have everybody
hitting big shots and making free throws. You had the drama, the
cross-river rivalry. They beat us at their place and we beat them
at ours. I guess that's the way it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have started as a typical exhibition game, where
conditioning and execution were the chief concerns, but some time
before the half it became a battle that neither team wanted to
lose. There were bumps, flagrant fouls and the arguing of
officials' calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks wanted it just as badly as the Nets, but the Nets had
more at stake: it was their home court. The Knicks had edged them
by 88-87 on a free throw in the final moments in Wednesday's
exhibition at Madison Square Garden, and Friday night it was the
Nets' turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get a win,'' said Nets Coach John Calipari, whose
club was led by Keith Van Horn's game-high 33 points. ``It doesn't
matter if it's preseason. You just want to get a win to get the
feeling of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets got that feeling when Chris Gatling scored the last of
his 18 points on a perfectly executed play with 21.3 seconds left.
Gatling, who exhibited a soft outside touch and smooth hook shot,
received a pass into the post from Lucious Harris, executed a spin
move and put in a jump hook.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dudley, who had played a physical style all night, fouled
Gatling, who hit the free throw to put the Nets ahead by 92-90. The
Knicks' two last-gasp 3-point attempts fell short.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets had battled the Knicks throughout the game, just as
they have been battling injuries during the preseason. During
halftime Friday, Van Horn began complaining about spasms in his
left thigh. He tried to stretch and tried to play the third
quarter, but ended up hobbling to the Nets' locker room less than a
minute into the half.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Calipari was beginning to lament over yet another
injury to one of his players, Van Horn emerged from the trainer's
room with a smooth gait. Van Horn's injury was not serious, just a
cramped thigh.
</P>
<P>
   The picture of the 6-foot-10-inch power forward returning to the
game with 6 minutes 39 seconds remaining in the third quarter was
more gratifying than the minor feelings of accomplishment that came
from this meaningless victory.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who sank a 12-foot jump shot 24 seconds after
re-entering, was outstanding in his first preseason game. After
missing three days of practice and Wednesday's contest against the
Knicks with food poisoning that took six pounds off his bulked-up
frame, he showed no loss of strength or finesse on powerful moves
to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn scored 17 of his points from the free-throw line. He
appeared rusty early in the game as he missed eight of his first
nine shots, but midway through the second period his game returned.
</P>
<P>
   A serious injury to Van Horn would have been enough to send
Calipari into a deep depression. Training camp has been more like
basic training at the club's Champion Center, as numerous Nets
players have pulled up lame since training camps officially began
eight days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles (bruised right knee) and Rony Seikaly (sprained
left ankle) sat out Friday's game and are not expected to return
for a few weeks, and Jayson Williams and Sam Cassell played
sparingly because of aches and pains. Williams, the hardy
rebounder, played only 16 minutes because of a sore right ankle he
turned Wednesday night _ he still grabbed nine rebounds _ and
Cassell, who has back spasms, was on the floor for only 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Nets' starting five was together for only 39
games, as Van Horn, Williams and Cassell missed key stretches with
an assortment of ailments.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets proved their resiliency in making the playoffs, and
Friday night they showed that they have not lost that trait. With
Eric Murdock and Lucious Harris playing the guard spots for most of
the night, and Van Horn (nine rebounds) doing his best to make up
for Williams' absence on the boards, the Nets took the Knicks to
the final moments.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Knicks played all but seven minutes without
Patrick Ewing, who sprained his right knee. And the reserves Marcus
Camby (blister) and Dennis Scott (hamstring) missed the entire
game. But the Nets' casualties were probably more critical.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, the Nets matched JAYSON WILLIAMS' $20,000
contribution to Continental Arena employees who lost money during
the seven-month lockout, bringing the total to $40,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
