<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VOLVO IN FORD'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest (but surely not the last) auto merger, with Ford
Motor Co. buying up Sweden's Volvo AB, poses an interesting
challenge for Ford: how to make it appear that the event has not
taken place. The world's second-largest auto maker cannot afford to
deprive Volvo of an essential characteristic: its uniqueness.
</P>
<P>
   From a purely corporate perspective, the deal makes sense.
Volvo, for all its appeal as the builder of cars with high quality,
tasteful design, and good driving characteristics, was doomed by
its small size to an inferior position when competing with
American, European, and Japanese behemoths in an intensely
competitive industry. Speculation on some form of merger for Volvo
has piqued the financial markets for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Ford can use its great size to provide efficiencies that will
make Volvo more competitive and innovative in ways that will be
essentially invisible to consumers. It has taken an important first
step by saying it intends to treat Volvo as an autonomous operation
in Sweden _ much as it has done with its earlier acquisition of
another distinguished car maker, Britain's Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   Current markets impose heavy burdens on auto makers worldwide.
Collectively they can turn out 60 million cars a year, but people
are buying only 50 million. Lower production costs are essential in
such circumstances to allow for more competitive pricing. The road
to those lower costs runs through consolidation so development and
capital costs can be spread over the broadest possible production
base. In such an environment, small may be beautiful, but it is no
guarantee of success _ even when small consists of building 400,000
cars a year, as Volvo does.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has more than 70 years' experience in Europe, where it
account for 10 percent of auto sales. This deal requires a
fascinating combination of the brute strength provided by Ford's
sheer size and the delicacy needed to maintain an operation with
Volvo's special identity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
