A5026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-WORD-BOS &LR;      01-30 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mayoral appointee in Washington, D.C., has lost his job
because he used the word ``niggardly'' to describe a budget he
administered. Any dictionary will show that the word means miserly,
parsimonious, stingy, or tight-fisted and has nothing whatever to
do with the unacceptable racial slur except that it starts with the
same four letters. Will the word ``niggling,'' as in, ``I have a
niggling suspicion that racial sensitivity has run amok in this
land,'' be next on the list of forbidden words?
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary, the foremost authority on
derivations of the language, notes that niggardly has obscure
origins but may be Scandinavian or Old French. It does not share
root words or other etymological connections with the racial slur,
which, like Negro and Nigeria, derives from ``nigrum,'' the Latin
word for black.
</P>
<P>
   These simple facts seemed not to matter to the cabal that called
for the ouster of the offending mayoral aide, David Howard, who
happens to be white. The newly elected mayor, Anthony Williams, who
happens to be black, was already under pressure from some black
activists who thought he was appointing too few people of color.
When Howard's comment started rumors _ completely unproved _ that
he had uttered the other N-word, Williams was only too relieved to
accept his aide's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   What Williams should have done is stand up for Howard, the
facts, and the English language, which is the envy of the world for
its richness and nuance. Poets and essayists have used niggardly or
a variation since Chaucer's time because it was just the word they
needed to convey their intent precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this from Samuel Richardson's ``Pamela,'' widely
believed to be the first English novel: ``What is my single
happiness if I suffer it, niggard-like, to extend no further than
to myself?''
</P>
<P>
   It is sad to think that a brave word could die from disuse
because of ignorance compounded by hair-trigger sensitivities,
leaving a vision that extends no farther than oneself. It's a view
of the world that is downright _ well, you know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
