u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-HINGIS-     01-30 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-HINGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POISED AND POTENT HINGIS GETS 3RD TITLE IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TEN-AUSTRALIA) 
(js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ Martina Hingis has a Rebound Ace court at
home in Switzerland, and perhaps that explains why she is equally
at home on that same surface here on Centre Court at the Australian
Open.
</P>
<P>
   One day after winning her third consecutive women's doubles
title in Melbourne, the Swiss teen-ager on Saturday won her third
consecutive women's singles title by defeating the unseeded
Frenchwoman, Amelie Mauresmo, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   It was a most convincing victory, accomplished in just over an
hour, and though Mauresmo saved six match points in the final game
of the match, Hingis' potent cocktail of baseline accuracy,
all-court coverage and tactical flexibility lent an air of
inevitability to the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The two had played twice before, and on both occasions, Hingis
had won in three sets: first in the Fed Cup semifinals in
Switzerland in July and then in the third round of the U.S. Open in
September.
</P>
<P>
   But this encounter came on a much larger stage, and Hingis'
victory gave her a fifth Grand Slam singles title at age 18. She
has now won 21 singles matches in a row at Melbourne Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just played some awesome tennis, and it just brings some
good luck to me,'' the second-seeded Hingis said of the year's
first Grand Slam tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the kangaroo doll given to winners in Melbourne,
she said, ``that's six in a row, it's a real family.''
</P>
<P>
   The only set Hingis dropped in singles this year came in the
fourth round against 16th-seeded Amanda Coetzer. Her other
victories were utterly convincing, and it appears that her renewed
focus on her tennis has lifted her game in the first part of the
year. After losing to Lindsay Davenport in the final of the
tournament in Sydney that preceded the Australian Open, she never
got the chance for a rematch in Melbourne because Mauresmo upset
Davenport in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The French 19-year-old, who was the world's top-ranked junior in
1996, was not as poised or precise Saturday, but she will now jump
from 29th to at least 18th in the world rankings. Hingis will stay
at No. 2 behind Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can continue playing like this the whole year too.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a cool, breezy day, more like spring in Paris or Zurich
than summer in Australia, when Hingis and Mauresmo walked on Centre
Court together and posed for the customary pre-final photographs at
the net.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is 14 months younger than Mauresmo, Hingis has been
playing important matches in this evocative stadium for much
longer, but the reception for both players as they were introduced
was equally warm.
</P>
<P>
   The first set would quickly become a less balanced affair. The
French teenager looked understandably nervous in the opening game,
making two unforced errors off her forehand wing and
double-faulting to lose her serve. Hingis then took a 2-0 lead when
Mauresmo overhit a backhand which she was poorly positioned to
strike with such force.
</P>
<P>
   Judgment would prove a problem throughout the set for Mauresmo,
who often seemed to be guiding her groundstrokes, instead of
letting her racquet move freely through the ball. But then Hingis,
a power thinker instead of power player, knows how to get the worst
out of her opponents, and she had decided that the path to victory
lay along the backhand diagonal.
</P>
<P>
   While Mauresmo was occasionally able to overwhelm the Swiss from
the baseline or force her into awkward positions with her heavy
topspin, she was unable to sustain such shotmaking, and Hingis
broke her again in the seventh game and then served out the set.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Hingis formidable is her versatility. She is often
forced into the role of counterpuncher because of the taller,
stronger players, like Davenport and Venus Williams and Mary Pierce
who are now her primary challengers. But Hingis has not won the
last five Grand Slam titles in women's doubles (with three
different partners) by coincidence. She is very comfortable at the
net, and in the opening game of the second set, she proved it,
getting a break point with a lovely forehand drop volley and
getting the break with a crisp forehand volley crosscourt. Her
approach shots do not have the bite of Jana Novotna's, but the
element of surprise works in her favor, and by now it looked like
Mauresmo's first Grand Slam singles final would be a brief
experience.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauresmo righted herself in the next game, taking a 0-40
advantage on Hingis' serve. Though the Swiss got back to deuce with
some more aggressive play, Mauresmo would hold firm for her first
break of the match.
</P>
<P>
   They would exchange breaks again to 3-3, but after Hingis broke
Mauresmo yet again in the seventh game, the French player would
prove incapable of returning the favor. She took a 0-40 lead, but
Hingis reeled off five consecutive points to go up 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   She soon had her first match point on Mauresmo's serve, but she
would need nearly seven more minutes to close out the championship,
as Mauresmo saved six match points, often with winners or forceful
shots. When Mauresmo saved the sixth with a backhand volley winner,
the increasingly frustrated Hingis leaned forward and shrieked in
the direction of the court that has been so good to her.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauresmo would miss her next two volleys into the net, and
Hingis raised her arms in the air and threw her racquets into the
crowd. She has won three Australian Opens, one Wimbledon and one
U.S. Open singles titles. All that she is missing is the French
Open. Perhaps it's time she ripped up the Rebound Ace in
Switzerland and replaced it with red clay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
