<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CENSUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING NOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 31, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its 5-4 ruling against the use of statistical sampling during
the next US census, the Supreme Court has imposed a heavy burden on
Congress and the Clinton administration to provide enough resources
to allow for the most aggressive head count possible. Even with
that head count, it is certain that thousands of people will go
uncounted, disproportionately the urban poor and ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling, which did not turn on the constitutional
phrase ``actual enumeration,'' did approve use of statistical
sampling for purposes other than the apportionment of congressional
seats. Equity demands that Congress take advantage of this method
to make the fairest possible distribution of federal aid,
especially since undercounting tends to be highest among those most
in need of support.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer, in his dissent, made arguments for
statistical adjustments that may yet carry the day if the court is
asked to test the issue on constitutional grounds. Statistical
adjustments, he contends, ``would not substitute for, but rather
would supplement, a traditional head count and would do so to
achieve the basic purpose of the statutes that authorize the head
count _ namely, accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer took note of the fact that the Census Bureau has for
decades used some estimating techniques to improve census accuracy
_ notably the ``imputation'' of the number of residents in houses
where no one answers requests for information. This has the
misfortune of possibly over-counting wealthier households with more
than one dwelling and undercounting poorer ones, but it establishes
the principle of making common-sense adjustments to counts that
would otherwise be even less accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Counting 270 million or more noses in the year 2000 will not be
easy, but using a medley of techniques can produce a satisfactory
and useful result _ provided the Census Bureau is given enough
tools and enough personnel. The burden is now on Congress and the
administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
