A5031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-SUPER-BOS &LR;      01-30 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SUPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY COMMUNION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 31, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be nearly impossible to explain to a foreigner just
what Super Bowl Sunday is all about. The game plans concocted by
the coaches appear as intricate as the derivatives portfolio of a
high-flying hedge fund. Their terminology has followed psychobabble
and management-speak into dank caves of pretentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   But complexities of the bomb and the blitz are much easier to
elucidate than the anthropological meaning of this American ritual.
Why does everybody watch the game? What is it about this one
sporting event that induces a national communion? Why are the fates
of great corporations shaped by the commercials they sponsor on the
Super Bowl telecast?
</P>
<P>
   A cynic might say that the secret of Super Sunday, the reason
for the impassioning frenzy of fans and casual spectators alike, is
the genius of the point spread. In a society predicated upon the
investment ethic and the spirit of capitalism, there is no other
contest _ not even the Kentucky Derby _ that attracts so much
wagering. For one splendid Sunday, every citizen seems to have a
few bob riding on the outcome of the same game. As a Runyonesque
character once said: The greatest thing in life is to gamble and
win, and the next best is to gamble and lose.
</P>
<P>
   But an intelligent foreigner would still want to know why
America's heterodox population agrees to make such a fuss about
this one oversold, overpublicized televised sports program. Sad to
say, the best answer may be precisely that nobody wants to miss
what everyone is expected to see. In other words: Hype works.
</P>
<P>
   It would be dispiriting, however, to admit to a curious
outlander that we Americans are a society of hustlers and marks.
For some nations there is no indignity greater than being duped.
</P>
<P>
   Better to dwell on the balletic beauty of Denver Bronco blockers
knocking Falcons off their feet so Terrell Davis can cut back
against the flow of the defense. Under all the salesmanship is a
game both simple and subtle that has become, for many, the true
national pastime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
