A5032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-EXERCISE-BO     01-30 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-EXERCISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEAT EQUITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, February 1, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cheer went up from the couch last week with publication of the
latest exercise studies in the Journal of the American Medical
Association. The articles concluded that for the sedentary
individual, simple changes in lifestyle _ climbing the stairs
instead of taking the elevator, walking instead of driving, just
vacuuming the house _ are as beneficial as health club workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The report went straight to the truth of most health research:
People hate to exercise. Never mind the masochists on the rowing
machines and the runners in the rain; the average person would
rather do almost anything than put another ``have-to'' on the
schedule, especially if it involves heavy equipment and expensive
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The JAMA studies, while not intended to, have fed the fantasies
of people longing for the science that will tell them that staying
healthy is easy. They're figuring that if researchers are saying
it's OK to incorporate exercise into the daily routine and skip the
trip to the gym, then surely the study is not far off that finds
that punching a TV clicker vigorously from a prone position while
doing leg lifts is a respectable way to burn off the calories in
the bowl of chips on the coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with exercise is that it's such a long-term
proposition. It lacks the sizzle of instant gratification, the quid
pro quo that says, ``You sweat, now you get.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider how well that concept might work in a restaurant
aerobics room where patrons planning to indulge could pay up front,
calorically, so they might enjoy the rest of the evening with the
``No-Guilt Gourmet.'' A chef might even wheel the dessert cart
through the predinner exercise session to inspire another set of
jumping jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing stores could also cash in on a preshopping workout
area, where consumers would burn off pounds and more easily suck in
the gut before facing the dressing room mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting calisthetics directly with the temptations and goals
of life would make workouts more compelling. The sit-ups wouldn't
be any easier, but they'd sure seem that way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
