<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-INS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNFAIR FEES FOR WOULD-BE CITIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, February 1, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money has become a bigger barrier to becoming a United States
citizen. On Jan. 15 the federal Immigration and Naturalization
Service raised the application fee for becoming a citizen from $95
to $225. In October the INS raised a host of other fees.
</P>
<P>
   The agency argues that the increases are needed because fees
didn't cover costs. It estimates that it is losing $17 million a
month, and fees haven't increased since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This argument makes sense within reason, but some of the
increases are unreasonably high. For example, the fee for a
petition to classify an orphan as a relative _ for international
adoptions _ went from $155 to $405. A husband and wife who want to
become citizens have to pay $500 _ $450 in application fees and $25
apiece for fingerprinting, a fee that went into effect last March.
</P>
<P>
   These fees have more than doubled in some cases for a
notoriously slow service that is making only modest improvements.
The INS has a backlog of 1.8 million citizenship cases _ down from
a high of 1.9 million _ and it can take two years or more for forms
to be processed.
</P>
<P>
   Over a year ago, INS Commissioner Doris Meissner promised that
the citizenship fee would not increase until the service was more
efficient. In early 1998 the average wait was 27 months. As of last
December it was 23 months. The INS hopes to reduce the wait to 12
months by the end of September and to six months a year after that.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the long delay and the new high prices threaten
low-income immigrants because national welfare reform has changed
the rules. Legal aliens are no longer eligible for such safety net
programs as food stamps and Social Security assistance. Some states
have stepped in to replace some of these programs. But in many
cases, immigrants get less money or must meet residency
requirements that exclude them.
</P>
<P>
   The INS should be able to cover its costs. But its sharply
higher fees unfairly pose sudden obstacles with only the
possibility of far-off improvements. America should embrace
qualified new citizens, not shackle them with burdensome fees
before they ever take the oath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0055EST &QL; 
