<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LIGHTNING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP LINE IS GOLDEN FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The worst team in the NHL put a scare into the
Stars last night _ one that was eventually overcome by the line of
Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   After the trio had a hand in three goals in the Stars' 4-1
victory against the Tampa Bay Lightning, coach Ken Hitchcock said
the team can't continue to rely solely on its top line.
</P>
<P>
   ``What won the game was talent,'' Hitchcock said. ``Our talented
players came to play tonight, but I thought some of our players
really struggled.'' Modano had a goal and an assist, Hull a goal
and an assist and Lehtinen two assists to help the Stars overcome a
slow start and push their league-best record to 29-9-7. The
Lightning fell to a league-worst 11-32-4, but didn't play that way
as they slammed bodies from the opening drop of the puck, scored
first on a power play and played inspired hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we come out East and play teams once, when you're No. 1,
they're going to throw everything they've got at you,'' Hitchcock
said. ``It took us too long to wade into the game, far too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing under the experimental two-referee system, the first
period was wrought with eight penalty calls by officials Lance
Roberts and Brad Watson. That created problems for the Stars, as
they couldn't get their power play going and gave up an early goal
on the penalty kill.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning winger Wendel Clark deflected in a Petr Svoboda shot
at the 1-minute, 52-second mark of the first period, and the Stars
were climbing up a hill. On their way up, they also had to battle a
rugged effort from the Lightning, which recorded 31 hits to the
Stars' 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really came out hard and we were lucky we came out of the
period down just one,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars quickly made up that deficit when Modano, after
weaving through the slot, pushed home his own rebound 30 seconds
into the second period. Lightning replacement goalie Corey Schwab,
who relieved starter Bill Ranford in the first period after Ranford
suffered a cervical sprain, made some critical saves, but he
couldn't stop Hull and Modano.
</P>
<P>
   Hull then notched the game-winner, his team-leading 18th goal,
when Modano skated in hard on the forecheck, whipped a pass out of
the corner and found Hull in the slot. Hull lifted a slap shot
under the crossbar, which Schwab never saw and it was 2-1 at the
10:38 mark of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Stars goalie Ed Belfour performed magic in between, stopping 31
shots, including two without his stick. Belfour made a chest save
on Stephane Richer and then gloved the rebound shot off the stick
of Brent Peterson to freeze the puck at a time when the Lightning
looked dangerously close to seizing control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie played a great game,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen then set up Sergei Zubov for an insurance goal at the
7:27 mark of the third period, and the Lightning ran out of gas.
Hatcher earned his seventh goal of the season to complete the
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But while the final score made it look like an easy Stars
victory, Hitchcock said the team has to play better at 6:30 tonight
when they visit the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who put us on our heels were our people, who should
be putting the other people on their heels,'' Hitchcock said of his
third and fourth lines. ``And it's going to be the same thing
against Florida. They've been sitting there two, three days getting
revved up for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the Panthers 3-0-1 since acquiring winger Pavel Bure in
a trade, Hitchcock will be sure to ask more from the Stars tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll get an earful of it,'' Modano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
