<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO BOWLER ROLLS HOT PATH TO TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stepladder finals Fourth seed Roger Bowker and fifth seed Jason
Hurd will begin the stepladder finals at 3 p.m. today in Dallas at
the Don Carter Professional Bowlers Association Classic at Don
Carter's All Star Lanes-West.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Couch, third seed, will face the winner of Bowker-Hurd
</P>
<P>
   David Wodka, second seed, will meet that winner
</P>
<P>
   Mike Miller, first seed, will meet the last survivor
</P>
<P>
   Call (214) 358-1382 for ticket information
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mike Miller of Albuquerque, N.M., had the first-place
seed all but locked up before the position round of match play even
began at the Don Carter Professional Bowlers Association Classic
last night.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the only touring bowler with a thumbless delivery,
defeated Jason Couch in the final match-play game, 238-216, to keep
himself atop the field of 24 with a total pin count of 10,453at Don
Carter's All Star Lanes-West. Miller, who led the tournament since
game 13 of match play, dominated the field with a match-play record
of 20-3-1 _ a record Couch called ``unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The best match-play record in PBA history is 22-2, earned by
George Pappas in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get anxious in a situation like that,'' said
Miller of match play. ``You're ahead, things are going well and you
want sometimes for things to be over. I tried to be patient tonight
and let myself enjoy the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Couch, who finished third with 10,248 pins, are
joined by David Wodka, second at 10,250, Roger Bowker, fourth at
10,172 and Jason Hurd at 10,133 on the stepladder finals at 3 p.m.
today, which will be taped by ESPN and televised at 1:30 p.m.
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, whose last title came in Wichita in 1992, said this
tournament marks a comeback that has been building during the past
six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years have been brutal,'' Miller said. ``I
had my head beat in week after week after week. It helps to have a
tournament like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller won't be the only player in the top five with something
to prove. Wodka, who moved past Couch by two pins with his
position-round victory against Bowker, has made six television
shows but has never won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping this will be the one,'' Wodka said. ``I'm going to
be loose, that's for sure. I won't lose because I'm tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch, who has five titles, has never won a tournament from any
position but the top seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to prove to myself that I can win from any position,''
Couch said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he liked his chances from the top seed. Of the two
titles he holds, he won one from the top seed and another from
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was on television \Rin November\S, I went out
there and I didn't play the lanes properly,'' Miller said. ``So,
\Rtoday\S, I'm going to look and see what's going on and make my
decisions more prudently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do what you can do and let God take care of the
rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
