<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-WALKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS OPEN WALKER BIDDING AT $5 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks tendered a contract offer to power
forward Samaki Walker yesterday for four years and $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   But snags may be forthcoming, because Walker said he is seeking
a long-term contract in the neighborhood of $7 million to $8
million per season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five million? I don't think so,'' Walker said when asked
whether he will sign for $5 million per season. ``I'm looking at a
lot of guys out there now that I know I've been able to accomplish
a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's ahead for Samaki Walker, and I think the
Mavericks do, too. If they want me here, I think we'll get a fair
deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson said he wants the
6-foot-9, 258-pounder in the fold. But at what price?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'd like to be here,'' Nelson said. ``It really just
depends on if the numbers can be worked out, and what he has in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we made him a very fair proposal. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has given teams until March 13 to sign players who will
be entering their third season and approaching free-agency status
after the 1999 season. Walker, who turns 23 on Feb. 25, falls in
this category.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said it won't be difficult for him to stay in Dallas if
he doesn't sign a contract by March 13. But if he isn't signed by
then, the Mavericks can't discuss a contract with him again until
July 1, when he becomes a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll give me a chance to go out and really prove myself
even more, which means it's a 50-50 situation,'' Walker said,
referring to if he misses the cutoff date. ``You can go out and
have a hell of a season, or you can go out and have a disastrous
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Walker's injury problems played a role in the
Mavericks' offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our kind of guy, a great guy, and perfect in the locker
room,'' Nelson said. ``There's only one thing. He's been
injury-prone from college all the way into his first two years
here. There's the physical things that we have to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker missed the final 40 games last season because of a stress
fracture of his right foot. As a rookie two years ago, he missed 34
games with various injuries, including a loose bone chip in his
right foot and a second-degree sprain of his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Late in practice yesterday, Walker sprained his right ankle when
he was accidentally stepped on by center Shawn Bradley. He limped
off the court and is questionable for the preseason game against
the Phoenix Suns tonight at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Mavericks' highest-paid players are Bradley and guard
Michael Finley. Bradley played one season at Brigham Young and
signed an eight-year, $44.2 million contract with the Philadelphia
76ers after spending two years on a Mormon mission.
</P>
<P>
   Finley is in the first year of a five-year, $42 million contract
extension he signed before last season.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who had eight double-doubles last season, said he's not
asking for Bradley or Finley money. ``I'm not trying to compete
with Finley's contract,'' he said. ``I'm looking for the fairness
for Samaki Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finley is the straw here, he's established. If I'm going to be
the sidekick and the guy that's going to also be the foundation and
focus of this team, then that'll show.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker averaged 11 points and 8.4 rebounds and shot .504 from
the field in the 26 games he played last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make this a big rivalry between myself and the
Mavericks,'' Walker said. ``I want to get a deal done as soon as
possible, but I want it to be as fair as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows the game is definitely won inside-out. And if
you've got a guy that can average a double-double night in and
night out, they should be rewarded for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
