<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AIDES DECIDE ON SENDING TROOPS FOR KOSOVO TRUCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs 11th graf, beginning ``In this effort,'' to add info on
command of U.S. NATO troops. No other changes.) 
(ATTN: Ariz., Va., Ind., Fla., Calif., Conn., Neb.)  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's top national security advisers
decided Friday that the United States should commit several
thousand ground troops to an international force in Kosovo to
monitor any eventual cease-fire there, according to administration
officials and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials were promoting the plan around Capitol
Hill on Friday before discussing it with Clinton on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the United States and its allies, meeting in
London, on Friday ordered the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, and leaders of the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo to
sit down to a tight schedule of peace talks. NATO is expected to
vote on Saturday to authorize air strikes against the Serbs if they
do not agree to a political settlement of autonomy for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative plan, as outlined by administration and
congressional officials, would involve 2,000 to 5,000 U.S. troops
in a NATO force of more than 20,000 ground troops to monitor a
cease-fire in the separatist province of Kosovo, which has been
torn by warfare. Those troops could remain in Kosovo for as long as
three years under one of the proposals, according to a
congressional official.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the French and the British announced that they
would send ground troops to Kosovo as part of a NATO peacekeeping
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case the administration is making is to say the Europeans
can't handle this themselves,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
``The larger question is whether we should commit troops. They want
to commit, but the mood of my colleagues is extremely skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   More meetings are scheduled through the weekend to refine
details of a possible NATO air strike and of the components of a
NATO ground force that would enforce a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prospect of another troop commitment in the Balkans,
Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the new chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said he gave his full support to the
administration's plans when the national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, telephoned him Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where we have no choice but to commit
ground troops, and I'll have to lead that effort to convince the
Senate,'' said Warner, who added that he had been urging the
administration for weeks to make such a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made an enormous investment in Bosnia,'' he said, ``A
continuing destabilized Kosovo will put our people at risk and
bring to a halt the creeping progress being made there.''
</P>
<P>
   In this effort, the White House and congressional Republicans
have said they would prefer to have U.S. troops under U.S. command
within NATO, as has been the practice in the past in many
instances. But Pentagon officials indicated that they would be
willing to have a smaller role in the Kosovo effort, and allow
Europeans to command the NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   In the hourlong meeting Friday, the president's senior advisers
also discussed the immediate problem of how to persuade the two
warring parties in Kosovo to accept a cease-fire, according to P.J.
Crowley, spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   There are 700 unarmed monitors operating under the auspices of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe on patrol
now in Kosovo. They will be especially vulnerable to being taken
hostage or being attacked during the talks.
</P>
<P>
   But according to an administration official, the monitors could
be removed from the region within eight hours in the event of a
decision to carry out air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The violence in Kosovo continued unabated Friday. In Rogovo more
than 24 ethnic Albanians were found shot. Serbs said they had
raided a guerrilla group, but the ethnic Albanians said most of the
dead were civilians. Monitors said it appeared that the killings
were in revenge for the shooting of a Serbian policeman by the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   A similar pattern was behind the massacre at Racak two weeks
ago, where 45 ethnic Albanians were shot at close range by Serbian
forces after the Kosovo Liberation Army killed four Serbian police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The repetition of such attacks, with the Serbian forces having
far superior weapons and numbers of policemen and soldiers, pushed
the NATO allies into seeking a speedy solution and backing it up
with the threat of force.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he was not impressed with the bombing proposals
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced that the kind of air strikes that are being
contemplated would convince Milosevic to sign a cease-fire,'' he
said. ``They are not strong enough or sustained enough to inflict
significant damage on Milosevic's military capability.``
</P>
<P>
   The administration plans to formally present its plans for
troops to Congress once the president agrees.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Seven senators sent the president a letter Friday urging that
the United States, in concert with NATO, take military action
against Milosevic. It was signed by Evan Bayh of Indiana, Bob
Graham of Florida, Charles Robb of Virginia, Dianne Feinstein of
California, and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, all Democrats; and
by Richard Lugar of Indiana and Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, both
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The letter warned that a delay in action ``may result in more
innocent civilian casualties and in the questioning of NATO's
ability to preserve peace in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But those sentiments will be challenged by other senators who
remember the administration's earlier promises that the
peacekeeping effort in Bosnia, begun after the signing of the
Dayton accord, would have a definite ending _ a promise that was
repeated twice but has yet to be kept.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the architect of the Dayton accords, will not
take part in the coming talks on Kosovo in Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials say Holbrooke has been heavily
involved in helping shape U.S. policy in response to the recent
crisis in Kosovo, even as he has struggled to reach a settlement
with the Justice Department to end an ethics investigation that has
sidetracked his nomination to the position of chief delegate to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, Dick has been an important participant _
at least by phone _ in every major conversation on this subject
over the last two weeks,'' a senior administration official said.
``That cell phone is glued to his ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they know of no plans for
Holbrooke, who is as close to Milosevic as anyone in the
administration, to travel to Belgrade to deliver an ultimatum. But
they say it is an option that will be considered if NATO gets much
closer to a military strike against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who lives in New York, where he is vice chairman of
the investment banking firm of Credit Suisse First Boston, was
traveling Friday in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, on private
business. Friends said he had no immediate plans to travel to the
Balkans and was expected back in the United States this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
