<SLUG> BC-DOG-GONE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING CANINE HELPER RETURNS TO DISABLED OWNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN and JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Five days of anguish ended in elation for Jeff
Horny when he was reunited with Tyler the golden retriever, his
companion and assistant for years.
</P>
<P>
   The dog somehow wandered off Monday from Horny's home on Blix
Street in suburban North Hollywood, leaving the quadriplegic
heartbroken and unable to perform many of the tasks that Tyler had
made possible.
</P>
<P>
   The reddish canine picks up Horny's keys, turns on lights and
even opens doors -- which is what the dog apparently did Monday
inside his home before wandering off through a gate that was left
ajar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' Horny said after Friday's reunion. ``I'm going
to appreciate him much more, because you don't appreciate things
until they are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of speechless. I'm not going to let him leave my bed
because I'm going to sleep for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   First, however, Tyler will get a steak dinner, and Horny will
call off the bloodhounds -- literally.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of Horny's dog had drawn national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Sympathetic to his story, a producer from the TV show ``Extra''
was helping find a way to pay for a pet-tracking bloodhound named
Luca to search for Tyler. American Airlines donated a ticket to fly
the tracking dog and his handler from Dallas to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyler, it turns out, had trotted about three miles to North
Hollywood Park, where he befriended two teen-agers and followed
them home.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the mother of one of the teens saw a story about the
lost dog on television and got in touch with Horny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that we found the owner,'' said Connie Smith, whose
17-year-old son, Patrick, and his girlfriend found Tyler in North
Hollywood Park on Monday. ``We could have taken him to the dog
pound shelter, but we wanted to find the owner because the dog
looked very well taken care of and was very lovable. It wasn't just
any old dog.''
</P>
<P>
   First thing today, Horny said, Tyler will start wearing a tag
with his owner's name and phone number, which should have been done
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's priceless to me,'' the 26-year-old man said.
</P>
<P>
   Rescued about seven years ago off a freeway near San Antonio,
Texas, Tyler was professionally trained to assist disabled people.
The retriever was selected a few years later to pair up with Horny,
who broke his neck in a car crash caused by black ice on a Texas
roadway in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Horny, an actor, spent years training Tyler to do what most
people consider ordinary tasks, such as turning lights on and off,
opening doors, pulling away chairs for him and retrieving items
that he has dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll grab whatever he can to get it to me,'' Horny said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler retrieves his owner's wheelchair if it slips away from him
as he gets into his vehicle, and also pulls his owner up small
hills.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's work gives Horny his independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to call someone to pick up my keys,'' he said.
``If I needed help up a ramp, I don't have to get somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The canine also travels with Horny in his sport-utility vehicle
to go to work auditions, run errands and eat at restaurants. He
flies with him on vacations and visits schools to educate children
about disabled populations.
</P>
<P>
   When his buddy was missing, Horny notified animal control
officials, most kennels in his neighborhood and the Los Angeles
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very important to him because he helps him out,'' said
Officer John Catalano of the North Hollywood Division.
</P>
<P>
   Horny's father, Ben Horny, flew in from Texas on Thursday night
and spent most of Friday tacking up more than 400 lost-dog fliers
around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm posting them every place I can find a tree, an empty hand
-- even the homeless,'' Ben Horny said during the search.
</P>
<P>
   Several people called to report they saw Tyler roaming the
streets blocks away from his home, his owner said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tyler has left his yard to nose around the alley
before, he had never run away, said Horny, adding: ``I don't think
he was meaning to leave. He's always sniffing around.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
