 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton's top national
security advisers decided Friday that the United States should
commit several thousand ground troops to an international force in
Kosovo to monitor any eventual cease-fire there, according to
administration officials and members of Congress. By Elizabeth
Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ By summoning the fighting parties in
Kosovo to the peace table next week, virtually at gunpoint, the
European allies hope to duplicate the feat of the United States in
imposing a peace settlement on Bosnia in Dayton, Ohio more than
three years ago. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-QUAKE (Armenia, Colombia) _ Desperate survivors of
Colombia's deadly earthquake raided relief centers and stores in
the battered provincial capital of Armenia on Friday, as security
forces struggled to stop a third day of looting. Thousands of
people, angered by having to stand in long lines and fill out forms
to receive handouts of aid, tore down a chain-link fence and
stormed the main Red Cross relief center in Armenia. By Larry
Rohter. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-LOVERS (Karachi, Pakistan) &UR;  &LR; _ True love may never run
smooth, but rarely is the road as treacherous as it has been for
Humaira and Mehmood Butt, Pakistani lovers who, though joined in
marriage, have a powerful man trying to tear it asunder. By Barry
Bearak. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CARTOONIST (Paris) _ More than one French chief of state
has felt the felt-tipped sting of Plantu, a cartoonist who is one
of the most powerful political institutions not found in the 1958
French Constitution. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHIZOPHRENIA-COPE (New York) _ Schizophrenia afflicts an
estimated 2.7 million Americans. It is an illness notable for its
laceration of consciousness, and for the terrible isolation it
imposes on sufferers. It also exacts a severe toll from family
members who often can do little but watch helplessly. The public,
however, usually hears about schizophrenia only in the context of
lurid headlines. And sensational news coverage reenforces the
mistaken belief that violence frequently accompanies the illness.
By Erica Goode. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-ABORTION-BOMB (Birmingham) _ A year after an abortion clinic
was bombed here, the man accused, Eric Rudolf, is still at large
and the victims are still suffering. By Rick Bragg. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-DEATH-PENALTY (St. Louis) _ When Pope John Paul II
condemned capital punishment during his pastoral visit here, the
100,000 people gathered before him in an indoor stadium roared with
applause. But most American Catholics do not agree with the pope
about the death penalty or about a range of other crucial issues,
including abortion, birth control and women serving as priests. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NANNY-SETTLE (Boston) _ The case of the British au pair Louise
Woodward continues to resonate in Boston where people rehash and
rehash, debate at brunches over defense claims of medical evidence,
which are now considered by many to be baloney, etc. Meanwhile, a
settlement was reached Friday in the wrongful death lawsuit against
Woodward, barring her from profiting from her story. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ICKES-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno rejected
on Friday an independent counsel investigation of former White
House deputy chief-of-staff Harold Ickes for allegedly lying to a
Senate committee looking into campaign finances. By David Johnston.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MANAGERS (Washington) _ Senate Republicans have given
Henry Hyde just about everything he could ask for _ the trial, the
witnesses, the videotapes _ and what have they gotten in return? A
heap of abuse and comments about the Alamo. The House managers are
true believers, men on a mission, and they just can't be satisfied.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ The White House is planning not to demand
to call additional witnesses unless depositions from three
witnesses next week produce damaging new evidence against President
Clinton, administration officials said Friday. By James Bennet.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WALTERS (Undated) _ The videotaping of Monica Lewinsky's
testimony could scoop Barbara Walters, whose planned interview is
still on hold because of Kenneth Starr's gag order; Walters says
she doesn't like it, but thinks her questions will be different
from those asked in the deposition. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Economic growth surged in the fourth
quarter as consumers ignored the financial crises abroad and prices
rose at the slowest pace in 40 years. Gross domestic product grew
at an annual rate of 5.6 percent, well above expectations. During
the full year, the economy expanded 3.9 percent, yet inflation
remained in check. By Sylvia Nasar. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ Brazil's crisis of credibility
became increasingly acute Friday as signs of panic began to appear.
Paul Volker, the former chairman of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board
warned on Friday that Brazil's leaders were underestimating the
financial crisis confronting them. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-BARON (Undated) _ In court documents filed last week in
U.S. District Court in the Southern District of New York, a former
executive of Bear Stearns Cos. alleges that his firm allowed the
chief executive of a small brokerage firm to violate securities
laws. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES-CELEBRITY-MODEL (Undated) _ Women's magazines, taking
their cue from other magazine categories, have shifted their focus
from the placid, youthful beauty of models to the expertly pancaked
visages of movie stars and talk-show hostesses. By Alex Kuczynski.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-VOLVO (Goteborg, Sweden) _ Yet on Friday, as Swedes
digested the news that Ford had reached an agreement to buy Volvo's
car business for $6.45 billion, there were few signs of shock or
remorse. Instead, reactions among people both inside and outside
the company ranged from pragmatic acceptance to outright optimism.
By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KELLOG-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Kellogg's earnings before charges
declined 41 percent in the latest quarter, to 23 cents a share,
matching expectations. The company spent more on promotions and
advertising to stem sales lost to lower-priced brands. Revenue was
flat in the quarter. On a net basis, the company posted a profit
increase. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Now comes still more proof that Bill
Clinton has frightened his opponents into switching teams: This was
the week that the 13 House managers decided to become, of all
things, touchy-feely P.C. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIPP (Undated) _ As the impeachment trial progresses,
historians, pundits and senators are trying to cast President
Clinton and his actions in historical context. No one is doing the
same for Linda Tripp, but perhaps they should. Ms. Tripp has a
historical lineage of her own: the citizen denouncer. By Amy
Waldman. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUVOIR-PARIS (Paris) This is where Simone de Beauvoir lived
and loved, marched and wrote, so Paris is the natural place for
scholars to gather to start celebrating the 50th anniversary of her
seminal feminist book, ``The Second Sex.'' For four days here last
week, they debated Beauvoir with a mixture of joy and reverence,
and at the end, their unsurprising conclusion was that ``The Second
Sex'' was as topical and worthy of study as ever. A perhaps more
pressing reason to raise Beauvoir's voice here was that 13 years
after her death, she is still not a prophet in her own country. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHOLOGY-WAR (Undated) _ The first stone in the war between
Longman and W. W. Norton, the David and Goliath of the anthology
publishing world, has been cast. With the recent publication of
``The Longman Anthology of British Literature,'' Longman has
mounted a challenge to Norton to become the literature anthology of
choice in colleges and universities around the country. By Joyce
Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCANDAL-HISTORY (Salt Lake City) _ Examining the four-year
campaign by Salt Lake City that eventually won it the right to hold
the 2002 Winter Olympic Games. It was an aggressive, highly
organized effort by a city determined not to fail again after
losing the the 1998 winter games by four votes. By Jo Thomas and
Kirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Miami) _ The time has come to lay the cards
on the table. We've done a week's worth of storytelling, laid out
all the Super Bowl nuances, explored the peripheral issues. Now
there is a championship to decide. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-TAGLIABUE (Miami) _ Usually, commissioner Paul
Tagliabue's annual Super Bowl news conference produces few
surprises. But Friday, Tagliabue shocked many at his annual state
of the league address by making a passionate plea to elect former
New York Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor to the Hall of Fame. By
Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-SHARPE (Miami) _ Shannon Sharpe, the Broncos' All-Star
tight end, makes headlines with his provocative comments, but the
real issue is the quality of his play. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-BUCHANAN (Miami) _ Ray Buchanan has made himself
famous in five days, by predicting his team _ the Falcons _ will
win the Super Bowl, by wearing a dog collar to media day, by
getting into an absurd war of words with his verbal counterpart on
the Broncos, Shannon Sharpe. By Charlie Nobles.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-SMITH-JOCKEY (Hallandale, Fla.) _ When last seen riding in a
race, Mike Smith was hurtling through the air from the saddle of a
horse at Saratoga on Aug. 31. He crashed through the hedges lining
the rail, fractured two vertebrae in his upper back and began an
agonizing five-month exile from his career as one of the leading
jockeys in America. By Joseph Durso. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
