<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SANDIEGO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE BEATS SAN DIEGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Jelani Gardner was hyped up. Not just game day,
but all week.
</P>
<P>
   Emotion was a big part of his preparation, and, to his credit,
he realized afterward he allowed his emotion to run too far.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was ejected for a flagrant elbow to Kevin Hanson's jaw
with 2:57 to play, but by then another message was sent and
received.
</P>
<P>
   After being held to seven points by San Diego in the last
meeting, Gardner scored a game-high 19 points as Pepperdine
thrashed the Toreros 72-58 Friday in front of 2,155 at Firestone
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   However, as soon as the final buzzer sounded Gardner headed for
San Diego coach Brad Holland to offer an apology for his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for what I did,'' Gardner said. ``It was the
wrong thing to do, but in the heat of the battle a lot of things
happen. It's no excuse, but if you're watching I probably get hit
like that every time I run a play. But I had no intent of being a
dirty player.''
</P>
<P>
   No question the officials were paying close attention to any
type of physical play. Less than a minute early Gardner and San
Diego's Dana White were assessed double technical fouls after the
Waves' Kelvin Gibbs (13 points, 10 rebounds) was fouled on a layup.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most intriguing and exciting aspect of a game that
was one-sided from tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned many lessons this year, and that's what I've
told this team,'' Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar said. ``This is
another lesson. We lost our composure a little bit, and that just
can't happen, but I don't think we're going to let that overshadow
the effort we gave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've addressed it and it's uncharacteristic of our team to
react that way. The first year I was here we were 6-21 and we
didn't react that way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the only thing Gardner did remotely wrong on what was
otherwise a brilliant night.
</P>
<P>
   He hit 8 of 10 shots from the field, made all three of his
3-point attempts and had two rebounds, two steals and two assists.
Of his five turnovers, many were a result of a fumbled pass.
</P>
<P>
   The performance is customary for what the senior has done since
conference play began.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's led Pepperdine in scoring in six of the seven West
Coast Conference games its played, and is averaging 17.9 points in
league play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come out here and kill these guys because I had my
worst game last (Saturday),'' Gardner said. ``I couldn't think
about anything else all week but coming out here and proving what I
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth straight win for Pepperdine (15-7, 6-1 WCC) also
pushed coach Lorenzo Romar's career mark to 38-38. The third-year
coach, in the midst of rebuilding Pepperdine's tradition, can move
pst .500 for the first time with a win tonight against St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves should be well-rested because it didn't take them long
to put San Diego (12-7, 3-4) away, beating the Toreros in every
facet of the game.
</P>
<P>
   That was on display as Pepperdine used a 17-0 run that lasted
6:15 and enabled the Waves to take a 21-3 lead with 11:01 left in
the first half. San Diego, which went 7:58 without a field goal,
committed eight turnovers and attempted six shots during that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our intensity because if we jump on teams quick we're
a hard team to come back against,'' Gibbs said. ``We killed them in
rebounds the first half (18 to 9) and when we play teams that like
to transition, like us, that's good for us. I don't think there's
any team in this conference that can transition with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
