</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BACKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, ANDERSON PLAY GAME OF TAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For just a moment, forget that Sunday's Super Bowl is
(begin italic) the biggest football game in the world. (end
italic).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, think of it as a game of tag. That's what it will seem
like for defenders on both teams trying to catch Denver's Terrell
Davis or contain Atlanta's Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Let George Sefcik explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing tag around a tree when you were a kid,''
Atlanta's offensive coordinator said this week. ``If you're on one
side and the tree is your blocker, and if you can get the tagger to
lean around to one side, you're gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what trying to tackle Terrell and Jamal can be like,''
Sefcik said. ``They both have great vision. They both have great
balance. They both have great quickness. And just because a play is
called one way, that doesn't mean they'll end up running that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two guys are extremely good at playing tag.''
</P>
<P>
   It might sound simplistic, but it won't be simple for the
opposing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   To upset Denver, the Falcons must at least slow down the runaway
yardage machine that Davis has been. To defend their title, the
Broncos cannot allow Anderson to gobble up large chunks of yards
and the scoreboard clock at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   No one ran for more yards in the regular season than Davis, who
became only the fourth player in NFL history to crack the
2,000-yard barrier. The only one who ran for more yards than
Anderson (1,846) was Davis.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first Super Bowl in history matching the leading rusher
in the AFC against the leading rusher in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   In the playoffs, Davis has been even better, averaging 183 yards
in two games and 6.9 yards per carry. Anderson was held to 67 yards
in the NFC title game two weeks ago, but it was the Minnesota
Vikings' insistence on stopping him that helped quarterback Chris
Chandler become almost unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Anderson. Anderson and Davis. They have been on a
collision course all season.
</P>
<P>
   They come at a defense in different ways, creating different
problems. Davis is more of a slasher who can confound a defense by
cutting back behind his blockers. The 234-pound Anderson is more
powerful, pounding away and wearing down a defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each brings something that is equally difficult to stop,''
said Broncos defensive end Neil Smith, who played against Anderson
last year but also has played against Davis while with the Kansas
City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get a few more people around Jamal to stop him
because he has a low center of gravity,'' Smith said. ``But to stop
Terrell, you have to get to him. He's very good at not allowing
that to happen until he's past the line of scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   Incomparable, and difficult to compare. That's Davis and
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S BEHIND THEM
</P>
<P>
   Their backgrounds couldn't be more different.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, each was a low-round draft choice _ Anderson the 201st
player selected in 1994; Davis the 196th pick in 1995. Yes, each
grew up in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   But their formative years were like comparing Wonder Bread and
stale crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's father, a retired police officer, was a bodyguard for
Muhammad Ali, Richard Pryor and Diana Ross, among others, and now
is chief of security for Mike Tyson. Ali was in the waiting room
the day Jamal was born, and Anderson remembers Sugar Ray Leonard
singing at one of his birthday parties. Anderson and his brothers
used to perform skits for the guests at the barbecues his father
would host for his celebrity friends.
</P>
<P>
   Just your typical childhood. Yeah, right, says the engaging grin
that spreads across Anderson's face. He credits growing up around
people who lived in the spotlight for his ease at basking in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I was raised around, most of the time they handled
the media really well and had a great relationship with them,''
Anderson said. ``So I'm just trying to be natural. It's no problem.
I try to have fun with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun is not a word that would be used to describe Davis'
childhood. He doesn't talk about it, but did write about it in his
autobiography, ``Dreams in Motion,'' which was released during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis told a tale of being 9 and having his father hold a gun to
his head to instill toughness in his sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't scared. I knew he wasn't going to kill us,'' Davis
wrote. ``He loved us too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Davis now looks at the world through eyes that
can be dark and distant, while Anderson's dance and dart the way
Ali used to in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S IN FRONT OF THEM
</P>
<P>
   Each has an unbelievable future. But this is more about what is
immediately before them: Their contrasting offensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos come at a defense with the smallest offensive line
in the league, but also one of the most athletic. They attempt to
get a defender out of position or off balance, allowing Davis to
slice behind the mismatch and be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they try to push you one way, you immediately have to get
back on the other side because Terrell's going to read it,'' said
Falcons free safety Eugene Robinson, who played against the Broncos
in last year's Super Bowl while with the Packers. ``Last year, we
couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis ran for 157 yards and three touchdowns in the Broncos'
upset of the defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' line is bigger and more traditional. They are
looking to capture ground by exploding off the line and into
defenders. Then comes Anderson, running behind those big ``trees''
and daring you to tag him.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT KEEPS THEM GOING
</P>
<P>
   It's called motivation, and each has it by the gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Davis. He rushed for 1,750 yards last season and was
then MVP in the Super Bowl. This season? The 2,008 yards. The 23
touchdowns. The league MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play this game,'' Davis said. ``I don't try to
compare myself year to year. I go out there to clean the slate and
do something not totally different, but stick with the same game
plan. Doing the little things, it helps the bigger picture come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson ran for 1,000 yards in each of the past two seasons.
But this season, he set an NFL record with 410 carries, nearly
doubled his rushing output from 1996 and 1997 combined and scored
more touchdowns (14) than he totaled in his first four seasons with
the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading this magazine before the season where they
listed the Top 25 players in the league,'' Anderson said. ``I was
like No. 70. They had the Top 25 running backs. I was like No. 22.
I'm like, `Come on, guys. There are 21 running backs in this league
who are better than me? I don't think so.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I read and hear stuff like that and I love those little
motivating tidbits from extra-smart critics,'' he said. ``I'm
always out to prove somebody wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
