</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY NOT AT JORDAN'S EXIT DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There are plenty of differences between John Elway and
Michael Jordan, but let's start with the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Elway is not the barometer, pulse, heart, mind, body, soul,
marketing force or best player ever to play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   To the NBA, to the game of basketball, Jordan was all of that.
He was maybe even more than all of that, which we will all find out
starting this coming Friday, when the NBA ``season'' begins.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jordan, Elway is not even universally considered to be
the best at his position. Just this week, even Elway listed Dan
Marino, Johnny Unitas and Roger Staubach as his top three all-time
NFL QBs. Other than Marty Schottenheimer, who said Elway might be
the best QB ever, most football gurus merely listed Elway among the
top with Joe Montana, Unitas, Marino and Sammy Baugh.
</P>
<P>
   The point is: If Elway wins a second consecutive Super Bowl on
Sunday, why would he walk away from the game?
</P>
<P>
   Could he walk away, considering what dangles out there?
</P>
<P>
   No quarterback has ever won three straight Super Bowls. No team
has ever done it. And if it were at all possible to summon the
strength and determination to slog through a 17th season, Elway
would be in a position to elevate his status, perhaps so that he
eclipses all the others.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying it would be easy. But it is enough to wonder if a
competitive son of a quarterback like Elway could really walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll be back, too,'' Elway told offensive coordinator
Gary Kubiak after the Broncos' AFC win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the door is open slightly more now,'' coach Mike
Shanahan said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Elways sees the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   And just maybe Falcons coach Dan Reeves did Elway a favor this
Super Bowl. Maybe by opening the old wounds and talking about their
embattled Bronco days, Reeves has steered some attention away from
a Super Bowl story line that says Elway, after Sunday, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Signs certainly do point to that: The victory lap at Mile High
Stadium two weeks ago; the talk among his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something about Elway this past week that seemed
to hint that perhaps he is more ambivalent about this decision.
</P>
<P>
   He won't talk about retirement, mostly because he does not want
to detract from the team or the game. But perhaps he understands
that there are as many good reasons for him to stay another year as
there are reasons for him to call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, while Elway must think first of his family and his own
health _ both things he wants to spend more time attending to _ he
does not have to grapple with the same issues Jordan had to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   Let's refresh our memories as to why it was perfect for Jordan
to retire at this exact time:
</P>
<P>
   A. Jordan's league was in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   B. Jordan had already won two three-peats.
</P>
<P>
   C. Jordan had secured his sixth championship with the
game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   D. Jordan had long battled with his owner and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   E. Jordan's coach was no longer employed by the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   F. While claiming to be physically capable _ despite a cigar-cut
tendon in his finger _ Jordan said his mental energy had been
drained away, and, most important . . .
</P>
<P>
   G. Jordan had to leave a pretty, unspoiled, pristine last
impression.
</P>
<P>
   Elway does not have to worry about this. Already, Elway's skills
have slipped. The image of him is of a great athlete on the
downside of his career. Even he admits it.
</P>
<P>
   While a somewhat unsavory suggestion, Elway has heard the talk
that Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde was better than Elway in the
AFC championship game. Elway has heard talk that Falcons
quarterback Chandler is playing better than Elway
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we win, I don't care about quarterback ratings,''
Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   As for everything else surrounding Elway's decision, he has no
other reason to go, except if his body is too broken down or he is
too eager to spend time with his family. (Maybe Elway should wait
and talk to Jordan about the intricacies of car pooling and making
peanut butter and jelly sandwiches for the kids. It's not all it's
cracked up to be, at least not for more than two or three months.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Elway has a perfect relationship with his owner, who is
apparently considering offering Elway part ownership of the team.
Elway has a best friendship with head coach Mike Shanahan. He has a
team surrounding him that is, at least at this moment, poised to
make a run at football's grandest title: Dynasty. He has a
2,000-yard running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Terrell Davis has made me a genius,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe Elway does not have to go that far. But Elway does
grasp what an incredible situation he is in.
</P>
<P>
   After three disastrous Super Bowl losses that made it seem as if
he might have to leave the game with a sense of regret or failure,
Elway now is on the cusp of one of sport's most inspired
turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos were to lose Sunday, fine, he can still walk away
proud. Elway has made his donation to sports history with the
scrambling and the comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Broncos were to win a second consecutive Super Bowl,
who could blame or deny Elway if he woke up Monday morning with a
craving for a third?
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
