<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-LIPSYTE-NYT     01-30 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-LIPSYTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FROM TRIAL BALLOON TO PART OF THE NATION'S FABRIC  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Super Bowl may indeed be the quintessence of American boys
behaving badly, but it has never pretended to be anything else.
Because it is the national holy day of a secular religion linked to
illegal gambling, domestic violence, steroid abuse and
institutional racism, it is beyond scandal and star-fall. We should
be particularly grateful in these days of Olympic disgrace and pro
basketball depression.
</P>
<P>
   I began appreciating the Super Bowl 30 years ago, at what was
then called the American Football League-National Football League
world championship. An evening before the game, I was offered a
glimpse into the future if I promised to keep it in ``deep
background.'' Even more easily seducible then, I soon found myself
rocking gently on a luxurious yacht, drinking with Commissioner
Pete Rozelle and several owners.
</P>
<P>
   Rozelle took me aside, murmured of his concerns that pro
football was becoming too big too quickly, too intrinsic to the
national fabric. Could it sustain? He was as serious as any head of
state dreaming of an empire. He went on to leak the legend, which
he would soon share with everyone, that the term ``Super Bowl,''
then coming into vogue, had been coined by the son of the Kansas
City Chiefs' owner, Lamar Hunt, who was playing with a high-bouncer
called ``the super ball.'' Rozelle, the public relations master,
told this story with such elaborate reluctance that, in retrospect,
it is clear he was releasing a trial balloon he figured the news
media would either shoot down or claim to have sent up.
</P>
<P>
   As New York fans were reminded recently, that game,
retroactively called Super Bowl III, helped bring us into this rich
new Jock Pop world in which the Olympics became just another
super-spectacle competing for the entertainment dollar and short
white men made hoopla dreams come true. I wish I had been smart
enough that balmy night off Miami Beach to see that the fix was
already in, that these guys knew what they were doing. The NFL and
its Super Bowl were about franchising and marketing, about cities
desperate to appear ``major league,'' about cars and beer for
18-to-34-year-old male viewers who needed to watch mostly faceless
big guys whomp the cartilage out of one another. This was a boy's
dream of studly quarterbacks and their loyal meatball guards,
``Braveheart'' without the blue paint, 60-minute wars without women
or the responsibilities of peace. And it was all under the benign
fatherhood of intense coaches who would make them men.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the Olympics and the National Basketball Association
started to scramble.
</P>
<P>
   Since the olive oil payoffs of ancient Greece (winners got sales
franchises despite the amateur rules), the Olympics have been a
model of hypocrisy, continually bending their own rules for the
sake of business. All was justified for the survival of a
``movement'' that was supposedly larger than nationalism. The
Olympics fed on nationalistic rivalry, especially when it could be
televised.
</P>
<P>
   This is why it is so hard not to enjoy certain aspects of the
current bribery scandal (which will turn out to be far more
systemic than first reported) in much the way that agnostics
enjoyed the fall of those television preachers who always knew so
much about sin.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics lost its last claim to specialness in 1992, when it
opened its arms to the Dream Team, the NBA's Roman legion, which
claimed the world in ways that even the late Commissioner Rozelle
probably envied. Basketball is more portable and exportable than
football, but perhaps more fragile. All its players have faces.
Because individual stars become larger than the game itself, the
game is more dependent on them. The process of replacing Michael
Jordan (perhaps by a whole team, a rookie class or the redemption
of Latrell Sprewell) has already begun, but until it is complete
the game will be in recession. But the Super Bowl, with its red
meat soul, its aroma of beer, cigars and new car leather seats,
prospers and rumbles on.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal football betting, from office pools to serious gambling,
has become intrinsic to the national fabric. The only important
players who were ever suspended for an entire season, Paul Hornung
and Alex Karras, were punished because they bet on games, giving
the appearance of being inside traders. The nastiest backlash I've
ever had from a story was when I offered anecdotal evidence from
hot-lines and women's shelters that big games, such as the Super
Bowl, provoked male-on-female domestic violence. Right-wing
commentators in particular seemed incensed at this assault on
American manhood.
</P>
<P>
   That every level of the game encourages football players to use
anabolic steroids and other drugs that enhance performance, build
muscle mass or aid strenuous training is no longer even
interesting; fascinating will be how the pharmaceutical companies,
in their rush to cash in on the current men's health boom, will use
the game's image of manhood to market drugs. The continuing, almost
perverse, refusal to promote black coaches seems like a
one-industry refutation of a century of progress. So does the
pigskin curtain on what seems like an epidemic of players with
police records. Is it the drugs, a shared psychological profile of
player and felon or a sense that the super ball has just bounced
out of sight of everyday morality?
</P>
<P>
   Beats me. All I know is that Sunday I will be grateful and pay
homage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 0932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-FALCONS-NYT     01-30 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-FALCONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A LONG JOURNEY, CHANDLER FINDS SUCCESS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Atlanta Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler was outside a
restaurant here this week when some autograph-seekers began
sticking small pieces of paper in his face. While Chandler politely
signed, one man watching the scene from several feet away, stared
with a puzzled look. Finally, he asked, ``Who are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the pinnacle of what has been, until now, a mostly
nondescript career, Chandler is not a household face, especially in
a Super Bowl in which he is facing the future Hall of Famer, John
Elway, in what most believe is Elway's final season.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why Chandler can blend into a crowd. With
thinning hair and the look of a man on the street, he seems more
like someone who plays pickup games than a quarterback going to his
second consecutive Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the season, when it counted the most, Chandler
was playing as well as any quarterback in the game _ and better
than Elway. Chandler was the offensive player of the month for
December after his 118.6 passer rating helped the Falcons go 4-0 in
the month and he finished the season with a rating of 100.9, fourth
highest in the league. Elway was one spot behind him with a rating
of 93.0.
</P>
<P>
   The defining moment of Chandler's career _ at least to this
point _ came two weeks ago in the National Football Conference
title game against the Minnesota Vikings. In overtime, the
more-heralded Randall Cunningham seemed jittery, but Chandler
showed no sign of nervousness. He completed passes of 15, 26 and 6
yards on a 70-yard, 10-play drive that set up the game-winning
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that game people were always asking me, `Do you have
anything to prove?''' Chandler said this week. ``I thought the only
thing I had to prove was that I could take a team on my back. That
last drive really helped me, confidence-wise. I think it changed my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Life has been good for Chandler in many ways this season. Three
days after the Falcons won the conference championship, his wife,
Diane, gave birth to their third daughter, Brynn Brodie Chandler.
(Diane is the daughter of the former San Francisco 49ers
quarterback John Brodie.) In September, Chandler signed a
five-year, $27 million contract that guaranteed him $8.3 million
this season. And a week after the Super Bowl, Chandler will become
the first Falcon quarterback to play in consecutive Pro Bowls since
Steve Bartkowski in the 1980 and 1981 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely on a roll right now that doesn't happen very
often to anybody,'' said Chandler. ``The way the season has gone,
just having a beautiful baby girl and then the Super Bowl. Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   His football career, though, has not always been a fairy tale.
It has more closely resembled a train wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Tennessee Oilers traded Chandler to the
Falcons for the low price of fourth- and sixth-round draft choices.
That swap may go down as one of the most lopsided trades ever,
although it was not seen that way at the time. The Oilers had Steve
McNair, a young and talented player, and Chandler was seen as
expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons Coach Dan Reeves did not think he had acquired a star
player either. Reeves thought Chandler would be a stopgap until the
Falcons were able to draft a young thrower.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was definitely underrated by me,'' Reeves said. ``I had no
idea he was as good a football player as he is. He's been a great
fit for us because he loves what we do offensively and we construct
a game plan around what he does well.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Falcons throw a lot of deep passes, something
Chandler excels at.
</P>
<P>
   Still, until this season, Chandler had always been seen as a
mediocre player. At one point in his career he played on five teams
in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was taken as a third-round draft choice out of the
University of Washington by the Indianapolis Colts in 1988 and won
the starting job as a rookie, but he has never stuck with a team
for as long as three seasons. After two seasons with the Colts, he
went from Tampa Bay to Arizona to the Los Angeles Rams to Houston
to the Falcons. Along the way, he has taken a beating from head to
toe, with at least three severe concussions and  &UR;  &LR; several knee
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   He also ran into competition from quarterbacks who were
considered better. With the Colts it was Jeff George; with the
Buccaneers it was Vinny Testaverde; with the Oilers it was McNair.
With &UR;  &LR; Tampa Bay, Chandler began the 1990 season as the starter, but
the Buccaneers went 0-6 while he threw 14 interceptions and only 5
touchdowns. He was benched in favor of Testaverde and soon found
himself inactive for most games as the No. 3 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably one of the worst times of my career,''
Chandler said. ``I wasn't sure where my career was headed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the NFL was mostly political,'' he said. ``It was
discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late 1991, Chandler was traded to the Cardinals, where
he came under the tutelage of quarterbacks coach Jerry Rhome, whom
Chandler credits with turning his career around. Rhome took a
bitter, discouraged quarterback and began working on improving his
mechanics and decision-making. The two watched hours of film
together, with Rhome pointing out what was good and bad about his
throws. In a matter of months, Chandler was reading defenses better
than he ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, instead of wasting precious seconds overanalyzing in the
pocket, Chandler was making quick decisions and throws. He became a
different quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris' biggest problem used to be he would outthink himself,''
Rhome said earlier this season. ``He played golf the same way. He'd
stand over the ball and say: `OK, it's 200 yards to the hole. The
wind is blowing 200 miles an hour to the right. There's a tree
branch hanging over.' I'd finally scream, `Just hit the darn ball.'
Same in football. If you see it and feel it, just throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Chandler has done with the Falcons. He is 17-4 in
games he has started and finished the last two years. This season,
he recorded career highs in passing yards (3,154) and touchdowns
(25) while throwing only 14 interceptions. In two playoff games, he
performed better, completing 40 of 62 passes for 509 yards, with 3
touchdowns and 1 interception. By contrast, Elway completed only 27
of 57 passes for 355 yards with 2 touchdowns and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has this been a dream season?'' Chandler asked. ``Well, we
have one more step to climb before I can really answer that
question.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does win the ultimate game, maybe his face will start to
stick out in a crowd.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
