<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-KICKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER KICKERS HAVE A HUNCH IT COULD COME DOWN TO THEM  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One is probably headed for nomination to the Hall of
Fame. The other has a shoe that will be going to the Hall of Fame.
That's just one of the striking differences between the
place-kickers in Sunday's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons' Morten Andersen also uses a custom-made
shoe for his field-goal attempts that cost $5,000 just to develop.
The Denver Broncos' Jason Elam relies on a 10-year-shoe that sold
for $8.99.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, in his 17th season, has an NFL-record 26 career
game-winning field goals, including the 38-yarder against Minnesota
that put the Falcons in the Super Bowl; Elam has 6.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Elam, a sixth-year pro, will be represented in the Hall of
Fame before Andersen. After next week's Pro Bowl, he will ship his
aging kicking shoe to Canton, Ohio, in recognition of his league
record-tying 63-yard field goal last October against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   It has been eight seasons since a Super Bowl was decided by a
field goal or a missed attempt, and there has been only one other
field goal-deciding game in the Super Bowl's 32-year history.
Still, Elam believes it may well happen on Sunday, especially with
the forecast of a 50 percent chance of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're pretty close in talent all the way around,'' he
said. ``I don't think we're going to blow them out, and I don't see
them blowing us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Off this season's work, it's difficult to choose between the
two. Elam has made 27 of 31 field-goal attempts, including all four
of his tries in the post-season. Andersen is 28 of 33, including 5
of 5 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Both are deep into the mental side of handling the highs and
lows of being an NFL kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen said he seeks to practice in such a precise manner that
his training becomes a ``dominant response.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to rehearse so much that it becomes natural out there,''
he said. ``You remove all the variables _ remove all pressure and
everything you can't control _ and just focus on what you can
control. On the field, I let my skill take over. I try to kick
freely, meaning my mind is not cluttered. I'm just reacting, just
being.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam, a native Georgian and a childhood Falcons fan, said an
Atlanta sports psychologist has helped him grasp the mental part of
his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a golfer,'' he said. ``You always have the
same little routine. There are all kinds of thoughts that can creep
into your head, so you try to keep those under control. And you
don't want to get caught up in the moment. I'd say kicking is
probably 90 percent mental.''
</P>
<P>
   Both have a healthy reverence for the damage a game-deciding
field goal miss can wreak.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen had trouble forgetting the 1996 miss that ended
Atlanta's season and catapulted Jacksonville into the playoffs.
Elam said he was still upset about an overtime miss against the
Raiders five seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Self-effacing remarks can help. Andersen said he is the answer
to a trivia question: Name a kicker who has made a 60-yard field
goal and missed a 19-yarder?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you've got to take the good with the bad,'' he said.
``You've got to study your history, so you don't repeat it. As
athletes, we don't need a lot of mental luggage. I try not to carry
a lot of kicks around with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam remembers the words of the former kicker Matt Bahr: The joy
of making a game-winning kick doesn't remotely compare to the
prolonged agony of missing one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can drive yourself crazy if you don't watch it,'' Elam
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both have plenty of empathy for the Vikings' Gary Anderson,
whose only field-goal miss of the season, in overtime against
Atlanta, cost them a Super Bowl trip.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen and Elam also are aware of Super Bowl history. How
Baltimore's Jim O'Brien won the 1971 game with a 32-yarder, and how
Scott Norwood's wide right 47-yarder cost Buffalo a victory over
the Giants in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, a Pro Bowler at the time, soon faded out of the league.
``You wonder if he had made that kick if he would still be kicking
today,'' Elam said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson noted that Elam, 10 years his junior at 28, has a
wonderful temperament, especially for a kicker still in his 20s.
``He doesn't take himself too seriously and he's able to laugh some
things off. He has a nice dose of self-confidence, but also a nice
dose of self-irony.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen said a trip to Nepal just five years ago with his
father _ he saw how calm the natives were _ helped him learn to
have more inner peace. And patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kicker spends 97 percent of his time on the sidelines,'' he
said. ``The way he uses that time on the sidelines is crucial to
his success or failure on the field. I let the game play me. I
don't try to force anything. I just patiently wait.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
