</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-DEBT-REVIEW-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: Security system. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Reducing the federal debt to the public at this stage is
unquestionably the most important thing that I believe that we can
do if meeting the future needs of the economy is the standard,''
said Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan last week.
</P>
<P>
   To some people there is also a moral dimension to the issue.
Debt, in their view, is just plain wrong, an obligation that needs
to be paid off as soon as possible, whether it is owed by a farmer,
a company or the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the abstract we think of it as fiscal sin,'' said Robert
Reischauer, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, quickly
adding that ``rather than repent we charge yet again.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is on the political level that the issue gets messiest.
</P>
<P>
   While members of both parties pledge allegiance to austerity and
the long-term benefits it promises, history suggests that the
short-term drive to survive the next election leads to some degree
