<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIOLENT-CRIME-NYT     01-30 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIOLENT-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL POLICY ADDRESSES VIOLENT CRIME BY PLAYERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In recent months the National Football League,
embarrassed by its players being involved in violent episodes, has
been zealously enforcing its new policy on violent crimes. While
critics at first said the policy was nothing more than a
public-relations move, it turns out that the program has teeth, and
some players believe it could significantly curb the violent acts
committed by players.
</P>
<P>
   There have been about a dozen violence-related arrests of NFL
players in the last year, and almost all of those players have been
ordered to undergo counseling, according to team officials. And for
the first time, a player was fined by the league after an attack.
</P>
<P>
   The policy applies not only to players, but to any league
employee. A small number of team front-office personnel, as well as
coaches, have undergone counseling as part of the program, said
team officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The policy began in earnest last July 1 as a way to combat what
seemed to be an increasing number of problems involving players and
violence off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, any player who is arrested for a violent
crime, must be evaluated to see if anger-management counseling is
necessary. In most cases, players receive such counseling.
</P>
<P>
   If the player is convicted of the crime, or makes a plea
bargain, the player is fined by Commissioner Paul Tagliabue. The
amount of the fine is up to Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner has wide latitude to define what violent crime
is, but it generally includes assault, domestic violence and
weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   One of the players who has received counseling under the program
is Cornelius Bennett, the Atlanta Falcons linebacker who will play
in Super Bowl XXXIII on Sunday night. Bennett pleaded guilty last
year to sexual abuse and served a 35-day jail term. Because
Bennett's crime occurred before the implementation of the policy,
he was not fined by the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the policy is a very good one,'' Bennett said this
week. ``I think it will truly keep some guys in line. Fine guys,
suspend them, and get them help, and the crimes will stop, or at
least be reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   The only player to be fined in the seven months since the policy
became active is Keith Poole, a wide receiver with the New Orleans
Saints. In November, he was sentenced to two-months' probation for
attacking a man with a golf club. Earlier this month, Tagliabue
fined Poole $4,500, according to team officials. If Poole is found
guilty in another violent incident, he could be fined a more
substantial amount and suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Other players, already receiving counseling, could be fined in
the coming weeks if they are found guilty or reach a plea bargain
in pending cases.
</P>
<P>
   On average, according to team officials, 10 to 12 players are
arrested each year for violent crimes, ranging from bar fights to
domestic violence. Often, charges are dropped for a variety of
reasons, but a player who has been required to undergo counseling
would have to continue it.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Henderson, the league's executive vice president of labor
relations, and Lem Burnham, its vice president of player and
employee development, oversee the policy.
</P>
<P>
   One criticism of the program is that the league does not
publicize it enough. Players need to be reminded about it
constantly, some team officials feel.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of training camps this season, the league put
information about the policy into the playbook of each player.
League officials also met with every team to explain how the policy
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violent crime policy is something that players pay
attention to,'' Bennett said. ``It seems to have gotten the
attention of a lot of players. I hope it stays that way. Maybe it
will keep some guys from getting into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Assistants Seek Benefits &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Early last year at an NFL-sponsored coaching symposium in Miami,
a small group of assistant coaches staged a walkout, protesting
what they felt were declining life-style conditions for the
hundreds of assistants who compose the bulk of the league's staffs.
Tagliabue called the protest ``silly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the walkout may have been effective after all. It
gave the coaches publicity, and let owners know they were serious.
Now, months later, assistant coaches and owners are on the verge of
an agreement that would give the coaches, some of whom are at the
bottom of the football food chain, some much needed security.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League Coaches Association, headed by the
long-time assistant coach Larry Kennan, has been fighting for
better medical benefits and a more reasonable retirement age for
the 400 assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Kennan has been negotiating directly with members of the
league's benefits committee, and Kennan said he is hopeful an
agreement can be reached in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks that way, but I'm not going to count on anything
being done until it's done,'' he said. ``The best I can say is we
dealt with them in a professional manner. I think they wanted us to
go away, but we weren't going to do that. But also, there are some
fair-minded owners who wanted to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Most head coaches are millionaires with long-term contracts, and
if they are fired, they still get paid. There are also highly-paid
assistant coaches like the Jets' Bill Belichick, who can earn
$200,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of the assistants earn much less and usually do not
have long-term contracts. Some make as little as $20,000 a year,
and it is not unusual for as assistant to be fired twice in five
years. It is these assistants, Kennan said, who need to have a
voice.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kennan, the highlights of the coaches association's
latest proposal include:
</P>
<P>
   _The lowering of the age at which an assistant can claim a
pension. The current age is 65, and though neither side will say
what the new age will be, it could end up anywhere from 50 to 60.
</P>
<P>
   _Improved medical coverage and standardized health care.
Coverage now varies from team to team, with some programs being
good and others quite inadequate, according to the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   _A standard coach's contract, similar to the one given players.
Contracts for assistants also differ between teams, coaches say,
and again some are better than others.
</P>
<P>
   _Severance pay. Kennan said game officials, for example, are
paid a year's salary if they are fired, while assistant coaches are
not.
</P>
<P>
   There are potential problems, and the progress the two sides
have made could evaporate. Still, the coaches have established
themselves as a formidable bargaining entity and the NFL, to its
credit, is recognizing that some things need to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Upshaw Foresight Credited &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If a poll were taken of players regarding Gene Upshaw, executive
director of the National Football League Players Association, his
approval ratings would be sky-high. After watching professional
basketball players go through a destructive lockout, football
players have been privately thanking Upshaw for avoiding any major
conflict with the owners over the last collective bargaining
agreement, signed last year.
</P>
<P>
   This coming season, the salary cap will increase $5 million to
$57.5 million a team, which means more money for players. That is
another reason they are happy with Upshaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-BRONCOS-NYT     01-30 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS' COMMITMENT CAME FROM CELEBRATION  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Twelve months ago, the Denver Broncos had been Super
Bowl champions for a matter of minutes when, in the midst of the
celebration, Coach Mike Shanahan warned them of how difficult it
would be to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded our guys there is only one chance to get back to
the Super Bowl, and that is to have a better off-season workout
program than we did the year before,'' Shanahan recalled this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Broncos will be playing for a second consecutive
championship in Super Bowl XXXIII. Just to get to that point,
Shanahan said, players had to come to training camp with ``a sense
of urgency, some resolve that we weren't there as Super Bowl
champs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there as a team that was unproven and the one thing
that mattered is what we did this year _ not what we had done in
the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The off-season weight-lifting program was the start; more
players attended it than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, they have been on a mission. Much of Shanahan's
efforts have been geared to learning why teams do not repeat, and
what must happen for that rare twin to be accomplished. Only six
teams have repeated as Super Bowl champion, the last being Dallas
five years ago. No team has ever won three straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of focus,'' suggested Ed Donatell, the coach of
the Broncos' defensive backs. Like all the other position coaches
on the defending champions, he spent time with his players
discussing the philosophy of how you return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you win, everyone's after you,'' Donatell said. ``We talk
about it in our room all the time _ great teams keep getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Broncos see it, the fact that they did not go undefeated
has actually helped them, has positioned them to win this Super
Bowl. They won their first 13 games of the season. Then they lost
on the road to the Giants and at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The undefeated season was wearing on this team,'' Donatell
said. ``But the road losses refocused us. Personally, I wouldn't
want to have come here unscathed. I'd rather it doesn't come up in
a playoff situation. After we lost to the Giants and Miami, we
said, `Hey, back to the drawing board.'''
</P>
<P>
   This will be Falcons Coach Dan Reeves' ninth Super Bowl as a
player or coach, and his fourth as a head coach. His first three
appearances as a head coach came with the Broncos, all losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys forget the price they had to pay to get back,'' Reeves
said. ``I think it's a lot easier for a losing team to get there.
Winning teams forget. Mike's done a great job to get the Broncos
there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested to Shanahan, he has an advantage this year over
Reeves. His team has been there, and the Falcons have not been to
the playoffs since the 1995 season and have never been to the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say it's an advantage,'' said Shanahan, whose
Broncos faced a Green Bay team that was trying to repeat last year.
``Some people said we were at a disadvantage last year against
Green Bay, and that made us a little hungrier. When you talk about
those things, it comes down to how you play on Sunday. If you've
been there, or haven't been there, all that's thrown out to me.''
</P>
<P>
   John Elway is back for a fifth Super Bowl. Elway, who is
expected to retire after this season, returned for a back-to-back
attempt. He even wanted to retire before last year's Super Bowl. In
the week before the conference championship game last season, he
held a vote at the dinner table. Should he play in 1998? He voted
no, but was overruled by his wife, Janet, and their four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' he said, ``I can never get my wife and kids in
the same place. They're always out. So there will be no vote _ and
no absentee ballots.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
