<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      01-30 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCH THEM IF YOU CAN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant is not going anywhere for at least five years,
remaining with the Lakers in Los Angeles until at least 2003. The
same goes for Allen Iverson in Philadelphia, Shareef Abdur-Rahim in
Vancouver and Antoine Walker in Boston. The rash of young stars
signing lucrative extensions with their original teams has curbed
player movement and may signal a new era in the National Basketball
Association _ one with fewer monster deals but more permanence on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly how Commissioner David Stern and the National
Basketball Association owners had hoped the new collective
bargaining agreement would work _ and exactly how player agents
hoped it would not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that Antoine Walker, Allen Iverson, Zydrunas
Ilgauskas, Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Kobe will be staying with their
teams is something very positive,'' Stern said on Friday. ``The
movement that tends to occur at that age is not happening, and
that's immediate dividends for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not talking about how much more Allen Iverson and
Antoine Walker could have gotten,'' Stern added. ``They're talking
about signing the largest contracts in the history of the 76ers and
Celtics.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's no doubt that Kobe, Iverson, Walker and
Shareef lost considerable dollars under this deal, it just can't be
disputed,'' said Bryant's agent, Arn Tellem, after the 20-year-old
signed a six-year, $70 million extension with the Lakers. ``I don't
think the money they've lost has shifted to the middle class. It's
remained in the owners' pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a big-picture perspective, they're just fine,'' he added.
``But there's no doubt that they're getting less than what the
market will bear for their services.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant joined Iverson, Abdur-Rahim and Walker _ the first, third
and sixth picks in 1996 _ and the Cavaliers' Ilgauskas in receiving
enormous deals since the opening of camps last week. All signed
six-year contracts worth a reported $71 million, the maximum
allowed under the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But lost in the shuffle are a few players who cannot possibly
receive their fair market value: Jimmy Jackson, Dennis Rodman and
Rod Strickland, unsigned veterans hoping to hook on with a team.
</P>
<P>
   Because teams have few exceptions to offer, Kevin Johnson and
Rodman may have to retire. Many teams with salary-cap room spent
most of their money on one player, causing a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   After Houston acquired Scottie Pippen from Chicago in a
sign-and-trade deal, Charles Barkley was forced to play for the $1
million exception in Houston with the hope that he will be
compensated in a year. The acquisition of Vlade Divac in Sacramento
forced Corliss Williamson to play for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   While several middle-class players have benefited from the deal
_ Matt Geiger got a $54 million windfall from the 76ers and Charlie
Ward and Chris Dudley signed close to $30 million deals with the
Knicks _ guys like Sherman Douglas are still looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Williams for Alderman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams never understood why his peers holed up in their
hotel rooms and avoided the masses when they could have been trying
out new material on fans. He paraded around Manhattan during the
All-Star weekend last February as if he was running for office.
During the lockout, he was a one-man media conglomerate, appearing
on network and cable television and any 1,000-watt radio station
that had an antenna.
</P>
<P>
   His message: We need to think about our fans before ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the league has finally taken his lead. A kinder,
gentler NBA is emerging from the lockout. If it's not the free
scrimmages and the subsequent autograph sessions, it's the players
passing out signed basketballs before preseason games. In Portland,
Rasheed Wallace and teammates gave away hot dogs for an hour behind
a concession stand.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how long the goodwill will last and
whether or not it's merely designed to win fans back after the
messy labor dispute. But it's a drastic change from the slew of
scorned kids who chased athletes to their cars and through the team
hotels to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond strengthening the drug agreement, the N.B.A. has
implemented several marketing strategies to improve the league's
relations with its fans. Aside from an ``I Still Love This Game''
ad campaign, a few surprises are still expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sensitive to closing up the heretofore wide gap
between players and fans,'' David Stern said. ``The union and the
league felt it was time for the players to stress responsibility
and commitment to their teams and fans. Watching the players the
past few weeks has been as encouraging as watching the fans'
reaction to the open scrimmages. I suppose the fair question to ask
us is, `What took you so long?' Well, we knew this issue was coming
and we've tried to take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, incidentally, donated $20,000 of his new contract to
workers at Continental Arena Friday night during halftime of the
Nets preseason game with the Knicks. It was his way of saying
thanks to the parking attendants, concessionaires and ushers at the
arena.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Man of His Word &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Buck Williams' good name prevents him from pulling a Rodman,
retiring and unretiring within a span of 24 hours. But the 17-year
veteran, who said goodbye to the NBA and the Knicks during a
touching press conference on Wednesday, actually had a chance to
play for someone other than the Knicks this season.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone asked Williams through intermediaries to come to
Utah and play for the pro-rated, mid-level exception salary of
$1.75 million. The Jazz, in its quest to win a title, needed a
decent veteran off the bench after the loss of Antoine Carr via
free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have known about that before I retired, I might
have given it a little more consideration,'' Williams said. ``But I
gave my word.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Around the League &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Elden Campbell and Eddie Jones have seemingly been going
everywhere the past few weeks, except staying with the Lakers. The
newest rumor is Orlando, where Horace Grant would become expendable
if Dennis Rodman decides to play for the $1 million exception.
Since that may not happen, the Lakers are still shopping the two
players to Charlotte and Miami ... Vinny Del Negro is close to
signing a multi-year deal with Milwaukee... LaPhonso Ellis is
leaning toward signing for a mid-level exception in Atlanta ...
Talk about Knick curiosity: Latrell Sprewell's debut at Madison
Square Garden received a 4.1 rating on the MSG Network, meaning 4.1
percent of all television households were tuned in to the preseason
game with the Nets. The average regular-season rating for a game is
around 2.4.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-DAVIS-NYT &LR;      01-30 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS MAKES LATE PICKS PROUD  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI, Jan. 30 _ Terrell Davis, like Jamal Anderson, was nearly
a forgotten man when his time arrived for the National Football
League draft. Anderson was overlooked in 1994 _ 200 players were
selected before him. And the following year, Davis lasted until the
sixth round and was the 196th player chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal was in the same situation, and to come in from a late
draft pick and and do the things that we're doing right now, it's
great,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to go out there and play well so that people
that are drafted in the late rounds aren't discouraged about coming
into this league. At least they know that even if they are drafted
late, they can come in and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Contribute?
</P>
<P>
   Few could match Davis's run. Davis, 26, was named most valuable
player of Super Bowl XXXII last year in his hometown of San Diego.
Through 18 games this season he has rushed for a league record
2,374 yards. He has played seven post-season games in his career;
he has rushed for more than 100 yards in each. His playoff average
is a league-record 148.3 rushing yards a game and 5.8 average yards
a carry. He rushed for 199 yards against Miami and 167 against the
Jets in his two playoff games this year.
</P>
<P>
   This guy shows big all the time. He shows even bigger in big
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at any sport, it's imperative that if you want to
put your signature on it, you have to win championships,'' Davis
said. ``That's the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Michael Jordan and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar,'' Davis
added, ``you look at Emmitt Smith, you look at the people that won,
Joe Montana, Jerry Rice, all these people have won championships.
And that's what it takes to really put your signature on the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis played for George Allen at Long Beach State. He struggled
with injuries and struggled proving himself after transferring to
Georgia. But in Denver he has found a home.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dorsett is the player Davis wanted to emulate. And Davis
has begun to do that on and off the field in production and in
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   His dream run in Super Bowl XXXIII?
</P>
<P>
   ``The perfect run would be some sort of dive play,'' he said.
``I break a few tackles and outrun a guy into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, it would be the play to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   No question, Davis could do it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-1STLEDE-     01-30 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-1STLEDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(CORRECTING HEADLINE)  
 STAY-PUT ERA WARMS STERN'S HEART  
 CATCH THEM IF YOU CAN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
