<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PROMOTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMATIC PUPIL PROMOTION: MOTIVATOR OR DETERRENT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Ill)   (bl) 
By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It is not on the standard list of childhood
phobias, but an overblown fear of being kept back and made to
repeat a grade afflicts almost every member of Bonnie Kornblatt's
fourth-grade class at Meredith Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kid worries about it,'' said Diva, a fourth grader who
shakes her short black curls nervously as she contemplates the idea
of retention. ``You wouldn't be with your friends, you'd be with
younger kids. They'd tease you and call you names and think you
weren't smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Right, said Damon, adding: ``I had a friend who got left down
and he said it was really embarrassing. You feel stupid. And my
sister says if you stay back once, you'll never go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear of being kept back is intense these days, and not just in
Ms. Kornblatt's class. Nationwide, many schoolchildren either heard
or heard about President Clinton's State of the Union address in
which he advocated federal financial rewards for schools that end
the policy known as social promotion, or moving children from grade
to grade regardless of their performance.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, like Los Angeles, Chicago and other cities, is
already moving in that direction, adopting tougher standards for
promotion as part of an overall effort to raise academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   But while politicians decry social promotion, many education
experts say the real problem is that huge numbers of children are
already being kept back _ to their detriment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, by the time they are 15 to 17, 40 to 50 percent of
black and Hispanic children, and 25 to 35 percent of white children
are not at the grade you would expect for their age,'' said Robert
Hauser, a University of Wisconsin demographer who was co-editor of
a recent National Academy of Sciences report on testing and
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our report finds that all the available evidence shows that
retention leads to lower academic achievement and increases the
likelihood of school dropout,'' Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at their reading tables, in groups of five or six, the
Meredith fourth graders came up with all the policy arguments that
grown-ups have invoked in the long debate over promotion and
retention. They try to balance the blow to self-esteem and the
possibility that children will become too discouraged against the
need to master the basics of education before going on to more
advanced work, to establish that promotion and standards count for
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a cool thing to stay back,'' Julian said. ``Kids
really tease you, and treat you like you don't know anything. But I
think you should be left back if you really need to. Like if you
never know your times tables, you'll never catch up. You'll just
fall more behind. You could be in trouble if you don't know a lot
of multiplication.''
</P>
<P>
   And, being children, the fourth graders had some unusual ideas.
``I don't think it's good to keep kids back,'' John said, ``because
you might get addicted to your teacher if you stay for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most education experts, the Meredith fourth graders said
that children having trouble in school should first be offered
summer school, tutoring and after-school programs, with retention
used only as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather go to summer school than stay back,'' Doug
said. ``The kids at summer school wouldn't tease you because that's
why they'd be there, too. And nobody else would know.''
</P>
<P>
   And while everyone thought it would be a social disaster to be
kept back, some said that academically, it might be a motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good to make kids stay back if they don't get the
work the teacher assigned you,'' Jennifer said. ``Because the next
year, it's just going to be harder work, and how are you going to
keep up? You've got to learn. You've got to get an education.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, the school board is planning to hold summer
school for about 10,000 children who have done poorly in 3rd, 7th
or 11th grades. And next year, those who do not meet the benchmark
standards for promotion from 4th, 8th and 12th grades will be made
to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Philadelphia, 5.3 percent of all kindergarteners
through eighth graders _ 6,813 children _ were held back, a
retention rate typical of many urban school districts.
</P>
<P>
   But schools have had great discretion in making those decisions,
and at Meredith, principal Stuart Cooperstein said that only one
child out of 250 had been kept back last year.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next year, though, the new policy will impose citywide
standards for promotion, so that, for example, those finishing
fourth grade in June 2000 will have to pass language arts,
mathematics, science and social studies, and achieve certain scores
on reading and math tests, to go on to fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the bogyman is already at the door. In January,
letters went out to parents of pupils at risk _ about 50 at
Meredith _ warning of the possible consequences of academic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``A review of ----'s work this far,'' the letters say,
``indicates the possibility that he may not be promoted at the
close of this school year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with their school's low retention rate, all the students at
Meredith seem to know someone, in their family or their
neighborhood or their class, who had been held back _ and they
consider it an all-too-vivid possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really scared about it,'' Karen said. ``You want to make
your parents proud, and they'd be so disappointed. You'd be
embarrassed, and if you're 12 years old and you're in fifth grade,
kids would be calling you names all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think children should get help so they don't have to stay
back. Children who aren't so good at reading should get more help
than other children, because they need it. My mom said she'd try to
get me someone to come to my house and help with my homework, when
she's working.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials agreed to allow interviews of Meredith pupils
in the fourth and seventh grades on the condition that they be
identified only by their first name _ and by no name at all when
they talked about school difficulties they or their relatives
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened to my cousin,'' said one wide-eyed fourth grader.
``She had to stay back and she was so scared how much the kids
would tease her that she didn't go to school for the first two
days. She was so embarrassed to be older than the others. She felt
so stupid. But it made her work harder, so it wouldn't happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Another child, however, said his older brother had stayed back,
and although he was promoted the next year, he is still not doing
well.
</P>
<P>
   While some children, especially younger ones, thought staying
back motivated students to work harder, others who had experienced
it themselves or through relatives said the strategy could easily
backfire. ``I think you'd be so ashamed you might not go back to
school anymore, and then you'd drop out,'' said one. ``You feel
like you've already failed, so you give up.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, studies show that most children kept back more than
once drop out of school before graduating, and the current
Philadelphia policy _ but not the new one _ says no child may be
kept back more than once in kindergarten through eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh graders, who will have to meet the new standards
next year, had their own fears about being kept back, even though
none of those interviewed in Chuck Brenner's math class had heard
anything about the new policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be summer school for seventh graders who
aren't doing well?'' said Catie, in some surprise. ``OK, I better
start working harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said they had always worried about being kept back, so
the policy would not have any effect on them. ``My grandparents
tell me all the time, if I get a bad grade on a test, that I better
get to work, or I might have to stay back.'' Morgan said. ``I'm
already scared enough.''
</P>
<P>
   One seventh grader, hearing about the new policy, looked
stricken.
</P>
<P>
   ``This already happened to me,'' he said. ``When I was in third
grade, I wasn't doing so well and they wanted to hold me back. I
remember when they told me, I just went and sat down for a long
time. Then I asked my mom if I could go to summer school. My
parents were kind of disappointed in me.''
</P>
<P>
   How is he doing now? ``Not so well, really,'' he said. ``But I'm
trying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
