<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-2T     01-30 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ALL COMES DOWN TO DENVER'S DAVIS AND ATLANTA'S ANDERSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Expect styles that are scrappy and clever and then look
for fighters and holders and even biters when the Denver Broncos
and the Atlanta Falcons meet in Super Bowl XXXIII on Sunday at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This game will be all about grit. It starts, where all games do,
at the point of attack. Along line play. It will get nasty in
there. Downright dirty.
</P>
<P>
   And because Denver and Atlanta insist on physical, run-oriented
football and because each defense swears that the other side will
not be allowed to trample it with the run, something has to give.
Something has to break.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what happens during most of Super Bowl XXXIII, all of it
is set up to deliver the running game. See that 50-yard bomb?
Somebody's trying to set up some runs. See that fancy screen pass
right? The quick-trap running play is next. Run, run, run.
Play-action pass. Then more run, run, run.
</P>
<P>
   This Super Bowl pits the top rusher from the American Football
Conference, Denver's Terrell Davis, against the top runner from the
National Football Conference, Atlanta's Jamal Anderson. It is only
the second time this has happened in 33 Super Bowls _ the first
coming in Super Bowl XXVIII, when Buffalo's Thurman Thomas went
against Dallas' Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   These are two teams that run it till they drop.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta defense knows what is ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you are running, that is where you are going to find
us,'' said Don Blackmon, the Atlanta linebackers coach, of the
Falcons' run defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Crockett, a Denver cornerback. said: ``We will play this
game with all 11 players on the field involved in the run defense.
And if we could use 12 or 13, we would.''
</P>
<P>
   What's at stake in stopping the run? Well, you don't want to get
soaked. It's as if you have new shoes and you don't want to spill
water on them. Then you go outside and step into a puddle. Then it
begins to rain. A spill becomes a misstep, and then comes the
downpour.
</P>
<P>
   The team that kicks its running game into gear will most likely
kick its entire game into gear. All things flow from the run. Fancy
passes. Ball-control offense. A worn and tired defense for the
other side. A fresh one for you.
</P>
<P>
   And the effect on the other team? Soaked.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there will be plenty of fireworks in the passing game and
sparks in special teams play, but the running game is Super Bowl
XXXIII's backbone. Both teams have built themselves this way,
relying on effective offensive lines, dynamic backs and persistent
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   The glamour guys are Davis and Anderson. Davis rushed for 2,008
yards, averaged 5.1 yards per rushing attempt and scored 21
touchdowns in the regular season. Anderson rushed for 1,846 yards,
averaged 4.5 yards per carry and scored 14 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, Terrell Davis could have rushed for 2,500 yards this
season,'' said Bill Kollar, Atlanta's defensive line coach. ``There
were a lot of games where he ran for so many yards and Denver was
up by so much that they sat him down way early and just let him
rest. He's powerful and explosive and he breaks tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is powerful, too, but he dances more, jigs a little,
bounces inside and outside. This is unusual, especially considering
that both players stand 5 feet 11 inches, but Anderson weighs 234
pounds, 24 more than Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The lighter guy, not the heavier one, should do the dancing,
right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we've played a guy who like Terrell is so
determined and confident at running back,'' said Maa Tanuvasa,
Denver's right defensive end. ``He's got spin moves and can juke
you, but he doesn't mind pinning his ears back and running over
you. We understand that like Terrell, he is a special player.''
</P>
<P>
   Two special players who run behind two splendid offensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Gibbs, the Broncos' offensive line coach, keeps pressure on
his players. He is vocal and intense. His linemen play that way.
They are quicker and lighter as a group than most pro lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is not necessarily to blow guys 10 yards back off the
line of scrimmage,'' said Dan Neil, the Broncos' right guard.
``Sometimes all we need to do is get movement one way or the other
and create a seam. Terrell has great vision. He has a great feel
for defensive linemen. He reads them and then gets by them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos ask everyone to block. Even John Elway occasionally
throws a chip block on a defender. Denver's run assignments are so
intricate that one man who is imprecise can ruin the entire play.
</P>
<P>
   Denver loves to find or create a gap for Davis' quick-hitting
runs. And the line is wonderful at creating a wash, when defenders'
movements are used to wash or sweep them out of a play, forcing
them to overpursue and leave cutback lanes open for Davis. That is
one of the tactics Davis best employs: cutting back against the
grain and flow of the defense. He is often aided on cutbacks by his
receivers' blocks, especially those by the 6-5 Ed McCaffrey, who is
savvy at plucking off safeties.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and the Falcons approach the run game more simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Shanahan's history is to spread you out and get a couple
of quick scores and later give you a heavy dose of Terrell,'' the
Falcons' Blackmon of the Denver head coach. ``Our offense is
disciplined and hard-nosed. We play a power game.''
</P>
<P>
   One that says: Here comes the Atlanta offensive line. Here comes
Anderson. Stop it if you can.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson likes to cut back, too, but he runs behind a line that
is bigger than Denver's and that loves to drive block. Both
offensive lines are taught to finish their plays and to communicate
tirelessly. The tight ends _Shannon Sharpe for Denver and O.J.
Santiago for Atlanta _ both are adept at run-blocking. And the two
teams enjoy running from a double tight end formation, so expect
plenty of that on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Each star back is aided by a bruising, lead-blocking fullback.
For Denver it is Howard Griffith. For Atlanta is Brian Kozlowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to pack the mail and somebody's got to deliver
it,'' Griffith said. ``The blockers pack it. Those guys deliver it.
The main keys for me are creating angles for Terrell and getting
myself out of the hole so he can see clearly and more easily make
his decisions on where he will go. In our jobs as blockers, you've
got to check your ego at the door. I could catch 40 passes and run
for 800 yards in a season, but that way this team is not going to
the Super Bowl. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
