<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR HAS SOME INDIVIDUAL HITTING PROJECTS FOR THE BRAVES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Don Baylor suddenly became open to job offers last
September after his dismissal as manager of the Colorado Rockies,
he had a host of opportunities, but one clearly stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking of the World Series,'' Baylor said. ``When I
looked at the options I had, Atlanta was the choice for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In this last decade of baseball's century, the Braves have
played in the World Series four times, twice as often as any other
team. But their critics point out that they have won the World
Series only once and, with seven successive division championships,
they have squandered three other opportunities to reach the World
Series by losing in the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their October failures, the Braves have had far more
success than any other team in Atlanta. The Falcons, who have a
football game against the Denver Broncos Sunday night, are in the
Super Bowl for the first time. But their coach, Dan Reeves, can
relate to the criticism the Braves and their manager, Bobby Cox,
have endured because in the span of four seasons he took a team,
the Broncos, to the Super Bowl three times and lost each time.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Falcons lose, Reeves will again hear the cries that
he cannot win the ultimate game. Even though the Braves won
baseball's ultimate series in 1995, Cox has been maligned for not
engineering more championships. But if the Falcons lose, Reeves and
his team, unlike the Braves, will not have a guarantee that they
will be back in the playoffs next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves do not actually have a guarantee; it is just that
they are a good team that is the class of the National League East.
The Mets have made a flurry of moves this winter in an effort to
catch the Braves, but the Braves have made some moves intended to
correct the flaws that have undermined their previous post-season
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Using a piece of the strongest element of the team, the starting
pitching, the Braves traded Denny Neagle to Cincinnati for Bret
Boone, who is one of the league's best hitting and fielding second
basemen. Then they signed Brian Jordan to play right field and add
even more hitting to an offense that had four players slug more
than 30 home runs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are two real good defensive players, plus they
have an attitude about them,'' Baylor said of Boone and Jordan.
``They're not your briefcase-carrying guys. They're blue-collar
type of guys that they probably need in the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have also shaken up their coaching staff, which is
why Baylor now works for them. He has replaced Clarence Jones, who
for the past 11 seasons was their hitting coach. Baylor's
credentials for the job are exemplified in the six-and-a-half-year
success of Andres Galarraga, the Braves' first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   As the St. Louis hitting coach in 1992, Baylor rejuvenated
Galarraga and salvaged his career, turning him into a .300 hitter
with power and exceptional run-producing ability, which Baylor used
in Colorado for five years. As the Braves' hitting coach, Baylor
wants to address several aspects of the team's offense. For one
thing, he wants to slash the number of strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three years they've had over 1,000 strikeouts,'' said
Baylor, whose Rockies were the only NL team under 1,000 last
season. ``That told me a little something about their troubles in
the playoffs. It seems to me they didn't make an adjustment in
their approach to how they were being pitched. You have to have a
thought process: hit the ball the other way, cut down on
strikeouts, put the ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Braves tied a major league record last season by
hitting home runs in 25 consecutive games, Baylor said: ``You get
to the point where you hit a home run and strike out three times
and say, `I went one for four with a home run; that's OK' That's
not OK.''
</P>
<P>
   As potent as the Braves were offensively, Baylor sees some
individual projects that could produce even more runs with a more
versatile offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko: ``I want to see his left-handed bat be what Fred
McGriff was for that team,'' Baylor said. ``He can be one of the
premier guys in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones: ``With Chipper getting better every year, I'd
like to see what the deal is with his right-handed stroke, why
that's such a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones: ``He's one of those guys who tries to pull
everything. What he can do power-wise, there's so much potential
there. He had a real good second half. He's still young and
learning the league.''
</P>
<P>
   In getting hitters to be more disciplined at the plate, to
change their all-or-nothing approach, Baylor hopes to have the
Braves manufacture more runs as well as producing them with home
runs. If good pitching, which the Braves see in the playoffs, shuts
down the long ball, a team has to be able to score with singles and
sacrifice bunts, ground balls to the right side of the infield and
sacrifice flies.
</P>
<P>
   The method does not guarantee a spot in the World Series, but
the Braves, like their critics, are not satisfied with all of the
results in their decade and will keep making changes until they get
it right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Andro Noose &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is in no hurry to make a decision on the
status of androstenedione, the testosterone-producing pill that
Mark McGwire turned into a household name. The last thing officials
want to do is tarnish McGwire's superhuman feat last season by
labeling the pills off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   But however long officials take to settle andro's status and
whatever they decide, minor league players could be confronted with
a problem during the coming season.
</P>
<P>
   Because professional baseball players will be permitted to play
in the Olympics in Sydney, Australia, next year, minor leaguers who
are not on the 40-man rosters of major league teams will be
eligible for the United States team and the teams of other
countries. But if they use andro, they had better beware.
</P>
<P>
   The pill is on the Olympics' banned list, and all athletes face
the possibility of being tested for prohibited substances. The
company that manufactures andro has said that at least 100 players
in the minors and majors use it. If any of those wind up on
Olympics teams and test positive for andro, they will be banned
from the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan American Games in Winnipeg, Manitoba, in July will serve
as the regional qualifying tournament for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Learned Dr. Tewksbury &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Tewksbury has ended his 11-year pitching career, but his
campaign against the designated hitter goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a handful of classes to complete his work for a college
degree, Tewksbury took a course in the history of sports at New
England College this winter and carried his opposition to the d.h.
into the classroom. Not surprisingly, he concluded in a paper that
the d.h. has not achieved what the American League hoped it would
when the position was introduced in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In his paper, Tewksbury argued that the d.h. has not only
eliminated game strategy but has also slowed the pace of games and
lengthened them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it is documented that this increase is just a few
minutes,'' the 38-year-old retiree wrote, ``the lack of strategy
makes it feel like a much longer experience. My recommendation is
that the American League hand out free packages of No-Doz to
prevent their fans from falling asleep during AL games.''
</P>
<P>
   Tewksbury, who began his professional career in the Yankees
organization in 1981, has long criticized the use of the d.h., even
though he himself was not much of a hitter. He batted .132 in his
career, striking out 118 times in 380 times at bat. He also drove
in 19 runs, scored 19 and walked 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a worse feeling in the world than going up against
Pedro Martinez and knowing you don't have a chance,'' he said.
``But there's no better feeling than bunting someone over and
having the next guy drive him in.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Crawling After Clemens &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As long as owners grovel to players, as Drayton McLane Jr. keeps
doing with Roger Clemens, they will never have the upper hand in
the salary escalation game that they are losing badly.
</P>
<P>
   McLane, the Houston Astros' owner, apologized last month to
Clemens for comments made by the team's general manager, Gerry
Hunsicker, about Clemens and the new contract he was seeking in the
event the Toronto Blue Jays traded him to the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Last week McLane said he was looking forward to seeing Clemens
at a Texas sports function because he wanted to apologize to him
``for what transpired in December.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane obviously would still like to have Clemens, but Hunsicker
was more forthright when he said the player's contract demands were
outrageous. If McLane really wants Clemens to play for the Astros,
he should sell the team to the pitcher's agents, Alan and Randy
Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   In his Toronto contract, Clemens had a clause in a side
agreement, since ruled illegal, that said he could request a trade
to the Astros after any season. The agreement did not spell out the
reason behind the provision, but people who know the reason said
the clause was included in case the Hendricks brothers, who live in
Houston, bought the team.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his questionable apologies, McLane likely violated
baseball's tampering rules when he said of Clemens, ``We still
would love for him to be a Houston Astro.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
