u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-EDUC-NYT &LR;      01-30 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS AT U.N. SEEK SCHOOL GRANTS FOREIGNERS GET 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A group of American citizens working for the
United Nations in professional-level jobs is preparing to step up a
fight to receive the same education grants for their children that
foreign officials get in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement more than 50 years old, foreign professionals
working at U.N. headquarters as specialists in a range of fields
including economics, political affairs and technical or financial
services receive more than $15,500 a year for each child in school
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Americans do not get the grants, which were intended to allow
foreign families to pay for a private education in the language or
culture of their home countries, so that the children could return
comfortably to those nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be so bad if it were used for the purpose
intended,'' an American working here said. The reality, this
official and others from various countries said, is that the grant
buys entry to the best private schools and colleges for children
who may have been born in this country, have an American parent or
be part of a family settled here. Since 1994, U.N. officials may
apply for permanent residency after 15 years of work at the
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it so unjust is that many of these children are
Americans like our children,'' an American parent said, adding that
no effort is made to weed out dubious cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans _ about 108 officials with a total of more than
170 children _ want help from U.S. representatives in the U.N.
committee that determines these grants, said Stephen Baldwin, who
recently retired as an official in the Department of Economic and
Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Baldwin was among a group of Americans who petitioned
the U.N. Administrative Tribunal, the organization's highest
judicial panel, for equal treatment. They were turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin suggested in an interview this week that the General
Assembly, the group of 185 nations that formally sets the grant
levels, could freeze new increases until the Americans could be
brought into the program. This would not add costs to the
organization's already hamstrung budget.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, unlike many other nations, is perennially
reluctant to become involved in the cases of Americans working for
the United Nations, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very helpful to us if our own representatives were
to take up this case and say this isn't a level playing field,''
Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Another parent, who did not want to be named, said that the
American government's attitude ``represents the low esteem with
which the United Nations is held in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Some American officials have recommended abolishing the grant
entirely, but Baldwin said that this would be politically
unrealistic and ``draconian,'' since many families are involved who
do send their children to foreign-language schools and need
financial help living in New York. Average salaries for these
professional-level jobs hover around $75,000 to $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   The education grant has become an untaxed windfall for
foreigners, augmenting their salaries substantially, American
professionals say.
</P>
<P>
   The grants apply only to U. N. officials, whose salaries and
benefits are set or reviewed by the General Assembly and the
International Civil Service Commission. The supplements do not
apply to diplomats based in foreign missions in New York, though
they may qualify for other programs through their respective
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Americans in U.N. service are eligible for the grants when they
are sent abroad. But many U.N. officials spend a large part of
their careers at the headquarters here, where city neighborhood
schools may have problems and private education is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, Americans, who already have
lower net salaries than many foreigners because they are required
to pay Social Security taxes to the United States, say that they
often cannot afford the private schools to which their foreign
counterparts send their children.
</P>
<P>
   The supplements were originally for children up to the age of
11, who would then return to their home countries for secondary and
higher education. They are now being used up through university
level.
</P>
<P>
   The grants can easily be misused, U.N. employees say. A Canadian
reported cases of children from extended families being brought to
New York to raise the number of supplements added to an official
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Unmarried employees also say that they watch married colleagues
increase their incomes substantially with the education grants as
their families grow, while single officials live on flat salaries
at a time of financial crisis in the organization. ``Morale is
bound to suffer,'' a European said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARK-BOND-PERFIDY-2nd     01-30 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-BOND-PERFIDY-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: of the total.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deaton said the steering committee relied on citizen input, not
politicians or others with vested interests in considering which
projects to bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think there was (political pressure),'' Deaton
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Doug Ring, it's the children's museum that pushes the
project. It's not surprising it's a high priority. The K in Prop. K
was for kids. And the Boeckmann property has long had a high
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum and Santa Monica Mountains acquisitions, however,
were not on the Recreation and Parks Department's priority list,
according to Ann Kerman, director of resource development. Nor was
$10 million proposed to be bonded for a children's discovery area
at the zoo, she said, though it was listed in the ballot proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The other four proposed bond projects are $5 million to the
Cabrillo Aquarium, $7.4 million to the Griffith Observatory, $2.1
million to build a child-care center in North Hollywood and $1.4
million for sports fields at Washington Irving Middle School in
Glassell Park.
</P>
<P>
   The department's goal was to give the entire city as many new
parks, sporting facilities and child-care centers as possible,
while targeting a couple of regional projects, including the
observatory and aquarium, that were ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in many cases where land has already been purchased,
the lack of parks tax money is stalling projects, Kerman said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, property has been purchased for the Riverside
Performing Arts Center along Riverside Drive, but its $3 million in
bond money is nowhere on the radar through 2004, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Land also has been bought for a Branford Recreation Center in
the Northeast Valley, but none of the nearly $2 million needed is
budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sepulveda Recreation Center pool is closed while
it awaits $800,000 in Proposition K money that won't materialize
until sometime after 2004 under the current plan, according to
Kerman and records.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not what was envisioned by the proposition,'' Soboroff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the list of seven projects did not receive unanimous
support from the Central Regional Volunteer Neighborhood Oversight
Committee, the citizens group that represents the region with the
bulk of the projects on the bond list.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Smith, a central committee member, said she was opposed to
including the mountains purchase. She said the expenditure would
cut too deeply into the budget for parkland acquisition elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the rest of the city, the need for little parks
all over, for kids to be able to sit and play in open spaces. That
opportunity should not be lost,'' said Smith, a Lincoln Heights
resident.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing with Soboroff on overall spending, Miscikowski said
that all the projects should get to compete for fast-track
financing by bonding against future revenues. She said there should
be a level playing field for all projects, not just those that can
pay to get ahead.
</P>
<P>
   She called the current process ``clearly inequitable'' and said
she did not influence the placement of the children's museum on the
list of bond projects. She added the Santa Monica Mountains
acquisition proposal came out of the steering committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ring said the museum competed with other agencies for funding,
and he doesn't know how the final selection process worked. He said
the museum needs most of its money upfront to proceed with a
relocation from downtown to Griffith Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the children's museum has to wait 10 years, it will be
someone else building it,'' Ring said.
</P>
<P>
   The project is for the good of the community and the city's
children, not for himself or his wife, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Boeckmann said he never asked anyone to put his project on a
fast-track list, but that the city must decide soon whether to
purchase his property. Otherwise, he said he may develop it since
the costs associated with additional delays are mounting.
</P>
<P>
   He said Mayor Richard Riordan and then-Councilman Marvin Braude
originally approached him about selling the land for what he said
would have been far less than it was worth. Boeckmann said he
agreed and later said OK to another reduction to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The property is gorgeous, he added. ``It's a hell of a deal, in
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, he said that Miscikowski, who succeeded
Braude, met with him to discuss the property's acquisition.
Boeckmann said his position was that he couldn't wait forever, that
he'd already spent more than $1 million on the property and that
the project needed to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reasonably, this has already gone on too long,'' Boeckmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the seven projects moved quickly through the process and
into official city planning documents, many other projects
floundered, and applicants were never told how to appeal when they
lost out, said Smith of the central committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those that were politically well-connected ... appealed, but
the mom-and-pop groups didn't know they could,'' she said. ``There
was a lot of frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Several council members said they were surprised that a
mechanism had been devised for moving some projects ahead more
quickly, while others would have to wait to get cash directly from
assessment revenues or else find funds from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset that we're not following a more equitable process,''
said Councilman Hal Bernson, who represents the Northwest Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In Bernson's district, Mason Park, the Northridge Recreation
Center, Parthenia Park, Stetson Ranch and the Winnetka Recreation
Center are all on the slow track, with little or no funding
scheduled through 2004, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Michael Feuer's district has little Proposition K
funding scheduled for four projects, including a Studio City gym
and the Van Nuys-Sherman Oaks recreation building.
</P>
<P>
   While it makes sense to bond some projects, Feuer said
``well-heeled projects'' should not be the only ones that can get
bonding to move quickly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Hernandez, Proposition K's author, said his goal
was not to finance major land acquisitions in the mountains or to
tie up lots of money in big projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to tie up so much money this way,'' he said.
``While certain projects might justify some bonding, I have a hard
time justifying all of these.''
</P>
<P>
   What is needed, he said, is small parks, recreation centers and
other projects to help kids throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a city have an obligation to do this faster,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
