<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEAN-STREETS-NUN-LADN     01-30 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAN-STREETS-NUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NUN LOOKS BACK ON CAREER SERVING L.A.'S POOREST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Margaret Rose Welch grew up poor, as did Sergio
Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   But Welch entered a convent and the Immaculate Heart Community,
while Cruz joined a gang and got in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives crossed on Blythe Street, where the 74-year-old
Welch helped pull 35-year-old Cruz into a better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one great worry when I became a nun _ &UR;  &LR; that I'd be
bored,'' Welch said one recent morning on Blythe Street, an
impoverished neighborhood in northeastern Los Angeles, ``and I
haven't been bored _ and certainly not on Blythe Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Welch will retire as director of Casa Esperanza, or Hope
House, which is the center she created to provide health care,
employment and an array of other social services for Blythe Street
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Though gangs and drugs have not been completely eliminated from
Blythe Street, Welch said she will leave having come full circle on
the goals she set out to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz is one of her legacies.
</P>
<P>
   He was shot, busted by police and sent to prison before he
realized he wanted to turn his life around. But with a record,
finding a job was no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's employment program takes grants and works with such
employers as Mission Community Medical Center and others to train
and place Blythe Street residents.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect fit for Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting Welch, he had applied to six jobs and was turned
down six times. With no resume and a felony on his record, finding
a job was impossible until Welch hired Cruz as her personal
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just need a helping hand, and she was that angel
that gave me that help,'' Cruz said. ``Since I've been working with
Sister Margaret, it's been a blessing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch taught Cruz how to use a computer, and today he types up
job listings for other residents. He also runs Casa Esperanza's
weekly clothing giveaway program out of a tiny garage near the
center, which is housed in an apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of my job,'' said Cruz, as he sorted through
boxes of clothing. ``I love to work with people. I've been learning
how to work with people. People are poor here, but before, I didn't
care. Now, it's different. I care about them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Welch, the obstacles faced by Blythe Street residents are
familiar: She grew up poor, the daughter of a mining superintendent
father and a mother who was a teacher. She entered the convent
determined to help others and has since dispensed of her vows after
her religious order broke away from the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has battled with the Los Angeles Police
Department over their enforcement of an injunction for gang
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the critical thing is that you respect a gang member
as a person because they have value as a person, though you may not
respect everything they do,'' Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the gold heart pin Welch wears on the lapel of her jackets,
her kindness and generosity are more than just for show, said
Maritza Artan, who will take over as director of Casa Esperanza on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when a family is in a tight spot, Margaret has
always been there to help,'' Artan said.
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo removal program, the domestic violence workshops and
the English as a second language classes Welch has created compare
little to the small acts of compassions she exhibits daily, Artan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Casa Esperanza stocks up on baby formula and canned goods to
help residents in need, but Welch is known to take residents
personally to the store to buy groceries in emergency situations,
Artan said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's deeds don't go unnoticed. On a recent day, Blythe Street
resident Gloria Estrada stopped by Casa Esperanza and grasped
Welch's hands to thank her for the food and clothing she gave
Estrada's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just moved to the neighborhood, and we didn't have anyone
to help us,'' said Estrada, who is jobless and caring for her
17-year-old son plus two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no food, no nothing, and they really helped,'' Estrada
said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's concern for the downtrodden was rooted in the strong
sense of compassion her mother exhibited for others.
</P>
<P>
   The philosophy of the Immaculate Heart Community _ composed of
former nuns who continue religious teachings as lay people _ is to
foster people's access to truth, dignity and full human development
and to work to change conditions that hinder that access.
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy has always guided Welch's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Margaret does is talk to residents and find out what
their needs are, and she tries to address those,'' said Albert
Melena, youth director of San Fernando Valley Partnership, an
agency that has worked with Welch to create youth programs on
Blythe Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been dedicated,'' Melena said. ``And if you look at Casa
Esperanza's longevity, they've made the commitment to be there. And
Casa Esperanza will probably be the last ones there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-REVIEW     01-30 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY LIES THE PRINCE WHO GETS A LETTER FROM THE KING
</HEADLINE>
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Everyone knows that Shakespeare artfully used
royal intrigues and jealousies to weave tales almost dizzying in
scope. But however much he invented dialogue and situations, people
have always suspected that when it came to the motives and
character of kings and queens, Shakespeare got it right. He showed
royalty to be larger than life, but in the end very human.
</P>
<P>
   Now, from the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, comes evidence to
support that proposition: a most extraordinary document in the
voice of a modern-day king struggling with his own mortality as he
grapples with issues that were the stuff of the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   The document is a letter sent Jan. 25 by King Hussein of Jordan
to his brother, Prince Hassan, the longtime heir to the throne. It
was written in Arabic and distributed in translation by the royal
palace. In pained but regal tones, often blunt and sometimes
rambling, the letter reveals the intensely personal nature of the
king's decision about who should succeed him. It also shows what
went into that choice: grand strategy, pride, respect for law,
emotion, the weight of tradition and rumors of treachery.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, absolute power has always been lonely _ King
Hussein's own 1962 autobiography was titled ``Uneasy Lies the
Head.'' And of all the responsibilities a king has, choosing the
next king may be the heaviest. Consider the case of a predecessor
across the Jordan River, the biblical King David, who chose not his
eldest son, as would have been customary, but Solomon, the son of
his favorite wife.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four years ago, King Hussein too bucked convention by
designating his brother Hassan as crown prince, and until last week
that decision seemed unshakable. But as he tells Prince Hassan in
the letter, he questioned that choice as he lay ill with cancer
last year in the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota. When Hussein returned to
the kingdom, he made his choice known. Then he returned to
Minnesota for more cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In the king's telling, it is an epic tale.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of characters: Hussein, the gravely ill King of Jordan;
his 51-year-old brother, Hassan, who had ruled the land as regent
for six months; Hussein's eldest son, Abdullah, about to turn 37;
Hussein's fourth and current wife, Queen Noor; Hussein's younger
son, Hamzeh, 18; various unnamed court figures and
behind-the-scenes plotters.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOUGLAS JEHL
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Hassan was designated crown prince in 1965,
when the king's own oldest son was 3 and the country was in peril:
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I entrusted you with the post of crown prince and I was, with
the will of God, responsible for that decision at the time, at a
time when the eldest son of the King has not reached the age
defined by the constitution to allow him to assume responsibility
in case the king had died by the will of God.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, a dark atmosphere was affecting the whole nation
because dangers, rumors and speculation were rife concerning the
imminent end of Jordan, a country with a mission, principles and
morals, and a true affiliation to the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
   (END ITALICS HERE)Over time, the king had heard of words
directed against him, from within the crown prince's own circle.
But he could not believe that his brother would have been disloyal.
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   My small family was offended by slandering and falsehoods, and I
refer here to my wife and children. When I heard this most of the
time, I attributed it to the tendency towards rivalry among those
who pretend to be faithful to you.
</P>
<P>
   (END ITALICS HERE)Fie on those who had tried to stir jealousies
within the family! (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I have lived through many experiences and I noticed at an early
age how some some climbers climb onto the branch to ruin the
relation between brothers and between father and son, and I swore
to myself that this would not happen here in my lifetime. But
surely, this has become the objective of every declared or hidden
enemy, and all of those who have used all means at their disposal
to weaken confidence between leadership and people, but they have
not succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Of course, the king himself had been above
the plotters' machinations: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Their plan at this stage, together with those who want to
destroy Jordan, was to instigate infighting in the ranks of the
leadership after they failed to dismantle the base, and they find
in my being alive an impediment to all their designs, forgetting
that Al Hussein has lived only to gain the blessings of God, to
have a clear conscience and to achieve the best for all his people,
regardless of their origins, who cooperate in holding the banner
high and carrying the message of Jordan with their heads high, not
bowing except before God.
</P>
<P>
   (END ITALICS HERE) He had truly intended to honor his
commitment, but a question lingered: If his brother were to succeed
him, who would next become king? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I was determined to hand the first responsibility to you, but
after you, I envisioned a role for the family council in which to
ensure the unity of the Hashemite family, so that when the time
came for you to choose your successor, the family would have a
great role in naming the most suitable successor, in accordance
with the benevolent traditions of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-REVIEW     01-30 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY LIES THE PRINCE WHO GETS A LETTER FROM THE KING
</HEADLINE>
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
