<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-MEMORIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL MEMORIES BY THE NUMBERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FISCHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Catches in Percy Howard's National Football League career.
Howard, a rookie wide receiver for the Dallas Cowboys, scored a
Super Bowl touchdown on his only NFL reception, a 34-yard pass play
from Roger Staubach late in the fourth quarter of Super Bowl X.
</P>
<P>
   2. Men who have earned Super Bowl rings as a player, assistant
coach and head coach. Tom Flores was a backup quarterback for the
Kansas City Chiefs in IV and an assistant for Oakland in XI, and,
as a head coach, led the Raiders to victory in XV and XVIII. Mike
Ditka, who had been a player and an assistant coach on championship
teams in Dallas, led Chicago to victory in Super Bowl XX.
</P>
<P>
   3. Super Bowl titles won by Washington Redskins Coach Joe Gibbs
with as many different starting quarterbacks (Joe Theisman in XVII,
Doug Williams in XXII and Mark Rypien in XXVI). And linebacker Matt
Millen is the only player to earn Super Bowl championship rings
with three different teams: the Raiders in XV and XVIII, the San
Francisco 49ers in XXIV and the Redskins in XXVI.
</P>
<P>
   4. Receptions by the Green Bay Packers backup receiver Max McGee
during the 1966 regular season. McGee then made headlines in Super
Bowl I by hauling in seven passes for 138 yards and two touchdowns,
including the first score in Super Bowl history.
</P>
<P>
   5. Quarterbacks that Joe Namath said were better than Earl
Morrall before Super Bowl III. Namath said that in addition to
himself, the American Football League quarterbacks superior to
Morrall were Oakland's Daryle Lamonica, San Diego's John Hadl,
Miami's Bob Griese and Babe Parilli, Namath's backup.
</P>
<P>
   6. Super Bowl appearances by Don Shula, a record for a head
coach. Shula led the Colts in III, and the Dolphins in VI, VII,
VIII, XVII and XIX (two victories, four losses).
</P>
<P>
   7. Super Bowls among the 10 most-watched television programs
(total number of viewers), including the top four: Super Bowl XXX,
Dallas versus Pittsburgh, 138.5 million; XXVIII, Dallas versus
Buffalo, 134.8 million; XXVII, Dallas versus Buffalo, 133.4
million; XX, Chicago versus New England, 127.0 million.
</P>
<P>
   8. Number of astronauts who took part in a pregame tribute to
NASA and the Kennedy Space Center before Super Bowl XXIII in Miami.
Astronauts representing four phases of America's space program _
Mercury, Gemini, Apollo and the space shuttle Atlantis _ appeared
along with a lunar rover.
</P>
<P>
   9. Number of Super Bowl games, a record, in which Dan Reeves has
participated. Besides guiding the Atlanta Falcons in Sunday's game,
Reeves was a running back for Dallas in Super Bowls V and VI; a
Cowboys assistant in X, XII and XIII; and the Denver Broncos' head
coach in XXI, XXII and XXIV.
</P>
<P>
   10. Record number of turnovers committed by the Baltimore Colts
and the Dallas Cowboys in Super Bowl V. The mark was equaled by the
Denver Broncos and the Cowboys in Super Bowl XII. Craig Morton
committed 7 of the 20 turnovers in the two games, throwing three
interceptions while playing for Dallas in 1971 and four more while
playing for Denver in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   11. Plays called by Joe Montana in marching San Francisco 92
yards for the winning score with 34 seconds remaining in Super Bowl
XXIII against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   12. Most common number worn by winning Super Bowl quarterbacks.
Starting quarterbacks who have worn No. 12 have won 10 of the 18
games in which they appeared. The winning No. 12's are Joe Namath,
Ken Stabler, Bob Griese (twice), Roger Staubach (twice) and Terry
Bradshaw (four times). The losers are Staubach (twice), Griese, Jim
Kelly (four times) and Stan Humphries. If Chris Chandler leads the
Falcons to victory today, he will become the 13th. John Elway wears
No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   13. Years between Gene Upshaw's first Super Bowl appearance
(1968) and his last (1981). Upshaw, a Hall of Fame guard for the
Raiders, also played on the winning team in 1977. He is the only
player to participate in Super Bowls in three different decades.
</P>
<P>
   14. Passes completed by Miami's Griese in the Dolphins'
back-to-back Super Bowl triumphs of 1973 and '74. Griese completed
8 of 11 pass attempts in VII and six of seven passes in VIII.
</P>
<P>
   15. Points scored by Green Bay kicker Don Chandler in Super Bowl
II. His point total (four field goals, three extra points) was 1
more than the entire Oakland team scored. Still, no place-kicker
has won the Super Bowl most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   16. Rushing attempts by Oakland running back Clarence Davis in
Super Bowl XI. In one of the most underappreciated performances in
Super Bowl history, Davis gained 137 yards for an 8.6-yard average.
He had runs of 20, 35, 13, 18 and 16 yards.
</P>
<P>
   17. Yards gained by the Minnesota Vikings' rushers in Super Bowl
IX. Pittsburgh's Steel Curtain defense held Chuck Foreman, Fran
Tarkenton and Dave Osborn to an average gain of less than 1 yard
per carry.
</P>
<P>
   18. Offensive plays needed by Washington to score five
touchdowns in Super Bowl XXII against Denver. The 35-point outburst
in the second quarter is the best performance in one quarter in
Super Bowl history.
</P>
<P>
   19. Time, in seconds, needed by Pittsburgh to score two
touchdowns in the fourth quarter of Super Bowl XIII against Dallas.
Scores by Franco Harris and Lynn Swann (following Randy White's
fumble of a short kickoff) turned a 21-17 Pittsburgh lead into a
35-17 cushion that held up for the Steelers in their third Super
Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   20. Cost, in dollars, of the highest-priced ticket to Super Bowl
XI. The price rose to $75 by Super Bowl XXI, and soared to $275 for
Super Bowl XXXI. This year's top price was $400.
</P>
<P>
   21. Height, in inches, of the Lombardi Trophy, presented each
year to the Super Bowl winner. The trophy is made of sterling
silver and weighs seven pounds three ounces. A stylized football of
regulation size sits atop a three-sided base. Each trophy, created
by Tiffany, is valued at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   22. Players on the Giants' Super Bowl XXV roster with previous
Super Bowl experience. The wily Giants controlled the clock against
Buffalo's hurry-up offense, setting a Super Bowl record for
possession time (40 minutes 33 seconds).
</P>
<P>
   23. Size of William (Refrigerator) Perry's ring, which he
received for being with the winning Bears in Super Bowl XX. An
average man's ring size is 10. The 40-diamond, 10-karat gold ring
weighs two and a half ounces and is big enough to allow a silver
dollar to pass through.
</P>
<P>
   24. People who have attended every Super Bowl game. This group,
dubbed the Super 32 Club, includes 10 writers (Larry Felser, Jerry
Green, Jerry Izenberg, Dave Klein, Will McDonough, Norman Miller,
Bob Oates, Edwin Pope, Cooper Rollow and John Steadman), six
photographers (John Biever, Vernon Biever, Walter Iooss Jr., Mickey
Palmer, Dick Raphael and Tony Tomsic) and eight others: Don Weiss,
Lamar Hunt, Jack Steadman, Ed Sabol, Steve Sabol, Art Speiler, Tex
Schramm and Lee Remmel.
</P>
<P>
   25. Length, in miles, of electrical cable needed for Super Bowl
XXXII (compared with just nine miles of cable in 1988).
</P>
<P>
   26. Players on Washington's Super Bowl XVII roster who were
obtained as free agents; 14 of them were not even drafted by NFL
teams. The Hogs, the Smurfs and the Fun Bunch helped John Riggins
outgain the entire Miami offense.
</P>
<P>
   27. Members of the silver anniversary Super Bowl team: Vince
Lombardi; coach; Joe Montana, quarterback; Franco Harris and Larry
Csonka, running backs; Lynn Swann and Jerry Rice, wide receivers;
Dave Casper, tight end; Art Shell and Forrest Gregg, tackles; Gene
Upshaw and Jerry Kramer, guards; Mike Webster, center; L.C.
Greenwood and Ed Jones, defensive ends; Joe Greene and Randy White,
defensive tackles; Jack Lambert and Mike Singletary, inside
linebackers; Jack Ham and Ted Hendricks, outside linebackers;
Ronnie Lott and Mel Blount, cornerbacks; Donnie Shell and Willie
Wood, safeties; Ray Guy, punter; Jan Stenerud, kicker; John Taylor,
kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   28. Years in which the Super Bowl stock market indicator has
been ``correct.'' This theory holds that a victory by a National
Conference team or an original (pre-1970 merger) NFL team _ the
Browns, the Colts or the Steelers _ points to a bullish market
during the calendar year. But a victory by an American Conference
team indicates a drop in the market by the end of the year. From
1967 to 1997, the theory worked 87.5 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   29. Yards lost by the Dolphins' Griese when sacked by Dallas
tackle Bob Lilly in Super Bowl VI. Some reporters called the sack
(for the most yards in Super Bowl history) Miami's finest example
of open-field running. The Dolphins lost, 24-3, becoming the only
Super Bowl team to go without a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   30. Length, in seconds, of a television commercial during the
Super Bowl. The cost of a 30-second commercial in 1967 was $37,500.
This year, the average cost of a 30-second spot is $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   31. Points scored by the Cowboys in Super Bowl XIII, the most by
any losing team. (The Steelers scored 35 to win.) The
Pittsburgh-Dallas contest was the first Super Bowl rematch
(Pittsburgh won, 21-17, in Super Bowl X).
</P>
<P>
   32. Weight, in tons, of the stage used during the halftime show
in Super Bowl XXXII. The 5,000-square-foot structure, the world's
largest portable stage, was put up and disassembled by 500 workers
in less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   33. Number of seasons the Atlanta Falcons' fans have waited for
the team to reach its first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
