<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEALTHY-CEMETERY-ART-     01-30 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTHY-CEMETERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE HAMPTONS, EVEN BURIAL SITES CONFER STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. _ Death has begun to imitate life out here on
the East End of Long Island, where the rich, the gifted and the
beautiful gather each summer to calibrate status. The most
fashionable place to be dead in the Hamptons is fully booked.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations to rub shoulders for eternity with famous artists
and writers like Jackson Pollock and A.J. Liebling are no longer
being taken, unless you know the right person.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Courtney Sale Ross, widow of Steven Ross, the
entrepreneur who built a family funeral parlor business into Time
Warner Inc. When Ross died of cancer in 1992, his widow bought 110
grave plots, at a cost of $77,000, at Green River Cemetery in the
East Hampton hamlet of Springs. Her expressed purpose: to provide
plots for generations of Rosses to come.
</P>
<P>
   Only one deceased person without a reservation has got into
Green River in the last eight months. Mrs. Ross gave a plot to the
family of Alan Pakula after the award-winning film director died
last year in a freak accident on the Long Island Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just gave the grave site to a friend,'' said Bert Fields,
a lawyer for Mrs. Ross. ``I don't think she wants to start giving
them out to strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ross purchase _ a graveyard echo of land grabs that have
been rattling the Hamptons for decades _ gobbled up about a quarter
of the burial space then available in the three-acre, nonprofit,
nondenominational cemetery. Since then, all the remaining plots
have been sold. Cemetery managers from across the United States
describe the size of the Ross buy as extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, I have never heard of such a thing in such a small
cemetery,'' said Dick Fisher, publicity director at Forest Lawn
Memorial Park, the burial complex with more than a half-million
graves in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ross Domain,'' as some here call the family's graveyard
spread, has become a symbol of how the Hamptons elite, often
without meaning to do so, can stir up deep-rooted resentment among
locals of lesser means.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is animosity,'' said Deanna Tikkanen, a past president
of the Green River Cemetery Association. ``People with money are
buying up the plots and they are not leaving anything for the local
people.'' She said she quit her unpaid position with the cemetery
because wealthy summer people kept calling and pestering her for
plots.
</P>
<P>
   Green River Cemetery, created in 1902 as a modest burial ground
for families of local fishermen, farmers and tradesmen, ran out of
space last year. The cemetery became chic in the years after
Pollock, the abstract expressionist painter and longtime resident
of Springs, was buried there in 1956. It took 85 years for the
cemetery's original two acres to sell out. But when an extra acre
was added in 1987, it was snapped up in just 11 years. Mrs. Ross
took by far the largest single slice.
</P>
<P>
   While the East End has many cemeteries with space available, any
resident of Springs without a prepurchased plot must now be buried
outside the community, said Freston ``Pete'' Anderson, the current
president of the cemetery association.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on unlocking the graveyard once again for locals, the
cemetery is buying another acre, said Anderson, who works for the
Town of East Hampton as a member of the bay patrol. He said that
cemetery trustees, a group of local volunteers who serve two-year
terms, passed a new bylaw last fall to limit the purchasing power
of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ross rule,'' as Anderson called it, limits any buyer to no
more than eight graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an old-fashioned local cemetery,'' said Anderson,
whose parents and grandparents are buried there. ``I think the
community really did want to hang the previous trustees who sold so
many plots to Mrs. Ross.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ross declined to be interviewed for this article. But her
lawyer, Fields, said she bought so many graves because she had a
difficult time selecting an ``appropriate burial place'' for Ross
and, in the future, ``she didn't want anyone in her extended family
to go through that anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was thinking ahead, which is characteristic of her,'' he
said. ``She always thinks three or four generations ahead. It is
all so the family can be together. Keep in mind they live in East
Hampton. They are not just weekenders.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Mrs. Ross ``was not aware she was monopolizing the
remaining grave sites, and certainly would not want to antagonize
anyone at a difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of the graves was negotiated by Edward Blier, a
Time Warner executive who worked for Ross for many years. Blier
said Mrs. Ross chose the cemetery because she knew and admired many
painters who were buried there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started talking about a smaller number of graves, then Mrs.
Ross said, `So, let's just have a lot more space so it can be
landscaped and have other family members,''' Blier said. ``It was
unusual, but it seemed entirely normal because the cemetery seemed
to have a lot of space at the time.'' Blier added that he remembers
no disagreement at the time among cemetery trustees about the
wisdom of selling so many graves to one person.
</P>
<P>
   A former cemetery trustee who attended meetings on the Ross
purchase agrees. The former trustee, Tim Miller, a surveyor in
Springs, said there were no objections at the time because the
cemetery wanted to raise a sizable sum of money to buy more land.
Only later, as the cemetery quickly began to fill, Miller said, did
local people and new trustees begin to grumble about the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Blier, who has owned a home in East Hampton for 39 years, said
that reports of class resentment over the cemetery were
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody started a class war out there,'' he said. ``It is a
simply wonderful place, and was discovered. It is nobody's fault
that artistic people have come out and they have attracted money
people. There is a certain inevitability of change anywhere in the
world. The art is to manage the change graciously.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Management of change in the Hamptons is, however, rarely
gracious.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that's because there is so much of it to manage. The
number of permits last year for new houses in East Hampton jumped
32 percent over the previous year. If the current pace of
development continues, the South Fork of Long Island will be
``built out'' in less than 10 years, according to the Group for the
South Fork, a land preservation fund.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of who is being managed and of how rich
and litigious many of them are.
</P>
<P>
   Protests over large houses, like the 72,000-square-foot mansion
being built by the industrialist Ira Rennert in Sagoponack, led the
neighboring town of East Hampton to pass an ordinance last year
that limits new houses to no more than 20,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   While squabbles over Hamptons real estate are usually among the
rich, the dispute over the Ross purchase at Green River Cemetery
tracks a different, and much less publicized, fault line of
conflict. It is the animosity that many working-class residents
feel toward the summer people whose expensive cars paralyze traffic
on Montauk Highway and whose indifference to prices has driven up
the cost of everything from groceries to gasoline to parking
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local people think, why should they have so much and I
work very hard and I can't even afford to take a vacation or have
medical insurance,'' said Mrs. Tikkanen, the past president of
Green River Cemetery. Her family has lived in East Hampton for 13
generations and she works in the family awning and boat-cover
business.
</P>
<P>
   Green River Cemetery hardly looks like a Hamptons hangout. Much
of it is a lichen-covered confabulation of disordered headstones
surrounded by a white rail fence badly in need of paint. The
graveyard existed in uncrowded and contented obscurity until
several years after Pollock was buried there beneath a 50-ton
boulder.
</P>
<P>
   But since then about 30 notable painters and writers have joined
Pollock, some with little or no connection to either Springs or
East Hampton. When the writer John O'Hara was buried in the
cemetery in 1966, Pollock's widow, Lee Krasner, who was also a
celebrated painter and was later buried there, protested, ``He's
not even a summer rental,'' according to two biographies of
Pollock.
</P>
<P>
   The Ross property in the cemetery lies behind Pollock's grave.
Set well away from the knot of other graves, almost as if buffered
by a moat of grass, Ross' headstone is a small and tastefully
unobtrusive boulder. It seems to echo the larger Pollock stone.
</P>
<P>
   The only other nearby graves are those of Ross' parents, Max and
Sadie. Their bodies were moved to the cemetery after Ross died.
Pakula is buried in a far corner of the Ross property.
</P>
<P>
   A man who pays careful attention to the distribution of space at
Green River is Donald Ferriss, who lives next to the cemetery and
who sold it the land where Ross is buried. Ferriss, a real estate
agent, said he sold the acre at a below-market price of $60,000 out
of a sense of responsibility to the community where he has lived
for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ferriss said he was ``disappointed'' when he learned that he
had, in effect, helped subsidize the plots purchased by Mrs. Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't why I got involved in this,'' Ferriss said. ``I
don't bear the Rosses any ill will, and I'm not trying to turn it
into class warfare, but I would have preferred that it was handled
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferriss is selling the cemetery another acre, this time for
$120,000, to again create space for local people. He said he
heartily approves of the new ``eight is enough'' rule limiting the
buying power of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been no public announcements of the sale or
of the availability, after it is cleared, of more graves. The
president of the cemetery association said he was not looking
forward to making the announcement that the graveyard is once again
taking reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put in the paper that there is going to be a new
section, the phone is going to ring off the hook,'' Anderson said.
``I just know it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
