<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-JAMAL-NYT &LR;      01-30 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-JAMAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE LIKES ATTENTION, AND CARRIES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jamal Anderson strolled with relative ease through the
weeklong blitz of anticipation for Super Bowl XXXIII. He smiled a
lot. Talked a lot. Smiled some more. Quite charming. Easy.
Reflective. Enlightening in his conversation. Easy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he can only run the football that way against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can run the ball against anybody,'' Anderson said. ``No
question. They've played really well. But it's the same for both
defenses. When you play well against the run, you build up a lot of
confidence. So the first quarter, the first half, is going to be
really important. Not only for Jamal Anderson, but for Terrell
Davis against our defense, because both of us have excellent
run-stopping defenses and they pride themselves on shutting down
the running back.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished. Smiled some more. Easy. Talked some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to act natural,'' Anderson said. ``I'm having fun
with all of the attention. I have fun doing my job. I'm just
relaxed and am doing my thing. People keep saying that I'm a ham,
but I'm not a ham, I'm just being natural.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a ham.
</P>
<P>
   He is a good ham.
</P>
<P>
   He is 26. In 1994 he was a seventh-round pick from Utah, the
201st player selected in the National Football League draft. He
attended high school in El Camino, Calif. He grew up watching his
father work in security and he was always around boxing stars
including Muhammad Ali, Sugar Ray Leonard and Mike Tyson and other
stars like Diana Ross, Donna Summers and Richard Pryor .
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Anderson learned how to be a ham from some of the biggest
hams.
</P>
<P>
   He also, obviously, learned toughness and fortitude, how to turn
a shaky start into a solid finish. This is a strong, durable
running back. He can squat 670 pounds and bench press 465 pounds.
He carried the ball an NFL-record 410 times this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, just to think about the fact that nobody's carried this
many times,'' Anderson said. ``The significant thing is I didn't
sustain a major injury. I've been playing since I was 7 and I've
been getting pounded every year since then. I had 410 carries this
season but I don't feel it. I feel 100 percent fresh. People talk
about the residual effect, the wear and tear on your body. But
that's 10 or 20 years. I'm only in my fifth year and realistically,
I didn't even play my first two years, so this is really my third
year. So, I've got seven or eight more years of dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   What a ham. A good ham.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, one day of dominance from Anderson will do. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
