<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Growing Lexicon of Offense
</P>
<P>
   Another word died last week, said Sol Steinmetz, a New York
lexicographer.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was in an uproar about whether the new mayor was
right to accept the resignation of a white aide who had offended a
black colleague by using the word ``niggardly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Williams said the aide, David Howard, had used
poor judgment even though the word has no racial links; it comes
from a Scandinavian word for ``miserly,'' which predates the slur
it sounds like by several hundred years. (Now the mayor is in
trouble with some activists who, like Howard, are gay _ another
word that has been through some changes in recent years.)
</P>
<P>
   After the smoke clears, there will be agreement on one thing,
predicted Steinmetz: ``No one is going to risk using that word
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, linguists are finding an expanding list of benign words
shunned because they either sound offensive or might otherwise be
misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   Chicanery _ deception by trickery, from the Old French chicaner,
to quibble _ is sometimes avoided as an affront to Hispanics
because it closely resembles the word chicano. Terms like queer the
deal, chink in the armor and nip in the air are also on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Another phrase in full retreat is ``to call a spade a spade,''
first used by Plutarch and once synonymous with ``to call a bucket
a bucket'' _ meaning to call things by their true names or to be
straightforward to the point of rudeness.
</P>
<P>
   Not all misunderstandings involve such sensitive matters as race
or ethnicity, of course. And some perfectly innocuous-sounding
words have acquired a bad reputation unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Sheidlower, senior editor in the Random House reference
department, said ``picnic'' has recently come under suspicion
because of an untrue story that it refers to parties in the
countryside where black children were ``picked'' and assaulted.
(The known parentage of the word goes back to mid-18th-century
French pique-nique, but beyond that, its roots are unclear.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to accept the fact that some words are of
unknown origin,'' Sheidlower said. And that's how rumors about
words get started.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MELINDA HENNEBERGER
</P>
<P>
   With Sweets, It's Nurture, Not Nature
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, scientific studies have demonstrated what
everyone else has always known: Women love chocolate. In study
after study, women rate this most irresistible of sweets as their
No. 1 food craving. So intense is this peculiarly female devotion
that scientists have suggested a woman's burning desire for
chocolate might have a biological basis. Researchers have even
suggested that opiates or other chemicals in chocolate thought to
be capable of mimicking the brain chemistry of a person in love
might be what makes women reach for that extra truffle.
</P>
<P>
   But the days when science provided sweet comfort for female
chocolate addicts may have ended. According to a study to appear
later this year in the journal Appetite, researchers report that
not all women are so obsessed. Spanish women who crave sweets were
considerably less attached to chocolate and no more enthralled by
it than Spanish men.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that American women adore chocolate, researchers
suggest, is that people tend to crave and enjoy familiar foods.
American women, drowning in a chocolate-saturated culture, can't
help but learn their naughty little addiction.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't American men go wild for their Ghirardelli as well?
Researchers suggest that in a culture in which gals pop bonbons and
guys carve up steaks, chocolate, along with quiche, may be one of
those foods that real men just won't eat.
</P>
<P>
   This theory also suggests that women could, by repeated
exposure, teach themselves to crave other foods instead, like
sweetened rice cakes. Until researchers come up with a more
palatable hypothesis, women chocoholics will have to seek
reassurance elsewhere, possibly the nearest chocolate shop.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAROL KAESUK YOON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
