<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 31, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-IDENTITY-REVIEW (Washington) _ For a generation,
Republicans have represented resurgent American conservatism. But
now, with the budget balanced and significant reductions in crime,
welfare, divorce and single motherhood, Republicans find themselves
defined by impeachment and their argument that President Clinton
represents a nation in moral decline. They are also finding that
Americans are leery of a party that appears to be pressing for
moral cleansing. By Richard L Berke. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW (Berlin) _ If the late '90s have
produced a dirty word in Europe, it is perhaps `conservative.' The
right-of-center ideology that played an important role in
privatization, advancing the market economy and facing down the
Soviet Union has fizzled. At the beginning of the decade,
conservatives were in charge or on the rise nearly everywhere in
Europe, but today there is not a single major country where that is
true. By Roger Cohen. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   ZERO-TOLERANCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Zero-tolerance'' policies of
seizing cars, boats and other property of persons suspected but not
convicted of drug trafficking or other offenses pleased
criminal-justice conservatives, but enraged scores of motorists,
boat owners, civil libertarians and policy analysts. Critics
complained that draconian steps tie up enforcement personnel better
deployed elsewhere, swamp overburdened administrative systems and
worse, provide little if any deterrence. By David Johnston. (`a'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-RITUALS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Although resisting major
change, the Catholic Church has been enacting lesser changes in
ritual and practice designed to render ancient religious customs
compatible with the spirit of the times. In much of this, experts
