<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      01-30 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S NEW CENTRIST LEADER BOWS TO RELIGIOUS RIGHT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Roni Milo, the former mayor of Tel Aviv, is Israel's
Mr. Secular. A former member of the conservative Likud Party, he
founded the political center last spring partly to create an
enlightened middle-of-the-road movement that would not capitulate
to religious coercion by strictly Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, though, when his brainchild, the center party, had
its debut, Milo was No. 4 on the party ticket. The party leader,
Yitzhak Mordechai, the newly ousted defense minister, was wearing a
yarmulke, quoting from psalms, and kissing his own fingertips after
gently tugging the beard of a strictly Orthodox rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   These things were symbolic, meant to signal from the start that
the Kurdish-born Mordechai, who does not normally wear a skullcap,
wanted to be the candidate of his people, the Sephardic Jews who
happen to comprise a crucial constituency of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mordechai went on to cast the deciding vote in
Parliament on a contentious bill sponsored by the strictly
Orthodox, that struck at the core of the party's fledgling identity
as it heads toward the May 17 elections here. The Parliament was
deadlocked on the bill, which intended to bypass a Supreme Court
order to integrate the all-Orthodox religious councils by including
Reform and Conservative Jewish members. At the last minute,
Mordechai swept onto the floor and broke the tie with his vote
against religious pluralism, a triumphant look on his face as he
hugged Aryeh Deri, the leader of Shas, the religious Sephardic
party.
</P>
<P>
   In one fell swoop, Mordechai cost the center some of its support
among secular Israelis and raised howls of criticism from Jews
abroad. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, the No. 2 man in the party, was in the
United States trying to raise funds for the new center party at the
time of the vote; Milo was on his way. They were put in the
position of trying to explain exactly where the party stands on the
secular-religious divide when Mordechai seemingly betrayed them by
voting his conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mordechai is trying to court the Shas vote, that is crystal
clear, but it seems that this time he has just gone too far,'' said
Chemi Shalev, a political analyst for the Maariv newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The potential trade-off seems clear: traditional Sephardic
voters for center-left voters. But whether Mordechai will be
successful in winning over Shas voters is uncertain. It depends on
the rabbi whose beard he tugged.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, the spiritual leader of Shas, dictates whom
the party endorses, and he criticized Mordechai for leaving Likud
and joining forces with the secular Milo, whom the strictly
religious see as Public Enemy No. 1, according to the Shas
newspaper. But the same newspaper indicated that Mordechai still
stands strong because he is Sephardic and traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu came under fire last week from within his own party
because he no longer has a Sephardic minister in the top ranks of
his Cabinet since he dismissed Mordechai last weekend. Now
Netanyahu is flanked by two elite old-timers _ Ariel Sharon, the
foreign minister, and Moshe Arens, the new defense minister. Most
of the field workers for the Likud Party are young and Sephardic,
and some believe a leadership team consisting of Netanyahu and two
Ashkenazi men over 70 could be a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   When Mordechai cast his vote on the religious council's bill,
the Labor Party jumped right on it. ``The new center party
presented itself to the public just last night speaking of its
desire to create a new political culture of reconciliation,'' it
said in a news release. ``Apparently this doesn't apply to the
religious community, at least in so far as Reform and Conservative
Jews are concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   On the left and the right, the two major parties are flummoxed
by the entrance of Mordechai into a race where the traditional
political dynamic is in constant flux. Both Netanyahu and Ehud
Barak, the Labor Party leader, are banking on the hope that
Mordechai and his party will stumble and fade because of
inexperience and incongruities among them.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the concerns of last week highlighted the constituent
and personality politics that seem to be dominating this volatile
election season. So busy were the politicians talking about
themselves that no one seemed to notice that a key day had come and
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was supposed to have marked the completion of the
implementation of the Wye peace accord. But the peace effort is in
the deep freeze, and forgotten in the electoral fuss. Nobody
mentioned it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
