<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Sunday, Jan. 31. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STARR (Washington) _ A look Starr's post-impeachment
options. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 3:30 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Paris) _ Developments concerning NATO and Kosovo.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 3:30 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-BOWL (Miami) _ The Broncos' Terrell Davis was the
leading rusher in the AFC. The Falcons' Jamal Anderson was the
leading rusher in the NFC. Sunday they meet in the Super Bowl,
where they will go against two of the top rushing defenses in the
league. Whoever wins the ground game is likely to win the title
game. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `s' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRON-POWERSHARE (Washington) _ The new environmental
proposals that the Clinton administration is sending to Congress in
its budget request for the year 2000 include new ways to deliver
money to state and local governments to spend as they see fit, a
sign that environmental power-sharing is taking a firmer hold than
ever before. Among other things, the White House is seeking
expanded grants of conservation funds to states for purchasing
ecologically sensitive lands; federal payments to cities for
controlling the air pollutants that cause global warming; tax
credits to make it cheaper for local authorities to issue bonds for
environmental purposes; and bigger federal contributions to state
revolving funds that pay for municipal water treatment. By John H.
Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `w` category.)
</P>
<P>
   WEALTHY-CEMETERY (New York) _ In a cemetery in the Hamptonson
Long Island, one wealthy family has essentially tied up all the
available real estate.
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA-ONLINE (Undated) _ With 15 million subscribers, America
Online is now the gateway to cyberspace for more Americans than the
next 15 largest Internet service providers combined, according to a
report released last week by the International Data Corp., a market
research firm. This week, announcing strong earnings, the company
said 1.6 million accounts were added in the last three months of
1998 alone. But some members have begun to chafe at its definition
of civility, or at least the way it seems sometimes arbitrarily
applied. And some civil liberties advocates are scrutinizing the
service more closely as a new breed of institution that governs
speech and yet is immune from First Amendment claims. By Amy
Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PROMOTION (Philadelphia) _ Fear of being kept back in
school is intense these days. Nationwide, many schoolchildren
either heard, or heard about, President Clinton's State of the
Union speech in which he advocated federal financial rewards for
schools that end the policy known as social promotion, or moving
children from grade to grade regardless of their performance. Most
education experts say social promotion has not been widespread for
years. Philadelphia, like Los Angeles, Chicago, and other cities,
is already moving in that direction, adopting tougher academic
standards for promotion, and creating programs as part of a
comprehensive policy to phase in higher academic standards. By
Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
