<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-TRAILER-PARK-2TAK     01-30 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-TRAILER-PARK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY HOMEOWNERS AT NEW YORK CITY'S LONE TRAILER PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Griswold!'' cried Bill Henrich. ``You know they
don't like loose pets!''
</P>
<P>
   The dog scurried back onto the porch, having run up against one
of the many rules that regulate Henrich's pristine community: Dogs
must be leashed inside the premises. Lawns must be kept mowed. Cars
cannot be repaired in the street. Drivers must obey the
seven-mile-per-hour speed limit. Potential residents must undergo
strict financial scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Such strictures are common to co-ops, gated communities and
similarly elite, and expensive, housing. But Henrich, a 47-year-old
bus driver at La Guardia Airport, lives in a mobile-home park _ the
city's only one _ perched on the far western edge of Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   In the popular imagination, the term ``trailer park'' suggests
downward mobility, the back end of the American dream. In fact,
over the last few decades federal regulations have raised the
quality of mobile homes, now known formally as manufactured
housing. To many Americans, they represent the first rung of
homeownership.
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly true for some of the 128 homeowners who live
in the Goethals Garden Homes Community, a semirural slice of land
near the Goethals Bridge. And to working-class New Yorkers, for
whom a tight housing market often means choosing among overpriced
and unattractive options, the lure is particularly powerful: The
mobile homes offer more space for less money than do most
apartments, as well as privacy and a peace hard to come by
elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It beats anywhere,'' said Lourdes Espinoza, who between rent
for the land and the mortgage on her three-bedroom mobile home has
been paying $700 a month. Her family is growing, so she is planning
to move, but for young couples with small families, or retirees,
the park is ideal, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The park may seem to be an experiment worth duplicating in a
city ever in search of creative housing solutions, but that seems
unlikely: Zoning regulations passed in the early 1960s ban trailer
parks. So, while the state now has 1,985 registered trailer parks
containing 86,737 units, New York City has exactly one.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-acre Goethals park was established in 1969 by two
brothers, Fred and Frank DeDomenico, who took advantage of a zoning
loophole permitting mobile-home parks on land zoned for
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   After the brothers had started developing the site, the City
Planning Commission closed the loophole, and they had to file suit
to continue. After five years, they won, and in the early 1980s
tenants began moving in.
</P>
<P>
   The location has its drawbacks: The park lies in a flight path
and next to the Staten Island Expressway, and its back end abuts a
mosquito-friendly marsh. Smells from the Fresh Kills landfill and
industrial areas occasionally waft over the park, Ms. Espinoza
said. And many residents face a long commute: It can take Henrich,
for example, up to two hours to get home from work.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the rules. One relatively new resident, who would
not give his name during an recent interview, complained that he
was not allowed to lay a concrete path outside his door or install
a wood-burning stove, and he had to keep the wheels of his trailer
covered.
</P>
<P>
   But most residents say the rules have helped save the place. In
1995, the park was more than half-empty, and the community was
crumbling. A rent strike had soured relations between the owner at
the time and tenants. Many of them, fearing that the park would be
sold, panicked and moved out. Maintenance and sanitary conditions
were on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Seventh Garden Park Limited Partnership bought
the park, and Garden Homes Management Corporation, which owns 70
trailer parks in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, took over
management. Garden Homes put several hundred thousand dollars into
upgrading the park, said Helene Stancato, director of the company's
manufactured-housing division, repaving the roads, adding street
lights and ``heavily'' upgrading the sewage treatment plant. It
also lowered the rent, which is now $410 a month including sewage,
garbage and water service; taxes, and grounds maintenance.
(Residents own their homes but lease the land.)
</P>
<P>
   And it established, in a park where homes are about 25 feet
apart, what Ms. Stancato calls ``reasonable rules for community
living,'' rules like, ``You can't let dogs poop on other people's
places,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the park is full and the bad feelings are gone.
Maintenance problems are quickly dispatched, residents say, and the
grounds are nearly immaculate.
</P>
<P>
   The determination to preserve order is visible at the park's
front edge, where signs on the fence list the various regulations
about dogs and cars and decorous signs announce, ``E-F Row,'' ``G-H
Row'' and so on. Each row consists of perfectly aligned homes of
virtually identical rectangular contours, all with clapboard siding
and pointed shingle roofs. The visual effect is that of a small
Levittown.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their prefabricated nature, the homes have been
inimitably individualized. Some have open porches, some have
screened porches, and some have small storage sheds in the rear.
They have been painted yellow or blue or beige or white, and the
small lawns are bedecked with dolls or animals or Madonnas or
``Welcome'' signs. Some have little fountains and fish ponds in the
front. The park is relentlessly cheerful, and almost eerily
tranquil.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For many residents, that is the lure.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Soto, 35, moved to Garden Homes two years ago, after 15
years in the Sunset Park section of Brooklyn. There, life was full
of noise and commotion, and enough danger to make his children
virtual prisoners in their apartment, he said. A few years ago, on
the Fourth of July, the children looked out the window and saw a
shooting. ``My wife said, `It's time to get out of here,''' said
Soto, a doorman in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   At Garden Homes, his two boys are free to ride their bikes along
the paved roads. He has a porch, and a shed he built himself; next
season, he wants to add a deck. Inside, the Sotos have a washer and
dryer, a big closet and more space _ including three bedrooms and a
300-square-foot living room _ than they could afford in Sunset
Park. The total price: $43,000, including taxes. The requirement
that residents own, not rent, keeps things orderly, he said. ``When
you own, you take care of things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another relative newcomer from Brooklyn is Raymond Morales, 56,
who moved from Canarsie a year ago with his wife, Olga, and their
15-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said: ``People say, `You live in a trailer park,' like
it's a slum. It's mostly professional, hard-working people.''
</P>
<P>
   A security officer for Citibank in Brooklyn, Morales was paying
rent of $1,200 a month in Canarsie. ``I said, `Let me buy my own
thing,''' he recalled. He spotted the park from the road while
driving by.
</P>
<P>
   For $47,500, he bought a home. He has his own driveway to park
his three cars. He has central heat and air conditioning, two
bedrooms, one-and-a-half bathrooms, a washer and dryer, a spacious
living room and a kitchen. His mortgage is $275 a month; his rent
$410, bringing the total to $685.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' he said. ``We are out of the jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   John Wildrick, 66, has watched the park sag and then rebound
from the front porch of the mobile home he moved to 16 years ago. A
former typewriter mechanic _ ``I worked on every typewriter in the
book'' _ he gave up his two-story home elsewhere on Staten Island
after he was struck by a degenerative muscle disease. He now uses a
motorized scooter to get around.
</P>
<P>
   The strike and associated court battles were a ``regular
mess-up,'' he said, speaking in his faux-wood-paneled living room,
pink curtains catching the light behind him. The lesson, he said,
was that ``here, people have to work together a little.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the park's residents seem to have knit a workable
community fabric, in which families largely keep to themselves but
respect each other's differences. Henrich noted that the park
accommodates a surprising diversity of residents. ``Blacks, whites,
all kinds of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it should be,'' he said, adding, ``Not that I'm
a liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Henrich's parents were among those who fled after the rent
strike; they took their mobile home to New Jersey. But Henrich
liked the park, so he bought his own home and stayed behind. He
said he would stay in the park as long as he could.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard rumors that the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey might take the land to build a second Goethals bridge, but
Greg Trevor, a spokesman for the authority, said a new span would
not affect the Garden Homes property.
</P>
<P>
   That is good news for Henrich. ``I don't know where I could
go,'' he said. ``I don't know what else I could afford.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
