<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-INMATE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENCY FOR KILLER SURPRISES MANY WHO FOLLOWED CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REEDS SPRING, Mo. _ For three days, hiding in a hunting blind,
wearing camouflage and face paint, the killer lay in wait. Then, on
a gravel path snaking through the dense woods of this hilly Ozark
town, he saw the victims and he pounced.
</P>
<P>
   He ambushed them as they trundled down the path on their
all-terrain vehicles _ a 69-year-old man who the authorities say
was the killer's former drug partner, the man's 56-year-old wife
and the couple's 19-year-old grandson, a paraplegic who had to be
tied to his vehicle to drive it.
</P>
<P>
   The killer, Darrell Mease, shot all three with a shotgun from
about 30 feet away and then, for good measure, he got up very close
and shot each one in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Folks around here say there has rarely been a more cold-blooded
killing in this part of Missouri, a rustic stretch of country just
over the Arkansas border.
</P>
<P>
   And so it seemed all the more unusual that Gov. Mel Carnahan, a
proponent of capital punishment, would allow himself to be swayed
by a request from the visiting Pope John Paul II and decide to
commute Mease's sentence to life without parole just two weeks
before he was to die by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of the defense lawyers who has been handling the legal
appeals of Mease's death sentence could not conceal his surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, this case was probably one of the weaker
clemency cases,'' said the lawyer, Kent Gipson. ``In this case
there were no real claims of mental illness, no question of guilt.
It was a triple murder. He had one argument dealing with
post-traumatic stress from Vietnam, but really he had a snowball's
chance in hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Gipson said he could name ``lots of others,'' including people
already executed, who were much more sympathetic candidates for
clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess timing is everything, huh?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mease's unwitting good fortune began in November when the
Missouri Supreme Court scheduled him to die on Jan. 27, which would
have been the second day of the scheduled two-day visit to St.
Louis by the pope, the leader of a church whose doctrine staunchly
opposes the death penalty. A few days after it set the execution
date, the court abruptly changed it to Feb. 10. The court offered
no explanation, but the move was widely interpreted as a way to
avoid such a glaringly uncomfortable coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   While he was in St. Louis, the pope urged Carnahan, in person
and through an aide, to spare the life of Mease, who is 52, and
also made public appeals against the death penalty. And Carnahan,
who has approved 26 executions since he took office in 1993, said
he was so moved by the pope's entreaties that he decided to make
one exception.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the decision was not very popular among
those who knew the victims, Lloyd and Frankie Lawrence and their
grandson, William, who lived in the town of Shell Knob, about 25
miles southwest of Reeds Spring.
</P>
<P>
   George Marion, who described himself as one of Lloyd Lawrence's
``closest buddies,'' said that if he could get close enough to the
pope, ``I'd cock him straight and sure in the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lawrence, son of Lloyd and Frankie, said that what upset
him was not that Mease's life was being spared; he was angry that
no official had called to inform him of the change in plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, we told the jury that we'd be fine with
whatever they worked out, whether it was death or life in prison,''
Lawrence said. ``What bothered us is that we did not hear from
anyone. As far as I'm concerned, the governor and the pope are
showing more mercy towards a convicted killer than towards us.''
</P>
<P>
   But here in Reeds Spring, where the population of 411 has been
preoccupied lately with the indictment of the mayor on charges that
he persuaded a 15-year-old girl and other minors to engage in
sexually explicit conduct while he photographed them, people seemed
more astonished than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so amazing that someone would be in prison for
murder from such a small place as Reeds Spring, and then the pope,
from Rome you know, would be here and all these events would come
together,'' said Terry Teague, 41, who owns a sign shop in town.
</P>
<P>
   Few people in this part of Missouri are Roman Catholic; many are
of fundamentalist Christian faiths. And like many people here,
Teague described himself as a supporter of the death penalty but
said that because he knew Mease's family, he sympathized with them.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that sometime before the 1988 murders, Mease, a
carpenter and handyman, had begun working for the elder Lawrence,
whom they described as one of the region's primary makers of the
drug methamphetamine. Lawrence, who owned wooded property in Reeds
Spring, also ran illegal cock fights.
</P>
<P>
   James Justus, the Taney County prosecutor on the case, said that
Mease got involved in Lawrence's drug operation, but that the two
had a falling out and Mease stole six two-liter Pepsi bottles full
of methamphetamine worth thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Justus said, Mease fled, believing Lawrence had put
out a contract on his life. But he got tired of running, Justus
said, and decided to come back and kill Lawrence and take over the
drug business himself.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1988, Mease hiked into the woods on Lawrence's property
and ambushed the Lawrences. Mease, whose girlfriend testified
against him, confessed to the murders, but on appeal said his
confession had been obtained illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Justus said he supported the governor's right to commute a death
sentence, but was disappointed that he chose this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hard decision to go for the death penalty,''
Justus said, adding that in the 20 murder cases he has tried, he
has asked for the death penalty in only one case besides the Mease
case, and his request was not granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made that decision and convinced 12 jurors and a judge it
was the right decision,'' Justus said of the Mease case. ``We've
also spent the last nine years arguing his appeals and have
convinced every one of them it was the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In Reeds Spring, Mease's mother, Lexie, who described herself as
a devout Pentecostal, said she believed all along that her son's
sentence would be commuted, ever since he had a conversion soon
after his arrest. She also believes he will be let out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to be in the position he was in so he can come out and
do God's work,'' Mrs. Mease said. ``By being there, he can
understand what it is to be in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mease had apparently believed he would be spared, deciding
not to make funeral plans to avoid suggesting he did not have faith
that God would save him.
</P>
<P>
   But Mease's younger brother, Larry, 51, said his own convictions
had been less sure. Until his brother was on death row, Larry Mease
had been a death penalty proponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was looking at the victims' side,'' he said. ``It's
different when you're on the other side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
