<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS HOPE PLAN FOR TAX CUT WILL UNITE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Minn., Mo., Mich.)  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In placing income-tax reductions at the heart of
their agenda this year, Republican leaders are hoping to rally
their fractious party around an issue they have long believed is
economically sound as well as politically appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stars in many ways are lined up in the Republicans'
favor _ the federal government's coffers are overflowing _ they
face a difficult battle to enact their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some Republicans acknowledge that their real goal this
year is to force a debate on a big tax cut, pass it even if
President Clinton is sure to veto it, and use the issue to define
what their party stands for heading into the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will lose if we don't have an agenda that includes bold
examples of economic common sense,'' said Frank Luntz, a Republican
pollster who has long argued that taxes are the most powerful issue
available to the party. ``This is not only good politics but
honest, good Republican principle.''
</P>
<P>
   The skirmishing over fiscal policy as the nation moves from an
era of huge budget deficits to one of projected surpluses will
intensify on Monday, when Clinton sends Congress his budget
proposals for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The president has framed the debate in a way that suggests
cutting taxes would imperil efforts to ensure the viability of the
Social Security and Medicare systems, a political maneuver that
Republicans say is misleading but that nonetheless could be hard
for them to counter.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also say that an across-the-board reduction in the tax
rate would favor the rich over the middle class, a longstanding
argument but one that continues to put Republicans on the
defensive. Moreover, Democrats have their own agenda of narrowly
drawn tax cuts intended to help specific groups like parents with
children, an approach they hope will neutralize the political
advantage Republicans have long held on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   There are encouraging signs for the Democrats. A survey this
month by the Pew Research Center asked which party had the best
ideas on tax cuts. The Democrats were favored over Republicans, 45
percent to 32 percent, roughly the same breakdowns as on
traditional Democratic issues like education, Social Security and
patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public overwhelmingly favors saving Social Security to tax
cuts and prefers targeted tax cuts as a means of solving problems
to across-the-board tax cuts,'' said Mark Mellman, a Democratic
strategist. ``The basic fact is that the Republicans have run out
of compelling things to say to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Confident that tax-cutting remains a potent issue for them,
Republicans are piecing together their initial legislative
tax-cutting proposals. Republican aides said Sen. Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, the chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, would
introduce a plan soon under which income-tax rates could be cut as
much as 14 percent across the board over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the cuts would be phased in slowly. For next year, the cut
would probably be no more than 1 percent, building to as much as 4
percent in 2002 and 14 percent in 2009.
</P>
<P>
   The Domenici plan is based on estimates of budget surpluses
released on Friday by the Congressional Budget Office. Those
estimates showed that the government would have an overall surplus
of nearly $2.7 trillion from this year through 2009. Most of the
surplus is accounted for by excess payroll-tax revenues that are
earmarked for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But starting in 2001, the government will begin running a
surplus even without relying on revenues from the Social Security
payroll tax, money that Republicans say makes it possible to cut
taxes without endangering Social Security. Under that accounting,
the budget surplus over the next decade that does not come from
Social Security taxes would be nearly $800 billion, and Domenici is
considering using about $640 billion of that to reduce income-tax
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams of Minnesota is working on a 10 percent
across-the-board rate cut that could be phased in more quickly than
Domenici envisions. Former Vice President Dan Quayle advocates a 30
percent across-the-board rate cut.
</P>
<P>
   Enacting a 10 percent across-the-board reduction would reduce
the current top rate of 39.6 percent to 35.6 percent, and the 28
percent rate to 25.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Income-tax rate reductions across the board are one of the few
issues on which economic and social conservatives are united,
Republicans said, and one of the best ways for the party to hammer
home its message that the government should be smaller and less
intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The across-the-board tax cut says Washington doesn't have all
the answers,'' Grams said, ``and it ensures that your family's
dollars are spent on family priorities, not on Washington's
spending schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic argument over income-tax rate reductions centers on
whether it is fair to low- and middle-income workers, and on
whether tax cuts are the best way of bringing more economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   A study this month by Citizens for Tax Justice, a
liberal-leaning research organization, found that 62 percent of the
benefits of a 10 percent across-the-board income-tax reduction
would go to the wealthiest 10 percent of the population. The bottom
60 percent would get less than 10 percent of the benefits of the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than embracing the administration's plan for saving
Social Security now and strengthening Medicare,'' said Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader in the House,
Republicans are intent on pushing through ``a massive GOP tax cut
for the wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were resigned to similar Democratic
attacks throughout the debate. But they said there is a strong case
to be made that an across-the-board rate cut would be a good thing
for the economy, as it would stimulate more consumption and
savings. And they said tax cuts would surely be fairer and more
productive than allowing Democrats to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When, if not now, would we cut taxes?'' said Sen. Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich. ``If we can see trillions of dollars in surplus in
the years ahead, when will we ever have a day in which there isn't
some new program or old program, or some new idea that somebody
comes up with, that somehow warrants keeping the money here.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Republicans have been united in rallying
around an income-tax cut. But their tax-cutting agenda fell victim
last year to squabbling within the party's ranks, and some
Republicans remain wary of Clinton's ability to maneuver them into
a situation in which they do not manage to pass the kind of big tax
cut they are discussing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one risk for Republicans, and it's a significant
one,'' said Luntz. ``That is to promise the public a tax cut and
then not deliver. It's one thing for Bill Clinton to veto it. It's
another to talk about it and then not pass it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
