<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HONGKONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG RULING MAY OPEN DOOR FROM CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a landmark decision that could open this enclave
to thousands of mainland Chinese, a court ruled Friday that four
children born in China to Hong Kong parents have the right to live
here.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing the children to stay, Hong Kong's Court of Final
Appeal asserted that local laws take precedence over mainland
Chinese laws, which make it extremely difficult for people born in
the mainland to move to Hong Kong, even if their parents are
residents of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Chinese fit that definition. And officials
here said they expected a flood of mainland residents would now try
to enter Hong Kong, either by legal means or by sneaking across the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means, potentially, the pool of persons in the mainland
eligible for right of abode in Hong Kong will be substantially
greater than our original estimate,'' said Regina Ip, the secretary
of security.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong became part of China on July 1, 1997, the
territory remains off limits to most mainland Chinese. China and
Hong Kong impose strict immigration laws because both sides fear
that Hong Kong, with its high wages and living standard, will
become a magnet for people from the poorer mainland. People who
travel between Hong Kong and China must still pass through
checkpoints that bristle with guards, searchlights and razor-sharp
fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got 1.2 billion people north of the border, at least
200 million of whom would love to live here,'' said Michael
DeGolyer, a professor of government at Baptist University in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Before the handover, though, Hong Kong made an exception to its
rules for children of Hong Kong residents who were born on the
mainland. Under the terms of its constitution, the Basic Law, Hong
Kong granted those people the right to live in the territory. More
than 40,000 people _ the majority of them children _ moved here and
claimed residency.
</P>
<P>
   That loophole was closed after the handover, when China
dissolved Hong Kong's democratically elected legislature and
replaced it with a Beijing-appointed assembly. Among the new
legislature's first acts was to tighten the immigration
regulations, so that children of Hong Kong parents would have to
apply for permission to live here from the mainland Chinese
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the children, who range from 8 to 20 years old, sued
the Hong Kong government _ contending that the new rules violated
the Basic Law, which guarantees the territory a high degree of
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Friday, Hong Kong's highest court struck down the
rules, which means the children do not have to return to China.
Moreover, children of Hong Kong parents who currently live in China
can apply to courts here rather than in China for the right to move
to the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-democracy leaders applauded the ruling as a ringing
affirmation of Hong Kong's judicial independence, at a time when
other recent cases have raised fears that the courts here were
surrendering their authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS31-COX     01-30 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: Researchers fight to stay a step ahead of the
AIDS virus' ability to take on new forms
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago, Bruce Almond learned he was out of
options.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old Inman Park resident, who tested positive for HIV
in 1990, underwent a test in January 1997 that indicated he had
developed resistance to just about every AIDS drug on the market.
In other words, they would no longer work.
</P>
<P>
   But Almond was optimistic. He had never progressed to full-blown
AIDS. The amount of virus in his blood was reassuringly low. He was
healthy and vigorous; he could have passed for someone 10 years
younger.
</P>
<P>
   So he and his doctor decided he would stay on his HIV
medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor didn't really change the cocktail around,'' Almond
said. ``He said, `Let's just stick with what we've got.'''
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS virus is clumsy. And that may be one of its greatest
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   When HIV copies itself, as it endlessly does in the human body,
it is liable to make mistakes. These mistakes change the virus'
genetic blueprint ever so slightly _ enough to create a
drug-resistant version of the virus, much harder to treat.
</P>
<P>
   This genetic sleight of hand is nothing new to doctors, who face
it with other infectious diseases. What dismays AIDS specialists
and their patients, though, is the frightening swiftness with which
HIV can mutate and shield itself against anti-HIV drugs. Just a few
missed doses can allow a person's infection to resurge _ often in a
less vulnerable form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the resistance issue is a major one, and will remain
a critical one for a while,'' said Dr. Mark Feinberg, associate
director of AIDS research at Emory University's Rollins School of
Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   HIV resistance will be a major topic at this week's Conference
on Retroviruses and Opportunistic Infections in Chicago, where more
than 3,000 AIDS doctors and researchers will discuss advances and
obstacles in HIV treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the discussion will focus on a relatively new tool, HIV
resistance testing, and whether it can help physicians predict the
success or failure of drug treatment. Genetics laboratories and
pharmaceutical firms are pushing the technological envelope in
developing and honing these resistance tests, which they say could
_ and should _ become a routine part of HIV care.
</P>
<P>
   Yet AIDS specialists are divided over the usefulness of these
tests. They do agree on one thing: Once resistance begins,
patients' options diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical roulette
</P>
<P>
   When a person taking anti-HIV drugs develops drug resistance,
the virus is no longer held in check. Mutated, resistant forms of
HIV quickly proliferate. If enough resistant virus is present, the
patient may have to change drugs _ if other drugs still are
options.
</P>
<P>
   Only 14 anti-HIV drugs have Food and Drug Administration
approval. Optimally, the drugs should be taken in combinations of
two, three or more. But resistance to one anti-HIV drug often
confers cross-resistance to other drugs in the same class, further
reducing options.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had hoped that protease inhibitors, the powerful class
of drugs that revolutionized HIV therapy a few years ago and led to
dramatic drops in U.S. AIDS deaths, wouldn't show significant
cross-resistance. But they do.
</P>
<P>
   Now, doctors and patients must play a perilous game of chemical
roulette, switching drugs to find a regimen that the patient can
tolerate and that HIV can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic theme is, the more drugs a person has been treated
with, the less likely he will respond,'' Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Because even a brief halt in drug therapy, via missed doses, can
allow resistance to develop, patients must follow strict dosing
routines. That can be difficult because a typical regimen can
require five separate doses with numerous pills, some to be taken
on an empty stomach, others with meals. The drugs also have severe,
sometimes intolerable, side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors frequently pin drug resistance on non-adherent patients,
which frustrates people who have followed their regimens. ``I've
never missed a dose, ever,'' said Brandon Abernathy, 38, of East
Point, who has been HIV-positive for at least 17 years. He recently
changed his therapy after being tested for resistance. ``I've never
been more than an hour late, and I can count those times on one
hand. I eat when I'm supposed to. I'm educated about this disease.
That's why I've lived so damn long.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially frightening is that people are starting to become
infected with HIV strains already resistant to several drugs. ``You
can imagine how terrible a situation that is for someone,'' said
Feinberg. ``Not only are you infected, but most of the drugs we
have won't work for you. It puts us back where we were 10 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   A 'show-me field'
</P>
<P>
   HIV resistance tests fall into two categories. Genotypic tests
genetically map part of the particular strain of HIV infecting a
person and look for key mutations believed to correlate to
resistance against specific drugs. Phenotypic tests assess how
various drugs directly perform against particular viral strains.
The tests cost hundreds of dollars, and none has been approved by
the FDA, so insurance companies won't always pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that perform resistance tests say they should be a
vital tool in formulating ``drug cocktails'' for people with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many physicians are extremely good at almost intuitively
knowing what to give the patients,'' said virologist Paul Feorino,
who is the laboratory director at Applied Sciences in Norcross,
which performs genotypic resistance testing. ``Now we give them the
tool so they can make the rational choice, rather than trying to
guess from their experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many noted AIDS physicians, including Feinberg, dispute the
tests' worth. They say the tests aren't sensitive enough, that not
enough is known about how HIV's genetic mutations translate into
real-life clinical outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resistance testing would be useful if you could reliably
predict whether someone is going to respond to a different
combination of drugs than the one they're being treated with,''
Feinberg said. ``But even if it were to prove to be useful, you
still need drugs to switch people to,'' he continued. ``You want
people to be healthier and live longer. You don't want to document
helplessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors don't need resistance tests to determine whether a
patient's drugs have quit working. An increasing viral load _ or
worse, an AIDS-related illness _ is a good indicator. The doctor
then must come up with alternatives, which may not exist.
</P>
<P>
   And this may be why AIDS doctors haven't fully embraced the
concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut reaction is that we're much better off knowing the
patient's resistance profile,'' said Dr. John Mellors, an AIDS
expert from the University of Pittsburgh. ``But proving that has
yet to be done in a trial. There has to be a strong correlation
between resistance testing and response to the therapies. This
field is a show-me field.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies to be presented at this week's conference on
retroviruses may help establish that correlation. Visible Genetics,
the parent company of Applied Sciences, believes research data are
solid enough to support FDA approval for its test, said Robert M.
Lloyd Jr., Applied Sciences' scientific director.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, those who already have developed total drug
resistance can't wait for the next new AIDS drug, but must make do
with what they have. ``Even someone who gets a resistance test that
says they're not going to respond to a given combination of drugs,
and that's the last combination available, I'm sure every physician
in their right mind would give them a chance and try them,''
Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   For some, a wait for new drugs
</P>
<P>
   Almond's luck didn't last. Recently, he sipped Ensure to try to
restore some of the 40 pounds he lost during his first AIDS-related
hospital stay, over Christmas and New Year's. He suffered a staph
infection, pneumonia and peripheral neuropathy, which causes
numbness or intense pain in the hands and legs. ``I didn't even
want to look in a mirror for a while,'' Almond said, his voice
shaky but cheerfully determined. ``But I think I'm on the mend.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been off anti-HIV medication for more than a month, on
doctor's orders, because in his weakened state he couldn't bear the
drugs' side effects. Now, he wants to go back on medication and be
retested for drug resistance. ``I feel like that's too long for me
to be off anti-retrovirals,'' Almond said. ``The virus might be
going wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have developed multi-drug resistance anxiously await
new HIV drugs, several of which are on the horizon. There's no
guarantee the drugs will work for them, but with AIDS, no one
expects guarantees. ``If you're almost dead, they'll try
anything,'' Abernathy said. ``They'll do anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
