<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5179 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER31-COX     01-30 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: `I didn't know a man could get breast cancer'
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A bruise, maybe a burn. It had to be one
or the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was an odd, comes-and-goes annoyance in any case: A bit of
soreness in the chest that didn't hurt much unless you poked it or
rolled over on it. Not the sort of thing a man worries about. Not a
busy man like Ron Stickney.
</P>
<P>
   Even in retirement, the guy never stops.
</P>
<P>
   He volunteers with the Red Cross, rides with the Citizens
Observer Patrol. He serves on the altar every Sunday morning at
Mary Immaculate Catholic Church, and calls bingo every Monday night
at his community clubhouse. Plus all those Moose, Elks, Eagles and
Knights of Columbus meetings.
</P>
<P>
   That's how so much time passed in a flash after his early
retirement as production supervisor at the GM radiator plant in
upstate New York (35 years and never sick a day).
</P>
<P>
   It was three years before he got around to finding a doctor near
his Cypress Lakes home just outside West Palm Beach. He remembers
the date of that routine checkup: Dec. 16, 1996. He was 59 years
old. He waited until the very end of the exam to mention the
soreness that had started a month before.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered: Could it have anything to do with the oddly
inverted nipple he noticed, oh, six months or so back?
</P>
<P>
   It took three days to get the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advanced breast cancer,'' Stickney says, still sounding
amazed. ``I didn't know a man could get breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like most of the 1,600 American men who will get the same
news this year. He had three weeks to absorb the meaning of
``malignant neoplasm of the male left breast'' before surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That was the easy part: In and out of the hospital in one
morning, Jan. 7, 1997. A simple scar; one nipple gone. You'd hardly
look twice.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part was getting at the cancer below that had already
invaded the bone and moved on: Six months of chemotherapy, 28
radiation treatments for the chest, 47 more for the ribs, back and
right arm.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Stickney did his best to keep up his usual pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cancer can really prey on you, boggle the mind,'' he
says. ``If you keep busy, you keep your mind off it.''
</P>
<P>
   But not entirely. He wanted to know more about the disease, but
everything he read was written for women. ``It was pretty
frustrating,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered if there was some way to help spread the word. Soon
after his surgery, under heavy chemical and radiation bombardment,
he read about Race for the Cure, the annual fund-raiser for the
South Florida Chapter of the Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd like to be part of it,'' he says. ``But the more
I read, the more I thought that was all about women, too. I decided
to forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It came back to him, though, when he read about this year's
race. He's 61 now and feeling a lot better _ a little weak, a
little puffy from steroids and other medicine, but strong enough to
be out on the neighborhood track every day for a brisk, four-mile
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read about this year's Race for the Cure, I really got
engrossed by the idea,'' he says. ``So I called, and they were
really encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to get Jan. 30 penciled in to Ron Stickney's
busy schedule. He'll join the 5K Walk down Flagler Drive today and
then gather with other breast cancer survivors. At least a couple
of the others will be men.
</P>
<P>
   Stickney can't wait for people to ask him about his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a bit embarrassed,'' he says. ``There are probably a
lot more cases out there. Men don't know it can happen so they let
it go. I want to tell them not to wait, like I did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
