<HEADER>
A5182 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-DRUG31-COX     01-30 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-DRUG31-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   HEALTH/SCIENCE: Early tests of anti-depressants seem promising
for dogs
</P>
<P>
   WITH ART on Cox WAN
</P>
<P>
   By Christi Mays
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ After at least a dozen trips to the veterinarian
to get stitches, Barry and Eva Vokes knew they had to do something
to keep their two Doberman pinscher dogs from continually hurting
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time Rex and Prince were loving house dogs who
couldn't stand to be apart from the other. Then, out of the clear
blue, a vicious fight would erupt and the blood would flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, there was no problem at all,'' Barry Vokes
said. ``But more often than we would like, they would go at each
other and we never have been able to figure out what set them off.
One minute they're just peacefully lying there and the next minute,
they're going at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vokeses found themselves in the emergency room of their vet,
Dr. Layne Gregory of Hewitt Animal Clinic, at all hours of the day
_ and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very expensive patching them up,'' Vokes said.
</P>
<P>
   The veterinarian put the dogs on an anti-depressant drug called
amitriptyline, also known as Elavil. The drug is similar to a newly
labeled anti-depressant drug the federal government approved
recently for dogs called Clomicalm by Novartis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a definite improvement,'' Vokes said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the dogs were put on the twice-daily medication, there
have been no major fights and no midnight trips to the vet, Eva
Vokes said. The only visit the Vokes have made to the vet has been
for checkups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we've been giving it to them, the skirmishes are few and
far between,'' said Gregory, an 18-year veterinarian. ``They
haven't been depressed, sedated or changed in personality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't affected them at all that we can tell,'' Barry Vokes
added.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-depressant also has helped curb Rex's compulsive
chewing, Eva Vokes added.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chewed on a lot of things,'' she said. ``Without the
medication, the walls got holes in them and the chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Gregory, veterinarians for years have been
prescribing anti-depressants such as amitriptyline and Prozac to
dogs and cats with anxiety disorders and behavior problems, such as
aggression, fear and inappropriate waste elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's five or six drugs that work well,'' Gregory said.
``All seem to have a good track record. What's good about them,
they do help these guys live a happier life. It can get them over
some rough spots.''
</P>
<P>
   The approval to label Clomicalm as a drug that relieves
separation anxiety in dogs has drawn considerable publicity and
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hot topic of vet meetings for years,'' said Dr.
Robert Barkley, owner of Animal Clinic and a vet for 25 years.
``(Clomicalm) is kind of controversial right now between doctors
and drug companies because it stimulates an unbelievable amount of
interest and questions, which is good because everybody needs to be
educated on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that there's a drug labeled as an animal anti-depressant
that will help with behavioral problems, such as separation
anxiety, some fear owners and even some veterinarians will be
looking for a ``quick fix'' for an unruly pet.
</P>
<P>
   Before any drugs are administered, Barkley and Gregory agree,
that all other options should be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   If pet owners are having problems with a dog or cat, they also
need to examine any changes that might have upset the animal's
life, such as a recent move, a new baby in the household, a
divorce, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reason for separation anxiety in dogs is that
owners don't spend enough time with their pet, Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, don't expect a pill to solve a problem of owners not
spending enough time with their dog,'' he said. ``No. 2, if we use
medicine or an anti-depressant, use it after we've ruled out
internal physiological problems and medical problems and use it in
combination with behavior modification. . . Many times, these drugs
are supposed to be used in combination with behavior modification.
That's a biggy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some veterinarians will be reluctant to jump on the
Clomicalm bandwagon until other vets have paved the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to see me practicing on my clients until
there's been a million doses given,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Having been a vet for 25 years, he said he's used new drugs and
procedures that have later come back to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play this very cautiously,'' he said, explaining that
sometimes a new cure can relieve one symptom but cause other
problems in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Both veterinarians said dogs and cats are usually tapered off
antidepressant drugs after a couple of months and many never have
to be placed on them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually these kinds of problems are more short-lived,''
Gregory said. ``This simply helps the animal feel more normal.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are times he's seen these drugs fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they just don't work at all,'' he said. ``Just like
with people, sometimes they don't work every time. But it seems
like the failures are the exception rather than the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, anti-depressant drugs have been the only solution
that saved a dog or cat's life, Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some animals can be such a problem, their owners were going to
take them to the pound or put them to sleep, he said. ``I've seen
these drugs save a lot of dogs and cats and get them out of a bad
situation.''
</P>
