<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASS-CLASS31-COX     01-30 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-CLASS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fishing schools in session
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rich Tauber, the energetic professional bass fisherman
from Woodland Hills, Calif., quickly rigs a soft plastic bait Texas
style, the silhouette of his tying projected overhead for the 200
knowledge-thirsty anglers in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Tauber, noted for his mastery of finesse fishing and other
techniques born out West, swings the lure in front of a man sitting
in the front row and jiggles it at eye level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, my man,'' Tauber says, ``How long can you put up
with me shaking this in your face like that?''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupts in laughter, but Tauber's point is well-made.
This ``doodling'' technique _ dropped straight down into a brush
pile _ is murder on Kentucky bass, known as spotted bass on Lake
Lanier, where they are most abundant in Georgia. ``Just think what
it does to those Kentucky bass,'' Tauber continues. ``I'm talking
about those bass can't stand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those attending last Saturday's sessions of the BASS
Fishing Techniques Institute '99, sponsored by the Bass Angler's
Sportsman Society and hosted by Kennesaw State University, tried
feverishly to follow Tauber's presentation, watching the overhead
projector and Tauber while keeping notes at the same time. Some
even glanced over the shoulder of the next person to see what he
wrote down, almost like cheating on a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of ideas from the West, completely new ways of
fishing,'' said James Clark of Suwanee, a former Memphis
firefighter who's new to Atlanta and to Lake Lanier. ``The
doodling's got me curious.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauber was one of six professionals-turned-instructors for the
two-day bass class, held last week at the Wyndham Garden Hotel in
Marietta, which attracted anglers of all skill levels, from the
beginner to the budding pro. Tauber joined other well-known pros
Alton Jones, Jack Hains, Larry Nixon, Greg Hines and Gerald
Swindle, to give tips on all facets of bass fishing in a
classroom-like atmosphere. The class, one of nearly 50 such
seminars held around the nation through the winter months, cost
$89, laughter included at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys aren't just instructors, they're entertainers,''
said Terry Faust, director of student financial aid at Kennesaw
State, a volunteer in running the seminar and an avid bass
fisherman on Lake Allatoona. ``This has been as much fun as
informative.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was well attended despite the severe weather last week.
The strongest storms roared through Georgia early Saturday morning,
forcing many of the attendees to drive through wind and rain, which
shows how serious some people are about catching bass.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Higdon and his 10-year-old son Josh got up at 4:30 a.m. to
drive the three-plus hours from Oldfort, Tenn., right through the
teeth of the storms. The heavy rain slowed them to 25 mph several
times, but the trip was worth the hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh is just getting into fishing,'' said Allen Higdon, who
frequently fishes the Tennessee River system. ``This will help him
learn to catch more and maybe help keep him out of trouble.'' Josh
then joked he can catch more fish than his dad. ``Son, you're going
to need more than this class to whip me,'' the father said
</P>
<P>
   Josh later added, ``I could do this class five days a week,
seven hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The class had several husband-wife duos, taking advantage of the
half-price deal for family members. Allen and Janice Cronan of
Cumming were hoping to figure out what went wrong on a recent trip
to Lake Okeechobee, Fla., during which they basically were shut
out. ``We didn't do so well,'' Allen said, to which Janice added,
``Obviously, our techniques are lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Cronan, a longtime bass fisherman and a member of the
Southern Anglers Bass Club, was surprised by how much he learned in
the seminars, even the basics. ``I learned I was setting the hook
totally wrong,'' Cronan admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Fred and Sharri Hickey, empty-nest parents of five children,
attended the seminar as they embark on a hobby they can share
together. ``She's new to fishing. I'm new to this type of
fishing,'' said Jack, a live-bait angler who has mainly fished for
catfish and bream. ``We just bought our first boat now that our
kids are gone, and we're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the pros learned a few things. ``One thing I like about
these is to come and listen to Jack and Rich,'' said Jones,
referring to Tauber and Hains, the other two instructors Saturday.
``Overall, I think doing these makes me a better fisherman. To help
people learn, we're forced to think out and analyze what we're
trying to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Hains, the 1975 BASS Masters Classic champion, added, ``From Day
1, it's about the basics. That's what we teach. That's what we
shouldn't take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
