</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITING-NOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs waiting on committments
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's recruiting efforts have picked up steam, but
the next few days will determine just how high the Bulldogs' class
will rank on the national level.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who added Middle Georgia Junior College linebacker
Kendrell Bell, wideout Michael Johnson of Tulsa, Okla., and
All-America offensive lineman Alex Jackson of Quincy, Fla., are
still waiting on a handful of nationally ranked prospects.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of that list are three players who could help fill
Georgia's biggest need _ running backs Bruce Thornton of LaGrange,
Nick Maddox of Kannapolis, N.C., and Cedric Cobbs of Little Rock,
Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, a 5-11, 182-pound Super 11 choice by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, will announce his choice between Georgia and
Tennessee on Monday. Thornton, who rushed for 1,920 yards and 28
touchdowns as a senior, eliminated Florida and Auburn, where he
visited this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, ranked the nation's No. 1 tailback prospect by some
recruiting services, made an official visit to the Georgia campus
this week. Maddox, who rushed for 2,574 yards and 34 touchdowns as
a senior, visited Florida State this weekend. He'll choose from
among Georgia, FSU, Florida and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbs, a 6-1, 217-pound Parade All-American, has narrowed his
list to Georgia and Arkansas. Cobbs, who rushed for 2,043 yards and
15 scores last season, is expected to announce his decision on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan also is eagerly awaiting announcements
from wideouts Reggie Brown of Carrollton and Durrell Robinson of
Duncan, S.C. Brown, the Journal-Constitution player of the year,
will choose from among Georgia, Ohio State and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who had 73 catches for 1,386 yards and 28 touchdowns
as a senior, has narrowed his list to Georgia and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs also are hoping for offensive lineman Kevin
Breedlove of Clemson, S.C., who visited Florida this weekend. He
also is considering UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker for Jackets
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech is expected to receive a commitment from Early
County linebacker Recardo Wembush, who also visited Florida,
Florida State and Alabama. Wembush, who had 165 tackles and three
interceptions as a senior, is regarded as the state's top
linebacker prospect.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets lost offensive lineman Ronald Samuel, who
decommitted to Tech and says he'll sign with Auburn on Wednesday.
Tech hosted defensive lineman Greg Gathers of Reserve, La., who
also is considering Southern Methodist and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Americus package for FSU?
</P>
<P>
   Americus High coach Don Ragle said defensive lineman Alonzo
Jackson will announce his commitment Monday. Both Jackson and
quarterback Fabian Walker are believed to be leaning toward Florida
State over Georgia. Walker, who broke the state's all-time passing
mark, also is considering Florida, but he must improve his
standardized test score.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetness for Miami
</P>
<P>
   Miami has landed quarterback Jarrett Payton of St. Viator High
in Arlington Heights, Ill., the son of NFL Hall of Fame running
back Walter Payton. The younger Payton passed for 973 yards and
rushed for another 1,400. He picked the Hurricanes over Indiana,
Penn State, Notre Dame and Wisconsin. ... Memphis got running back
B.J. Edwards of Memphis. ... Ole Miss got Marietta tight end Lee
Jackson and Appling County linebacker Lanier Gothie. ... The
defection of quarterback Chris Simms from Tennessee to Texas might
be just what Creekside defensive end Charles Roberson needed. The
Vols now have a scholarship open, and that might go to Roberson,
who also is considering Mississippi State. ... Westlake receiver
Detronn Harris is visiting Auburn this weekend, and will choose
from the Tigers, Arkansas and SW Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
