<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DUVAL31-COX     01-30 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval's '99 pace is upshift in gear that has PGA trailing his
wake
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Something looked strangely familiar to Johnny Miller
last Sunday as he watched television scenes from the Bob Hope
Chrysler Classic of David Duval's amazing 59 and second win in as
many 1999 starts. Somewhere in the moderately distant folds of his
brain, Miller, who won 11 times over a 24-event stretch in 1974-75
and sent golf's other major stars reaching for extra buckets of
range balls, remembered how it was to lap PGA Tour fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminded me a lot of me,'' Miller, 51, said by telephone
this week from Napa, Calif. ``When you're playing like that, it all
seems so easy. It's like a walk in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Miller was the last fellow to clang a golf ball against
this many flagsticks. To collect tap-in birdies with such insane
frequency. To over a couple of seasons so dramatically dominate the
game. To experience confidence overflowing like the foam from a
beer mug. Duval, with his nearly surreal Sunday at the Bob Hope
Chrysler Classic, has won nine times in 28 events.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger who?
</P>
<P>
   Although golf's idiotic Official World Golf Rankings still leave
Duval at No. 2 and looking up at Woods, who has one PGA Tour win
(Atlanta's BellSouth Classic) since July of 1997, Miller has no
doubt about the former Georgia Tech player's status:
</P>
<P>
   ``He might say to Tiger, `See you. You thought you were the man,
but I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in 1997 when it appeared as though Woods would
earn an oversized cardboard paycheck every time he planted his
spikes into the ground. Now Duval has that same magic, and more.
Granted, with the PGA Tour's ballooning purses, the money earnings
are now impossible to compare, but in two events the 27-year-old
from Jacksonville Beach, Fla., already has passed $1 million and is
13th on the all-time earnings list with nearly $7.5 million.
Clearly, his colleagues must think they are playing with Wiffle
balls. Once, Duval did not know how to win. It took 86 events and
seven runner-up finishes to break through. Now he looks like he
can't lose. Surely, it can't last, but you can't erase being
52-under par for his first eight rounds of the year.
</P>
<P>
   When Duval arrived at the Phoenix Open this week, Justin Leonard
said, ``I was shocked he missed a putt. I think it was the first
putt I've seen him miss since (the President's Cup at) Melbourne.''
</P>
<P>
   The 59 was such an incredible feat for a final day that to watch
it unfold seemed as mind-boggling as the Falcons finding themselves
in a Super Bowl. Golf's historians and observers will argue for
Miller's 63 at Oakmont in the 1973 U.S. Open. Or then-46-year-old
Jack Nicklaus' 65, with a back nine of 30, at the 1986 Masters. Or
Arnold Palmer's 65 at Cherry Hills in 1960 to snag a U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   That they happened in major championships will always allow them
special treatment. That is, perhaps, until Duval starts chewing
through the upcoming Grand Slam schedule.
</P>
<P>
   There had been two other 59s registered in PGA Tour competition,
but they were yawners compared with what Duval accomplished Sunday
in the Bob Hope, assembling a round of golf that bordered on the
ridiculous. Nobody's ever sizzled a Sunday with a 59, coming from
seven shots behind to win a tournament. Nobody in a couple of
decades has put together such a flag-rattling performance with his
iron game. On 17 holes, the former Georgia Tech player had a putt
for eagle or birdie. His longest birdie putt was 10 feet. Of the
other 10 birdies, five were no more than 36 inches and three were
five feet or closer.
</P>
<P>
   That opened Miller's mental scrapbook, too. In the Sunday 61 he
shot to win the Tucson Open in 1975, Miller missed two five-foot
putts. His back-to-back wins at Phoenix and Tucson were by 14 and
nine strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same thing,'' Miller said. ``People that year were
saying I was the best player in the world. But it was almost
sacrilegious for somebody to say you were better than Jack
Nicklaus. Kind of like it was before with Jack and Arnie. I'm a
nice guy, but not everybody liked me because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller calls the normally stoic Duval ``a modern-day Ben
Hogan,'' describing a player whose facial expressions could not
allow a 66 to be determined from a 76. The on-course Duval is a
striking contrast to his in-the-locker room or on-the-range
personality, where a belly laugh is as likely as a laser 2-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind those Oakleys (sunglasses) he doesn't show any
emotion,'' Miller said. ``I guess it took winning by one and
shooting 59 to get him excited. . . . He's a nice guy. I don't
think he's the life of the party, but he doesn't mind being at the
party. I think when a round is over, David is as happy as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Odder than anything was Duval's ability to make the 59 seem
almost routine. Striking a 218-yard 5-iron to six feet at the 18th
for eagle appeared as mechanical as a 150-yard 7-iron to the middle
of a giant green. If the round had been of the pleasure variety
with friends, many of the birdie putts would have been gimmes.
</P>
<P>
   As an overwhelmed Jeff Maggert noted, ``Normally when there's a
guy shooting 59, he's making all these long putts all day. But most
of these were three or four feet. It was a 59 that looked
effortless.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Phil Mickelson said, ``It was amazing _ it seemed like he
was a foot (from the pin) every hole. He never had to use his
putter. I thought it was an amazing day of ball-striking. It was
just incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   As dumbfounded as the rest of the world was about the radar game
he displayed, Duval said, ``It was like pitching a perfect game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever fully appreciate what happened on
Sunday,'' said Duval, who fist-pumped his way around the green in
an uncharacteristic display of jubliation. ``Maybe in a few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Loren Roberts said, ``I don't know how you couldn't rank him as
the No. 1 player in the world right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson said, ``I don't know how the rankings are done, but it
doesn't make any sense to me for anybody else other than David to
be on top.''
</P>
<P>
   That opinion is not limited to American shores. A month away
from the first World Golf Championship, which will pay $1 million
to the winner, it seems we already have a recognized leader in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``David has caught Tiger Woods right now, which is good for the
game of golf,'' Scotland's Colin Montgomerie said. ``No one in golf
has ever perfected this game, and no one ever will. But I think 59
is damn near perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're not trying,'' Mickelson said. ``But the
level of play has certainly increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine months ago during Atlanta's BellSouth Classic when a Golf
World cover proclaimed him as ``America's Best Player,'' Duval was
clearly embarrassed. Now the statement doesn't cover enough global
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's real important whether I feel that or
not,'' Duval said. ``You know, it doesn't help you once you start a
tournament. It doesn't do anything for you. I think it's a
reasonable conclusion to draw based on the past however many months
. . . but I'm not putting a whole lot of stock in that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval knows one thing very clearly. In his own mind, regardless
of the mammoth pile of money that's building before his Oakleys, he
will not feel fulfilled until he finds a major championship. That
he could not hold a three-shot lead on the back nine at Augusta
last April is a demon he cannot wait to exorcise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to win one major,'' Duval said. ``I would like
to win a couple or several.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the spring and summer are concerned, Miller cannot
wait to sit back and watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majors are really going to be interesting,'' he said,
``because the Masters is perfect for David.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Mickelson is drawing something from Duval's success.
Taking in the Fiesta Bowl before the Mercedes Championships, the
two players decided that if either of them won, he would pick up
the tab for their chartered plane to Hawaii. Armed with $468,000
from the Mercedes win and still awaiting the air fare bill, Duval
then lost his bet with Mickelson on the Fiesta Bowl, giving
Tennesseee and 3 1/2 points. Mickelson got to pick a five- or
six-night trip anywhere in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty juiced,'' Duval said. ``He found a $7,000-a-night
place in Aspen, (Col.), but he's since located a house for a dollar
a square foot in Vail, (Col.). It's 11,000 square feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
