<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More money doesn't mean more wins, Canadiens say
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ``CH'' on the jerseys doesn't quite stand for
``Canadiens Happy,'' especially in light of plunging revenues, a
massive tax migraine and a 2-1 loss at Florida on Wednesday that
illustrated continuing offensive problems.
</P>
<P>
   But at least ``CH'' no longer stands for ``Canadiens Hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   After an 11-game winless streak that enabled general manager
Rejean Houle and coach Alain Vigneault to carve out an inglorious
place in franchise history, Montreal is nearing respectability
again. The Canadiens hired former coach Jacques Lemaire as a
consultant and, by coincidence or not, won four straight games and
had a 10-4-1 streak going into Saturday's game against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal allowed only 1.87 goals per game during the span, a
full goal less than during an 8-18-7 start (2.88) that had Quebec
natives dreading Houle as much as the English language.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say what they think they have to say,'' Houle said.
``All we're trying to do is win more games. When you're not
winning, people ask questions. Do you have the right coach? Do you
have the right general manager? Did he make the right move? When we
start winning, they say, `The players are playing better.' The
focus is on the players. When you're losing, the focus is on the
coach and the general manager. I don't think it should work that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Montreal, we have so many experts. They will always
challenge the decision of the general manager. They will challenge
the team, too, because hockey is a part of their life. But we are
doing the best we can. We don't want to lose, I can tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Houle said the Canadiens ``have enough money in the budget to
win,'' but the financial picture has cast doubt they will be able
to retain high-salaried players like Mark Recchi. Molson, which
owns the team, showed a $6.63 million profit in its hockey
operation in 1996-97 but had a $2.34 million loss last season.
Problems range from the devalued Canadian dollar (worth
approximately 65 U.S. cents) to annual property taxes of $6.24
million at the $178 million Molson Centre to $5.2 million in
interest payments on the arena debt. The six teams in Canada do not
get the tax breaks that the 21 franchises in the United States do.
</P>
<P>
   But, Houle said, ``If we had another $10 million, it doesn't
mean we will win more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to win in Montreal is as great as for any team in the
four major sports. Winger Shayne Corson said, ``When you don't play
well, you hear a lot of noise. When you do play well, you hear a
lot of noise. It's just a different kind of noise. But all we can
do is control what we can control.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens have received excellent goaltending from Jeff
Hackett, who was acquired in a goalie swap with Chicago for Jocelyn
Thibault, and defense. Montreal could use more help up front, but
Houle said, ``This is our team for now.''
</P>
<P>
   He is being aided in personnel matters by his former Canadiens
roomate, Lemaire, who had been in semi-retirement after resigning
as New Jersey's coach but staying as a consultant after last
season. Lemaire remained under contract to the Devils, but general
manager Lou Lamoriello let him out of the deal without compensation
from Montreal on the understanding that Lemaire would not coach.
Lemaire then signed a three-year deal with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Lemaire's arrival fueled rumors he would replace Houle as
general manager, but Houle said, ``It was my idea to bring Jacques
in. I'm not paying attention to what anybody else thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
