<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retirement time for Gretzky?
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that Michael Jordan has retired from basketball,
hockey fans hope their sport won't have the same kind of giant void
to fill. Wayne Gretzky means as much to the NHL as Jordan did to
the NBA. ``Because of my situation, because of my age, I guess I'm
always going to be asked `When are you going to retire? When are
you going to be done?''' said the New York Rangers center, who
turned 38 Tuesday. ``And it's going to happen. I'm going to have to
retire, but I haven't thought a whole lot about it. . . . The end
of the season, I'll sit down and make my decision on what my future
is.'' Atlanta fans hope Gretzky will stay around at least another
season so they can see him in person against the Thrashers. Gretzky
celebrated his birthday with three assists in a 4-1 win over
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Confident Carolina
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Pavel Bure, Florida is the trendy choice to
catch Carolina in the Southeast Division. But Hurricanes general
manager Jim Rutherford still thinks his team is stronger. ``Our
experience will keep us at the top of our division when the season
ends,'' Rutherford said. ``But it's good to know that the first
half we had has forced other teams to get better.'' Carolina stayed
out of the bidding for Bure because Rutherford was skeptical of his
commitment. ``He's a player who walked out on his team,'' said
Rutherford, overlooking his own October 1996 acquisition of Keith
Primeau, who held out for three weeks until the Red Wings traded
him to Hartford for Brendan Shanahan. ``A guy like Bure is not
going to disrupt anything, but I don't know if he's going to give
(the Panthers) their money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden Quinn
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Maple Leaf coach Pat Quinn got the golden parachute when
he was fired as president and general manager of the Vancouver
Canucks. Financial documents of Canucks parent Orca Bay Hockey
Holdings showed that Quinn pocketed $887,500 in his settlement
before signing a three-year deal worth $1.1 million a season to
coach Toronto. Quinn, a former Atlanta Flames defenseman, is a
leading candidate for coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Bruin teammates continue to marvel at the endurance of
defenseman Ray Bourque. ``He's 38 and playing 30 minutes. I don't
know how he does it,'' said Kyle McLaren. ``I'm 21 and barely
getting 25 (minutes). And I'm very tired after games. He's a
machine.'' . . . Flyers winger Dainius Zubrus, upon being
misidentified as Mikael Renberg in photo captions in both
Philadelphia papers after a recent game: ``I'm much better looking
than him. I should take him to court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
