<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meetings bring GMs onto ice, two-referee system onto agenda
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General manager Don Waddell will attend this week's GM
meetings in Palm Springs, Calif. Among the items on the agenda is
the two-referee system that has been utilized for several games
this season. Reviews of the system generally have been positive,
and it's expected the GMs will recommend to the owners that two
referees be used in playoff games. . . . Waddell will participate
in his first GMs hockey game Monday at the meetings. ''I had to get
my skates sharpened,'' he said. ''I haven't played in a while.''
Among the GMs is Philadelphia's Bobby Clarke, a Hall of Famer who
gave out his share of cheap shots in his career. Waddell: ''I'll be
looking out for him.'' . . . The team is at least two weeks away
from finalizing its negotiations for a practice site, most likely
to be the IceForum in Duluth. ....Team jerseys are also likely to
be unveiled some time in February.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Before Pavel Bure made his home debut for the Florida Panthers
Wednesday, team president Bill Torrey said, ''Pavel won't just put
fans in the seats, he'll pull fans out of them, too.'' Turns out
Bure not only is pulling fans out of their seats, he's helping pull
wallets out of their pockets. The Panthers have been selling
authentic Bure Panthers jerseys for $324, replicas for $199,
plaques for $70 and glossy photos for $6. Imagine the sales blitz
when the team can manufacture Bure buttons, pucks, pins and
T-shirts. ''It's the greatest thing to hit South Florida since they
brought hockey here itself,'' fan Tony Jones told the Miami Herald.
Prior to 19,250 fans jamming the new National Rental Car Center for
the Florida-Montreal game Wednesday, owner Wayne Huizenga said Bure
''brings a new level of excitement into a new building. While it's
exciting to be in a new building, you need something different,
something we've never had before. You can see it tonight. We've got
a full house and everybody's talking about it.'' The Panthers and
Bure's agent, Mike Gillis, are putting the finishing touches on a
five-year contract extension expected to be worth $47 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
