</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CONFLICT-OFINTEREST31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conflicts of interest long IOC way of life
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bob Helmick remembers talking to Juan Antonio
Samaranch in the IOC's suite at the plush Lausanne Palace about a
U.S. vacancy on the committee. It was 1986, and Julian K.
Roosevelt, a New York yachtsman and a relative of two U.S.
presidents, had died recently.
</P>
<P>
   Helmick, himself selected for IOC membership a year earlier,
pushed for Donna de Verona, a former gold medalist swimmer. At the
time, the independent-minded de Verona worked the Olympics as a
color analyst for ABC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaranch immediately said she could not be in because she had
a connection with ABC,'' Helmick recalled. ``The other reason he
said was, `Donna will not be able to be controlled.'''
</P>
<P>
   From selecting its members to choosing Olympic host cities, the
IOC long has operated in a capricious manner, making up the rules
as it goes along _ if there are any rules to begin with. To his
credit, Samaranch is beginning to streamline the process for cities
to bid for the Games. Four members that he appointed to the IOC
have been forced to resign for having their palms out to the Salt
Lake group that won the 2002 Winter Games under suspicious
circumstances. Five others have been asked to quit. Reforms have
been put in place to curb abuses in deciding on the site for the
2006 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But with other IOC doings, conflicts of interest and
questionable business practices remain. Overlapping relations
involving people with connections to the IOC and the outside sports
world create these apparent conflicts, according to critics who ask
whether the Olympic ideals are attainable without a complete
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   The Gilady connection
</P>
<P>
   Alex Gilady is an IOC member from Israel. He also is a senior
vice president of NBC Sports, which has a contract to carry the
next three Olympiads.
</P>
<P>
   For years, all major networks were invited to submit bids to the
IOC for coverage of the Games. But when NBC surprisingly locked up
five Olympiads through 2008 in two separate deals, the other
networks were locked out of the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports officials wonder if Gilady's insider status didn't
kill their 1995 efforts to secure the Sydney Games in 2000, which
the network dearly wanted because they will be in the homeland of
network owner Rupert Murdoch. Two days after Fox privately made a
proposal of $701 million, NBC met with Samaranch and offered a
take-it-or-leave-it $1.27 billion deal for Sydney and Salt Lake.
The IOC took it.
</P>
<P>
   No other network was allowed to beat the NBC offer. CBS, which
paid $913 million for rights to the 1992, '94 and '98 Winter Games,
didn't even know the bidding had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been with CBS, having invested close to $1 billion in
rights fees for three Olympics, I would have been very upset that
we didn't get the opportunity to at least continue the CBS Winter
Games coverage,'' said Neal Pilson, former president of CBS Sports.
Still, he would not accuse NBC or the IOC of wrongdoing. ``That is
a decision for the Olympics to make, and that is a private
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Helmick was more critical, although with good reason. He was
forced to resign from the IOC over conflict-of-interest charges
involving side business deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilady is on the payroll at NBC,'' said Helmick. ``I had my
five or six clients who had no ties to the IOC... and I was forced
to resign. The inconsistency is enormous.'' NBC acknowledged
Gilady's connections with the IOC and international sports
officials. Gilady has sat on the IOC Radio/TV Commission since
1985, and Samaranch picked him for IOC membership in 1994. He
joined NBC in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that I became a member of the IOC and suddenly NBC
says, `Wow, we can jump on this occasion and make him work for
us,''' Gilady said. ``I was working for NBC (13) years before the
IOC invited me to join them, because the IOC thought I could help
in my areas of expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time he was hired, ABC was the American network
synonymous with the Olympics, and they had European-based
executives that nurtured relationships with the IOC,'' said NBC
spokesman Ed Markey. ``NBC had virtually no profile with the IOC.
So one of the main responsibilities for Alex was to help build a
real presence in the international sports community... (and)
bolster NBC's profile, specifically in the Olympic community.''
</P>
<P>
   Some argue he's filled his role too well.
</P>
<P>
   John Boulter, a former top official with longtime Olympic
sponsor Adidas, spoke well of Gilady, but added: ``You have to say
there is a little bit of an apparent conflict of interest. He's not
president of the IOC, but if he was, he could almost sign both
sides of (TV) the contract. It must be a little strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential conflict involves Manolo Romero, a Spanish
broadcasting executive with close ties to the IOC. Romero received
a contract with the Salt Lake Olympic organizers to supply TV for
the international networks covering the Games _ for which he is
well-qualified, having done so in Atlanta. But his bid was not the
lowest and the Salt Lake offer was based on a recommendation from a
panel that included three business associates _ including Gilady _
according to the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us, `He's the guy the IOC likes to work with,''' Ken
Bullock, a board member of the Salt Lake committee, told the
Journal. ``It was kind of an insider-trading thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga veteran at exerting leverage
</P>
<P>
   The IOC family consists of Olympic committees from individual
nations as well as individual sports federations. Many IOC members
rose to power in sports through those organizations, some of which
tend to conduct business in the same vein as the IOC did with Salt
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Sun reported that one IOC member named in the Salt
Lake scandal, along with another official with ties to the
international track and field federation, sought $1 million to
support Toronto's bid to host the 1993 world indoor championships.
The bid group declined and later was awarded the event, according
to the newspaper, which did not name the two.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime president of the Association of National Olympic
Committtees of Africa is IOC member Jean-Claude Ganga, who
allegedly accepted $216,000 in goods and services from the Salt
Lake group. He first made headlines at the 1976 Montreal Olympics
by orchestrating the African boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga took advantage of the tangled web that connects big
players in the Olympic movement. Early on, he forged a relationship
with the late Horst Dassler, who owned Adidas and ISL, the IOC's
marketing partner. Ganga struck a deal for Adidas to outfit his
track athletes in the economically deprived Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Boulter suspects that Ganga benefitted personally from some of
the Adidas goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew (the Congo was) going to send five athletes (to the
Olympics), but you get an order for 50 track suits, 100 pair of
shoes. You wonder what's happening with it. One looks at the good
way Jean-Claude lives, and you wonder how . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Boulter witnessed a comical effort by Ganga in the late 1970s to
call an African boycott at Wimbledon. Boulter recalled Ganga saying
at a dinner with David Grey, then secretary of the International
Tennis Federation, ```You in tennis, you are the worst for
discriminating against us poor Africans. You have to change this
and give us Africans a chance. If not, you saw what we did in
Montreal. We shall boycott Wimbledon.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was a short pause, and David said, `Jean-Claude, remind me
how many Africans took part in Wimbledon last year?' And the answer
was zero.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Wimbledon setting, Ganga had no leverage. Not so in the
Olympic arena, where he practices the craft as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Track's Nebiolo has powerful sway
</P>
<P>
   One of the system's best manipulators is Primo Nebiolo, powerful
head of the international track and field federation.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1988 Seoul Olympics, Nebiolo and leaders of the
boxing and swimming federations held the local organizers hostage
during the scheduling of events for the Games. The federation
chiefs knew thatNBC wanted to shift starting times of some events
so they would be shown in prime time in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Track and field leaders conducted at least five negotiating
sessions with South Korean officials before a deal was struck in
1986. In the end, Nebiolo's representative was told NBC wanted 20
track events to be shown live in the United States. A price of $1
million per event was agreed upon, and a South Korean company paid
a sponsorship fee _ not so coincidentally of $20 million _ to
Nebiolo's federation. It used the money to set up a foundation
that, among other things, pays for an annual gala to honor athletes
and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Helmick, who headed the international swimming federation then,
got wind of the track deal and pursued his own negotiations. First,
he said, he discussed it with Samaranch and Gilady. ``Gilady told
me what the value was, and what Primo was doing,'' Helmick said.
</P>
<P>
   After the swimming federation decided a schedule change wouldn't
hurt its athletes, Helmick approved the shifting of several events
to late morning. His federation was paid $4 million, which he said
was deposited into an account that later funded athletes' travel to
world championships. Helmick said he took nothing for himself but
believes the track federation chief profited from his own deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the distinct impression that I could personally get 5
percent of it,'' Helmick said. ``I got the distinct impression that
that is what Primo was getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Helmick concluded, ``This activity has been going on for
years.'' He believes nothing less than Samaranch's ouster can save
the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   That's not likely. Samaranch approved the selection of all but
23 of the IOC membership, now at 110. And in 1995, the body raised
the IOC's mandatory retirement age from 75 to 80.
</P>
<P>
   Why? To allow the president, now 78, to serve another term.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
