<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roy a rich goalie
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Patrick Roy, the one free agent that the Atlanta
Thrashers might have been interested in spending big bucks on, is
off the market. The two-year contract extension he signed with the
Avalanche will pay him $7 million next season and $7.5 million in
2000-2001. The goalie, who makes $5.1 million this season, also
will receive a $500,000 signing bonus. With Roy taken care of,
Colorado's next challenge will be finding a way to re-sign center
Peter Forsberg, eligible to become a restricted free agent after
this season. The Avalanche will get a financial boost next season
when Colorado opens the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   Flurry of Fleury rumors
</P>
<P>
   Now that Pavel Bure finally has been traded, attention turns to
the Theo Fleury auction in Calgary. ``The latest rumor is I'm going
to Washington for Monica Lewinsky,'' Fleury joked. Among teams
interested in Fleury are the Flyers, Maple Leafs, Red Wings and
Coyotes. Fleury will be an unrestricted free agent after the
season, and has said he will test the free-agent market this
summer. Fleury wore No. 74 for North America in the All-Star Game
because Detroit's Brendan Shanahan has seniority over him for No.
14. The same situation occurred when the two played for Team Canada
in the Olympics last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chelios loves Chicago
</P>
<P>
   If Chris Chelios has his way, he'll retire from the Chicago
Blackhawks. That's what he says. ``I swear on four of my kids'
heads that . . . I have no interest in being traded anywhere,''
said Chelios, who turned 37 Monday. ``As bad as things are right
now, I want to be here when this thing turns around and lead the
charge. I want to stay in Chicago. I don't know how I can put it
any simpler. Things are going bad here, but I'm not the type of
player that is going to quit or ask to be traded. . . . My heart is
in Chicago, and it's always going to be in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation was high for Vancouver signing Marc Crawford,
still under contract with Colorado, to replace fired coach Mike
Keenan. Colorado will get at least $200,000 and a second-round
draft choice. The pick could become a first-rounder, and the payout
increases with any playoff success Vancouver may have. . . .
Crawford is the Canucks' fifth coach in the last four years. Keenan
lasted 14 months. . . . Darren McCarty on the disappointing Red
Wings: ``Right now, we're Team Schizophrenia. We stink.'' Detroit,
which won the Stanley Cup the last two seasons, is 9-13-2 on the
road, including a loss at expansion Nashville. . . . The top rookie
scorer is Vancouver's surprising Bill Muckalt, who had 14 goals and
13 assists in the first half. Drafted 221st overall in 1994, he
played the last four seasons at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
