<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ATROCITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE BY MUSLIM MARAUDERS ERASES INDONESIAN VILLAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMBON, Indonesia _ The village of Benteng Karang, established in
1962, population 1,360, is dead now.
</P>
<P>
   The former residents of the once-bustling hillside community,
too traumatized to return, live under blue tarpaulin sheeting in a
local army camp, the victims of five days of violence that set
once-peaceful Muslim and Christian neighbors against each other the
week before last.
</P>
<P>
   The village, about 17 miles northeast of Ambon, is one of
several closely knit hamlets shown on local maps as Telagakodok.
</P>
<P>
   Laurens Saropy, a 53-year-old farmer, and a handful of other
evacuees said they were forced to flee for their lives when a mob
of several thousand Muslims stormed through the village, hacking to
death at least 15 people and setting homes and a church on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first warnings came not long after the Muslims arrived at
Telagakodok,'' said Saropy, a Christian. ``A police patrol came and
told us we had to get out. They only said, `Get out, get out!' They
didn't protect us. They ran too because the mob was too big.''
</P>
<P>
   A single criminal act _ the robbery of a Christian bus driver by
Muslims _ set off the violence, which started with riots in Ambon
and then spread over the next several days. The death toll in Ambon
officially stands at more than 50, but credible accounts put the
number of dead as high as 100.
</P>
<P>
   The robbery, in a suburb of Ambon, led to fights and
shop-burnings by the bus driver and a group of supporters. It did
not help that the robbers were alleged to be immigrant Muslims from
South Sulawesi, who control much of the local pedicab business, a
source of resentment among many Christians.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, with the army and the police standing on the
sidelines, the lawlessness intensified with Christian mobs
attacking Muslim businesses in the town center and along the
harbor-front, the scene of some of the worst violence.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that police say two young women were dragged from a
karaoke bar and hacked to death; their bodies were thrown into the
sea. A pair of German travel writers said they saw the bodies of
two elderly Muslims lying outside their hotel, battered and stabbed
to death. One victim was decapitated.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Cornelius Bohm, who has lived in the area for 32 years,
said rabble rousers on both sides inflamed the situation by burning
churches and mosques.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as churches and mosques are burnt, it is almost
certain to be 100 percent war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of another Muslim was found stuffed down a well that
was later sealed by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the riots in Ambon the mobs arrived at Benteng
Karang from nearby Muslim communities, Hitu, Mamala, Morela and
Kaitetu.
</P>
<P>
   One of the evacuees, Margareta Masansoni, 65, said she was
warned by her children that people armed with gasoline bombs were
attacking the village. ``I went out of the house and saw people
standing nearby with knives,'' she said. ``I don't know what caused
it. They were stealing, and killing people. I am certain there was
a woman raped _ 40, maybe more, died in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My children wanted me to run,'' she continued, ``and they
helped me but I only wanted to walk and asked for help from God.''
Then she broke down crying: ``I don't even have a single rupiah.
It's too difficult to go back and build again.''
</P>
<P>
   Saropy, the farmer, said relations with the Muslims have not
always been bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to come and go between the Muslim villages,'' he said.
``There was always a good relationship. We don't wish to have a
dispute with the Muslims because not all people are good and not
all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had lived in the village for more than 30 years, but
was now contemplating a government offer of resettlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've no money to start again,'' he said. ``These are the only
clothes I have. I could only come out with a few things _ my
village is finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
