<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5195 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-FAIL31-COX     01-30 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-FAIL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Disturbing' stats show racial disparity in test scores among
teacher candidates in Georgia
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Black teacher candidates failed a teacher licensing
exam almost four times as often as their white peers since the
state instituted the test in mid-1997, according to new statistics
from the commission that certifies Georgia teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The black failure rate at some historically black colleges in
Georgia is more than 80 percent. Statewide, nearly 57 percent of
black test-takers failed the exam, compared to 15 percent among
whites.
</P>
<P>
   The results raise hard questions about whether the education of
black children in their earliest years has been so weak that it
creates a vicious cycle: poorly prepared students go to college and
end up teaching the next generation of poorly prepared students.
</P>
<P>
   Educators and researchers debate the racial disparity, but some
of the explanations that emerge include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Teachers of all races tend to have lower expectations of black
students in elementary and secondary school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Black students taking standarized tests perform worse when
they feel anxious about representing their race.
</P>
<P>
   _ The overwhelmingly white, female teaching corps in elementary
and secondary schools lacks the ability to relate to black children
and to have black children relate to them in a way that makes
learning relevant and exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The racial disparity in the test results shadows what other
states have experienced for decades, and to a slightly less extent
what Georgia experienced with the previous teacher licensing test.
But because the new test is tougher, it has approximately doubled
the failure rate for all groups, making the racial disparity far
more troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disturbing report,'' Clark Atlanta University
education Professor Evelyn Gilliard said after learning that her
campus's failure rate was 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that black children are more likely to become
engaged in learning if they have at least some black teachers. But
with a school-age population that is 37 percent black, Georgia has
a teacher corps with a black ratio that is stagnant at 19.7 percent
_ and the new exam could lower that percentage even further in the
short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some areas we need to put more emphasis on,'' said
Ruth Pace, an elementary education professor at the historically
black Morris Brown College, which had 28 of 38 test-takers flunk
the latest exam, even though the private Atlanta school has a
history of placing highly successful African-American graduates in
Georgia classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   After attending a workshop on the test last week, Pace concluded
that Morris Brown students need more instruction on how to teach
children reading and writing.
</P>
<P>
   The new statistics are related to a statewide failure rate
reported last month. But now, for the first time, the statistics
have been broken down by race for each of the 34 public and private
campuses with teacher-training programs. The test, called Praxis
II, is a set of national subject-matter exams considered much
tougher than the state-designed Teacher Certification Test it
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher candidates may re-take the test an unlimited number of
times, but they cannot be certified _ and in some education
programs cannot even graduate _ until they pass the test.
</P>
<P>
   The new report covers the first seven administrations of the
test through last September. Among students who indicated they were
in Georgia education programs, 24.1 percent of about 7,200 students
failed; among another 2,969 test-takers not affiliated with Georgia
colleges but seeking state certification, 28 percent failed.
</P>
<P>
   Many educators find the results deeply disturbing for a variety
of reasons: _ The failure rate among African-Americans threatens to
discourage prospective teachers at a time when more black teachers
are badly needed in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some educators say students who have spent four years passing
courses, paying tuition and receiving decent grades _ or even HOPE
scholarships _ should not now be excluded from the teaching
profession because of a new test. This is like changing the rules
halfway through a race, they say.
</P>
<P>
   _ The test represents a bold and necessary rise in academic
standards for Georgia's future teachers, many say, but it fails to
factor in the importance of subtle values such as social skills,
commitment to teaching and an ability to make children want to
learn.
</P>
<P>
   Questions revolve around who is to blame for high failure rates.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that weaknesses among black education students must
be viewed in a larger context that includes the elementary, middle
and high school ``pipeline'' that delivers black students to
college and education programs. ``What does (the Praxis II data)
say about African-American students who are passed on, who are not
held to high standards throughout their elementary, middle and
secondary schools?'' asked Jacqueline Irvine, an education
professor at Emory University who served on the Diversity Issues
Advisory Group that oversaw release of the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come to colleges and universities and they come right
smack in the face with this issue of, `I have not been taught this;
my work has not been critically reviewed; I have not been given
honest feedback about my performance,''' Irvine said.
</P>
<P>
   Minority parents have long criticized the low expectations set
for their children, goals that experts say result in watered-down
curriculum and low standards of behavior, even as inflated grades
allow for college admission.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at historically black colleges agree the problems
start before college.
</P>
<P>
   Since 83 percent of white test-takers at historically black Fort
Valley State University passed Praxis II, in contrast to an overall
school pass rate of 36 percent, ``obviously the material is being
covered,'' said the education dean, Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, pass rates of black students at larger, more
diverse schools also are lower than the pass rates of whites. At
Georgia State University, for example, the pass rate for blacks was
58 percent, not much more than the black pass rate reported for
highly selective, historically black Spelman College, where all
five white test-takers failed. The pass rate for GSU whites was 94
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another contributing factor, which may affect black scores on
SAT tests as well, is cultural, experts say. While testing
companies such as Educational Testing Service, which designs the
Praxis series as well as the SAT, have largely eliminated biased
questions through scientific statistical techniques, black students
tend to be less tutored in test-taking tricks and can be affected
by psychological pressure. One study found that female and black
test-takers do worse when given psychological cues emphasizing
their gender or race, such as filling out demographic information
before taking the test.
</P>
<P>
   But some black student-teachers have little patience with such
excuses. ``I don't object to the test,'' said Sheila Raper, 24, a
Georgia State University education senior who recently took the two
portions of Praxis II required for middle school certification.
``If I do bad, I'll take it again. I'll work on my weak areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Adkins, 29, a black early childhood education student at
Clark Atlanta University, was more emphatic. After hearing
classmates complain that Praxis II was intimidating other black
education students into changing fields, Adkins declared, ``If you
fail, you take it again.'' Adkins passed the Praxis II content-area
``exercises'' for elementary education _ mostly an essay test _ but
will re-take the elementary curriculum and instruction multiple
choice test in March. If a person is truly committed to the
profession, she said, ``You do whatever is necessary to become a
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Dandy, an education professor at Armstrong Atlantic State
University who runs a minority-recruitment education program called
Pathways to Teaching Careers, said Georgia needs more black
teachers with a strong commitment. Not that black students can't
thrive with white teachers, she said, but too many black males now
go through school, especially in rural areas of Georgia, without
ever having a black teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine,'' Dandy said, ``going through 12 years of school
without (an adult) who likes the same role models, who listens to
the same music, who laughs at the same riddles, who eats the same
foods, who worships in the same kind of worship service, who has
the same culture as you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
