A5196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERTARIAN31-COX     01-30 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTARIAN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Libertarian alternative appeals to some
 &HT;    By Julie Kemble Borths
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As long as the U.S. Congress is tied up in the
impeachment trial against President Bill Clinton, the people who
gather each month in Tom Brown's living room are happy. Not that
they have anything against Clinton in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only time we're safe, when the Legislature is not
in session,'' said Jack Matheney of Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Brown agreed. ``At least safe from new harmful legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Matheney are members of the Libertarian political
party _ a group they say is a growing force in American politics
with about 300 elected officials nationally claiming affiliation
with the party.
</P>
<P>
   Matheney said the party wants government to play a smaller role
in people's lives, taxes to be more tied to direct services and
fewer ``entitlement'' programs. Libertarians, he said, belong to
``a party of individual liberty and responsibility . . . a party of
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something members don't see much of right now in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more concerned with Bill Clinton's inappropriate
relationship with the Constitution than with any woman,'' said Bob
DeBrosse.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Matheny said, in Clinton's speeches lately ``he's
talking all these new programs that are (not in the) Constitution.
He's going to steal the money for it from the people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to discourage many who want the government to do
less, not just talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're true believers,'' Matheney, 53, said. ``We don't live by
the whims of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBrosse is a Piqua city commissioner and a Libertarian. As an
elected official, he is part of a ``farm team'' being built by the
party. And, he said, residents have supported his views.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about two years ago the city commission disagreed
on whether to change electrical permit regulations to allow
property owners to do their own work even if they did not live in
the building. When they did not change the law, voters did. Such a
change reflects the Libertarian view that property owners should
have more freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Many Libertarians look at the two-party system as ``one beast
with two heads,'' DeBrosse, 45, said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling them the ``dempublicans,'' Brown said most elected
officials keep trying to use the same ways to solve the same
problems. As a result, he said, voters are staying away from the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   And some are finding a place with the Libertarian party. In the
last two years, the national Libertarian Party organization claims
a 12.3 percent jump in membership; there are 182,481 members
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Jay J. Krull, 34, of Kettering, said he was ``disgusted'' in
1996 by the ``failure'' of the Republican revolution and became a
Libertarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Democrats and Republicans, you're not going to see
wholesale change in government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That change won't be easy but Ron Williamitis, 47, said it's
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working for a playing field where everyone can
compete,'' he said. ``Where you can be responsible for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Jeff Zweber, 30, cited the computer industry.
Left to its own devices ``because Washington didn't understand
it,'' the field ``created more wealth than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Most national problems, Krull said, are caused by the laws
created in Washington. ``The right hand causes it and then the left
hand offers a solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time to be a Libertarian,'' Zweber said. ``People
are getting the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
