<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROTALK31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Modern two-way radio links families
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you think you need a bit more than a pager to
keep in touch with family members but you don't want the expense of
equipping everybody with cellular telephones, Cobra Electronics
might have a solution for you.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra offers a whole line of small, relatively inexpensive
two-way radios that can be clipped onto a belt like a pager. The
Microtalk radios sell for as little as $100 a pair at electronic
retail and sporting goods stores.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way radio is a popular way of communicating on worksites,
but it's generally been considered impractical for family
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra's basic Microtalk radios are 4 inches high and weigh less
than 8 ounces. They transmit up to two miles in open country or a
mile in a residential neighborhood. You can use them around home,
in an amusement park, a shopping mall or anywhere else where the
family is spread out over a small area.
</P>
<P>
   The base model units can transmit on any of 14 channels. The
next model up in the line adds message-scrambling capability to
keep outsiders from overhearing your conversations.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the line is a two-way radio that adds a weather
monitoring function. Cobra said that model, which will sell for
about $169 when it hits the market this summer, is designed for
hikers and other outdoor enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Microtalk radio line won an Innovation Award for product
excellence at the 1999 International Consumer Electronics Show held
in Las Vegas earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find Microtalk in stores, check the Cobra Web site
at cobraelec.com/index.html for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
