<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ULTIMATUM-350&AMP;     01-30 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ULTIMATUM-350&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITON TAKES ULTIMATUM TO KOSOVO RIVALS
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook came
here Saturday to tell Yugoslav and ethnic Albanian leaders that
they must appear in France on Feb. 6 to negotiate effective
self-government for Serbia's battle-ravaged Kosovo province or face
NATO bombing and other military action to force them to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic received Cook for what the
British minister called a ``business-like'' meeting of some 35
minutes. As usual, Milosevic did not appear in public himself
Saturday, letting other Serbian leaders express wary willingness to
attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Serb forces in Kosovo continued to hit the
ethnic-Albanian fighters hard, to seize as much ground as possible
before negotiations begin, Western diplomats here said, while there
was a grenade attack on a Serbian cafe in the Kosovo capital,
Pristina, and another reported attack on a Serbian couple in a
fiercely contested village.
</P>
<P>
   Cook acted on behalf of the six nations of the Balkan Contact
Group _ the United States, Britain, France, Russia, Germany and
Italy. He said Milosevic supported a peaceful solution and promised
a speedy response to the Contact Group demands.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said he stressed to Milosevic the need to reach a
settlement in February and the unity of the international demand
for Kosovo's self-government within the Yugoslav Federation, which
is made up of the republics of Serbia and Montenegro, and not in
Serbia itself, as Milosevic wants.
</P>
<P>
   Cook then flew to Skopje, Macedonia, where he is scheduled to
meet with three ethnic-Albanian leaders, including Ibrahim Rugova,
the nonviolent elected leader of the Albanians, and Adem Demaci and
Bujar Bukoshi, who have connections to the armed Albanian rebels of
the Kosovo Liberation Army. Cook was expected to give them the same
marching orders: go to France at the end of next week prepared to
negotiate on an interim settlement that will let Kosovo run its own
affairs, but not give it independence, with Kosovo's future status
to be determined after three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Serbian officials close to Milosevic said he was likely to send
a delegation to the talks. He would not go there himself, but
instead probably send Serbian President Milan Milutinovic, a
Milosevic loyalist, whom Cook also met Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is said by these officials to resent the pressure of
the West to sacrifice Serbian sovereignty over Kosovo, which was
the heart of the Serbs' medieval empire and is the cradle of
Serbian nationalism, and to fear that he could be arrested on a
secret indictment for war-crimes charges if he leaves Belgrade now.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is widely considered the main architect of the Bosnian
Serbs' aggression during the 1992-95 war in Bosnia, but Western
leaders have never given any public indication he could or would be
called to account for alleged war crimes there by facing the United
Nations' tribunal for war crimes in The Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian officials, insisting on anonymity, said that
Milosevic was likely to concede only when pressed very strongly by
NATO and its bomb threats, so he can explain his concessions to his
people without paying a significant political price.
</P>
<P>
   The same officials noted that Kosovo is a political and
financial drain for Belgrade, and if NATO is willing to take
responsibility for restraining the rebels and keeping Kosovo from
independence for three years, Milosevic may see that as an
advantage. This would be especially true if he can also win a
lifting of harsh international economic sanctions against Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, state television in Belgrade showed Milosevic
telling the visiting Russian Communist Party leader Gennadi
Zyuganov that Yugoslavia ``advocates a peaceful solution to the
problems in Kosovo through direct political dialogue with
representatives of national communities in Kosovo and state
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic, in an interview Saturday,
said ``there is no reason for us to say `no' now.'' He noted,
though, that the federal government and Milosevic had not yet made
a decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic, a recent addition to the Milosevic government who
describes himself as a nationalist democrat, said that
international law, which recognizes Serbian sovereignty over
Kosovo, ``must be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic said he favored a negotiated solution, but with these
preconditions: that there be ``no independent Kosovo, no `greater
Albania,' and no equal status for Kosovo as a third republic within
Yugoslavia _ that is a secret name for an independent Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also important, Draskovic insisted, to guarantee equal
rights to all citizens of Kosovo, including the minority Serbs, who
make up only about 10 percent of the 2 million people estimated to
live in the province.
</P>
<P>
   There should also be no independent state institutions set up by
the ethnic Albanians, Draskovic said. That means, he said, no
separate Albanian police force, for instance, but only a state
police force that could contain a large majority of ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo now, the minority Serbs hold every major position of
power, even in cities where they represent less than 1 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   But the ethnic Albanian leaders all seek independence, and the
Kosovo Liberation Army is fighting for it. The Albanians are
finding it hard _ even under strong Western pressure _ to unite
under one negotiating position and one delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians insist that Belgrade respect a cease-fire and draw
its troops and special police forces down to levels agreed on last
October. That is also a demand of the Contact Group. But the
Albanians find it much harder to renounce, as the Contact Group
insists, their goal of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Pleurat Sejdiu, a rebel spokesman based in London, reacted
cautiously to the Group's demands, saying: ``We are not rejecting
the Contact Group statement. We just can't say anything positive
about it. This is not the time to talk. The fighting has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, another 24 Albanians, three of whom were dressed in KLA
uniform, were killed by the Serb police. International monitors
said a number of them appeared to have been shot in the head at
close range. The monitors' leader, U.S. diplomat William Walker,
said in an interview Saturday that an investigation into the deaths
was in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday night, six Serbs were badly wounded when a grenade
exploded outside a Pristina cafe owned by Serbs. In Pristina, the
Serb Media Center on Saturday said a Serb civilian was killed and
his wife seriously wounded when assailants threw a grenade into
their bedroom. The attack occurred in the contested northwestern
Kosovo village of Rakos.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said the 30-page Contact Group proposal offered the
population of Kosovo, which is about 90 percent ethnic Albanian,
self-government, stability, democracy and control of their own
police force and legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Belgrade it offers an opportunity to get themselves out a
conflict that they cannot win,'' he said. ``It is in the interest
of both sides that they accept this offer and that within the very
tight timetable we have set they get down to reaching an
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals were backed Friday night by the United Nations
Security Council, where the Russians also went along, and NATO
countries were meeting Saturday in Brussels to authorize
Secretary-General Javier Solana to launch air strikes if the
parties _ especially Milosevic, Western officials make clear _ do
not comply or negotiate in good faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1355EST &QL; 
