<HEADER>
A5205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWO-CITIES31-COX     01-30 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWO-CITIES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Super cities: Atlanta and Denver
 &HT;    By David Goldberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Picture, if you will, a large metropolitan area that
consistently blows past its regional rivals in economic expansion,
population increases and every other kind of growth.
</P>
<P>
   An expanding, mega-hub airport and relatively low-cost suburbs
beckon to still more refugees from older cities and declining rural
areas, and yet the region is struggling with maddening congestion
and air-quality problems. Because the area is widely seen as the
economic engine for the entire state, the new governor is fixated
on addressing threats to the capital city's quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the suburban traffic has made in-town areas popular
again, and downtown is suddenly showing signs of new vitality.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an Atlantan, you might think you're looking in the
mirror. But you're actually glaring into the eyes of Atlanta's
Super Bowl rival, Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first moved here, what struck me was the similar size
and age,'' said Steve Turner, a native of Atlanta who now works as
an urban designer in the planning department of Denver's
consolidated city-county government. ``The neighborhooods close to
the core were built around the same time. I live in Congress Park.
Whenever people visit me from Atlanta they say, `Wow, this looks a
lot like Virginia-Highland.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are some obvious differences, of course. Metro Atlanta has
about a million more residents. Atlanta is a mecca for
African-Americans, while Denver's nearby Rocky Mountains call out
to die-hard skiiers.
</P>
<P>
   But the two have plenty in common: superior climate, a young,
high-wage population and lots of jobs, to name a few. And in both
cases, phenomenal economic success has both cities wondering how to
cope with the people, cars and environmental damage that have come
with it.
</P>
<P>
   City rankings of all sorts regularly have Denver and Atlanta
nudging each other in their top 10 lists. In ranking
``wealth-creating'' cities, Fortune recently put Atlanta eighth and
Denver ninth. Money Magazine's ``Best Places to Live 1998'' had
Denver second and Atlanta sixth.
</P>
<P>
   On the flipside, the Sierra Club's list of ``most
sprawl-threatened'' places (aside from Los Angeles) put Atlanta on
top and Denver five slots below. Indeed, ``sprawl'' was the first
word that came to the minds of some outside observers asked to
compare the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   James Howard Kunstler, who wrote ``The Geography of Nowhere''
and travels the country speaking on urban issues, criticized both
cities for their ``automobile slums.'' ``Each (football) team
represents a regional capital of suburban hyper-growth, both of
which are rapidly becoming places not worth living in,'' Kunstler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hanson, a Denver resident who has spent time in both
cities, made similar observations as he sat in the Wynkoop brewpub
in Lower Downtown sipping an ESB (for Extra Special Broncos, what
else?).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very similar in that you have an interesting core city
and a lot of sprawl that's not interesting around it,'' said
Hanson, 40. An architect and stay-at-home dad, Hanson lives in a
100-year-old home in Capitol Hill, which is roughly analagous to
Grant Park. He noted that both cities began life as rail hubs. ``We
wouldn't be here if it weren't for the railroad _ same as
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Differences? ``There are no mosquitoes here. We weren't burned
by Sherman.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, though, the fact that Atlanta was torched by
Union Gen. William T. Sherman during the Civil War puts the two
cities on roughly the same development timeline. Incorporated in
1861, Denver was just four years old when Atlanta began rebuilding
after the war ended in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason many neighborhoods in Denver instantly call to
mind parts of Atlanta, Turner noted.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has its own Buckhead in the Cherry Creek Mall area,
minutes from downtown. Like Buckhead, it is the central city's cash
cow, supplying about a quarter of the sales-tax dependent budget.
And as in Buckhead, the boom began around a revamped older mall
surrounded by single-family homes; it is now a shopping haven with
high-rises.
</P>
<P>
   But Cherry Creek is a pedestrian's paradise in comparison to
Buckhead, complete with a recreational trail along the namesake
creek that bustles with elderly walkers, young skaters and joggers.
To picture the district's main drag, Colorado Boulevard, think
Peachtree in Buckhead, only wider.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, the Denver Technology Center along Interstate 25
south of downtown, which now has nearly as many jobs as the central
business district, can be likened to Perimeter Center. Just south
of there, northern Douglas County was the fastest-growing county in
the nation for much of the 1990s (think Gwinnett County in the
1980s).
</P>
<P>
   Residential and office development there spins out from Park
Meadows mall. (The malls even have oxymoronic names in common. Is
Perimeter Center at the perimeter or in the center? And where are
the park and meadows at Park Meadows?)
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, that area was just fields,'' said Larry
Mugler, who analyzes development for the Denver Regional Council of
Governments (the acronym for which is pronounced ``Dr. Cog'').
</P>
<P>
   Today, Park Meadows seduces customers with opera Muzak, parquet
floors and marble-accented restrooms. Shopper Barbara Meehan, who
lives just outside Denver, has visited Atlanta and sees it as less
a metropolis than a hick-opolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of Atlanta as alligators and snakes and that sort of
stuff,'' Meehan said. ``Atlanta is a strictly Southern town. They
have trees and we have mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are clear regional differences. For both
Atlanta and Denver, ``frequent flyer'' ranks in the top five
``lifestyle interests,'' according to demographic research firm
Polk Intelligence. But when Denverites are skiing, Atlantans are
playing tennis. While their Western counterparts are camping and
hiking, the Southerners are reading the Bible or other religious
texts. Almost 30 percent of Denver residents say they are regular
bicyclists, twice the percentage in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   New governors in both states came to office promising to address
the quality-of-life issues associated with congestion and sprawl.
But while Democrat Roy Barnes is emphasizing mass transit in a
region that has poured billions into asphalt, Bill Owens _
Colorado's first Republican governor in 24 years _ is pushing
highway projects he says have lagged the area's growth.
</P>
<P>
   While Denver is a bit behind Atlanta in its physical sprawl, it
appears ahead in downtown redevelopment. The city and
quasi-governmental development agencies have offered aggressive
incentives to spur housing developments downtown. Streets are
bustling even after business hours, especially along the 16th
Street mall, where a free shuttle bus carries visitors along the
restaurant-shopping corridor, and in Lower Downtown, better known
as LoDo.
</P>
<P>
   A once-seedy warehouse and old-time office district, LoDo is
what downtown Atlanta's Fairlie-Poplar district wishes to be.
Already inching its way back with artists' lofts, a brew pub and
eateries several years ago, the district took off after the city
opened Coors Field there for the new Rockies baseball team. Another
anchor is Denver's Union Station, which, unlike Atlanta's Union
Station, was left standing. Today, LoDo is the focus of the
region's nightlife, luring locals and tourists alike, even in the
baseball off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has room to add thousands more residents close-in, thanks
to the closure of two close-in airfields _ Lowry Air Force Base and
Stapleton Airport. Redevelopment has already begun at Lowry, where
the tightly clustered rooftops of a new neotraditional village have
sprouted in the shadow of enormous military aircraft hangars. Real
estate signs foretell a new business park nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But even filling in the airfields won't accommodate the 1
million additional residents expected by 2020, regional planners
said. Further sprawl is almost inevitable, Mugler noted, but local
governments want to limit it. To articulate what they don't want
for Denver, the planners recently compiled figures comparing the
region with Atlanta: While 82 percent of Denver's population lives
within 17 miles of downtown, 45 percent of Atlanta's population
lives farther out than that.
</P>
<P>
   But when they forecast job growth, they look to Atlanta as an
inspiration, Mugler added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is in some ways a cautionary tale for us,'' he said.
``But as an economic success it's something to aspire to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
