<HEADLINE>
JOAN ENGEL STERN, 78, BALLET DANCER
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joan Engel Stern, a dancer in a ballet troupe founded
in the United States by the British stars Alicia Markova and Anton
Dolin, died on Jan. 18 at her home in Manhattan. She was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, the family said.
</P>
<P>
   Born Shirley Engel in Baltimore, she was known as Joan Engel
when she became a professional dancer. In 1945 she became a
founding member of the touring troupe formed by Ms. Markova, now
Dame Alicia, and Anton Dolin, later Sir Anton.
</P>
<P>
   Engel also appeared in the Broadway shows ``Life With Father''
and ``Out of This World.'' She taught later at the American Academy
of Dramatic Art in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her husband, Irving; a son, Anthony Marc
Benjamin, and a daughter, Lisa Stern Lasday, all of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
