<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FREYBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. RICHARD H. FREYBERG, 94, HELPED FORM ARTHRITIS GROUP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New York, Michigan, California)   (dal) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Richard Harold Freyberg, a leading rheumatologist
who helped organize the Arthritis Foundation and build it into
today's 700,000-member organization with a professional staff of
750, died Jan. 23 at his retirement home in Venice, Fla. He was 94
and formerly lived in Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Freyberg came to New York in 1944 as director of the newly
established Division of Rheumatic Diseases at the Hospital for
Special Surgery in Manhattan, a post he filled for nearly three
decades. Concurrently, he served as chief of the arthritis clinic
at New York Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He left for Palm Desert, Calif., in 1974 to help establish the
Arthritis and Rheumatism Wing of Eisenhower Medical Center there.
After retiring to Florida, he remained active in his field as a
lecturer and writer. Dr. Freyberg was co-author of ``The History of
Rheumatology,'' published in 1985 by the Arthritis Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Goshen, Ind., he attended the University of Michigan
on a basketball scholarship but became captain of the track team
and a noted middle-distance runner. He graduated from Michigan in
1926 and from its medical school in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   After completing his residency in internal medicine, he was
asked to set up the Rackham Arthritis Research Unit at Michigan. He
directed its research projects until his move to New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Dr. Freyberg and a few colleagues met in a New York
hotel room with Floyd B. Odlum, an industrialist afflicted with
rheumatoid arthritis. That meeting led eventually to the founding
of the Arthritis Foundation with an initial fund-raiser led by Bob
Hope that netted about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation moved to Atlanta in 1977 and now operates with an
annual budget of $110 million to support research, cures and
prevention and to improve the lot of those affected. Dr. Freyberg
was a director for 22 years and more recently remained an honorary
trustee.
</P>
<P>
   He also became active in the American Rheumatism Association and
was president in the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Freyberg's wife, Helen Beckman Freyberg, died in 1985 after
50 years of marriage. He is survived by a daughter, Joanne Moss of
Birmingham, Mich.; a son, Thomas, of Palos Verdes, Calif.; five
grandchildren, and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
