<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS ON CHRISTIANS A `BLOT' ON INDIA, PREMIER TELLS NATION
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ In a somber address to the nation, Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee on Saturday made his strongest
condemnation yet of the recent attacks on Christian places of
worship in India and the murders of an Australian missionary and
his two young sons as ``a blot on our collective consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Such violence violates our tradition and culture of
tolerance,'' he said on the 51st anniversary of the assassination
of India's pacifist leader, Mohandas K. Gandhi. ``It goes against
everything that Gandhiji and our savants have taught us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the prime minister's remarks, broadcast on the state-run
television station, did nothing to quiet the opposition Congress
Party and some of his own allies who say the government has moved
too slowly to stop the sectarian violence and acted too quickly to
exculpate Hindu militants who belong to groups associated with the
Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party that Vajpayee heads.
</P>
<P>
   The party came in for heavy flak Saturday even from one of its
longtime leaders, Madan Lal Khurana, the Tourism and Parliamentary
Affairs Minister, who resigned in part over the violence against
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Khurana said he had been silenced when he
tried to speak out within the party against Hindu militants who
have been making irresponsible, anti-Christian statements. These
individuals, who are part of organizations that are in the same
family of Hindu nationalist groups as the party, are damaging the
image of the party and India, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khurana said he had been personally shaken after the missionary,
Graham Staines, and his sons, 10 and 6, had been burned alive in
their van in the eastern state of Orissa as a mob chanting Hindu
slogans circled them. He had written a letter to the party, leaked
to newspapers, asking for permission to ``atone'' for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Khurana's resignation complicated Vajpayee's efforts Saturday to
reclaim the secular high ground. The prime minister fasted for
religious harmony and vowed to see that all those who had committed
sectarian crimes would be punished. He noted that suspects had been
arrested in the Gujarat attacks and that no efforts were being
spared in searching for the Staines' killers.
</P>
<P>
   Also fasting Saturday was Home Minister L.K. Advani, who _ long
before any investigation of the missionary's killing was near
completion _ said that a youth group that is part of the same Hindu
nationalist family of organizations as the Bharatiya Janata Party
had not been involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party president, Sonia Gandhi, speaking Saturday at
an observance of the anniversary of Gandhi's death, accused the
government of weakness and hesitance in enforcing the law to
protect minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Places of worship have been torched, innocent people bullied,
threatened, beaten, injured and even killed,'' she said. ``Instead
of moving swiftly and decisively to end the violence and apprehend
the perpetrators, homilies are given about national debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, an Italian-born Catholic and the inheritor of the
Nehru-Gandhi dynasty, was referring to remarks Vajpayee made
earlier this month when he visited the district in the western
state of Gujarat where more than two dozen attacks on Christians
and their institutions have been reported to the police.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister condemned the attacks, but he also called for
a national debate on religious conversions. Hindu militants have
been accusing Christian missionaries of converting Hindus through
bribes and intimidation and maintain that all conversions should be
outlawed. Leaders of the groups said that Vajpayee's call for a
debate on the issue had vindicated their position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
