<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARY U.S. BROODS ON A PEACE EFFORT MINUS KING HUSSEIN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With King Hussein of Jordan lying gravely ill from
cancer in a hospital in Minnesota, senior Clinton administration
officials say they are alarmed at the prospect of pursuing a
comprehensive peace in the Middle East without the Arab leader
widely seen as most committed to the goal.
</P>
<P>
   American officials had hoped that the king's decision to return
home this month after six months of cancer treatment at the Mayo
Clinic in Minnesota was a sign that his health had improved, and
that he might remain on the throne for at least a few more years.
</P>
<P>
   But those hopes were dashed this week when the king's doctors
announced that his lymphatic cancer had returned.
</P>
<P>
   The frail, painfully gaunt 63-year-old monarch returned
immediately to the United States, but not before dismissing his
brother as heir and naming instead his 36-year-old eldest son. The
palace intrigue shocked Jordanians and many foreign leaders, who
had come to take the country's political stability for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of King Hussein to Jordan and to the region can
hardly be overstated,'' Sandy Berger, the national security
adviser, said in an interview. ``This is someone of enormous
integrity and courage who believes deeply in broadening the peace
process, and who has been prepared to take risks for that _
political and personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior administration official said: ``King Hussein has
led his country for almost half a century, most of that time as a
good friend of the United States and a vital proponent of Middle
East peace. And it's strange and frightening to think of the peace
process without him.''
</P>
<P>
   The king's illness has complicated the peace effort by
unsettling Israel's political and military leaders as their
negotiations with the Palestinians are gridlocked and as Israel
prepares for national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jordan's humiliating defeat in the 1967 war, when the
Israelis captured eastern Jerusalem and the West Bank, the king has
been that rare thing for Israel in recent years: a reliable friend
in the Arab world. Since offending Arab neighbors by signing a
peace agreement with Israel in 1994, he has done more than any
other Arab leader to shift it from pariah status.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was desperate last October to avoid breakdown
of a summit meeting in Maryland between Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Israel and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader. So
he asked Hussein to leave his sickbed in Minnesota and join in the
negotiations. In announcing an interim peace agreement three days
later, Clinton said the king was ``at the heart of this success.''
</P>
<P>
   The king, who came to power in 1952, when he was only 16, has
brought Jordan prominence all out of proportion to its size and
economic and military might. With a population of 4 million people,
Jordan is an impoverished, landlocked, resource-poor nation
surrounded by oil-rich neighbors _ some threatening, notably Iraq
to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials and scholars who have studied
Jordan say they are convinced that Crown Prince Abdullah is
committed to the policies of his father, especially Hussein's
devotion to a comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abdullah and the other children have been raised by a father
who has for his entire life been committed to peace,'' said Judith
Kipper, a Middle East specialist at the Council on Foreign
Relations who knows the king and his family well. ``I don't think
Abdullah wanted power. I don't think he really expected it. But he
is absolutely prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger shared Ms. Kipper's appraisal of Abdullah, who was
educated in part at Georgetown University in Washington. ``We've
had a lot of contact with the crown prince over the years,'' Berger
said, ``and he is a very bright man, highly respected in the
Jordanian military. I think that the crown prince is deeply
committed to the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is undeniable that Abdullah, who has spent his career in
the military, has little background in politics or economics, and
that Jordan's neighbors may quickly try to exploit his
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine that Assad and Saddam won't see him as a
child,'' said a senior aministration official, referring to
President Hafez al-Assad of Syria and President Saddam Hussein of
Iraq, who have both een in power for nearly three decades.``That
does carry great danger, especially if Iraq tries to make
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is thought to be a particular threat, given Saddam's call
this month for the overthrow of neighboring Arab governments that
have supported economic sanctions against Iraq. An estimated
300,000 Iraqis live in Jordan, and many are loyal to the Iraqi
leader.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say they made a quick decision last week to
offer as much public support as possible to Abdullah to bolster his
standing at home and in the region.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright hastily
rearranged a Middle East tour to include a visit to Amman, the
Jordanian capital, to meet the prince and express confidence in the
stability of a key American ally. ``I wanted to stop here to make
very clear that the U.S. stands with Jordan,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats who have served in Jordan say the king's
decision last week to overturn decades-old succession plans and
name Abdullah as heir was not so surprising, especially if his
death is near.
</P>
<P>
   While the king's brother and longtime heir apparent, Prince
Hassan, is widely respected for his intelligence and commitment to
the Middle East peace effort, he is also considered aloof. He has
inspired little affection among the people and the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince Abdullah does have the tie with the military, which is
the bedrock of stability in Jordan,'' said Roscoe Suddarth, the
American ambassador to Jordan from 1987 to 1990. ``I think all of
his instincts will be very much to follow in his father's
footsteps. On balance, I'd say that he's a good choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
