<SLUG> BC-GUNMAKERS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DELIBERATIONS AHEAD IN GUNMAKERS' LIABILITY SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When he left his home in Japan for a business trip to
California in 1994, Koichi Sunada could not have imagined the
sudden decision he would face in America: whether to authorize
doctors to remove his 22-year-old son from life-support machines.
The young man, who had been living in New York after immigrating to
the United States, was shot by a robber while Sunada was in
California, and was left brain dead in a Queens hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying recently in Federal District Court in Brooklyn,
Sunada recounted the nightmarish days after his grief-stricken
wife, at home in Japan, called him in California with the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Kei was shot,''' Sunada said. ``If you live in
Japan, the words `to be shot' are words one never hears.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunada told of rushing to New York and seeing his son _ a
physical fitness and karate enthusiast who had dreamed of becoming
an auto-racing driver _ tied to machines that were sustaining a
futile heartbeat, a hole visible in his head.
</P>
<P>
   Sunada, a 53-year-old urban planner, was not testifying at the
trial of his son's killer. That took place three years ago; the
gunman was convicted and sentenced to 25 years to life in prison.
Rather, he was testifying at the trial of others he also considers
responsible _ more than 25 American gun manufacturers, including
the giants of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sunada and relatives of five other people killed with illegally
obtained handguns, as well as a teen-ager severely wounded with
such a gun, are the plaintiffs in a potentially precedent-setting
civil suit being closely watched across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that the manufacturers are collectively liable
for the shootings in the case _ even if it cannot be proved which
company's gun was used in a given shooting _ because their
marketing and distribution of handguns has been so negligent that
they have fostered the illegal firearms traffic that put the
weapons into the hands of the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it is the first time such an argument has gone
to trial _ the jury could begin deliberating on it this week _ and
that the outcome could set a precedent for similar suits that
various cities have more recently filed, or are planning to file,
against gun makers, much as states have sued the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   But those are the far-flung implications and legal abstractions.
Sunada's testimony dealt with the agonizing personal circumstances
that helped give birth to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that since my son was brain dead, I should remove
the life-support systems,'' he testified, as he relived that day at
the hospital four and a half years ago. ``I was in shock. The
inside of my mind was in confusion,'' he said, his Japanese
rendered into English for the rapt jurors by an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   But after taking a night to think it over, he said, ``I agreed
to the removal of life support, and he died.''
</P>
<P>
   The gun makers deny the plaintiffs' central contention _ that
the companies oversupply states with weak gun-control laws and that
many of the excess guns end up in the hands of illegal traffickers
who resell them to criminals and youths in states with strong gun
laws, like New York.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say that the oversupply argument is based on
flawed data, that they cooperate with law enforcement, and that to
hold them liable would be to shift the blame to them from the
criminals who used the guns.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who have followed the case have seen it in terms of
David and Goliath _ a small group of people who have suffered the
consequences of the illegal trafficking, and four lawyers with
limited resources, versus major gun makers like Smith &AMP; Wesson
Corp. and Colt's Manufacturing Co. and their team of a dozen
well-financed lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four lawyers for the plaintiffs _ Denise Dunleavy,
Michael S. Feldberg and Marc E. Elovitz _ say they entered the case
only in the last two months, as the trial neared. For virtually all
of the time since the suit was filed in 1995, they said, the lawyer
who brought it, Elisa Barnes, had carried it forward as a solo
practitioner in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   One of the companies' lawyers, James P. Dorr, suggested,
however, that the David and Goliath perception was somewhat
exaggerated. He said other lawyers had helped Ms. Barnes behind the
scenes on pretrial matters like depositions. Ms. Barnes said that
other lawyers had volunteered to do two depositions for her, but
that she had done more than 30 others.
</P>
<P>
   But when David and Goliath were mentioned, she laughed at the
comparison. To become a figure of Biblical dimensions, she said,
``I'm going to have to go to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The gun companies' lawyers have expressed unhappiness that the
judge, Jack B. Weinstein, allowed the suit to go to trial,
maintaining that it had so little merit that he should have
dismissed it long ago. Instead, he ruled in 1996 that it was
possible the plaintiffs could convince a jury of their theory of
industrywide ``negligent distribution'' of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge has made clear that whatever cause lies behind the
litigation, he will not allow any crusading oratory. When Ms.
Barnes said to the jurors, ``We're going to ask you to turn off the
spigot'' that allows illegal guns to come into New York State, the
judge immediately stopped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you won't be asked to do that,'' he declared, adding that
the jurors would be asked to determine only whether the defendants
were liable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1420EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
