<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: HUD RESHAPES BOSTON PROJECTS AS MODELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For almost three years Rosa M. Cabrera has been living
in a temporary rental apartment, planning for the day she can move
into a new apartment at a South End complex going up on the site of
her former home.
</P>
<P>
   The new development, called Camfield Estates. is being built at
a cost of $17.6 million by the Federal Department of Housing and
Urban Development. It will provide 102 town houses, replacing 136
leaky, pest-ridden apartments in low-rise precast-concrete
buildings, which were demolished. Initial occupancy is scheduled
for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cabrera and other former tenants who were relocated before
the buildings were demolished intend to return _ and as the owners
of the development. They formed a residents association in 1992 to
influence the development process, and since then they have
undergone hours of training, financed by HUD, in real estate
development and management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I don't mind the time, as long as when we move back,
we don't have the same problems as before and these apartments are
there for other generations,'' said Ms. Cabrera, who is a
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Camfield Estates is replacing a development called Camfield
Gardens, one of 11 privately built but federally insured
developments that HUD repossessed in the South End, Dorchester and
Roxbury districts of Boston. With a total of 2,200 apartments,
these 11 developments form one of the nation's largest housing
revitalization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Demonstration Disposition, the program was intended
to serve as the model for the recycling of about 7,600 apartments
that HUD repossessed under its multifamily insurance programs
across the country. It is questionable, however, whether Congress
will appropriate enough low-income housing subsidies to make this
approach possible on so broad a scale.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston pilot program, HUD is investing $320 million for
new construction and renovation of 1,850 apartments in all 11
developments. Of that total 1,453 apartments will be in renovated
properties and the rest, 397, will be in new projects. Camfield
Estates is the first of the new ones.
</P>
<P>
   To make the apartments affordable, HUD is planning to deliver
them debt-free so that rents will not have to cover any mortgage
payments. In addition, the agency will supply housing subsidies to
the projects over 15 years under the Section 8 low-income housing
program, in effect a rent supplement making it possible to hold
tenants' rents even below the buildings' requirements for
operations and reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Project-based Section 8 subsidies for new construction have been
a rarity in recent years. Their effect will be to make it possible
to rent 87 percent of the new apartments to households earning 50
percent or less than the median income in the area. The the median
income in Boston is $44,000, so most tenants will be earning under
$22,000. They will pay 30 percent of their income as rent.
</P>
<P>
   Though financed by the Federal government, construction has been
managed by a state agency, the Massachusetts Housing Finance
Agency. So far, about 450 households have been relocated during
construction and about 200 apartments have been renovated and
reoccupied in various projects. First occupancy at Camfield Estates
starts in the summer, but completion of all 80 buildings is not
expected until 2002. The development cost per apartment is likely
to average $120,000, said Robert L. Pyne, development director of
the state housing agency.
</P>
<P>
   A central element of the program has been to involve tenants in
the redevelopment process. During the planning stages, the tenant
association at each complex received about $95,000 to hire a team
of professional advisers _ a lawyer, architect and development
consultant; a liaison with the construction company and a community
development corporation experienced in management.
</P>
<P>
   Once construction is completed, the tenant organization at each
complex will decide whether it wants to own the property alone or
in partnership with a private real estate company, or whether it
will forgo ownership entirely. In that case, HUD officials say that
they will sell the complex to a private company for $1 if it agrees
that for at least 30 years it will maintain the development for
low-income occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Camfield Estates is on 3.5 acres off Tremont Street in the
city's much sought after South End neighborhood, which in recent
years has become a popular residential location. The development it
replaces was built in 1971. Blaming poor design, construction and
management, HUD was obliged to foreclose in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the tenants' association won a $93,000 planning grant
from HUD It hired a development consultant and decided it wanted to
assume ownership and renovate the project, hoping for a HUD grant
to pay for it. A year later the Massachusetts agency became the
program administrator for HUD and found that demolition and new
construction was the way to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The new complex is designed as town houses around an oval
garden, with Domenech Hicks &AMP; Krockmalnick and Hezekiah Pratt &AMP;
Associates as the architects. There will be parking for about 80
cars, a community building with offices and a computer learning
center, ample landscaping and a large community garden. The total
development cost is estimated at about $167,000 per apartment.
Construction began last March.
</P>
<P>
   According to Paulette Ford, president of the Camfield Tenants
Association, the tenants are eager to move into brand new
apartments, but have been disappointed with some aspects of the
construction. They wanted an all red-brick facade to blend with the
neighborhood's Victorian architecture. Less costly gray vinyl
siding was chosen instead. They also feel that there should have
been more larger apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is will the buildings be sold to the
residents and kept affordable,'' Ms. Ford said. In the '60s more
than 2,000 housing units in nearby Roxbury were razed and tenants
were relocated with the promise that they could return to new
housing. But fewer than half the units were ever built and
apartments that did come back on market were too small or costly
for many of the displaced families to occupy.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is how long the process of vacating,
demolishing and completing construction will take. At Camfield
Estates it has already run on for six years, twice as long as
anticipated. Many families who were relocated have scattered and
will not return despite their original intention to do so. Camfield
had 126 households in 1993. Now 78 say they will return, according
to Ms. Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, housing advocates see much to admire in the
program. ``This program is revitalizing what was a seriously
distressed inner-city neighborhood and delivering high quality
housing with more tenant involvement than usual,'' said Aaron
Gornstein, director of Citizens' Housing and Planning Agency, a
national affordable housing advocacy group based in Boston. ``But
as in many complicated large-scale development projects, there have
been glitches along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he questioned the adequacy and timeliness of the
tenants' training and the length of the development process. And he
noted that in the long term there is uncertainty about the
availability of adequate subsidies to maintain affordability.
</P>
<P>
   For some relocated tenants affordability is already a concern.
Ms. Cabrera's income is too high to make her eligible for a rent
subsidy, and she expects a new rent of about $1,000 a month, phased
in over a few years, compared with the $476 a month she had been
paying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard,'' she said. ``But we'll have brand-new
apartments, I can return to be with my neighbors, near my job and
we'll help set an example for the other developments in the area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1422EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-DAVOS31-COX     01-30 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-DAVOS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rubin warns of trade crisis
 &HT;    By Andrew J. Glass
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ The United States cannot run huge trade
deficits with its major trading partners indefinitely, U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned an international conference
of political and business leaders here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international system cannot sustain indefinitely the large
imbalances created by the disparities in growth and openness
between the U.S. and its major industrial trading partners,'' Rubin
declared at the weeklong World Economic Forum being held at an
Alpine ski resort.
</P>
<P>
   While Rubin promised not to use the dollar ``as an instrument of
trade policy'' he conceded at a press conference following his
speech that financial markets might act in coming months to drive
down the value of the dollar, as measured against the euro and
other major trading currencies. The possible drop in the dollar,
which would reflect the huge U.S. trade huge deficit, would make
foreign goods more expensive in the United States while American
products would be cheaper overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Savings rates in the United States are far too low, Rubin noted,
striking a familiar theme in the four years he has served in the
Treasury post. But in response to a reporter's question, Rubin said
``he could not presume to advise Americans not to invest in
securities,'' a form of consumption that does not alleviate the
impact of the trade outflows.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin also seemed reject any major restructuring of the
International Monetary Fund and other global financial institutions
that have been widely criticized since the Asian financial crisis
first erupted in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Widely discussed reforms that sound attractive on their
surface, on full examination often raise serious questions to which
there are currently no good answers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin also ruled out the creation of a so-called ``early warning
system'' that would alert governments and private investors to
impending trouble in capital markets or third-world economies.
</P>
<P>
   Neither his 26 years' experience as a Wall Street trader nor his
service in several roles in the Clinton administration, Rubin said,
had assured him that such a predictive system would work. What is
more, he said, ``the early warning system itself could create
precisely the instability and even panic that such a system is
designed to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
