<SLUG> BC-R-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BETTY CURRIE'S P.C. PASS
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING from Friday, Jan. 29, to sub 7th graf to insert
`niggardly') (bl) 
By FRANK RICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you can't beat 'em, join 'em. Bill Clinton, aspiring to be
President Pothole, gives a focus-group-driven laundry list of a
State of the Union speech that stops just short of promising every
citizen a health-club membership _ and what do Republicans do to
counter it? Both of the members of Congress giving the GOP
televised response advertise that they've had Clintonesque marital
fissures in their own families, and one of the pair, Jennifer Dunn,
goes on and on about how ``sound,'' ``strong'' and ``prosperous''
the country is on Clinton's watch.
</P>
<P>
   As if this weren't enough, Pat Robertson pronounces the
president's speech a ``home run'' _ and, in another
Alice-in-Wonderland reversal, Rush Limbaugh soon decides to join
Larry Flynt's crusade by inexplicably Flynting a conservative GOP
senator by name on his radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes still more proof that Bill Clinton has frightened his
opponents into switching teams: This was the week that the 13 House
managers decided to become, of all things, touchy-feely P.C.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation could first be sighted last weekend when the
managers, some of them in jus'-folks sweaters suggestive of
Clinton's golf-course wardrobe, reported on their first official
tryst with Monica Lewinsky, speaking empathetically about how
``personable and impressive'' she was. Henry Hyde went so far as to
say that the point of the meeting was ``to get a sense of how she
(Ms. Lewinsky) feels.''
</P>
<P>
   But the final proof came 48 hours later when the guys produced
their long-awaited witness list, and it did not include Betty
Currie.
</P>
<P>
   The president's secretary up until that moment had been
considered nearly as certain a witness as Ms. Lewinsky. Her
presence had frequently been cited by the House managers as
crucial; anti-Clinton pundits had piled on with plausible
explanations of why she was, as they put it, ``the one essential
witness.'' If you believe that the obstruction of justice count is
the more solid of the two impeachment articles, they argued, no one
is better placed at the Clinton-Lewinsky-Vernon Jordan nexus than
Mrs. Currie to get at the gift-hiding, job-searching and
testimony-coaching at the core of Clinton's possible
witness-tampering in a federal case.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Currie failed to make the witness list, there was
bafflement from Republicans like Susan Collins as well as Democrats
like Charles Schumer _ not to mention much of the press _ and no
credible on-the-record explanation for this omission from the
prosecutors. But the niggardly, not-for-attribution mutterings were
clear enough: The 13 white men cowered at the prospect of throwing
hardball questions at an African-American woman who might break
into tears.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think it might be a little late for such heightened
sensitivities. Given that the House managers include one member
who's spoken before a racist group and others who have fueled the
attack on quotas, affirmative action and Anita Hill, why run away
at this make-or-break juncture from as valuable a witness as Mrs.
Currie? Such is the ever-increasing power of Bill Clinton to set
the agenda for even his fiercest adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   The president who promised a cabinet that looked like America
had, in typically shameless fashion, done the same with his defense
team: one disabled lawyer, one black woman lawyer, one white woman
lawyer, one Brooks Brothers lawyer and, to wrap it all up, one Good
Ole Boy. The 13 managers clearly, if belatedly, took this
stage-managed diversity to heart. Given the choice between calling
a black woman who might actually help their case and summoning
Sidney Blumenthal, an unshakable Clinton partisan who is more
peripheral to it, they blinked. The politics of P.C. trumped the
legal imperatives and inviolate principles that supposedly governed
their prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's main virtue as a witness is that his public persona
is so annoying _ he's the recurrent hangnail of the Clinton
scandals _ that he could arouse national sympathy for Kenneth
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   But the managers didn't consider the prospect that in the world
of P.C. they've now entered, even the choice of Blumenthal could
backfire. All he has to do to become a martyr is convince America
that he has been targeted by the Clinton-bashing Rev. Jerry
Falwell, who, just days before the release of the witness list,
proclaimed that the Antichrist is alive, ``male and Jewish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
