<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELPHI31-COX     01-30 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELPHI31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delphi `set free' by GM to become publicly traded company
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner and Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ General Motors Corp. on Friday will nudge its
huge auto parts division out of the corporate nest in a move that
will forever alter Dayton's identity as a GM town.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest automaker will offer up to 18 percent of
Delphi Automotive Systems in an initial public offering of stock on
the New York Stock Exchange. The IPO is scheduled to take place
Friday, a spokeswoman for the exchange told the Dayton Daily News.
GM plans to distribute the remaining stock in Delphi, the world's
largest maker of auto parts, to GM shareholders later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The spin-off, which has been two years in the making, will
immediately make Delphi one of America's largest independent
companies. It also will remove 15,000 of GM's 20,000 Miami Valley
workers from the automaker's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi's pending independence has brought both anxiety and hope
for workers whose future largely depends on whether the new company
sinks or swims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that it will work, but I guess it's wait and
see,'' said Ahmad Abdul-Majid, a worker at the Delphi brake plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad deal for people that's been working for GM all
these years,'' said Harley Turner, another brake plant worker. All
the GM job security and benefits and even the GM purchases of
Delphi products will be up in the air, he said. ``It's going to be
tough _ that's what everybody is worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a Wall Street tradition, Delphi leaders are
expected to celebrate the offering when Delphi Chairman and Chief
Executive J.T. Battenberg III rings the bell to open trading on the
New York Stock Exchange. Delphi officials believe the stock,
trading under the symbol DPH, will open at about $16 a share,
according to GM filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Delphi, based in Troy, Mich., has 204,000 employees in
169 manufacturing plants, 40 joint ventures and 27 technical
centers spread throughout 36 countries. Outside the state of
Michigan, no metropolitan area has more Delphi workers than Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's legacy as a GM town will linger, but as an independent
company, Delphi will easily eclipse the automaker as an economic
power in the Miami Valley. Only Wright-Patterson Air Force Base,
with 20,700 employees, will have a larger local work force.
</P>
<P>
   Once the spin-off is complete, the Moraine Truck Assembly plant
will be the only GM factory in the area. A new diesel engine plant
in Moraine, expected to open in 2000, is expected to be a joint
venture between GM and Isuzu Motors Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, GM has served as a source of security and
prosperity for Delphi workers, but they may emerge from the
spin-off with a brighter future, one automotive industry authority
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delphi is being set free and I think you're going to see the
company absolutely blossom in this role. I think it's a positive
deal for all those involved, shareholders, employees and
(Dayton),'' said David Cole, director of the University of
Michigan's Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation.
``(But) it's a tough world and Delphi will have to be tough and
smart to stand out against the competitors out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the spin-off, Delphi's primary goal remains
increasing its non-GM business internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, about 35 percent of Delphi's business comes from
sources other than GM's North American operations. That's up from
17 percent in 1992, but Delphi officials want at least 50 percent
of their business to come outside GM by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delphi has proven its ability to compete,'' said John F.
``Jack'' Smith Jr., GM's chairman and chief executive, in a letter
to shareholders. ``But the fact is, for competitive reasons, many
manufacturers simply refuse to buy components from Delphi as long
as it's part of General Motors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cole also warns that Delphi can no longer expect a free ride
from GM when bidding as an automotive supplier. After the spin-off,
GM will buy parts from any supplier it chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to have to work like crazy to keep GM's
business,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi and GM executives spent most of last week on their IPO
road show trying to convince potential investors nationwide that
their company will be profitable and stormy labor relations with
its blue-collar work force have calmed. Falling prices for its auto
parts and high labor costs are the main challenges facing Delphi
executives as they tout the new stock.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi's board also cut bonuses for the company's top executives
following weak 1998 financial results. Excluding several charges
and the impact of labor strikes, Delphi's net income was $889
million last year, down 36 percent from $1.38 billion in 1997,
according to SEC filings.
</P>
<P>
   Battenberg, for example, had his bonus cut 56 percent to
$450,000 for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Even if investors embrace Delphi stock, local labor experts say
nothing is guaranteed for Dayton and other communities that depend
on the massive company for jobs and income.
</P>
<P>
   `` My crystal ball says there will be fewer (plants and jobs in
Dayton 10 years from now),'' said Steve Dandaneau, a sociology
professor at the University of Dayton. ``Common sense says there
will be fewer. Older plants and equipment will be retired ... I
wouldn't be surprised if there were 50 percent fewer workers in 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which posted $28.5 billion in sales for 1998, has
seven divisions that make brakes, shocks, struts, air conditioners,
compressors, steering systems, air bags, and many other automotive
parts. These components are then integrated into systems that are
often tailored to fit specific vehicle models for about 30
automakers worldwide. Some of those companies include Chrysler,
Ford, Honda, Harley-Davidson, Hyundai, Isuzu, Mercedes Benz,
Mitsubishi, Suzuki and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   The company now supplies parts to every major automaker in
Europe and provides cockpit modules to Fiat, Volkswagen AG and
Daimler-Benz AG.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi's roots trace back to GM's beginnings in the United
States. GM founder Billy Durant bought AC Spark Plug in 1909. Four
years later, Durant acquired Dayton Engineering Laboratories
(Delco). Soon, he acquired companies owned by Dayton inventor
Charles Kettering, father of the self-starter.
</P>
<P>
   Delco is Delphi's main ancestor in Dayton. Delco products, Delco
Moraine and the Inland division employed thousands of local workers
for decades before they were consolidated in the late 1980s. The
three divisions were part of GM's massive Automotive Components
Group, which eventually was named Delphi in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
