<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-NYT &LR;      01-30 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WAR HAS WROUGHT: SIERRA LEONE'S SAD STATE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Issa Alison-Konteh sat at an
intersection in this capital, an unsteady stool beneath him, the
gutted Piccadilly chicken grill behind him, a crumbled house beside
him and two burned-out buildings before him.
</P>
<P>
   The two buildings were set aflame last February, when
Nigerian-led peacekeeping troops swarmed into Freetown and restored
President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah to power. He had been ousted a year
earlier by rebels who contend that they are battling a rich clique
that they say runs what the United Nations ranks as the world's
poorest nation.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a so far vain but extremely brutal campaign to recapture
the city, the rebels returned and destroyed the house and
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicians do their own, the rebels do their own, and
you're caught in the middle,'' said Alison-Konteh, 39.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of civil war between the rebels and a
government that says the guerrillas are merely out for their own
gain, Sierra Leone lies in ruins, a country only in name. More than
440,000 of its people _ about 10 percent of the population _ have
fled to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Government authority has dissolved. The main national defense
force is the Kamajors, a ragtag militia of men and boys who often
wear mirrors on their chests in the belief this will ward off
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the government's only significant support has come
from a West African peacekeeping force headed by soldiers from
sub-Saharan Africa's most populous country, Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But that support seems about to evaporate, leaving Sierra
Leone's capital under attack and its northern and eastern regions
in the sway of rebels who, according to the government, foreign
diplomats and locals, terrorize residents by hacking off hands and
feet of captives to show what vengeance they can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big mess,'' said a Western diplomat in the region. ``It
is not a mess that will be easy to clean up.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this change lie in Nigeria. The former dictator
there, Gen. Sani Abacha, found it useful to draw attention away
from his record of abuse at home by promoting democracy abroad _
which in Sierra Leone meant heading up the peacekeeping force known
as Ecomog and restoring Kabbah to power in 1998 (the grateful
Kabbah promptly renamed one of Freetown's main arteries Sani Abacha
Street).
</P>
<P>
   But Abacha died in June, and his successor, Gen. Abdulsalami
Abubakar, has promised to restore civilian rule in Nigeria and said
he hopes to withdraw all its troops from Sierra Leone by May. In
addition, the price of oil, Nigeria's chief source of wealth, is
plummeting, slicing at the money needed to help keep Sierra Leone
together.
</P>
<P>
   As for Washington, it gave Ecomog $3.9 million in 1998 for
peacekeeping in Sierra Leone. This year, as part of the United
States' shrinking total peacekeeping budget in Africa, only $1.3 is
budgeted. No reliable figures exist about the costs incurred by
Nigeria, though some diplomats have suggested that they might reach
as high as $1 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Nigerians are in Freetown, a city of ruins that
belies the optimism of its name, given when it was settled two
centuries ago by freed slaves from Britain and America.
</P>
<P>
   The first university in sub-Saharan Africa was founded here. But
now there is only death, despair and devastation. Nigerian forces
shell the hilly outskirts of eastern Freetown, where the rebels
have fled for now, retreating from their latest offensive, launched
Jan. 6, to retake this skeleton of a city.
</P>
<P>
   The latest assault on Freetown followed three months during
which the rebels killed and maimed villagers in eastern and
northern Sierra Leone. The rebels' actions seemed to be a reaction
in part to the public execution in Freetown of 24 soldiers involved
in the 1997 coup against Kabbah and, more important, the death
sentence handed out last October to their leader, Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, who is appealing the death sentence and is believed to
be in jail somewhere in Sierra Leone, founded the Revolutionary
United Front in 1991, saying he was disgusted with the
mismanagement and corruption of successive civilian governments.
</P>
<P>
   A cashiered army corporal, Sankoh directed his guerrillas from
the bush. He has been seen in the outside world only a few times
and is said to inspire religious devotion among his followers, an
unknown number of whom are now fighting on his behalf and demanding
his release.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Sankoh signed a peace agreement with Kabbah, who had
been chosen president in what were considered fair elections. The
elections followed five years of rule by the military, whose young
officers enriched themselves in the country's diamond mines _
tapped since by the government and the rebels to finance their war
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1996 accord quickly unraveled. The military staged a
coup in 1997 and invited the rebels to join them in Freetown in a
partnership that lasted until February 1998 when the Nigerians
helped restore Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels now trying to topple the president are made up of
Sankoh's group and former members of the military. No one knows
exactly how many they are; nor is there a precise number for the
Ecomog forces in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's group, consisting of men and boys from rural areas,
says it represents disaffected Sierra Leonans against a powerful,
small elite in Freetown who exploit and monopolize the country's
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have vast mineral resources and yet we are the poorest
country on the face of the planet,'' said Martin Coker, the special
assistant to Sam Bockarie, the rebels' battlefield commander.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in the bush on his satellite phone, Coker said: ``Our
people are deprived of basic human rights to health, education, and
a better standard of living. It is a noble cause that we have
embarked on.''
</P>
<P>
   Coker, who said he lived illegally in the United States for a
decade and worked as carpenter in Washington until 1996, denied
charges by ordinary Sierra Leonans, the government, foreign
diplomats and international humanitarian groups that members of his
organization had committed atrocities. He blamed instead the
militia fighting for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Septimus Kaikai, the president's spokesman, rejected the rebels'
criticisms. ``There are no issues for these people,'' he said.
``They do not have a political agenda. They do not have a religious
agenda. There's no social agenda. What they're simply doing is
simply personal; it's personal aggrandizement, selfishness on their
part, just to amass wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   The government _ along with the United States, Britain and
Nigeria _ has accused Liberia of helping the rebels in Sierra Leone
with arms and men. Sankoh is a longtime ally of Liberia's
president, Charles Taylor, who was once a guerrilla leader himself
waging an extremely vicious seven-year civil war that ended in a
stalemate and in his eventual election as president.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has denied his government's involvement in Sierra Leone,
although he has said that Liberian individuals are fighting in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of the Liberian war _ reflected later in wars in
countries like Zaire, now Congo, Rwanda, the Congo Republic and
Sierra Leone _ included the widespread use of child soldiers and
the notion that unarmed citizens are fair targets.
</P>
<P>
   But the influence of Liberia's war may have been greatest on
Sierra Leone: in addition to close ties between Sankoh and Taylor,
soldiers, rebels and mercenaries from both countries are believed
to have fought in each other's wars, easily crossing the porous
border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   When Sierra Leone's rebels briefly held power, they proved
extremely unpopular among residents of Freetown, many of whom lined
the streets this month to cheer Nigerian soldiers. After the deaths
and mutilation of thousands in the capital during the latest
offensive, any reconciliation with the rebels is hard to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's main sports stadium, where thousands of refugees
and hungry gathered, there was no talk of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to be flushed out of the country,'' said Abdul
Margai, 28, whose house had been set afire by rebels. ``Just kill
them. We don't want to see them again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kill them,'' echoed Emmanuel Dijohn, 25.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, men, women and children walked in file, staring
straight ahead, carrying on their heads bags of rice, branches and
other tools to start over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello! How are you? Welcome!'' a woman cried to a reporter
drawn to a small fire burning in the ruins of her house.
</P>
<P>
   A group of boys had burned down the front of her house, leaving
only a back portion, which Fatimata Koroma was now cleaning. Mrs.
Koroma, 40, said she had fled the fire by jumping over a backyard
fence at least 2 feet above her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine a woman like me jumping this fence and then jumping
another fence higher than this one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fearful,'' she said. ``I would prefer to die than see
such things again.'' Then she returned to cleaning the remains of
her house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1442EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-2TAKES     01-30 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IMPEACHMENT TRIAL THE QUEST FOR WITNESSES A MATTER OF PRECEDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI AND KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., knows that President
Clinton is almost certain to be acquitted on the articles of
impeachment, because the Senate lacks the two-thirds majority
necessary for a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Smith knows, too, that the three witnesses about to be deposed
for Clinton's trial have been questioned time and again, and may
have little if anything new or revelatory to say.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as he gets closer to the moment when he will have to
cast a vote that will likely be remembered better than any other in
his political career, he finds himself craving an extra ounce of
confidence, a few more grams of assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like a greater sense of certitude than I have now,''
he said in an interview on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he could comfortably vote guilty
or not guilty on the articles of impeachment without an iota of
additional information.
</P>
<P>
   But no impeachment trial in the Senate, Gramm said, had ever
proceeded to a verdict without at least some word from witnesses, a
step that he said was proper and reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice is not an outcome, it's a process,'' he said in an
interview late Thursday. ``There's almost too much focus on the
horse race aspect of this _ who's winning, who's losing _ rather
than the system. We're setting a precedent that's going to be
important 50 years from now and 100 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   With the impeachment trial of President Clinton poised to round
a pivotal corner and turn toward fresh testimony from three
witnesses beginning Monday, the Republican senators who steered it
in that direction said they were not blind to the public distaste
for the proceedings or oblivious to the predictability of the
verdict at the end.
</P>
<P>
   They were not on a political suicide mission, they said, or a
crusade to humiliate the president at any cost, as many Democrats
have asserted. The Senate has 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats, and
it would take 67 votes to convict Clinton and remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In extensive interviews with a dozen Republican senators over
the last three days, they said they were trying to satisfy a
variety of needs and concerns that were more important than any
rapidly reached terminus.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them said they were interested in resolving lingering
questions about the evidence. Others said they were interested in
safeguarding Constitutional procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Several said they simply wanted to be as thorough and
responsible as possible, an effort that they said a few witnesses
and a few more days could only assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you say there aren't two-thirds, for each of us
who have to cast those votes on the articles, it makes a difference
in how we explain those votes,'' said Sen. Olympia J. Snowe of
Maine, a moderate Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe added that when future generations ``look back on the
record, they want to see how we arrived at this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania said that he shared that
concern and that he and many other Republican senators had not
firmly made up their minds about their votes on the two articles of
impeachment. The first article charges Clinton with perjury, the
second with obstruction of justice for trying to conceal his sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make the right decision,'' Santorum said. ``That's
important for me. I want to make a decision based on the oath for
impartial justice. If I don't get all the information, then I'm not
doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that for some senators, the vote to take videotaped
depositions from Ms. Lewinsky and presidential confidantes Vernon
E. Jordan Jr. and Sidney Blumenthal, was less an expression of any
confusion about the voluminous record of the case than an act of
accommodation for the House trial managers who had pressed for
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, several senators said that the depositions were by
no means a prelude to the appearance of witnesses on the Senate
floor. Sen. Richard Shelby of Alabama said he would vote against
such a scenario ``unless there was something explosive, like
dynamite'' in the depositions.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's a number of people on my side of the aisle who
would vote no,'' Shelby said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Most of the senators interviewed would not signal how they
intended to vote; they said that would be inappropriate, given that
they are acting in part as jurors who have taken oaths of
impartiality.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, most of the senators also declined to
discuss in detail what testimony from the three witnesses they were
most interested in hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was one of the exceptions. While he said he was leaning
toward voting for conviction on obstruction of justice, he said he
was tilting toward acquittal on perjury. He added that many
Republican colleagues were similarly inclined, and that Clinton
might win acquittal on perjury by a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd bet at least a third of my colleagues see it as I do,''
Smith said, explaining that he felt that Clinton's denials of a
sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky were artful enough to ``stay
on the legal side of perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas agreed that there were many
Republicans who would vote to acquit Clinton on perjury, although
he would not say where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them feel it's encompassed in the obstruction of
justice,'' said Hutchinson, whose brother, Asa, is one of the House
trial managers. ``Some of them feel that perjury would not rise to
an impeachable offense, but obstruction of justice does.''
</P>
<P>
   Those senators willing to discuss the upcoming depositions in
detail said there were several key areas of interest. One was the
precise course of events on the day when Ms. Lewinsky returned
several gifts, which the president had given her, to Betty Currie,
Clinton's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   House trial managers have contended that the purpose of a 3:32
p.m. phone call which Mrs. Currie placed to Ms. Lewinsky on Dec.
28, 1997, was to arrange the retrieval of the gifts, and that the
advance call somehow showed that Mrs. Currie was doing the
president's bidding. But Ms. Lewinsky has testified several times
that she gave the gifts to Mrs. Currie around 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that whole area needs clarification,'' Hutchinson
said, adding that further questioning of Ms. Lewinsky might
accomplish that. ``It's something I need.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa said he was particularly
interested in assessing Ms. Lewinsky's and Jordan's voices and
demeanors when they respond to inevitable questions about their
previous testimony that Jordan's efforts to find her a job were not
down payments on her silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so flatly unbelievable,'' Grassley said. ``It makes you
wonder how a lowly intern can get the attention of the president of
the United States, a $12 million-a-year lawyer like Vernon Jordan
and John Podesta, the president's chief of staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said, in reference to Jordan, ``I'd like to know how many
other interns in the White House he went to these lengths to get
jobs for. It's just _ it really smells, frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said he hoped to see Blumenthal asked anew about the
president's initial assertion to him early last year that Ms.
Lewinsky was a mendacious stalker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what he knows now,'' Grassley said, ``what's his
reflection of what the president told him? Was the president
obstructing justice by coaching him? He's either got to say what he
thinks, or take the Fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Gramm said that there was always the possibility to gain
more insight into the case than the thousands of pages of records
had provided.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he said: ``Anybody who says they've sat down and
read those six volumes is not telling the truth. I don't believe
it.'' He said he had read only ``bits and pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said he had learned ``a tremendous amount'' in the
trial so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn every day,'' Gramm said. ``Every time this ground is
plowed, you get a better understanding of the facts. I'm sure I'll
learn something in the last sentence that's spoken. Will it change
my mind? Maybe, maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, most senators, including Gramm, said these fine
points were not the primary reason for the depositions scheduled
for Monday through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate consideration, they said, was history. To proceed
to this next chapter of the trial was to stay true to the past, set
a good example for the future and craft an insurance policy against
any assertions down the line that Clinton's transgressions were
swept aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing what the Constitution requires, handling this
case the way every other impeachment has been handled,'' said Sen.
Mitch McConnell of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that Republicans were taking the long view. ``If we
shortchange this too much,'' he said, ``we will create a grassy
knoll for conspiracy theorists for the next century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
