<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YACHTING-AUTISSIER-NY     01-30 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHTING-AUTISSIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILOR OVERCOMES CALAMITY IN SOLO RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isabelle Autissier is as amazed as anyone at the success she has
resurrected from failure in sailing alone around the world.
</P>
<P>
   A string of mishaps at sea in December in the 27,000-mile Around
Alone race set calamity in motion aboard her yacht, PRB. The
sailboat's canted keel went haywire, the satellite antenna fell
overboard, and the boat's mainsail track jammed.
</P>
<P>
   Helpless in storms, and slow on a good day, the 60-foot sailboat
limped to Tasmania for repairs like a hot-air balloon with a slow
leak. For Autissier, hopes of winning the eight-month ocean race
all but evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this is now _ the race restart from
Auckland, New Zealand, on Feb. 6. The 41-year-old Autissier will
not only be among the dozen solo sailors expected to set out on Leg
3, but she is also in the lead by six hours on elapsed time. Her
position is a puzzle unless you know her drive, tenacity and vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had all those problems, all I could think about was to
get to safety,'' Autissier said last week in a telephone interview
from Auckland. ``We have an expression in France that says it is
`to save the furniture.' I was sure I would lose three or four
days. I had been leading, and suddenly, I felt I was out of the
race. I thought, `What have I done to the ocean?'''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Autissier fixed her boat and set out again, she was
about 500 miles behind the leader, Giovanni Soldini of Italy. But
her boat hitched a fast ride on a sizable cold front with 40-knot
winds. ``Suddenly, I did it,'' she said. ``I had good luck. I was
able to be very quick, and I caught up.''
</P>
<P>
   The next stage of the Around Alone race is apt to bring other
tales of turmoil at sea. But Autissier's travails through three
previous round-the-world races and this competition, have always
tested her shrewdness in the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Where she is headed now _ the 5,960 miles across the Pacific
Ocean to South America, around Cape Horn and north to Uruguay _ are
often kinder to her. ``In the Pacific Ocean, the low fronts are
slower, and more predictable, so you have time to do something,''
she said. ``The Pacific Ocean is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other sailors do not share that optimism, however. With
Cape Horn reaching down into the Pacific like a mad troll, the leg
can be treacherous. In previous round-the-world races, two solo
sailors, Harry Mitchell of England, and Gerry Roufs of Canada,
disappeared in those waters without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Pierre Mouligne, a Frenchman who lives in Newport, R.I.,
will sail at that low latitude known as the Screaming Fifties for
the first time. As the leader in Class II, for boats up to 50 feet,
Mouligne is anticipating the journey with trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leg 2 was easy _ cold and windy but not dangerous for me,''
Mouligne said from Auckland. ``But I dread Leg 3 as it could prove
to be a lot more difficult. So far I have done well, and I am
better prepared than ever before. But that is only part of the
equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a fast and well-outfitted boat, as Mouligne has in his
50-foot Cray Valley, makes the trip fairly palatable. But others
are not so fortunate. Fedor Konioukhov, the Russian sailor who has
trailed other competitors in Class I by as much as 4,000 miles,
might have to face that span of open ocean truly alone.
</P>
<P>
   Konioukhov was due to arrive in Auckland this weekend, but on
Friday he inexplicably began sailing away from that port. Race
officials did not expect him to arrive in time to make the race
deadline, which would result in his disqualification from the
competition. Konioukhov's participation was already in jeopardy for
failing to honor a waypoint on the route from Cape Town to
Auckland. More importantly, questions have been raised about his
boat's failure to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-foot yacht, Modern University for the Humanities, is
relatively old and weather-worn compared to others in the fleet. If
Konioukhov encounters trouble on the way to Cape Horn, other
sailors might not be able to rescue him. Autissier said it is in
Konioukhov's best interest to retire from the race in Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has trouble, of course, we would go to find him,''
Autissier said. ``But he is very slow, and it is very dangerous for
him. It might be that nobody is close enough to help him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
