A5264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      01-30 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Jan. 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slow-moving low pressure will crawl toward the central
Mississippi Valley on Sunday, causing an area of rain to expand
across the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys. Damp winds from the
east and southeast will stiffen during the day as the pressure
difference increases between the low and a strengthening high over
New England. A few thundershowers will be imbedded in the rain
area, but cool air near the ground will limit the threat of severe
storms. Meanwhile, patchy freezing drizzle will occur over parts of
the central Missouri Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty onshore winds will draw Atlantic moisture into the
southern Appalachians. Intermittent rain will develop from northern
Florida across Georgia and the western Carolinas. The precipitation
will begin as freezing rain and sleet in some of the higher
elevations. Farther south, partly sunny and warm conditions will
cover central and southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Cold and dry weather will prevail in most areas from the
northern Great Lakes to New England. Chilly winds from the
northeast will produce patchy clouds and flurries near the New
England coast. Otherwise, sunshine will be plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will persist in the Northwest as strong winds
from the Pacific promote periods of coastal rain and mountain snow.
Locally heavy snow will plague the Cascades and northern
Bitterroots later Sunday and Sunday night as a jet stream
disturbance arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will be dry and mild although some high clouds
will dim the sun over parts of New Mexico and the Rio Grande
Valley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Ocean Snow
</P>
<P>
   Snow and high pressure systems seldom go hand in hand. But, on
Thursday and Friday, an expanding area of high pressure in Quebec
was the catalyst for as much as nine inches of snow near the
Massachusetts coast. The clockwise circulation of air around the
high generated strong, cold winds from the northeast along the New
England coast. As the chilly winds passed across the milder ocean
water they garnered moisture that was deposited as snow after
reaching land. This is the same mechanism that sometimes leads to
heavy snowfalls for regions downwind of the Great Lakes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
