<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUPERFUND-2TAKES-N     01-30 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUPERFUND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI FACES BALANCING ACT ON SUPERFUND
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's Superfund program, which has been
responsible for cleaning up more than 300 hazardous-waste sites
across the state, is running out of money, putting Gov. George
Pataki in a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, is caught between environmentalists who
want him to refinance and even strengthen the program, and his
powerful corporate allies who want him to relax the stiff penalties
and cleanup rules that it imposes on businesses and the owners of
polluted property.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is considered a defining one for Pataki. In his first
four years as governor, his actions preserved hundreds of the
state's most cherished rivers, lakes, streams and forests _ firmly
establishing him in the public mind as an environmentalist, a
central part of his political appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also been pilloried in some environmental circles,
accused of neglecting the contentious issue of corporate pollution
while he pursues a Republican agenda of easing regulations to make
New York friendlier to business.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Pataki's efforts to protect open spaces have enabled him
to walk a political tightrope, as a Republican environmentalist who
has avoided any major fights with his allies in the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides reject the idea that he is pursuing conflicting
goals. But many experts say that the Superfund issue may force him
to choose a side. ``This is one of the most critical environmental
issues he will have to face as governor,'' said Larry Shapiro, an
environmental lawyer for the New York Public Interest Research
Group. ``It will be one of the most prominent tests of his
administration's commitment to protecting the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The state program, formally known as the Inactive Hazardous
Waste Disposal Site Program, was created to clean up toxic dumps
and spills not covered by the federal Superfund program. Since the
New York program was created in 1982, it has spent more than $1
billion. The last major infusion of cash it received was in 1986,
when voters approved a $1.2 billion bond act to refinance it, but
all that money is now either spent or spoken for.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the state's program has cleaned up more than 300 waste
sites, from landfills to abandoned dry cleaning plants and gasoline
stations, and it is still cleaning 511 others. But it lacks the
money to finish all of those or to clean up about 300 other
properties identified by state officials as posing a ``significant
threat to public health.''
</P>
<P>
   After avoiding the issue for years, Pataki and his aides have
said he intends to address the matter this year with a package of
proposals aimed at overhauling the program. But he has said almost
nothing about how he intends to renew the program, apart from
saying that he would add several hundred polluted sites not
currently on the list. His relative silence has left many questions
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The questions include: Should the program be paid for by
taxpayers or by the industries that use and produce toxic
materials? Do contaminated sites need to be thoroughly cleaned even
when they will be put to industrial use? And should the current
owner of a property be liable for a cleanup even though the
previous owners were responsible for the contamination?
</P>
<P>
   For the governor, the most critical question is how to refinance
the program, which some environmentalists estimate will cost $2.5
billion over nine years. Some environmentalists contend that the
state should continue funding a major portion of the program by
assessing fees and taxes on the industries that produce,
manufacture or use hazardous waste materials. But business leaders
have refused to accept that option, unless environmentalists agree
to make changes to the program that would be more favorable to
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to commit significant new money to the program
until program reforms are made that make more sense,'' said Kenneth
J. Pokalsky, the director of environmental programs for the
Business Council of New York State, a statewide chamber of
commerce. ``There are things that are wrong with the program as it
now stands.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has not said how he intends to respond. But an advisory
group he appointed to propose a refinancing plan is seriously
considering relaxing some of the program's rules, according to a
preliminary report it has circulated among its members. The Pataki
administration would not comment on the committee's work other than
to say that the group had reached no final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration disputes the notion that the Superfund
program is testing the governor's commitment to the environment,
saying that his record on pollution is as strong as it is in
preserving open space. ``There are those who like to build the
Republican stereotype of `good on land and bad on other
environmental issues,''' said Gary Scheffer, a spokesman for the
State Department of Environmental Conservation. ``But it doesn't
fit this governor, and that frustrates them.''
</P>
<P>
   One major change that corporate leaders are pushing for is in
the area of so-called cleanup liability. The current program holds
not only the major polluter of a site responsible for its cleanup
but also a long list of others _ from banks that foreclosed on
contaminated property to subsequent owners.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders say that the main polluters alone should be
held responsible. They contend that the current liability
provisions in the Superfund program are needlessly punitive and
have led to litigation that has delayed cleanup projects.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists contend that industry has overstated the
degree to which minor polluters are targets of Superfund programs.
They say that most of the protracted legal fights over cleanups
were started by major polluters who are dragging subsequent owners
of a contaminated property and other innocent parties into court to
share the cost of the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Another question being debated is the practicality of holding
property owners to stringent cleanup standards in all cases.
Business leaders want to allow owners to consider the realistic
health risks and the proposed uses of contaminated sites when
cleaning them up. For example, pollutants would not have to be
entirely removed from a contaminated property if, say, an
automobile repair shop was to operate there.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders contend that while no level of exposure to
hazardous materials is desirable, such risks should be put into
perspective, given the huge expense of cleaning a site to
preindustrial conditions. Otherwise, they say, many contaminated
properties will be left undeveloped and ultimately benefit no one.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and others argue that that approach is
dangerous because no one can say for sure how a property will be
used in future years as it changes ownership. They also contend
that failure to eliminate pollutants entirely poses a risk to
natural resources like groundwater and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that that approach doesn't work is because today's
corner gas station is tomorrow's condo,'' said Judith Enck, an
environmental analyst with the New York Public Interest Group. ``I
think this is just an attempt to get the cheapest cleanup costs
possible for polluters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
