<SLUG> BC-NY-DOGOWNER-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNERS KNEW MAN THROUGH HIS DOG
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JODI WILGOREN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was, as Beth Pacheco put it, ``just a wonderful,
warm story in a cold city.''
</P>
<P>
   With background barking as a kind of memorial music, more than
40 people, accompanied by about 30 dogs, bowed their heads in
prayer Saturday morning to honor a man they hardly knew.
</P>
<P>
   They did not know his religion.
</P>
<P>
   They did not know what caused his death.
</P>
<P>
   Most did not even know his last name.
</P>
<P>
   But they knew his dog, Hamlet. And so they gathered in Cadman
Plaza Park in Brooklyn Heights _ lawyers and bookkeepers and
doormen, shepherds and Dobermans and mutts _ to remember John
Tanski, a man who lived alone and died alone and is still alone,
his body unclaimed in the local morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``John died a lonely New York death, with no one to claim his
remains,'' said Jennifer Bausch, 29, a lawyer who organized the
makeshift service, brought the bagels and dog biscuits, and offered
a brief eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know John Tanski well,'' Ms. Bausch said. ``The only
thing I knew real well about John was that he loved Hamlet. That
was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlet, a 4-year-old shepherd mix whose black and brown coat is
highlighted with white fur, pouted a bit at the service, then
busied himself with a box of ``People Crackers'' from the doggie
snack bar. Neighbors said Tanski was 42 and lived off disability
payments after suffering a head injury years ago in a motorcycle
accident. They said he had rescued Hamlet as a puppy from a
homeless man who had abused him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing that ever happened to John was Hamlet,'' Ms.
Bausch said. ``The best thing that ever happened to Hamlet was
John.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bausch, with her huge gray bouvier des Flandres, Godiva, and
the other mourners knew Tanski and Hamlet by sight, from passing
one another in the park each day as they scooped their poop. He
would talk baby talk to the puppies as Hamlet flirted with their
parents, whose owners were part of the community of dog people in
anonymous New York who connect only through their pets.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 a.m., they would see Susanne Fordham, 47, and her hulking
90-pound red Doberman, Aranda. Afternoons, they would bump into
Mary Lee Graffeo, an actress, with Natick, half chocolate Labrador
and half Doberman. At night, they would meet Chris Hanscom-Bolton,
31, and Molly and Noodle, his poodles.
</P>
<P>
   Known to them as Hamlet's John, Tanski talked little of his
life, and rarely mentioned what must have been his many problems.
It was all about the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamlet used to steal Aranda's toys,'' Ms. Fordham said. ``So I
always brought two. John used to bring it back later in the day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a routine,'' she added. ``When Hamlet wasn't there, I
noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   The dogs and their owners began to worry when Tanski and Hamlet
disappeared from the park. It was Ms. Bausch, who knew where he
lived and went to check on him, who found him in his apartment at
the St. George Hotel two weeks ago. Neighbors said the Medical
Examiner's office told them he had been dead for four days. Hamlet
was hungry, but he had not soiled the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial service Saturday, publicized by word of mouth
and through a dozen simple fliers hung on trees and in pet stores,
there were dogs in sweaters and dogs in harnesses, sleek spotted
dogs and fluffy white ones, puppies and old-timers, dogs rubbing
noses and growling suspiciously, scampering about and sitting at
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I know them all so well, but they're always
here,'' Ms. Graffeo said to explain why she _ why they all _ had
gathered on this chilly morning. ``People who put a lot of care
into their dogs find a way to care about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pacheco, a retired college professor, does not have a dog,
but she saw Tanski and Hamlet on her frequent walks in the park, so
she attended anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sharon Blackburn of Plymouth Church of the Pilgrims in
Brooklyn Heights read from the Bible. Ms. Bausch quoted from her
own book, ``Dogs Never Lie About Love,'' sharing a passage in which
Napoleon came upon a dead enemy at the end of the Italian campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lay there deserted by all except his dog,'' Ms. Bausch
read. Napoleon, she said, was stirred to tears ``by the grief of
one dog.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending a week at the pound, Hamlet is now in a ``foster
home,'' and the Brooklyn Heights Dog Association is trying to find
him a permanent place in Brooklyn Heights, where he knows the
sights and smells. They are also searching for a final resting
place for Tanski, who they said was estranged from his family in
New Jersey. Only a relative can authorize cremation, so they are
collecting donations for burial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurt me all day, knowing he died alone,'' said Jim
Murray, 40, his two dogs, Ata, a mutt, and Henry, a border collie,
wandering around his ankles. ``I just hope, God forbid, when I go
at 100, people have this for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
