<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5292 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-625&AMP;ADD-N     01-30 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PREPARED TO AUTHORIZE STRIKES AGAINST SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-ULTIMATUM, KOSOVO-ASSESS) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO allies worked into the night Saturday
on a plan to authorize military action against Serbia at any time
if it does not agree to start talks next weekend in France with the
ethnic Albanian leaders of Kosovo about autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance ambassadors in Brussels prepared to give authority to
NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana, after he consults with
allied capitals, to order airstrikes against military targets in
Kosovo and elsewhere in Serbia unless President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia agrees to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   They met after Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of Britain presented
an international ultimatum to Milosevic and Kosovo Albanian leaders
in the region. Milosevic, who annulled autonomy for Kosovo 10 years
ago, made no direct response Saturday, Cook reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, meetings were scheduled throughout the weekend on
plans for possible airstrikes against Serbia if Milosevic resists
the negotiations. Also being discussed was how to send in American
ground troops should President Clinton decide they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's top national security advisers have reached
a consensus to recommend sending American ground troops should the
two warring parties agree to a cease-fire, administration and
congressional officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement released Saturday, David Leavy, a White House
spokesman, said ``the president has made no decision'' on whether
to send American troops should an international peacekeeping force
enter Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Six nations _ the United States, Britain, France, Italy, Germany
and Russia _demanded an end to all violence in a meeting of the
so-called contact group on the Balkans that had been scheduled in
London on Friday in the expectation that NATO would issue an
activation order Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Allies did not want to take sides with the
Kosovo Liberation Army, in effect becoming its air force against
Serbia in the rebels' struggle for independence, a goal none of the
contact group countries supports. Ethnic Ablanians make up 90
percent of Kosovo's people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making clear that the actions of the Kosovans in the
negotiations and on the ground will have a bearing on the decision
of the secretary-general to order strikes,'' a senior NATO diplomat
said. Further possible military measures to exert pressure on the
rebels, like a NATO naval blockade of major Albanian ports, are
still under study, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under what amounts to an international ultimatum, both sides
have seven days from Feb. 6, extendable by a week or less, to reach
agreement on autonomy along lines worked out over the last few
months by an American mediator for Kosovo, Christopher Hill, the
ambassador to Macedonia. The negotiations would be held in
Rambouillet, a rural 18th-century chateau 32 miles southwest of
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serbs and the Kosovo Albanians do negotiate a settlement,
officials said, the alliance would draw up plans for a
30,000-member NATO peacekeeping force that could stay in Kosovo for
years while a peace conference works out more permanent
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are considering plans to
contribute 2,000 to 5,000 troops to the peacekeeping force, and
leaders of France and Britain said last week that both their
countries would provide soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said no decision had yet been made on withdrawing
1,020 international observers from the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe who are now monitoring the situation in
Kosovo. A French-commanded NATO extraction force of 2,000 European
soldiers is based in Macedonia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albanian loyalties have been divided between the Kosovo
Liberation Army, armed through Albania by a financial support
network in Europe and the United States, and moderates led by
Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian nationalists view Kosovo, where the Serbs suffered a
historic defeat against the Turks in 1389, as holy ground.
Milosevic used the 600th anniversary of the battle to mobilize
support for the nationalist cause a decade ago, telling a million
Serbs at the site that they would never again be victimized.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO decision would reactivate plans for both immediate,
limited warning strikes and a wider ``phased air campaign'' that
could hit Serb air defense sites and other military targets not
only in Kosovo but also elsewhere in Serbia. Hundreds of planes,
mainly American, and dozens of ships are poised for operations that
could start from bases in Italy and the Adriatic within days.
</P>
<P>
   The supreme allied commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of the United
States, had authority to begin the bombing in October if Milosevic
refused to withdraw heavily armed police and army units that were
attacking Albanian villages as well as Kosovo Liberation Army
units, and to begin negotiations with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to the threat, Milosevic promised to comply, and Clark's
activation orders were suspended. But according to Western
officials, Milosevic did not do what he promised.
</P>
<P>
   After a Serbian attack that killed 45 Albanian civilians in the
village of Racak this month, the United States began mobilizing
international support for stronger action to stop the violence.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright lobbied allied foreign
ministers and went to Moscow to persuade Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov to support a call by the contact group for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright refused to say she would go to the contact group
meeting until she was assured that NATO allies, including France,
would vote to authorize military action.
</P>
<P>
   American negotiators accepted a decision by the Allies Saturday
to leave the primary responsibility for ordering military action
this time in the hands of Solana, a civilian, rather than Clark's.
NATO officials said Solana would consult with allied capitals
before going ahead, but that he would not have to seek a new
alliance decision to order Clark to launch the planes and cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The plans would also allow Solana to order bombing if there was
another major atrocity against civilians, though the threat of
imminent NATO action did not prevent a Serbian police raid on
Friday in which 24 ethnic Albanians were killed in the village of
Rugovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Solana could also give the order if Milosevic
refused to make good on the earlier promises to reduce police and
military forces in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is to show our determination to both
parties,'' a French official said. ``The Albanians see time working
in their favor, and the eventual emergence of a greater Albania,
but that is not what the international community wants. We want
substantial autonomy for Kosovo within Serbia for a determined
period of, say, three years, which will allow time to reach a
permanent settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, some Western officials hope, Milosevic could be history
and more moderate Serb leaders might agree to let Kosovo go.
</P>
<P>
   But the other side of the coin is that if the two parties do
agree to come to Rambouillet, American and European peacekeepers
could be stuck in Kosovo for years, as they have been in nearby
Bosnia since the end of 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
