<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIXOPEN-MEDIATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIATE IS READY TO END A LONG DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ When you have not won a golf tournament in
six years, it is natural to have doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Mediate's last victory on the PGA Tour came in 1993. But
Mediate, who started Saturday as the leader of the Phoenix Open,
insisted he was not looking for a place to hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I can win again; I just don't know when,'' said
Mediate, who started Saturday's third round at six-under-par 136
for the tournament, two strokes ahead of Tiger Woods. ``It's been
six years, but a lot of those years, I was hurt and didn't play
much. I just want to play well this weekend, be there on Sunday,
and maybe have a chance to birdie the last hole and win. If I get
in that position, I won't be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Mediate has overcome adversity to return as a factor on
tour. In 1994, he sustained a ruptured disk that required back
surgery and threatened his career. It was a turning point for
Mediate, but he accepted the challenge. Once overweight, he has
lost more than 60 pounds during the last five years, and he now
looks slender at 6 feet 1 inch and 190 pounds. Mediate maintains a
rigorous workout regimen, aimed at preventing back problems. And
while the change in his body forced Mediate to make changes in his
swing, he feels more comfortable than he has in several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked a lot in the off season, and I worked on the right
things,'' Mediate said. ``I want to be ready when I come out here.
I feel like it's my job, and I should be ready, or I shouldn't come
out. I'm stronger and hit the ball farther than I've ever hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 36, Mediate feels as if he has some good years
left on tour. But he admits the depth of talent is much greater
than it was when he joined the tour in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players out here today are so good,'' said Mediate, who
has two career tour victories, the 1991 Doral-Ryder Open and the
1993 Kmart Greater Greensboro Open. ``To win, everything has to go
your way, unless you're like David Duval, and kick everybody's tail
by nine strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done anything like that before, but a lot of these
guys have that kind of talent. Tiger Woods, Phil Mickelson _ you
can go on and on. Guys come out here ready to win right away.''
</P>
<P>
   But through two rounds at the TPC of Scottsdale, Mediate's
experience and patience had paid off. Historically, the Phoenix
Open has been a birdie-fest, like it was two years ago when Steve
Jones won the tournament at 26 under par. But this year, the rough
has been grown higher, some of the fairways have been narrowed and
some of the tee boxes have been moved back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's playing a lot more difficult,'' Woods said. ``You have to
be careful. The greens are more firm than they were in '97, when I
played here last. And the pins seem to be more tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediate agreed, but he was enjoying the challenge. ``It's kind
of U.S. Open-like,'' he said. ``The fairways are wider, but the
rough is tough, and the greens are firm. The course is very
difficult, and it's not going to get any easier. I don't know if
the course is going to let us shoot low scores, but I like it that
way. I think I'll handle it fine. I'm not much for 25 or 30 under
par. I have never shot that low, so I don't expect to.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-round play was suspended on Friday due to darkness, so
Mediate was not certain who his playing partner would be Saturday.
But there was a good chance that Mediate would be paired with
Woods, whose gallery was certain to be boisterous, especially at
the Phoenix Open, known for raucous crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Tiger doesn't bother me at all,'' said Mediate.
``He's a lot of fun to play with. We've had a good time the few
times we played. You can't let other people dictate what you're
doing, or you're going to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be out there with him. I want to feel that. It's
been a long time. Before I got hurt, I was there a lot, in
contention. I didn't win a lot, but I was there a lot. I love that.
I want to be in there and feel nervous, see how I handle it.
Hopefully, I can handle it and survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Through two rounds, Mediate was right where he wanted to be. And
he hoped that he was two rounds from victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my second tournament of the year, and I didn't know if I
was ready,'' said Mediate. ``I guess I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
