<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CO-OPS AND LIABILITY FOR HARASSMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many business owners are aware of the legal and
financial perils of sexual harassment in the workplace and have
taken steps to help prevent it. But co-op and condominium
associations, lawyers say, have generally failed to guard against
the possibility of such claims, despite the fact that some
buildings have many employees.
</P>
<P>
   Two 1998 U.S. Supreme Court decisions, however, along with a
recent New York state Supreme Court ruling on discrimination in
hiring, now make ignoring sexual harassment and discrimination _
and failing to deal with it properly when it occurs _ a risky
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that most buildings are unaware of the increased
potential for claims of discrimination and harassment being filed
against them,'' said Richard Siegler, a Manhattan co-op lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler said that one reason sexual harassment in the workplace
has not been a matter of concern for co-ops and condominiums is
because the male-dominated building service workforce makes it less
likely for the most common form of sexual harassment _ male
supervisor and female subordinate _ to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, however, a state Supreme Court Justice in
Manhattan began to chip away at the male domination of the building
service workforce by refusing to dismiss a discrimination complaint
brought by an African-American woman who had been denied a job as a
door person at 13 buildings. The ultimate outcome of the case has
not been decided.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Siegler said, the U.S. Supreme Court broadened the
federal sexual harassment laws to include so-called same-sex
harassment. In the case of Oncale vs. Sundowner Offshore Services,
he said, the court found that ``pervasive unwelcome conduct of a
sexual nature'' could constitute sexual harassment even though the
victim and the harassers were all males.
</P>
<P>
   And in the case of Burlington Industries Inc. vs. Ellerth,
Siegler said, the Supreme Court ruled that if a victim of sexual
harassment suffered a ``tangible job detriment'' _ such as being
denied a promotion or a raise _ then the company itself would be
held ``strictly liable'' for the harassment, even if it did not
have knowledge that the offensive behavior was occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that even buildings that have all male employees
can end up defendants in sexual harassment lawsuits,'' Siegler
said. ``And they can be held liable even if there was no knowledge
the harassment was taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Salvatore, a Manhattan labor and employment lawyer, said
that ``the only issue is how big a check you have to write _ and
it's not unusual to find six-figure verdicts in these kinds of
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Salvatore added, however, that the court did provide employers
with a defense against strict liability for claims of sexual
harassment. He said that if an employee has suffered no tangible
job detriment, and if the employer has a policy against harassment
and a procedure for dealing with harassment complaints, then the
company would have an ``affirmative defense'' to liability if the
employee did not report the harassment and take advantage of the
complaint procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that employers who are doing the right thing to
prevent and address sexual harassment claims have a defense against
liability,'' Salvatore said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, those employers who do not establish
policies and procedures for dealing with sexual harassment leave
themselves wide open to liability.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Salvatore said, employers _ including co-ops and
condominiums _ can conceivably be held liable for the improper
actions of individuals who are not even direct employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be harassment of a building employee by a vendor, by a
subcontractor, or even by a delivery man who makes regular
deliveries,'' he said. It is even conceivable, he said, that
harassment of a building employee by a shareholder _ who is an
owner of the company _ could constitute actionable sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harassment in the workplace is a minefield for the unwary,''
Salvatore said.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, should co-op and condominium boards do to avoid the
mines? ``The most important thing to do is to take a proactive
approach to discourage harassment and discrimination,'' said Nancy
Smith, a Montclair, N.J., lawyer who specializes in sexual
harassment law. ``And the best way to discourage discrimination and
harassment is through training.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said that all employers should consider hiring
consultants who specialize in training employees to think
differently about sexual, racial and religious discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's important for big companies to train their employees,
it's even more important for co-ops and condominiums to do the
same,'' she said, comparing training to an ``insurance policy''
against harassment lawsuits. ``When big companies lose lawsuits
they have deep pockets to dig into. But when a co-op or condominium
gets hit with a six-figure judgment, it's like the money is coming
from your own family.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegler said that his law firm has been recommending that client
buildings with more than 15 employees adopt a comprehensive policy
against all forms of harassment and discrimination and a procedure
for dealing with complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The policy, he said, should explain that harassment is not
limited to matters of a sexual nature but can include racial,
ethnic or religious slurs or jokes, and even teasing about a
disability. Harassment occurs, he said, when submission to such
conduct is made a term or condition of employment, or rejection of
such conduct is used as the basis for employment decisions
affecting an employee, or when the conduct unreasonably interferes
with an individual's performance or creates an intimidating,
hostile or offensive working environment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Siegler said, a complaint procedure should be
established so as to encourage employees experiencing harassment or
discrimination both to advise the offender to cease the behavior
and to notify a supervisor if it does not stop. The policy should
also require the supervisor to report the allegation to the
president of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Siegler said, the policy should require that all
complaints be promptly and thoroughly investigated and that
disciplinary action be taken if warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Taranto, president of Taranto &AMP; Associates, a Manhattan
management company, said that her company has gone one step further
to protect itself and its clients against claims of harassment and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling everybody to take out discrimination insurance,''
Ms. Taranto said, explaining that her company recently purchased $1
million in such coverage from Chubb Insurance for an additional
premium of about $5,000 a year. ``It's worth it. Discrimination and
harassment suits are becoming rampant. Everybody seems to have
something to sue about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
