<SLUG> BC-STATES-SEN-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SANTORUM SAYS WITNESSES NEEDED IN IMPEACHMENT TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan. 29, -- Pennsylvania Republican Sen. Rick
Santorum said witness testimony in President Clinton's impeachment
trial was crucial to helping him make up his mind about the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need that information,'' Santorum said. ``I want to have as
complete a record as possible. We have an obligation to bring this
case to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum's reaction came after a tumultuous week in the Senate
that ended with the preparation of subpoenas for Monica Lewinsky,
White House aide Sidney Blumenthal, and the president's friend
Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate rejected a motion to close debate and vote on the
verdict. It approved a Republican-backed plan providing a rough
outline for what could be the last two weeks of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the three witnesses to give depositions.
Then, they could give live or videotaped testimony in front of the
Senate, if approved by a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said he thought if the trial had ended without
witnesses, the House impeachment managers would not have had a fair
chance to present their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important the Senate have a trial,'' Santorum
said. ``We need to follow our constitutional mandate to vote on the
articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter would not comment on the trial, but in the past said he
wanted a full trial with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said he thought it would have been premature to dismiss
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Though calling witnesses will prolong the trial, Santorum and
Specter have said they will still manage to focus on other issues
including reforming Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Specter has said that the Senate's schedule isn't
full in January and February. He said work hasn't stopped on other
topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Security issue is the number one domestic issue
which has to be resolved,'' Specter said. ``We've been working on
it simultaneously while the impeachment proceedings have been going
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
