<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-DUDLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROUGH-AND-TUMBLE DUDLEY IS READY TO ROLL FOR KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chris Dudley clamped the rebound between his hands,
and using his elbows like a machete, cleared the space around him
Friday night. Along the way, he caught the Nets' Keith Van Horn
right in the goatee.
</P>
<P>
   As Van Horn checked his jaw alignment, you wondered if the
spirit of Charles Oakley had moved Dudley to display that kind of
rebounding form and technique in the Knicks' exhibition loss in New
Jersey. But this is Dudley. Always has been.
</P>
<P>
   In his 11 years in the NBA, he has defied his genteel Yale
pedigree _ one that includes his grandfather Guilford Dudley, the
former ambassador to Denmark _ by bashing and thrashing with
blue-collar appeal in the paint. While Oakley has been banished to
Toronto, Dudley survives him as the Knicks' intimidator.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be as feared as Oakley, but Dudley presents a prickly
thicket of sharp elbows around the basket. Van Horn knows that now
as the caretaker of a fat lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing that little Charles wasn't old enough to see
that one,'' said Dudley, who was called for a flagrant foul on the
play.
</P>
<P>
   Little Charles is 3{ months old, and the firstborn of Dudley and
his wife, who is also named Chris. Little Charles is the reason
Dudley rolled out of bed at 3 a.m. to help with the feedings during
the lockout. He is also the reason Dudley started his rigid
workouts just three hours later every morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get up at 6 a.m. anyway,'' Dudley said. So he forced
himself out of the house in San Diego and went through extensive
flexibility exercises, hit the weight room, worked on his game and
ran with a former Marine.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a very fit 34-year-old who arrived at training
camp in excellent shape after signing a four-year, $28 million deal
to be Patrick Ewing's support system. Dudley was pressed into a
29-minute performance on Friday when Ewing left with a mildly
sprained right knee during the second quarter. It's unclear how
long Ewing will be out, but whatever practice or playing time he
misses will be absorbed by Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dudley spent part of the off season tinkering with an
offensive game that has never wowed anyone, he reverted to what he
does best Friday night and ended the final exhibition tuneup with
13 rebounds and 4 points (1 of 6 from the field, 2 of 8 from the
free-throw line).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to work on their weaknesses in the off
season,'' said Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who watched Dudley take an
uncharacteristic 5 shots and grab just 2 rebounds in 17 minutes
during the Knicks' first exhibition game on Wednesday. ``He's tried
to keep developing his offensive game. But sometimes you forget who
you are. He had more shots than rebounds in the last game.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the team played well with Dudley on the floor. Before
back trouble put him on the injured list in February, his role as a
defender allowed Allan Houston and Larry Johnson to blossom. In
that way, Dudley is a nice fit for the new, more diverse Knicks.
But when Ewing is healthy and conditioned, there is no match for
the impact he can make offensively. Until Ewing's injury heals and
his form returns, Dudley has shown he can be an effective
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays very hard,'' Van Gundy said. ``You know what you're
getting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have paid handsomely to get it. Dudley's lucrative
deal was the payoff for the risk he took last year. Passing up a
three-year, $18 million offer from Detroit, Dudley dived through a
loophole in the former collective bargaining agreement by
re-signing with Portland for just over $1 million to facilitate a
sign-and-trade deal with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   After a touch-and-go negotiating process before training camp
two weeks ago, the Knicks came up with a contract to make up for
his sacrifice. Dudley had offers from other teams, Buck Williams
was about to retire, and the Knicks had just sent Terry Cummings to
Golden State in the Latrell Sprewell deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little apprehensive when it looked like things might
not work out here,'' Dudley said. ``But on the other hand, I don't
know, I was kind of at peace with it. I had some money because I'd
been in the league for a while, and I wasn't worried. I know it's a
saying that you put it in God's hands, but that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley just wants to perform. And do it in a way that will
conjure Oakley's image from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's added pressure, but I do want to step in
and help out in Oakley's loss,'' Dudley said. ``I don't know if I
have to do more. I think I've always been an aggressive player. I'm
not trying to change my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
