<HEADLINE>
BANKING ON SUPER BOWL T HELP FEED THE HUNGRY
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: N.J., Conn., N.Y., S.C.)  
(dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBA, S.C. _ Children do not go to bed hungry in the fine
homes of suburban Spring Valley's cul-de-sac neighborhoods. But
hunger is on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday they will show it.
</P>
<P>
   At dozens of churches in Spring Valley and Columbia, and
thousands more around the United States, teen-agers will stand at
the exits, soup pots in hand, collecting money for people who have
far less than they. They call it the Souper Bowl, playing off one
of America's most conspicuous days of consumption, Super Bowl
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 10th year, the Souper Bowl has raised more than $4.4
million for the poor and the hungry. Last year, 8,577 churches took
part in 50 states, raising $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Souper Bowl started at the Spring Valley Presbyterian Church
when a young intern, Brad Smith, prayed on Super Bowl Sunday for
parishioners to remember ``those without even a bowl of soup to
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, after Smith earned a divinity degree and
returned as the 900-member church's youth pastor, the empty soup
bowl image came back to him. He discussed it with members of the
church's youth group, and they came up with the idea of asking each
person in church on Super Bowl Sunday for $1 and a can of food.
Church members told their friends, who told their pastors, leading
22 churches in the area to take part that first year. They raised
$5,700.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the young people created fliers publicizing the
Souper Bowl. They added 124 more churches around the state and
collected five times the amount. In three years the Souper Bowl had
spread to churches beyond South Carolina, largely by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The money and food go to food banks, soup kitchens, homeless
shelters and local branches of Habitat for Humanity in thousands of
communities throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In New York last year, 375 churches took part, raising $76,853.
In New Jersey, 186 churches raised $43,366 and in Connecticut, 58
churches raised $11,765.
</P>
<P>
   Each church's youth group decides where to donate the money
collected. Advance sign-up is not required. Church leaders can _
and have _ decided to take part on Souper Bowl morning, by
gathering soup pots and announcing the collection at the worship
service. All Smith asks is that someone from each church call his
toll-free number that afternoon to report how much was collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contemporary church can throw its hands up, fight it or
pretend it's not there,'' Smith said recently of the materialistic
trappings of football's biggest game. ``Or we can acknowledge that
football transcends many things in our society, and we can use that
for good.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL itself has jumped on the Souper Bowl bandwagon. Several
teams, among them the Denver Broncos, the Super Bowl champions who
will defend their title on Sunday, have made public service
announcements for the Souper Bowl. Campbell's Soup has promoted the
event in its advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the number of churches participating grew by 60
percent, while the cash collected increased by 54 percent. Smith
believes the program's growth and its attractiveness to young
people lies with the fact that it is simple and it has integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Smith said his pride in today's young people had
swelled. Despite all the tales of troubled children, what Smith
says he sees in his own church and what he gleans in telephone
calls from around the nation is that young people are committed to
improving their world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our young people are bombarded with messages of hopelessness
and despair and yet every one of them is created in the image of
God and can make a difference,'' he said. ``They give, they care
for others, they are good stewards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
