<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNY AND REGENTS FIELD FLOOD OF CALLS ABOUT CHARTERS FOR SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The phone calls are already coming in, 50 or 60 a
week, to the State University of New York and the state Department
of Education, asking what it takes to start a charter school.
</P>
<P>
   A state law, passed last month, authorizes the university and
the Board of Regents to grant 50 charters each for new schools. In
addition, the Regents can approve an unlimited number of
conversions of existing public schools. The charter schools will be
publicly financed but will be run by teachers, parents and
community groups, independent of their local districts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the university nor the Regents are prepared to take
applications yet, but they are working together to develop
application forms, to set policy and to formulate a joint grant
request to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to have a draft of an application form in February,
for discussion. In the meantime, they suggest that potential
applicants look at application forms from Florida, New Jersey and
Massachusetts, to get an idea of what they might require.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY and the state both say that, in talking to officials in
other states, they have learned that it does not pay to rush.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, for example, issued five charters in three months, said
Scott W. Steffey, a SUNY vice chancellor who is heading the
university's new Charter Schools Institute, and officials in
Florida said that if they could do it again, they would not do it
so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they would have taken a year to 18 months,'' Steffey
said. ``We have the benefit of learning from their mistakes, and
will not move so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Kadamus, a deputy commissioner at the state Department
of Education, said it was possible that a few charter schools would
open as soon as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who are very far along, and have filled
out other application forms and have found financial backing,'' he
said. ``It is conceivable we could have people ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadamus and his department will brief the Regents on charter
school progress at their meeting this week. Steffey reported on his
progress at SUNY's board meeting last week.
</P>
<P>
   Steffey said he thought the typical approval process might take
six to nine months and include three phases: a written application
and interview; a contracting stage in which the university would
scrutinize the contracts a school intended to sign with teachers,
transportation companies, food vendors, testing companies and
others; and a preopening phase for ironing out final details, like
a certificate of occupancy for the space the school will use.
</P>
<P>
   But Steffey also suggested that potential applicants might seek
advice from groups that have been created around the country to
help develop charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   While the university and the Board of Regents have many
decisions yet to make, some policies have been established by the
new state law:
</P>
<P>
   Charters will be granted for five years but can be revoked for
cause, either by the university or by the Regents.
</P>
<P>
   A charter school cannot base admission on intellectual ability
or achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Schools intended for disadvantaged students are to get
preference.
</P>
<P>
   A school must have at least 50 students to qualify for a
charter. If it has fewer than 250 students, it will not be bound by
union agreements. But the university is allowed to grant 10
exemptions, so up to 10 schools can exceed 250 students and still
not be bound by union rules.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Board of Trustees is responsible for approving and
monitoring university charter schools and will probably set up an
oversight committee, the university's Charter Schools Institute
will handle most of the work. The institute is also intended to
conduct research on charter schools and other education issues, and
to serve as a national clearinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Aceto, president of SUNY's Faculty Senate, recently
expressed his dismay over Steffey's appointment as head of the
institute, saying that his career had been in marketing, not
education, and that he had no experience working in primary or
secondary education.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to newspapers, Aceto added that the Steffey
appointment was not a result of a national search, but of a
decision to select ``someone with no qualifications who is one of
their `own.''' Steffey declined to respond to such criticism, other
than to note his experience as an executive at Nynex.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of SUNY's academic affairs committee earlier in
mid-January, the chairwoman, Candace de Russy, asked Steffey how
the university would define and insure quality in charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   He said that those were among the questions the institute had
yet to answer. ``The whole question of how to make them accountable
but leave them free from reregulation is an extraordinarily
significant issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Badillo, vice chairman of the City University of New
York, who was a guest at the recent SUNY committee meeting, asked
whether City University could start a charter school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just submit an application,'' Steffey responded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
