<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECT-NH-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW HAMPSHIRE THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL IS WARMING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., N.J., Ariz.)  (rk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ The campaigning for president never really ends
in New Hampshire, home of the United States' first primary for the
better part of half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Lamar Alexander, the former Tennessee governor, who
finished third in the Republican contest in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of a few hours, not a few years, he was back, at
least in spirit. Bumper stickers in plaid (his campaign color
scheme) began appearing the morning after the primary, each
brightly emblazoned with ``2000!''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Alexander himself reappeared, working _ and
networking _ to get the Republican nominee, Bob Dole, elected. Then
just a few weeks after the fall election, he began returning on his
own, once again trudging about in search of votes and campaign
money, his eye now locked on February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has since become such a dogged fixture in New
Hampshire coffee shops, Rotarian meetings, high school civics
classes and such that the political quip of the moment is that he
should be paying New Hampshire taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same could be said of Steve Forbes, the publisher, who
finished fourth in the 1996 Republican primary. He, too, was back
on the trail in a matter of months and has since created something
of a permanent political presence in the Granite State, matching
Alexander almost visit for visit and, like Alexander, running some
of the earliest ads ever seen anywhere in primary campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But the days when Alexander and Forbes can claim New Hampshire
as their own little political playground are about to end. With the
2000 primary now little more than a year off, the rest of the
presidential wannabes, who for the most part have made only
scattered forays to New Hampshire and even fewer forays to other
states, are beginning to gear up for concentrated campaigning here.
</P>
<P>
   All the talk that they might bypass the New Hampshire primary or
the first-in-the-nation Iowa caucuses seems so far to be nothing
more than just talk. Oh, March 7 still looms as the most important
day of the season, with primaries in close to a dozen states,
including delegate-rich California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But no presidential hopeful has yet been so bold as to say that
New Hampshire and Iowa can now be ignored, that the early bounce
they have given winners no longer counts for much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other states keep rushing forward to be among the first to
hold their primaries, but candidates still look upon us as the
first of the first,'' said New Hampshire's chief election official,
Secretary of State William Gardner. ``Delaware is trying to steal
some of our thunder by scheduling their primary within four days of
ours instead of the usual week. But otherwise we haven't seen any
real signs that 2000 will be any different than other years for us,
and if we do we'll fight it.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was, then, that on Monday, Bill Bradley, the former New
Jersey senator and onetime New York Knicks star, arrived here for
his first real campaign outing of the year, trailed by a crush of
political reporters and live-at-6 TV teams, many from out of state.
More than anything that Bradley, a Democrat, said or did, that
clamoring gaggle of scribes and anchor people served notice that
Election 2000 was genuinely under way.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Vice President Al Gore will be in the state, not his
first trip but his first in this new phase of Election 2000 and one
meant to shore up his considerable lead in the polls, given the
Bradley challenge.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, three potential candidates are visiting
in the next two weeks: Alexander in still another foray, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona in his first visit in months and Elizabeth Dole
in her first trip here since resigning as president of the American
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Like McCain and a number of others, Dole, whose husband is Bob
Dole, is ``exploring'' whether to run at this point, but in the
parlance of presidential politics that essentially is a euphemism
for a test run or a marketing trial.
</P>
<P>
   So how is the field faring thus far?
</P>
<P>
   The latest New Hampshire polls, which should carry a ``Use At
Your Own Risk'' label this early on, have Gore comfortably ahead on
the Democratic side, with only Bradley daring to challenge to date.
On the Republican side Mrs. Dole and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
appear evenly matched, with the rest of the field trailing badly,
including the earliest starters, Alexander and Forbes, as well as
former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   According to Democratic Party officials, Gore is exceptionally
well positioned in New Hampshire, not just because he is so well
financed but because over the years the Clinton administration has
worked the state with great care.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, on the other hand, faces the daunting task of starting
from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Republican presidential aspirants in New Hampshire,
announced or otherwise, Alexander probably has the most extensive
political operation at this point, followed by Forbes. Both also
are well financed, especially Forbes because of his great personal
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   But party officials say that Mrs. Dole, Bush and Quayle are in
telephone contact with supporters across the state and that either
could be up and running with a strong organization in short order,
mainly because each has visited the state many times in earlier
campaigns, Quayle as the No. 2 on the Republican ticket, Mrs. Dole
to campaign for her husband, and Bush to campaign for his father,
the former president. The party officials also foresee no money
problems in the state for any of the three.
</P>
<P>
   For the other announced and unannounced Republican aspirants,
among them McCain, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, Gary Bauer of the
Family Research Council and Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire,
money and a strong campaign organization may be harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   But none are being counted out, given the quirky nature of the
state's politics: Many primaries over the years have turned on an
obscure issue or event that suddenly burst on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Any chance that Smith could become a ``favorite son,'' thereby
scaring off the other candidates?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not likely,'' says Stephen Duprey, the state Republican
chairman. ``The field is too strong for that, especially if Dole
and Bush jump in. In fact, I think the best bet at this point is
that we could have a field of at least eight candidates, one of the
largest ever. And if we do, we're going to have a real cat fight,
one that could have a surprise ending because the vote could be so
terrifically fragmented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
