u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      01-30 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH POLITICIANS SAY THEY ASKED ABOUT BID `IMPROPRIETIES'
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By KIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In the late summer or early fall of 1997, more
than a year before the Olympic bribery allegations emerged that
have since shaken this state to its core, two of Utah's senior
state politicians invited the president of the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee, G. Frank Joklik, to a get-acquainted meeting at the
state capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians were concerned. They had heard reports _ rumors,
really, they said _ about what the then-speaker of the House of
Representatives, Melvin R. Miller, termed ``improprieties,'' in
Salt Lake's conduct during the competition for the 2002 Winter
Games, which Salt Lake had captured in 1995. So they said they
asked Joklik, who had recently replaced Thomas K. Welch as
president of the Organizing Committee, what he could tell them
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He indicated that that happened when Mr. Welch was in charge,
and had nothing to do with him and was out of his purview,'' Miller
said. And that was pretty much the end of the conversation, Miller
recalled. Since he and the Senate president, Lane Veattie, had only
hearsay and rumors of what had gone on, they had no way to follow
up on their questions. ``You obviously had no basis on which you
could challenge Mr. Joklik's position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting has become even more loaded with meaning _ at least
in retrospect _ in light of the budget documents that have emerged
about how the Salt Lake Bid Committee had incorporated, as early as
1991, a specific program that included financial assistance to
people who could influence the awarding of the 2002 Winter Games.
The question of knowledge within the committee _ who knew and
understood what the programs included _ has become a central issue
as state, federal and independent investigations into the scandal
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik's attorney, Mark H. Tuohey, said Joklik had not
investigated the concerns raised by the Miller and Veattie because
their concerns were simply too vague. He also said that some rumors
had been floating around at the time about possible use of
prostitutes for International Olympic Committee members, but he
said those rumors had been found to be groundless, and that Joklik
thought that's what the officials were talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't, `Look, Frank, we've got problems with this and this
and this,' because he would have looked into that,'' Tuohey said.
``It just wasn't any more specific than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But politicians, business people and residents here say that
that obscure meeting in the office of the Senate president also
illuminates some other unavoidable truths in Salt Lake during and
after the city's race for the Olympic rings: There were rumors,
speculation, hearsay and gossip about the Bid Committee's doings
and the IOC members who were seen being whisked about town. And in
every case those reports ran hard up against a Bid Committee that
had become almost fortress-like in its power and its secrecy and,
many people say, its arrogance as an entity that did not like to be
questioned or challenged. Many residents swept up themselves in the
euphoria over the Olympics, also didn't want to believe what they
had heard and so didn't push.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were reluctant to turn over these rocks,'' said B. Gale
Dick, a retired professor of physics at the University of Utah who
has been a critic and watchdog of the Olympic effort on
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the Salt Lake City council, Deeda Seed, said she
heard about possible tuition payments to IOC family members as
early as 1996, but could not prove anything. She became the City
Council's liaison to the committee last year, but in meetings she
attended, the board never even recognized her to ask a question.
Ms. Seed acknowledged that her position as a potential
whistle-blower was probably hampered by the fact that she had been
critical of the Committee on other issues, and had probably been
stereotyped as a someone looking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem was I didn't have confirmation _ it was my word
against theirs,'' she said. But the program of direct payments,
including tuition and living expenses, and even American Express
bills of the children of International Olympic Committee members,
was well underway. Documents including itemized and numbered checks
paid to IOC members' children for college tuition, furniture, rent
and other items, were included in the Bid Committee materials that
have been shown to The New York Times by a person involved in the
bid process concerned that a fuller version of the story be made
public.
</P>
<P>
   The documents specifically show that the programs begun in 1991,
especially the scholarship program, were there and documented
within the Committee's budget documents. Regular checks paid to the
son of the IOC member from Mali for his tuition, room and board at
Howard University, were there along side direct checks paid to the
IOC member from the Republic of Congo, Jean-Claude Ganga. Ganga,
along with five other IOC members, was recommended for expulsion
last week by an IOC report, but he has denied any wrongdoing and
has said he will not resign.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who are or were close to the Olympic campaign now
say that the closed and sometimes high-handed nature of the Bid
Committee had become a symptom of its problems long before the
allegations of vote buying emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, for the example, the City Council from Park City,
a nearby mountain resort town where about 40 percent of the Olympic
events are scheduled to take place, journeyed down to Salt Lake to
lodge a formal protest that the planning was being done without
them, from within the committee's offices. The specific complaint
was the committee budget that had just been finished, without any
consultations, Park City officials complained, from the city that
is almost the Olympic's co-host.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't include us, or any of the venue cities,'' said
Myles Rademan, the public affairs spokesman for Park City. ``They
did it themselves, told us they would consult, but never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Rademan said he told the board members that Park City residents
deserved to know more of what was going on, and to feel that they
had representation. ``We can't run our city the way you run the
Olympics,'' Rademan said he told the board. ``We have a hard time
explaining to our people who you do business with when it's not
open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
