<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALLOFFAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF DEBATE: HALL OF FAME VOTERS REWARD TAYLOR'S ACCOMPLISHMENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The former Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor, considered
by many to be one of the greatest players of all time, was voted
into the Pro Football Hall of Fame on Saturday in his first year of
eligibility, despite the objections of some voters who felt his
history of drug abuse should have kept him out.
</P>
<P>
   Inducted with Taylor were two former Los Angeles Rams _ Eric
Dickerson, a powerful runner who holds the single-season rushing
record of 2,105 yards, and the offensive lineman Tom Mack, who
never missed a game in his 13-year career _ as well as Cleveland
tight end Ozzie Newsome, whose 47 touchdowns are the best at his
position, and the Buffalo offensive lineman Billy Shaw, a dominant
run blocker.
</P>
<P>
   Two finalists, wide receiver Lynn Swann and defensive lineman
Howie Long, were not voted in.
</P>
<P>
   But the nominee who drew by far the most attention in this
year's class was Taylor, the Giants' No. 1 draft pick out of North
Carolina in 1981. Some voters felt it would send a negative message
if Taylor, who has been arrested three times since his retirement
and recently spent time in a drug rehabilitation clinic, was voted
in. It did not help Taylor when, in a conference call with the news
media last week, he appeared to some voters as arrogant and
unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Taylor's remarkable accomplishments on the
field, as well as public pleas from the Giants owner Wellington
Mara, NFL Commissioner Paul Taglibaue and several football writers,
proved to be the determining factors. Taylor needed 29 of 36 votes;
the final tally was not released, but it was believed that there
were at least five members who voted against him.
</P>
<P>
   The voting committee was made up of news media representatives
from all 30 NFL cities, plus five at-large members and the
president of the Pro Football Writers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, in their private meeting to determine the entrants,
the committee will introduce a nominee and spend from six to eight
minutes discussing him. When Taylor's name was introduced Saturday,
several voters said, the committee argued for some 35 minutes, and
then had to move on to other candidates because the discussion
involving Taylor became too contentious.
</P>
<P>
   While the other entrants gave speeches and answered questions
after their names were announced, Taylor did neither, instead
releasing a statement through the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled by being elected to the Pro Football Hall of
Fame,'' Taylor said. ``As I have said, I feel like it is the
ultimate reward for playing the game that I love so much and gave
so much. I appreciate the debate and the consideration that was
given my nomination. Ultimately, this honor has to do with how I
played the game. Obviously the majority of the committee felt the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't always come across, but I do appreciate the
well-wishes and concerns of my family, my friends and my former
teammates. It means a great deal to me. It truly does.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor added: ``I want to thank my coaches, especially Bill
Parcells, my teammates, and the Giants' ownership, especially Mr.
Mara. I would not be receiving this honor if it weren't for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor dominated football for most of his career, which lasted
from 1981 to 1993. He went to 10 Pro Bowls, was a three-time
defensive player of the year and was named the league's most
valuable player in 1986. He had 132.5 career sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Many think Taylor is one of the top five players in history.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the few who changed the way a position was played.
Using a combination of power, speed and ferociousness, Taylor
terrorized offensive lines. Coach Joe Gibbs of the Washington
Redskins used an ``H-back'' player _ a hybrid of a tight end and an
offensive linemen _ almost specifically to counter Taylor, because
linemen were too slow to block him.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson recalled facing Taylor during his rookie season in
1983. Dickerson said that on one play in that game, the Rams'
coaching staff instructed him not only to block Taylor, but also to
hit him low and cut him down. ``I really didn't want to do that,
but I did,'' Dickerson said. ``When he got up, he looked at me and
said, `Don't you ever cut me again.' I said, `OK'''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor's destruction of offenses on the field was matched by
his self-destructive nature off it. He tested positive for cocaine
use in 1988 and was suspended for four games.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents that put his the Hall of Fame nod in jeopardy came
once his playing days ended. Taylor was most recently arrested last
Oct. 19 for purchasing $50 worth of crack cocaine from an
undercover police officer in a St. Petersburg Beach, Fla., hotel
room. There were 15 crack pipes in the room, the police said.
Taylor claimed he was set up.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Florida arrest, Taylor entered a drug
rehabilitation clinic in New Jersey, with Mara paying about $7,000
for the visit. Taylor said Saturday that he is in an outpatient
rehabilitation program but would not give details.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Taylor thanked Giant fans, who have seemed to
strongly support Taylor despite his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Giants' organization retired my jersey,'' he said,
``I said this then and I'll say it now: There has always been and
will be a Lawrence Taylor, but without the fans, there would have
never been an L.T.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1602EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
