<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5337 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-ADVANCE31     01-30 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-ADVANCE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shanahan's strategy hits mismatches, weak spots
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When you look into the beady yet steely eyes of a coach
whose team openly refers to him as The Mastermind, you know that
Mike Shanahan is obsessed by this Super Bowl and motivated by the
presence of Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can dodge questions about (Reeves) all he wants, but we
know there is something special about this game for Mike,'' tight
end Shannon Sharpe said. ``Everyone always says that the game will
be decided on the playing field, and maybe that's true. But I know
this much about this game: For the Falcons to win, they're going to
have to beat Mike, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory today will put Shanahan two-up over Reeves in Super
Bowl rings as a head coach. Denver veterans acknowledged privately
over the past week that Shanahan's renewed acrimony with the man
who gave him his first job in the NFL spawned unparalleled
attention to detail.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reeves, Shanahan is a control freak. His staff offers
little to his offensive plans. But unlike Reeves, whose offensive
bible remains the Tom Landry playbook he inherited more than three
decades ago, Shanahan changes week by week. With assistant head
coach Alex Gibbs, he sets out every game to identify the key
weaknesses in an opponent's defense and then pound away at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think back to last year's Super Bowl and all the yards we got
running left against the Packers,'' guard Mark Schlereth said.
``The thing with Mike is, he'll probe for a while to find your soft
spot. Once he's located it, look out. The same thing happened in
the Miami playoff game this year. We found a weakness and exploited
the heck out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Against a defense far better than advertised, the Broncos might
not enjoy many physical advantages, so Shanahan will attempt to
create mismatches. He believes in substitutions, formations and
movement, and they will be apparent early tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of the Denver attack is tailback Terrell Davis, the
former University of Georgia player who rushed for 2,008 yards this
season, but he also will act as a decoy.
</P>
<P>
   The other key for the Broncos will be Sharpe, a difficult
matchup for any defense. The nine-year veteran compensates for the
fact the Denver passing game lacks a viable No. 3 wide receiver to
team with starters Ed McCaffrey and Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that the Denver script calls for Sharpe to be
used in five different sets on the first seven plays alone. The
Broncos coaches think the Falcons might be counting too much on
their linebackers to help cover Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Broncos get Sharpe involved early, it will open the
run lanes for Davis, who rushed for 366 yards and three touchdowns
in the team's first two postseason victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is like a puppeteer with the offense,'' tackle Harry
Swayne said. ``And he's looking forward to pulling the strings in
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
