</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After the fun, under the gun
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Just because the Atlanta Falcons are playing in the
Super Bowl today for the first time in their 33 years doesn't mean
their game plan is new.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves' preachings are the same as they have been in
each of his 18 years as a head coach in the NFL: Run the ball well,
don't let the other team run the ball well, and don't make
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger issue going into today's game as roughly a seven-point
underdog against the Broncos, however, is focus, or perhaps a lack
of it.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable, although not guaranteed, that it could be a
big factor in preventing the Falcons from becoming the first
first-time Super Bowl participant to upset a defending champion in
the big game.
</P>
<P>
   This team, remarkable in its ability to shut out distractions,
won a franchise-record 11 games in a row. Not even Reeves'
quadruple heart-bypass surgery on Dec. 14 was enough to throw the
train off the tracks. But with players babbling and cavorting this
week, perhaps the breaking point has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' center Robbie Tobeck said. ``As soon
as Morten (Andersen) made that field goal, I was running around the
field, all crazy. Going through all the hard times, the coaching
changes, the losing, the fans really down on you _ it's great to
see the city of Atlanta on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Distractions or not, it all goes back to the plan. Reeves'
formula for success is common in the NFL. But the Falcons have been
uncommonly good in following the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson was the league's No. 2 rusher with
1,846 yards, breaking the century mark 12 times in the final 14
regular-season games. Anderson will have to be more decisive today,
though, than in the NFC Championship Game when he had 67 yards on
23 carries against the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Atlanta was No. 2 in the NFL against the run
this year. Today, the Falcons face the running back who was No. 1
in rushing. Denver's Terrell Davis proved he can do many things
while rushing for 2,008 yards and 21 touchdowns, but his ability to
cut back and change direction is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to stop him would be almost impossible,'' middle
linebacker Jessie Tuggle said. ``What we want to do ... is contain
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons led the NFL with a plus-14 turnover ratio for many
reasons _ indefatigable spirit was chief among them.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest play probably was when defensive end Chuck Smith
forced a critical fumble by quarterback Randall Cunningham in the
NFC title game. It set up a touchdown pass that triggered a
comeback from a 20-7 deficit. Some say the Falcons have nothing to
lose: The Broncos are favored; Atlanta is the dream team that
exceeded all expectations. Forget that. It took 33 years to get
here. It's time to make it count.
</P>
<P>
   ``As great as you felt seeing that field goal go through against
Minnesota, I told our football team to remember the feeling,''
Reeves said, ``because it ... is going to be the worst feeling you
ever had in your life when you end up on the short end of the stick
in the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
