<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PRESSURE31-COX     01-30 1798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PRESSURE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A week of pre-game hype and 100,000 fans can humble even the
best players
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Sunday evening, Jan. 24, 1982. Just minutes past 6
o'clock, a sub-zero wind chill deep-freezes the Michigan landscape.
Inside the Pontiac Silverdome, 81,270 fans are warm and toasty and
in full-throated roar. Down on the artificial turf stands Anthony
Munoz. The memory of the moment prompts a one-word remembrance:
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaaahhhh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you're aware of the millions and millions of people
watching,'' recalled Munoz, then a young offensive tackle for the
Cincinnati Bengals, now a sportscaster and a member of the Pro
Football Hall of Fame. ``This is the ultimate. You grew up watching
the Chiefs and Vikings, and Cowboys and Dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   And now millions and millions of people are watching the Bengals
and 49ers in Super Bowl XVI. Watching you. ``All of a sudden,
you're standing under the goalpost, waiting to be introduced,''
Munoz said. ``And you say, 'Knees, just don't buckle.' It's
unbelievable. You've arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Atlanta Falcons, that moment, that ``Aaaahhhh,'' finally
arrives tonight. After a week in the South Florida sun, a week of
Super Bowl babble and hype from Media Day to Elway to Ray's dog
collar to Shannon's Sharpe-tongued, nonstop blather, Super Bowl
XXXIII has arrived at last. Time to buckle your chin strap, but not
your knees.
</P>
<P>
   As Buffalo's Thurman Thomas quickly discovered in Super Bowl
XXVI, the weight of the moment _ and, in Thomas' case, the wait of
the moment _ can cause a man to lose his headgear. His head, too.
The pressure can be enormous when Super Sunday finally dawns, along
with the realization of just where you are and just what's at
stake. The jitter bug can infect anyone, but first-time Super Bowl
participants are especially at high risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting phenomena will be (that) the Broncos have been
through it all before, and Atlanta hasn't,'' said Dick Anderson,
the strong safety for Miami's three consecutive Super Bowl teams in
the early '70s. ``Will all the hoopla and press all week make
Atlanta less focused?''
</P>
<P>
   Denver has been there five times before, including last year's
31-24 upset of Green Bay in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's first Super Bowl, Dallas dominated the Dolphins 24-3
in Super Bowl VI in New Orleans. ``The thing that amazed you the
most was the hoopla that went on in the hotel all week,'' Anderson
said. ``The next year, all we were focused on was Washington.''
Those Dolphins beat the Redskins 14-7 to finish 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   Staying focused
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely impossible to prepare for,'' Randy Cross said.
``That first time you walk out on that field is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross played in three Super Bowls for San Francisco in the 1980s
and now lives in Atlanta. His Super Bowl baptism was in XVI against
Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting to that point, though, can be daunting enough. Ron
Jaworski had trouble sleeping all week before Super Bowl XV. By
Sunday, he was nervous and sleep-deprived and threw three
interceptions in Philadelphia's 27-10 loss to the Raiders.
Jaworski, with Redskins quarterback Joe Theismann, later advised
Phil Simms before Super Bowl XXI of the distractions and the need
for heightened concentration. Simms focused intently each day.
That, and coach Bill Parcells uncharacteristically scripting the
first five plays, helped Simms complete a record 22 of 25 passes
for 268 yards and three touchdowns in New York's 39-20 victory
against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weirdest thing is when you walk out on the field a couple
of hours before the game,'' Cross said. ``That stadium is usually
empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Not on Super Sunday. Instead, the stadium is at least
half-filled long before kickoff and later is jammed to capacity.
And not with the usual suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just fans dressed in the teams' colors,'' Cross said.
``It's filled with Roman royalty. Everybody's dressed up, like a
nonfootball crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a high-priced Super Bowl crowd. Corporate America come to
watch the gladiators. ``You're almost waiting for them to give
thumbs up or thumbs down,'' Cross said. ``That's when you realize
it's not just another football game. You've been told all week that
it is. It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it'd be another ball game,'' said Terry Hoage, the
ex-Georgia All-American safety who played for six teams in a
13-year NFL career and was a nickel back and special-teamer for
Washington in Super Bowl XXVI against Buffalo. ``But when I walked
out on the field before the Super Bowl, it was unbelievable. A
really big deal. The fanfare, the whole nine yards. Everybody's
into it. As a player, I looked up into the stands, and they're all
into the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoage's Super Bowl experience came in the frosty climes of
Minneapolis. ``It absolutely (stunk) as a player,'' he said. ``All
you could do was sit in your room all week and think about the ball
game or go ice fishing,'' he said. Indeed, some of the Redskins did
just that. ``Some of the outdoor guys _ Russ Grimm, Donnie Warren _
went ice fishing,'' Hoage said. ``They went snowmobiling to their
ice-fishing houses. I really couldn't see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the traffic
</P>
<P>
   Game-day transportation can be nettlesome, too. Before Super
Bowl XI, Raiders coach John Madden changed the travel itinerary to
have the team buses leave early for the Rose Bowl. ``Take off!''
Madden ordered after boarding a bus. At the stadium, only Madden
realized why six players _ including 6-foot-8, 310-pound John
Matuszak _ were missing. He kept quiet. ``As a head coach, you
can't go around and say, 'Hey, I lost six players!'. . . . Here I
am playing hide-and-go-seek before the damn Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later in Tampa, three Raiders _ Howie Long, Lyle
Alzado and Bill Pickel _ took a taxi to the game and got stuck in
traffic. Alzado, riding shotgun, was livid, screaming. The players
finally got out of the cab, walked a half-mile to the stadium and
helped stun the defending champion Redskins 38-9.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, walking wasn't an option for Cross' teammates.
In Pontiac, the 49ers were advised not to take taxis to the remote
Silverdome, for fear of traffic jams. ``Thank goodness we ignored
that,'' said Cross, one of 12 or 14 Niners who cabbed it to the
dome. Two hours before kickoff, already dressed in the locker room,
he said, ``We're sitting there drawing straws: Who's gonna play
quarterback? Who's gonna play running back?''
</P>
<P>
   The team buses were stuck in traffic. The rest of the 49ers did
not arrive until 90 minutes before kickoff. And in what state? ``On
edge,'' Cross said, laughing. ``It's kind of a bad thing to be late
for a Super Bowl and your wedding. Those are two things you don't
want to be late for.'' The 49ers won 26-21.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing the clock
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Slater was in his fourth season with the Rams when they
played Pittsburgh in Super Bowl XIV in Pasadena, Calif. ``I had a
tendency to get uptight,'' Slater said. ``But the guys we had _
(Jack) Youngblood, Hacksaw (Reynolds) _ did a good job of keeping
everybody loose.'' Including Slater. At least until the pre-game
introductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coming out in the stadium and watching 103,000
people come to their feet when the Steelers were introduced,''
Slater said. ``And many of them were Rams fans. Then we were
introduced. For a few minutes there, I was a fan, as far as the
whole aura of the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a spectacle, one whose enormousness is heightened by the
early-evening start and the seemingly interminable delay before the
kickoff. ``There's all this extra time from the time you leave the
field to the time you have to play football,'' said Cross. ``You
have to be on the field at 6 but the game doesn't start until 6:18.
You come out, then get introduced. They'll shoot off fireworks,
have Stealth bombers overhead. (Tonight) you've got Cher singing
the national anthem. God knows how that'll work out.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, you just want to hit somebody, just want to
play football. ``Everything's just so big because of the (pre-game)
program and the hype,'' Munoz said. ``It's almost like, 'Man, knock
me out and wake me up when they're ready to play football.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time you (play in a Super Bowl), it's hard not to
hyperventilate,'' Cross said. ``Football players are really on
edge. But it's not just the players; it's everybody. The coaches
are uptight. The guys who pour the Gatorade are strung out.''
</P>
<P>
   The hysteria, and the extra delay on the sidelines between
introductions and kickoff, conspired against the Bills' Thomas in
Super Bowl XXVI. ``That's the sort of weird thing that can happen
in this game,'' Cross said. The AFC's leading rusher that season,
Thomas missed Buffalo's first two plays of the game because he
misplaced his helmet. Both were running plays. ``I was very
upset,'' said Thomas, who finished with just 13 yards on 10 carries
in a 37-24 loss and with an everlasting Super Bowl stigma.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only Bill who succumbed to nerves that night. On
the opening kickoff, Buffalo's Scott Norwood kicked it prematurely
and had to kick-start the game again. After the first kick, Hoage
asked the referee, ``What do you think the odds are in Vegas they
they'd have two (opening) kickoffs in this game?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoage said, ``I don't think he thought that was too funny.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing comical about a slow start in the Super Bowl,
though. Forget Thomas. Ask the Redskins, who watched the Raiders
recover a blocked punt for a touchdown in the first quarter of
Super Bowl XVIII, then saw Jack Squirek return an interception off
Theismann 5yards for a touchdown seven seconds before halftime for
a 21-3 lead. Ask the Chargers, who gave up a 44-yard scoring pass
to Jerry Rice just 1:24 into Super Bowl XXIX, then a 51-yarder to
Ricky Watters on San Francisco's next possession in the 49ers'
49-26 rout.
</P>
<P>
   All of that ensued after Cross, who was doing color commentary
for British TV for the game, had warned, ``The Chargers have got to
survive the first 10 minutes of this game.'' The first 10 minutes
on the game clock? ``No, the first 10 minutes, period. A 7-,
10-point lead in a Super Bowl is a pretty big lead,'' Cross says
now, ``only because it causes people to press.''
</P>
<P>
   How might the Falcons react tonight if they fall behind early in
their first Super Bowl? Who knows? But know this: When asked if the
Falcons might be traumatized or shaken this week by the Super Bowl
XXXIII atmosphere, defensive end Chuck Smith said, ``I'm glad to go
through the emotional trauma. Great. Give me all the emotional
trauma that you can. Give it to me every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1607EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
