<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TURFWAR31-COX     01-30 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TURFWAR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Both sides see splendor in grass
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Atlanta Falcons' path to the Super Bowl was paved
with fuzzy concrete. And are they ever glad to get off it.
</P>
<P>
   While Denver has been insistent all week that the natural
playing surface at Pro Player Stadium offers an advantage to no
one, the Falcons can't wait to roll around on real grass for a
change. If that seems odd for a team that just went 12-1 on
artificial surfaces this season, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to playing on grass. It's the best surface
to play games on,'' Falcons running back Jamal Anderson said. ``We
practice on grass all the time, and it's a lot better on the body.
When you fall on it or carry the ball 25 or 30 times, you kind of
look forward to falling on grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I'm a little bit more confident in my footing on
grass. I'll try some different cuts on grass. When we're not on
grass, I may be a little more hesitant to make a sharp cut, because
I don't want my body going one way and my leg going another way.
When we're on grass, I can let it all hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have no idea what he's talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys have played in the NFL a long time and have
played on different types of surfaces,'' Denver safety Tyrone
Braxton said. ``It's a break for us, but it's not going to be a
great advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The field is all new grass and opulent, sodded just last month
by golfer Greg Norman's Turf Farm in Avon Park in central Florida.
Norman dropped by the stadium Tuesday to inspect the surface, which
appeared thicker than even at the height of the baseball season.
The strain of grass was developed for Norman at Penn State and was
named for him: GN-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt sweet to me,'' said Broncos wide receiver Rod Smith,
who walked on the surface at Tuesday's media day. ``I had on tennis
shoes but, I mean, it's the same for both sides. Like our field in
Denver is as hard as a rock. The grass is dead. But hey, if they
want us to line up in the parking lot, it's like, let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Dan Reeves signed on as coach, his team has played 27
games on artificial turf, including the last nine in a row, and
just seven on real grass. But Atlanta's 20-7 record on the
artificial surfaces suggests more than it should. Anderson is
hardly a speed back, and the receiver corps does not feature a true
breakaway threat.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Falcons have gone 3-4 on natural grass
under Reeves. Half of those losses came in San Francisco. The
record should also reflect that Atlanta's most impressive victory
of the season was a 41-10 rout of the Patriots on the grass field
at Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more excited than they are to play on grass,'' Falcons
wide receiver Terance Mathis said. ``We practice on grass all week,
and then we have to play on turf. We know what the turf does to our
bodies. Usually, it takes until Thursday to get over it for us
older guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might lose a half-step on grass but you're going to be
more daring. You're going to go crazy out there. You're going to
turn the corner a little harder. You're going to make a sharper
cut. You're going to take a chance of trying to make somebody miss.
You're going to dive after those balls knowing that grass is going
to give a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is inconclusive whether teams that play on turf at home
are at a disadvantage on grass-field Super Bowls. Turf teams Dallas
and Pittsburgh won six of their nine titles on grass fields, but
turf team Buffalo went 0-2 in its Super Bowls on grass. Among the
Bills, Steelers and Cincinnati Bengals, six of the past 10 teams to
lose in the Super Bowl had artificial surfaces back home. But
eventually, such analysis becomes meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Denver wide receiver Willie Green said, ``the
weather is more of a factor than the turf.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one, not even Greg Norman, can do anything about the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
