<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Only one detail left to cap off the week
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The grandest week in Falcons existence is one final
detail from completion. The world had so long gone out of its way
to avoid this franchise. Then, suddenly, in one mad dash, it rushed
to catch up on 33 years of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Buchanan dressed for the occasion, coming to the blow-out
media day wearing a dog collar. And thus did a Falcons cornerback
establish a fashion trend for future players looking to make a
spectacle of themselves. Next will come the whips and handcuffs.
It's going to start looking like a Bourbon Street novelty store.
</P>
<P>
   How many times in the past six days have I been asked by a
fellow sportswriter to relay old tales of Falcons woe? Ten? Twenty?
I should have prepared a lengthy memo before ever getting into
town, titled ``The Everlasting Shame of the California Championship
Trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a week of reassurance. Cher promised to wear
nontransparent clothing to her performance of the pre-game national
anthem. She must have gotten some bad information that good taste
and restraint were parts of the Super Bowl code.
</P>
<P>
   It was a week of reaching for obscure clues to today's outcome.
I once tried to get a prediction from a pig for one long-ago Super
Bowl. This time, others went to a New York color-psychology firm
for the inside skinny. ``While the black (jerseys) may make (the
Falcons) appear more formidable, rough and tough, it'll also make
them top heavy,'' said Samuelle Easton, the firm's president.
``They won't be able to overcome it.'' She claims to have nailed
the past two Super Bowls, which makes her record far superior to
the pig's.
</P>
<P>
   It was a week of strange concerns and confessions. First Falcons
receiver Terance Mathis complained about the decision to allow Pro
Bowl players and 10-year veterans to lead the Falcons off the
airplane in Miami. That was tantamount to a newlywed griping about
his wife rushing first into the honeymoon suite.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Mathis came forward with details of a drinking problem. A
pure shock, this stand-up, community-oriented guy weaving down that
particular path. We'll see if a catharsis is good preparation for
the big game.
</P>
<P>
   It was a week of taking sides and picking at old scabs. There
never was any question with whom Atlanta would side in the
Reeves-Shanahan-Elway triangle. Did you know that when Dan Reeves
went in for his mid-December bypass operation, surgeons had a
terrible time getting him set right on the table? Seems he was
reflexively flipping over onto the wrong side. From his Denver
experience, he just assumed that all sharp objects went into his
back. (Just another Super Bowl exaggeration).
</P>
<P>
   It was a week of the ridiculous. Shannon Sharpe woofed like no
one has before. Chris Chandler was being ranked ahead of Hall of
Fame shoo-in John Elway. Reeves became unhinged when it became
public he was working 292-pound rookie Bob Hallen at fullback. If
that prevents him from handing Hallen the ball on fourth-and-1 of a
tie game, then the breach will have been a valuable service to the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   As Super Bowl weeks go, the Falcons had themselves a fine one.
With their first visit, they pretty much got the full treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping they have a little something left for one final
detail.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: Steve(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
