<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MADDEN31-COX     01-30 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MADDEN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One of football's most vocal traditions
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It's two days before the Falcons and Broncos tee the
ball up for Super Bowl XXXIII, and Pat Summerall is relaxing
comfortably in the spacious Maddencruiser without his friend and
partner John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been together so long as a team, it seems odd to
see one of them at a football stadium without seeing the other. But
Madden is inside Pro Player Stadium for a taping session, and
Summerall isn't scheduled to begin his rehearsals on introducing
Cher singing the national anthem and the starting lineups for the
Falcons and Broncos for at least another hour.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ideal time for reflecting on a team that has been to
football announcing what Lewis and Clark were to trailblazing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if people care a lot who televises the Super
Bowl,'' said Fox game producer Bob Stenner. ''But I know when they
see Pat and John, that's a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Summerall's first game with Madden in Tampa has
been told time and time again. He saw this former Oakland Raiders
coach sweating profusely in the booth before the game even started
and thought it was nervousness about being on television. Only to
learn later Madden had a phobic fear of heights.
</P>
<P>
   But the roots of this team, which has set a record for longevity
in network announcing that may never be broken, began much sooner
than 1980. Only the old-timers remember Summerall spent the first
14 years of his television career in the analyst role that has made
Madden a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   The change to play-by-play was swift and unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was with CBS and working with Jack Buck as the No. 1 team
when (then CBS Sports chief) Bob Wussler called me at home,''
Summerall said. ''He wanted to see me, and when we talked, he said
he was going to move me with somebody else. Bob said he couldn't
tell who was talking, Jack and I sounded too much a like. So he
said he was making a change, and he'd like me to do play-by-play.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said OK. But I thought he was talking about taping some
games that season and maybe starting the following year. But he
said, 'Let's go this week. Who do you want to work with?' So just
like that, I started doing play-by-play in 1974 with Tom Brookshier
as my partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerall's first meeting with Madden didn't come with that
fateful game at Tampa in 1980. They had met on occasions when
Madden coached the Raiders, but it was only through the persistence
of CBS and the advice of a friend that pushed Madden into
television.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to do TV. I didn't like the things TV guys
did,'' said Madden, who was now sitting at a table in the
Maddencruiser and getting miked for an interview with a local Miami
station. ''The TV guys didn't know football. They were saying and
doing football things that were simply not true.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kept saying no to CBS until someone said, `Why not give it a
try. If you don't like it, you can just walk away from it. But if
you say no now, maybe three or four years from now you might wonder
what would have happened, except by then, maybe they won't want you
no more.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Madden gave it a try, and CBS did not shoot him to the top of
the depth chart. Madden worked those regional games that go to 5 or
6 percent of the country. And he didn't mind doing them because it
kept him close to the game he loved. He is certain if it wasn't for
television, he would have returned to coaching.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other analyst, Madden is responsible for the
degree of preparation network announcers now put into the game. He
pioneered arriving two or three days before the game and talking to
the players and coaches. But the evolution had nothing to do with a
conscious attempt at innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stopped flying on any planes, so the way I had to get to
places was on trains. So I'd leave early and would get to the city
about Thursday,'' Madden said. ''By getting there early and being a
former coach, I started calling coaches who were friends and I'd go
by and talk to them because the rest of the crew wouldn't get in
until Saturday before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''So we'd talk and watch films. The second year, I was working
with Gary Bender, and he said he'd like to do that, too. So he
started coming in early. It wasn't anything official. But (then CBS
executive producer) Terry O'Neil came in the next year and put that
in as policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the force of Madden's personality triggered a rise in
celebrity that transcended sports announcing like none before him,
with the possible exceptions of the late Howard Cosell and Don
Meredith, Summerall discovered his own presence did not go
unnoticed when he entered the Betty Ford clinic a couple of years
ago for alcohol treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He was overwhelmed by the response of people nationwide offering
support and encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ''They tell me I got more mail than anybody ever has, including
Elizabeth Taylor,'' Summerall said. ''I was amazed. I'll tell you a
funny story. When you're at the Ford Center, you're not supposed to
talk with anyone on the outside or get calls for three weeks. But
not long after I entered, a guy said I had a phone call. I didn't
know what to think. I was afraid maybe someone had died. I kept
thinking who could it be. So I got the phone, and it was Mike
Ditka. Nobody was supposed to get through, but Ditka got through.''
</P>
<P>
   If the team of Madden and Summerall could survive a round with
alcoholism, it was a pretty good bet that CBS losing the NFL to
Fox, and last year's rumors that Madden might jump to ABC and
''Monday Night Football,'' wasn't going to break them up.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, they talked about it but never made any kind of
pact that they'd be a package deal.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even network executives are bright enough to know not
to break up a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pat is a man of few words. John is a man of a lot of words,''
Stenner said. ''John can go off on a tangent, knowing Pat can
safely land the ship. You never know how it's going to turn out
when two people are put together, but Pat and John are one of those
examples of what happens when it's a perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
