<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALL-BISHER31-COX     01-30 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALL-BISHER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taylor earned a nomination, but does he truly deserve it?
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Electing new members to the Pro Football Hall of Fame is
not like picking the next pope. It is not heavy duty. There are 14
candidates of recent vintage, and one chosen by a veterans
committee, in this case, Billy Shaw, who vaulted from Georgia Tech
into a career as an all-time American Football League guard at
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding on Billy Shaw was no problem. His credentials and
life's record are without blemish. The problem is with a new
candidate named Lawrence Taylor, who was a linebacker for the New
York Giants for 13 seasons. Never in my 18 years on the committee
has such a firestorm broken out over a player up for consideration.
Usually, these meetings of the 30 or so delegates are rather civil,
good-natured and without cussing and fussing. This one was loaded
before any of us ever left our front doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has a record off the field to clog a court docket. Drug
abuse, family abuse, deadbeat father, more than just drug abuse,
drug busts. Twice recently.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, he has a record beyond challenge. Some with or
without license call him the ``greatest defensive player in
football history.'' There is no such thing as a ``greatest''
player. There have been great ones, but as a defensive player,
better than Dick Butkus? Ray Nitschke? Joe Greene? Name your own.
</P>
<P>
   That's moot. We get around now to life beyond the field. Should
that be factored into the career of these great athletes? Should
they be held to a higher standard than the rest of us? The Pro
Football Hall of Fame draws the line at the white lines; anything
off the field doesn't count. This is so published in the Hall of
Fame bylaws:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only criteria for election to the Pro Football Hall of
Fame is a nominee's achievements and contributions as a player,
coach or contributor in professional football.''
</P>
<P>
   To get in the Baseball Hall of Fame, players' character and life
off the field come into consideration. It's in the rules. That's
what keeps Pete Rose out, Shoeless Joe Jackson, too. Should the
same kind of standards not apply to the hall at Canton? Shouldn't
the National Football League have as much pride in keeping its hall
clear of character rubbish? Should I not be allowed, as a committee
member, to set some standards that I feel belong?
</P>
<P>
   As an alumnus of North Carolina, I take no pride at all in
Taylor's record. He has a life record that is shameful and reflects
on his university. Should I consider that? I do, and I did.
</P>
<P>
   Most candidates rarely speak out for themselves. Taylor has been
mouthing support for himself that should be embarrassing. On a
conference call this week, he said he had no intention of making an
apology to anybody just to get into the Hall of Fame. Fine, that's
his standard. I have mine. The Pro Football Hall of Fame needs one.
If Jim Brown and O.J. Simpson came up as candidates today, could
you vote for them? Think it over.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned, Lawrence Taylor went in, breezing. It was a
sprited debate with the pros making the cons feel like small
change. The atmosphere was intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   A motion was made to add to the by-laws for eligibility, one
similar to the standards of the Baseball Hall of Fame, that
character, contributions to society and conduct off the field
should be considered. Sad to report, the NFL has shown considerable
lack of interest in the character of its athletes, as evidenced by
the commisioner himself Paul Tagliabue who Friday recommended that
Taylor be inducted. Shame on him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
