<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consistency counts
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Falcons beat Minnesota in the Metrodome. After that,
nothing should seem daunting. The Broncos are the reigning Super
Bowl champs, but this game is on a neutral field. And the commodity
that so imperiled the Falcons in Minneapolis _ speed at every
position _ isn't a Denver hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of John Elway notwithstanding, Denver is a grinding
sort of offense. It pounds with Terrell Davis and its smallish but
fierce offensive line. It moves the sticks with percentage passes
to Ed McCaffrey and Shannon Sharpe. In sum, the Broncos are like
the Falcons, with one exception: Denver doesn't have Tony Martin to
run through a secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have the better defense, and it has been tested in a
way Denver's hasn't. San Francisco brought Steve Young and Jerry
Rice and J.J. Stokes and Terrell Owens to the Georgia Dome and
managed 18 points. On its last 10 possessions in the NFC
Championship Game, the highest-scoring offense in league history
could score only once. It has become fashionable to call the
Falcons' linemen and linebackers the best front seven in football,
but the secondary is substandard no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Buchanan has talked the big talk, guaranteeing a victory and
likening Sharpe to the equine Mr. Ed. But Buchanan has the capacity
to heap pressure on himself and then play surpassing football. His
interception against San Francisco on Nov. 15 was the Falcons' play
of the year, and his work against the outrageous Randy Moss _ who
proclaimed during the game, ``That Ray Buchanan can't cover me!'' _
was nigh heroic.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos aren't going to bomb the Falcons into submission.
They're no longer that kind of team. Elway hasn't passed for 200
yards in four of his past five playoff games. He hasn't had to. The
Broncos belong to Davis. Denver relies on him more than the Falcons
do on Jamal Anderson, which is saying something.
</P>
<P>
   And what is the one thing the Falcons do best? Stop the run.
Only one opposing back has gained 100 yards in the Falcons' past 26
games, and that one _ the Jets' Curtis Martin _ had 101. Limit
Terrell Davis to 101 yards and the Broncos must rely on Elway to
win the game, and he's no longer the daring young man of 1986. The
one time Davis was blunted this season _ 29 yards against Miami on
Dec. 21 _ the Broncos were helpless.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, the NFC Championship didn't follow the script.
Anderson gained only 67 yards. Minnesota had the ball longer. But
Chris Chandler kept the Falcons moving, fashioning a line for the
ages _ 27 of 43 for 350 yards, three touchdowns, no interceptions.
Chandler has been the best quarterback in football when it mattered
most this season, better than Young, Randall Cunningham and Elway.
This Super Bowl is a fitting stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons don't have to do anything they haven't already done.
The beauty of their season has been its week-to-week consistency,
even as the stakes mounted exponentially. ``It's like someone
dangled a diamond in front of us,'' said Bob Christian, the injured
fullback. ``As we went along, we realized, 'Hey, we can do this
thing.' ``
</P>
<P>
   They can and will. Falcons 23-20.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: Markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
