<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TUCKER-COLUMN31-C     01-30 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TUCKER-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For ex-Falcons, `Their success is our success'
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Talking football on Super Bowl Sunday with some former
Falcons. ...
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bartkowski, Falcons quarterback 1975-'85, still holder of
most of the franchise's career passing records, looks forward to
his role today: He'll speak at the team's pregame chapel service.
</P>
<P>
   Then he'll cheer a team _ and a quarterback _ that have ignited
the fan and the Falcon in him this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a swagger to 'em,'' Bartkowski says, approvingly,
of these Falcons. ``They're like a hired gun coming into town to
knock off the sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for the quarterback: ``Chris Chandler is spectacular. He
throws the ball great, has great touch; he just needed the
responsibility of being `the Guy.' I like to see a guy who has
knocked around a while, who didn't get a lot of credit while
playing on some bad teams, in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartkowski, 46, calls the 33-year-old Chandler ``a great kid''
as well as ``a very good friend.'' They played golf together during
the open week before the NFC title game. Bartkowski's oldest son is
now 17, born one year after the Falcons' closest previous brush
with the Super Bowl _ the favored 1980 team's long-lamented,
come-from-ahead playoff loss to Dallas at Atlanta-Fulton County
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have the best team in the NFL that year, not a doubt in
my mind,'' Bartkowski says. ``If we had gotten past Dallas, we
would have beaten Philadelphia (in the NFC title game) and probably
the Raiders (in the Super Bowl). I probably thought, like most
around me at the time, that there'd be multiple opportunities,
going forward, to reach the Super Bowl. And there might have been,
if Leeman (Bennett, the coach) had been able to stick around. Dan
(Reeves) reminds me so much of Leeman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the many dreary years between the Bennett era and the Reeves
era, ``it was extremely sad, a little bit embarrassing,''
Bartkowski says. ``You almost had to apologize for where you
played. ... (But) my contention is that Atlanta has always been a
football town. It became a baseball town by default. Now these guys
have seized the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Leeman Bennett, Falcons coach 1977-'82, also has a role today:
hosting a pregame radio show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost totally lost interest (in recent years),'' he admits.
``I would go to a (Falcons) game, watch three or four plays, then
someone would start talking to me. I didn't watch the games like I
enjoy watching games _ (that is,) as a coach watches games. I got
interested again (this season).''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was because his new radio show _ it aired after
Falcons broadcasts throughout the season but will air before the
game today _ gave him reason to pay close attention.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was because of how closely these Falcons match his
Falcons philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   ``As coach, I always felt like the team that had the best
running game and stopped the run would win,'' Bennett says.
``People thought that was awfully conservative back then. But it's
true.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that two teams adept at both running the ball and
stopping the run meet in the Super Bowl, what gives? ``It could
come down to whether Chris Chandler beats John Elway,'' Bennett
says, ``like he beat Randall Cunningham (in the NFC title game).''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kenn, a fixture at offensive tackle for the Falcons for 17
years, regrets only that he couldn't have played another four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite the dichotomy of feelings,'' he says, describing
his reaction to the NFC title game. ``One minute, I was ecstatic to
the point of tears because the Falcons were going to the Super
Bowl, and the next minute, I was saddened to the point of tears,
almost, because I had missed the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   He retired after the '94 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it'd probably happen in my lifetime,'' he says about
the Falcons in the Super Bowl. He laughs. ``But I thought I'd live
a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   R.C. Thielemann, unlike Bartkowski and Kenn and most former
Falcons, played in a Super Bowl. The offensive guard got there with
the Washington Redskins after spending eight seasons, 1977-'84,
with Atlanta. He heard the news of the Falcons' win over Minnesota
while visiting a volcano during a vacation in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started jumping around, and no one knew what I was doing,''
Thielemann says. Two weeks later, he says, ``I'm still shocked.''
And he figures the current Falcons are experiencing some culture
shock of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one really cared about the Falcons for many years,''
Thielemann says. ``No free drinks. No free food. Now, instant
celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewey McClain and Dave Scott are as relieved as they are happy.
</P>
<P>
   McClain, a Falcons linebacker 1976-'80, says, ``We've always
felt that we let the city down in 1980. There has been a monkey on
our backs ever since. Now that monkey is off our backs. Until this
season, we were the best Falcons team ever. Now we're the
second-best.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, a Falcons tackle 1976-'82, says, ``For me, this Super
Bowl brings closure to the late '70s and early '80s. It brings
closure to a time period when we could have, should have, gone all
the way and didn't. Well, now we've done it. Their success is our
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott _ like Bartkowski, Bennett, Kenn, Thielemann, McClain and
countless other Falcons past _ continues to live in metro Atlanta.
And on this Super Sunday, he speaks for most in the city: ``I've
enjoyed football more this season than any other time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tim(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   THE NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   0: Previous Super Bowls that have matched the NFL's top two
rushers, as this one does with Terrell Davis vs. Jamal Anderson
</P>
<P>
   28: Super Bowls, out of the previous 32, that have been won by
the team that rushed for the most yards
</P>
<P>
   6-3: Record of defending champions in the Super Bowl when they
make it back to the game the following season, as Denver has done
this time
</P>
<P>
   25: NFL teams that ranked ahead of the Broncos in passing
defense this season
</P>
<P>
   3: Franchises that have lost four Super Bowls _ Denver (1-4),
Buffalo (0-4) and Minnesota (0-4)
</P>
<P>
   1-7: Cumulative record of current Falcons players in previous
Super Bowls _ 0-4 by Cornelius Bennett, 1-1 by Eugene Robinson, 0-1
by Randy Fuller, 0-1 by Tony Martin
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
