<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-STORM-NYT &LR;      01-30 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-STORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S EMOTIONS OVERCOME AT END BY UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the old St. John's chant of ``Let's go, Redmen''
competing with the roar from thousands of boisterous Connecticut
fans in a sold-out Madison Square Garden Saturday afternoon, No. 9
St. John's and No. 1 Connecticut staged a highly charged battle for
Big East supremacy that seemed more like a neighborhood brawl. In
the end, St. John's bubble, blown big by a magical week of
basketball, was deflated in the closing minutes as Connecticut
prevailed with the final swing in emotion to win, 78-74, and remain
undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's has played an extraordinary week of games, and there
was no emotional or physical letdown Saturday. After taking No. 2
Duke in an overtime loss in a classic game last Sunday and then
coming back from a 15-point deficit to beat Syracuse on Wednesday,
St. John's led the undefeated Huskies until 4 minutes 57 seconds
were left in this game. Then Connecticut point guard Khalid El-Amin
stripped Reggie Jessie and fed Kevin Freeman for a layup that gave
the Huskies the lead at 69-67. They would not trail again.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton's 3-pointer opened the lead to 72-65 with 3:08
left, but St. John's would pull back to just 2 down when the
reserve Lavor Postell hit a 3-pointer with 34.9 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut made a succession of free throws to insure the
victory, and as the seconds wound down, it was Freeman and Hamilton
who bowed in celebration to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is 19-0 over all and 11-0 in the Big East. St.
John's is 17-5 and 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton had 22 points, Freeman 16 and El-Amin 15 and 6 assists.
Postell had 23 points and 11 rebounds; Jessie 17 had points and
Artest 14.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's opened the second half with a magnificent burst, a
10-3 run, that opened the lead to 12 points with 17:09 to play.
</P>
<P>
   With a 46-41 lead, Jessie hit a layup and then, on the next
Connecticut possession, Ron Artest intercepted a pass meant for
El-Amin at halfcourt. The ball made its way to Bootsy Thornton, who
hit what is for him now a routine 3-pointer. The run ended when
Jessie stripped Freeman of the ball as he went to the basket, and
threw an outlet pass to Erick Barkley, who missed. But Jessie
grabbed the offensive rebound and went back up for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   The speed of play, already fast, then became frantic, a
development that Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun had said before the
game would not be good for his team. But St. John's, with Barkley
temporarily out of the game after getting poked in the eye, could
not convert on any of the run-and-gun possessions and the Huskies
closed their deficit to 53-49.
</P>
<P>
   After St. John's took a timeout, Barkley was back, but he threw
a bad pass that was picked off by Rashamel Jones. Jones went to the
basket and Connecticut was down by only 53-51 with 12:38 to play.
St. John's would open the lead by to 7 points, but Hamilton hit a
3-pointer to tie it again at 61-61, and St. John's lost the lead in
the second half for the first time with 6:49 left.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's seems to have developed an affinity for giving its
fans a scare before getting fully involved in a game. The Red Storm
may have thought its game plan against Syracuse earlier in the week
worked pretty well: fall behind badly early and then use the team's
grittiness to make it a game.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's was down by 13 points after just four minutes, a
result of a torrent of scoring created by Connecticut's pressure
defense and fast-break offense. Hamilton, Connecticut's of the year
candidate scored 10 of the Huskies' first 16 points (Freeman had
the others), as St. John's, for the first time since its
lackadaisical loss at Miami, looked slow.
</P>
<P>
   But against Syracuse, when it trailed by 15 points midway
through the first half, St. John's proved no deficit was large
enough to intimidate the Red Storm. Against the Orangemen, the
players were convinced that Syracuse could not continue its torrid
shooting from the perimeter. Against Connecticut, St. John's did
not wait for the Huskies' offensive machine to go off the rails.
The Red Storm exploded instead, stepping up its offensive
rebounding, using its own pressure defense to create turnovers and
running off the next 9 points, 6 by Thornton, who had 12 in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the smaller St. John's lineup _ which, after
pulling Albert Richardson three minutes into the game, had nobody
on the floor anywhere close to the size of Connecticut's
6-foot-11-inch Jake Voskuhl _ grabbed 13 offensive rebounds and
scored 14 second chance points. The Red Storm caused nine
Connecticut turnovers and had five steals.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's tied the score at 26-26 with 8:20 left in the first
half after Postell grabbed a steal and fed Barkley, who ran the
fast break up the floor, only to pass the ball behind his back to
Postell for the layup, the end of a 23-10 St. John's run.
</P>
<P>
   After the game was tied again at 35-35 with 3:52 left in the
half, St. John's held Connecticut to just one score _ El-Amin's
3-pointer with 1:40 left _ and led at halftime, 43-38. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
