<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BICYCLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 10 SEASONS, VETERAN CYCLIST HOPES TO LEAVE HIS NAME IN
HISTORY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Italy, France, Spain, England, Calif.)  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Max Sciandri was still shaken an hour after he had been
introduced as the senior member of La Francaise des Jeux bicycle
team at a recent press conference here. ``It's my 11th year in the
sport and suddenly I'm presented as the oldest rider of the team,''
he said. ``The 10 years have gone by really quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to be one of the youngest riders on my teams,''
he continued in a tone of wonder, ``and now I'm the oldest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sciandri, who will be 32 on Feb. 15, was the first of 22
Francaise des Jeux riders introduced at a hotel in Paris a couple
of weeks ago. Across Europe, professional bicycle teams have been
staging their annual presentations, a chance for a little publicity
and a buffet lunch to thank their many suppliers before the
European season begins Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As officials admitted, La Francaise des Jeux slumped last year,
its second in the sport. In 1997, it won the team competition in
the World Cup series of classics and one of its riders, Frederic
Guesdon, won the esteemed Paris-Roubaix race, just as the French
team's directeur sportif, Marc Madiot, did in 1985 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   There were no comparable successes last year, and then the team
became marginally involved in the doping scandal that washed over
the Tour de France when three of its riders and its director were
questioned by the police.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Sciandri (pronounced SHAN-dree) seemed to speak for
the team when he said, ``I need a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his teammates, he has a high place to come back
to. He has won daily stages in all three big Tours, in France,
Italy and Spain, and finished in the top five in many one-day
classics, while winning one of them, the Leeds Classic in 1995. In
1993, he finished third in the World Cup standings and in 1996
third again in the road race at the Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, Sciandri has ridden in three countries for six
teams, a high number but fitting for somebody as international as
he is. He was born in Derby, England, to Italian parents who had a
restaurant there and now have two in Los Angeles. Sciandri holds
dual nationality; in Italy, where he lives with his wife and two
children outside Florence, and in England, which he represents in
the Olympics and the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to finally win a classic, a big classic, to be on the
books,'' Sciandri said in an interview after the team presentation.
``I've been close for 10 years,'' a reference to third- and
fourth-place finishes in Milan-San Remo, a third-place finish in
the Grand Prix of Zurich, fifth- and 11th-place finishes in the
Tour of Flanders and a fifth-place finish in both the Amstel Gold
Race and Liege-Bastogne Liege _ all World Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being so close so many times,'' he said, ``this makes you be
more hungry. I want to be finally on the books _ these famous books
_ so one day when I look back, at least I left a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Sciandri might have left a few signs already if not for injuries
and bad luck. More than once, especially when he rode for the
American-based Motorola team in 1992, 1993 and 1996, he appeared to
be well set up for a victory that did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to have had bad luck in my career,'' he said. ``A lot
of times. But I still carry on, doing my job, training in the right
way, doing all the right things. So, sooner or later, at least a
bit of luck has to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two years Sciandri has been dogged by injuries. He hurt
his back in a crash in November 1997 and was slow to return to form
last season, winning only two stages in the Dauphine Libere in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I was riding really well and it was getting close to the
world championships and I fell and broke my right arm during the
Zurich race in August. So I had to stay away from my bike for a
month and a half. Now I'm back on the bike, I've got 6,000 or 7,000
kilometers of training and I'm getting ready for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 10 years I'm going to start from one again. You have to
have motivation, you have to believe in something. When you're
training, you see some races in your head. I already have Milan-San
Remo in my mind. That race will be held March 20. I know I don't
have so many years left, so I'm going to have to go really hard
right from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sciandri said he felt comfortable with his role as the senior
rider for a team that had no designated leader. ``I feel a bit more
responsible, especially because this team counts a lot on younger
riders,'' he said. ``That's something I like.'' The average age on
La Francaise des Jeux is 25.
</P>
<P>
   At that age, Sciandri won a stage in the Giro d'Italia, finished
second in Paris-Camembert and sixth in the Classica San Sebastian,
a World Cup race. ``Time's gone by quickly,'' he concluded. ``It's
been great, a really good time of my life these 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot from cycling. In sports, you can learn
things that help a lot in your life. It's not only getting on your
bike and suffering. Cycling is made of sacrifice, of training, of
hard work. Work and work.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
