<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NY-ELK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: ELK MAY SOON ROAM CATSKILL RANGE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Mont., Pa., Wyo.)  (bl) 
By NICHOLAS KARAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wapiti, alias elk, may again roam the Catskill Mountains of New
York. This range of the Appalachian Mountains in southeastern New
York just west of the Hudson River was once the home of waapiti, as
the Shawnee called the elk and as the first colonists misnamed this
second-largest member of the deer family.
</P>
<P>
   The last New York elk was shot on the Raquette River, in the
Adirondacks, in 1847. Elk lasted longer in more southerly and
westerly areas of the state. The last trace of elk in New York
disappeared about 1870. About the same time, they also disappeared
on the west side of the Delaware River, on the Pocono Plateau in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the flood of resort-bound travelers to the Catskills
and Adirondacks that caused their demise, but rather subsistence
efforts of earlier settlers. Elk were sought as food and clothing
by America's frontier people, and as the population expanded
agriculture westward, the elk disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Indigenous Eastern elk are extinct, and so are six other
subspecies that once thrived in the United States and
central-western Canada. The Eastern elk (Cervus canadensis
canadensis erxleben) was somewhat smaller than the Western animals,
darker in color and crowned with lesser antlers.
</P>
<P>
   The only species that survived is the Yellowstone elk (Cervus
canadensis nelson bailey). It found sanctuary in this nation's
first federal park, Yellowstone National Park, established in 1872
by President Ulysses S. Grant.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rocky Mountain Elk Foundation has its way, elk will
return to the Catskills, where outdoor activities already include
fly-fishing for trout from spring to fall, rafting and canoeing in
the summer, and deer hunting in the late fall. Elk have been
successfully reintroduced recently in Pennsylvania, and New York
may be next.
</P>
<P>
   The first hurdle in the re-establishment of an elk herd in New
York is to locate suitable habitat. To find it, the foundation
endowed a two-year study, a joint venture by researchers at Cornell
University and SUNY's College of Environmental Science and
Forestry. The Catskills came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biologically, a few areas in the state, including portions of
the Catskills, have a relatively large amount of habitat that can
meet the needs of elk,'' William Porter of SUNY said.
</P>
<P>
   Deer hunters need not fear that the larger elk, 700 to 800
pounds, would drive out deer, Porter said. ``Elk probably will not
compete with white-tailed deer because the two species prefer
different foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Habitat, however, is not the big problem if elk are to be
successfully reintroduced. They must also find social acceptance
and approval among the human residents of areas where introduction
is proposed. This includes parts of Greene, Sullivan and Ulster
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eastern Catskill region has higher social feasibility than
other areas we examined,'' said Jody Enck of Cornell's human
dimensions research unit, ``because social and economic
characteristics of towns and villages here make them the most
likely to be able to benefit if elk restoration occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the area to handle tourist interests, a social
criterion, was a factor Enck used in his evaluation of various
regions. This area has a well-developed tourist-based economy and
the idea has already found support from outfitters, retailers and
motel/hotel interests.
</P>
<P>
   Approval for the introduction of elk to the area will come from
public debate, and sampling by the state's Department of
Environmental Conservation. The Rocky Mountain foundation and the
state department have been quick to point out that restoration of a
once-native species requires a public scoping process and
completion of a state environmental quality review process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the DEC would consider a proposal for the restoration
of elk,'' said Gary Parson, the department's wildlife bureau chief,
``we'd want to be sure that it was both biologically feasible and
that the local people are in favor of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The RMEF,'' according to its field director David Ragantesi,
who leads 2,000 members and 10 volunteer chapters in New York,
``has fulfilled its role by funding the study. Now we hope to
encourage public discussions about elk restoration in this area to
determine if local and regional support exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The RMEF will be glad to assist these discussions by providing
information on positive and negative impacts of an elk
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1984, the elk foundation has more than 110,000
members nationwide who helped generate nearly $70 million to
conserve and enhance 2.3 million acres of wildlife habitat. The
RMEF is headquartered in Missoula, Mont. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
