<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-WOODSTOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WOODSTOCK HELPS MOTHER OUT OF CRISIS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IVER PETERSON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, N.Y. _ For people who feel trapped by city life, who
daydream about living without woes among the dharma spirit shops
and tie-dyed jogging tights of a rural arts colony like this one,
the reality is that even here, weird and sad things happen. It's
just that Woodstockers seem to be pretty good at coming to the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a Woodstock moment last summer when the organizers of
a benefit for the local youth center, not wanting to take $12,000
in receipts home, stashed the proceeds in a clothes dryer for
overnight safekeeping. When half of the money _ but only half _ was
missing the next day, residents passed the hat and replaced the
money.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, residents have raised $20,000 to plug the gaps
in the medical insurance of a carpenter, Jonathan Kellogg, who has
leukemia. Roxy Dawn, a longtime resident, turned a solitary
Christmas 10 years ago into an annual Christmas party attended by
hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   But however distressing the theft of donated money may be,
however dispiriting a solitary Christmas or frightening the onset
of a dread disease, few, if any, people in Woodstock have been
tested by the kinds of horrors that Sharon Wilber has faced.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock may have its quirks _ keeping sidewalks clear of ice
does not seem to be of much interest here _ but when trouble struck
Ms. Wilber, the town, led by an oil-burner repairman named
Christopher Neal, responded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilber was always the family rebel, she told her friends. At
38, she was the mother of eight children from two failed marriages
and other relationships, and she lived with her six youngest
children in a tiny, decrepit cabin owned by her mother, Edith
Murray, in the Bearsville Flats west of town.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Ms. Wilber's precarious life as a janitor and
community volunteer fell apart when her son Devin, 7, pushed his
bike out onto Route 212 without seeing a car that was bearing down
on him. He had been on his way to his grandmother's house. He died
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Neal, 49, born and raised in the Bronx, came up here 20 years
ago for the music and ``the scene.'' He has known Ms. Wilber almost
that long, so of course he attended Devin's wake. ``I said,
`Sharon, if there's anything I can do, you let me know,''' he
recalled. ``I mean, what could I do for her? But you always say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilber didn't ask for anything, but she had a piece of
offhand, awful news. ``She said, `Oh, by the way, my mother's
having the cabin bulldozed down. The boys are out there seeing what
they can get out,''' Neal recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It was true: In whatever spasm of grief or anger that held her,
Ms. Murray had chosen that moment to have the cabin that Ms. Wilber
and her children lived in knocked down. Ms. Murray said it was
unfit for habitation, The Woodstock Times reported. She had wanted
her daughter out for years, she told others. Ms. Murray and Ms.
Wilber later refused to speak of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Neal refused to speculate on Ms. Murray's motives. ``I don't
want to go there,'' he said. ``I don't think we can ever know.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Neal chose to act. He knew that Steve Dallow, a
dentist and a volunteer fireman, had a three-bedroom house in the
Bearsville Flats for sale for $59,000. ``I said I'd come over and
write out a $1,000 check for a binder on the house,'' Neal said.
``Steve said, `Never mind the binder, just put the money in your
fund.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the next month and a half, while Ms. Wilber and her children
camped at the homes of friends, Neal wrote fund-raising letters,
knocked on doors and stood on the green with his dogs and a sign:
``Help Sharon Wilber.'' He got a lot of spare change, many small
checks and a few big ones. The summer people chipped in, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't give anybody any peace,'' said Gale Brownlee, who
watched Neal through the window of her Century 21 real estate
office on Main Street. ``He went door to door; he stood out there
and sold raffle tickets. He didn't let people forget for a minute
that there was a family in need.''
</P>
<P>
   By September, nearly $70,000 had been raised. It paid for a new
roof on the house, a full tank of oil and the title, free and
clear, in Ms. Wilber's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, those kids needed a home,' Neal said. ``The town came
through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
