<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL NEGOTIATES WITH MAYOR OVER HOMELESS CENTER  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With four community agencies in Brooklyn facing
eviction as early as Monday, the New York City Council is in
last-minute negotiations with the Giuliani administration to avert
that showdown and to resolve broader policy disputes over the
city's homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the chances of a settlement, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
said at a news conference Sunday that ``there are many ways to do
that.'' But he cautioned, ``We may be able to work it out; we may
not be able to work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had said that the four groups would be removed from a
city-owned building to make room for a new homeless shelter, whose
creation he said was necessitated by a new law limiting the size of
shelters. The council, which passed the law over the mayor's veto,
has denied that the measure forces the creation of new shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has said he chose the site, in the Cobble Hill
neighborhood, because it is in the district of Stephen DiBrienza,
the chairman of the council's General Welfare Committee and the
sponsor of the law on homeless shelters. The mayor has said that
DiBrienza wants more shelters, so one should be in his district.
But DiBrienza has said no new shelters are needed and has accused
the mayor of petty retaliation over other issues in the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's plan provoked a backlash, especially because it
would have forced out the 25-year-old South Beach mental health
program, which provides classes, counseling and other services for
about 500 outpatients. So he agreed to let that agency remain,
occupying three floors of the four-story building. But he said the
other groups would have to leave to make way for a small shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had warned that they would evict those
groups on Friday, the last business day of the current lease. But
because of the renewed negotiations, the officials relented.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's chief attorney, Corporation Counsel Michael
D. Hess, notified a lawyer for one group that ``the city will take
no action to terminate or disrupt your client, Families First,
Inc., at 250 Baltic St., prior to Monday, Feb. 1.'' That group
sponsors counseling, training and social activities for families.
</P>
<P>
   The other groups facing eviction are the Cobble Hill Civic
Association, Community Board No. 6 and a program for the elderly
run by the Heights and Hill Community Council.
</P>
<P>
   DiBrienza, the council's lead negotiator, said the last-minute
reprieve was a hopeful sign, but he expressed frustration that five
days of talks had not yet produced an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One major sticking point is the issue of providing temporary
accommodations for homeless families who sometimes must sleep
overnight in chairs or on the floor of the city's application
center, called the emergency assistance unit, in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inhumane conditions like people sleeping on floors is what we
want to stop,'' said Michael Clendenin, a spokesman for the council
speaker, Peter Vallone. ``If there is other language for meeting
that goal, fine.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBrienza agreed, saying, ``The real stumbling block is children
on the floor. They simply have to take them out and let them sleep
somewhere in the system'' of shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor contends that the key problem is a 200-bed limit on
the size of shelters that he says was imposed by the new law. He
says the law would force the city to build new shelters for 18,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   But the council says the limit applied to new shelters and
exempted existing ones, and it passed an amendment to reaffirm the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Now, DiBrienza said, the administration is concerned that the
200-bed limit would apply to the replacements for any of the
existing shelters, an issue raised by plans to redevelop the
Bellevue shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to come up with a formula for flexibility,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, it would be unfair to use the four
community groups as pawns in the dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
