<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTVOLS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT celebrates national title
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Scattered showers did nothing to dampen the
enthusiasm of the Tennesseee faithful Saturday afternoon as more
40,000 turned out at Neyland Stadium for the official celebration
of Volunteers' 1998 football national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration of Tennessee's first national title since 1951
came almost a month after the Volunteers beat Florida State 23-16
in the Fiesta Bowl to wrap up a 13-0 season. Didn't matter. The
fans put on their Orange parkas and arrived in a mood to party.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a lot of places in the country where you'd get
this many people to come out on a day like today,'' said Tennessee
coach Phillip Fulmer. ``But it doesn't surprise me. These people
are why this season was so special.''
</P>
<P>
   The event, originally scheduled for Jan. 16, already had been
postponed once due to a conflict with the inauguration of Gov. Don
Sundquist. Saturday's event was going to take place rain or shine
for many reasons, not the least of which was the presence of four
recruits on this, the last weekend before national signing day.
</P>
<P>
   Neyland Stadium, the nation's second-largest on-campus football
facility, was decked out for the occasion. A JumboTron television
screen was brought in and two hours before the ceremonies fans were
treated to a complete replay of the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Painted orange and white logos on the field proclaimed Tennessee
to be the ``1998 National Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans coming to and from the event scrambled to buy hats, shirts,
posters, and anything they could get their hands on that declared
the Vols to be No. 1 for the first time in 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   A number of dignitaries spoke, including Knoxville Mayor Victor
Ashe and university President Joe Johnson. Sundquist was a no-show
due to illness.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest cheers of the day, however, were reserved for
Fulmer, linebacker and captain Al Wilson, and long-time radio voice
John Ward, who retired at the end of the season after 31 years at
the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just an incredible day,'' said Wilson. ``But you knew
after the kind of season we had, the people were going to turn out
no matter what. This place is really something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee team received four different national championship
trophies during the ceremonies: Associated Press (media poll);
Sears (coaches poll); McArthur Bowl (College Football Hall of
Fame); and Grantland Rice (Football Writers Association of
America).
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer, now 67-11 in seven seasons at Tennessee, received two
national coach of the year awards: one from the American Football
Coaches Association and the other from the FWAA.
</P>
<P>
   The team also received the official SEC championship trophy from
Commissioner Roy Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl sent a contingent to present the game's
championship trophy. Fiesta Bowl trophies also went wide receiver
Peerless Price, the offensive MVP, and to Dwayne Goodrich, the
defensive MVP.
</P>
<P>
   The day concluded with closing remarks from Fulmer who reminded
the crowd that when he took over as coach in 1992, he promised to
take the program to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're there,'' said Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Fulmer ended his celebration of the championship.
There was work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, signing day is Wednesday. The Orange White
spring game is April 24 and the Vols' 1999 opener is on Sept. 4
with Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
