</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS APPLYING THE PRESSURE TO IMPROVE DEFENSIVE SCHEME
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are not quite the Chicago Bulls, the Miami Heat or the old
Bad Boys from the Detroit Pistons, but the New Jersey Nets are
showing improvement defensively. In their 92-90 exhibition victory
over the New York Knicks on Friday night, they proved that coach
John Calipari's increased emphasis on defense is bearing fruit.
</P>
<P>
   In a reversal from Wednesday night's loss at Madison Square
Garden, when Latrell Sprewell hit wide-open jump shots and split
their defense for uncontested finger rolls, the Nets provided
adequate resistance in their final preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   With their rugged defender Jayson Williams playing only
sparingly, the Nets held the Knicks to 39 percent shooting from the
field, made 12 steals and pressured the Knicks into 24 turnovers.
Two nights earlier, the Knicks had blitzed their defense by making
49 percent of their shots.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Patrick Ewing played only eight minutes Friday because
of a mild knee sprain, but Sprewell, Allan Houston, Larry Johnson
and the rest of the Knicks' top players spent significant time
trying to break down the Nets' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still a ways away,'' Calipari said. ``But I think our
players have a better idea of what we're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Gill was among the most impressive defenders, especially
in the final minutes. With 5 minutes 58 seconds left and the score
tied, Calipari walked down his bench, looked at Gill and said, ``Go
get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari was referring to Sprewell, who had erupted for 11
third-quarter points and had just blown by Sherell Ford to draw a
foul. But with Gill covering him like a muscle shirt, Sprewell did
not score again, had one shot blocked and missed a potential
game-winning 3-pointer at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I relish those moments,'' said Gill, who scored 14 points. ``I
love making the big play, whether it be defensive or offensive. Cal
always puts me in that situation, and he's counting on me to come
up with a big play or something.''
</P>
<P>
   While Calipari's focus on improving the Nets players' perimeter
footwork _ with the aim to stop opponents from driving past them _
has helped, the greatest factor in the Nets' improvement has been
the addition of Jim McIlvaine.
</P>
<P>
   In both games, the 7-foot-1-inch center has been as good as
advertised, blocking five shots in 44 minutes. After finishing 26th
in the league in blocks last year with an average of 3.8 a game,
the Nets swatted 12 shots in the games with the Knicks. In one
first-half sequence on Friday, McIlvaine blocked Houston's layup
after Houston had gone by Gill and then rejected Kurt Thomas'
putback attempt.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine's presence allows the Nets to keep gambling on the
perimeter without always paying the price when their aggressiveness
gives opponents a path to the basket. ``I don't have to worry about
whether my man is driving on me when he's in there,'' Gill said.
``When Houston got past me, McIlvaine smacked it right out of
there. It was a pleasant surprise to have him back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as critical to the Nets' turnaround has been their
defensive rebounding. As strong as Williams is on the glass, the
Nets were a terrible defensive rebounding team last season.
Opponents scored many second- and third-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Williams playing a total of only 42 minutes in
both games, the Nets kept the Knicks from dominating the offensive
boards. The Knicks had seven offensive rebounds on Wednesday and
nine on Friday. The Nets, who outrebounded the Knicks in both
games, had a total of 37 offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be a better defensive rebounding team and I think
we're starting to do it and starting to concentrate,'' Calipari
said. ``But we still have a ways to go in a lot of areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' most glaring defensive deficiency on Friday was on
transition. In the first quarter alone, the Knicks scored 11 points
by beating the Nets up the floor. While the Knicks are not the
plodders they used to be, that still is unacceptable. ``If the
Knicks can make that a strength in a game with us, we're in deep
trouble,'' Calipari said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Nets are better defensively, but still not good
enough.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The Nets have offered Scott Burrell a one-year deal with
$537,500. Burrell, who can get the same amount in Houston, Miami or
Milwaukee, wants to play for the Nets but wants to be signed for
the $1 million exception. The Nets do not appear willing to give
Burrell more money and are expecting him to make a decision Sunday
or Monday. The free agent small forward visited Miami on Saturday.
The Nets also are interested in reacquiring Jim Jackson, the
seventh-year free agent guard who averaged 16.5 points, 5.8
rebounds and 5 assists with them in 33 games during the 1996-97
season.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
