<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     01-30 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Feb. 7)  
(mk) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE SENSE OF REALITY: STUDIES IN IDEAS AND THEIR HISTORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Isaiah Berlin. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In nine essays, the eminent philosopher argues that the search
for a utopian society is the pursuit of a fantasy and that ideas
have consequences, but rarely those that are expected. ``For anyone
wanting to understand the twists and turns of the history of ideas,
this book will be indispensable,'' John Gray wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOUDSPLITTER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Russell Banks. Harper Perennial, $15.
</P>
<P>
   This sprawling novel about the abolitionist John Brown, selected
by the editors of The New York Times Book Review as one of the best
books of 1998, is narrated by his third son, Owen, and is less a
historical epic about slavery than a domestic drama about the
challenge of living with a fanatic. The story tracks Owen's growth
from introverted son to struggling disciple to firebrand officer in
the bloody holy war of his father, whose failed raid on Harpers
Ferry in 1859 was one of the fuses that touched off the Civil War.
Last year in these pages, Walter Kirn praised the book's ``rich and
soulful'' language.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PILLAR OF FIRE: AMERICA IN THE KING YEARS, 1963-1965 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Taylor Branch. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.
</P>
<P>
   This middle volume of a planned trilogy on the life and times of
Martin Luther King Jr. covers such fateful events as the
assassinations of John F. Kennedy and Malcolm X and the signing of
the Civil Rights Act of 1964. ``By giving King such epic treatment,
Branch implies that he was an epic hero,'' Alan Wolfe wrote here in
1998. ``The great merit of Branch's stunning accomplishment is to
prove definitively that he was.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEARING THE CROSS: MARTIN LUTHER KING, JR., AND THE SOUTHERN
CHRISTIAN LEADERSHIP CONFERENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David J. Garrow. Quill/Morrow, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This book maintains that while the victories of the civil rights
movement were not King's alone, his leadership was indispensable.
In 1986 the reviewer Howell Raines, said ``Garrow has provided the
fundament of fact on which future King biographies must rest.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VISITORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anita Brookner. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This intensely introspective novel focuses on an emotionally
remote 70-year-old widow struggling to maintain her dignity in a
world without happy endings. ```Visitors' may be the book Brookner
has spent her life aiming toward,'' Jacqueline Carey wrote last
year. ``Nothing distracts us from the lesson that even failure can
entail an incredible triumph of will.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOREIGN CORRESPONDENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Geraldine Brooks. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after reaching out to pen pals in the Middle East,
Europe and America to escape her isolated childhood in 1960s
Australia, a journalist travels abroad to seek them out. In 1998
the reviewer Valerie Sayers, called this a ``charming and sharply
intelligent'' memoir ``full of a generous interest in the life
beyond the self.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESTINY OF FIRE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Zo Oldenbourg. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 13th-century France, this novel chronicles the suffering
of a noble family that was part of a pacifist sect deemed heretical
by the Roman Catholic Church, and whose members were persecuted
during the ensuing Albigensian Crusade. ``Oldenbourg brings back to
us the cruelty and terror of one of the unhappiest episodes in the
long story of man's inhumanity to man,'' Thomas Caldecot Chubb
wrote in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNICORN'S BLOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Finney. Picador USA, $14.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tale of intrigue at Queen Elizabeth I's court
involving the pursuit of a stolen diary said to contain secrets
that could threaten the queen's reign. ``Finney's intricate novel''
is ``swiftly moving and deftly woven,'' Julie Gray wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TSAR: THE LOST WORLD OF NICHOLAS AND ALEXANDRA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Kurth. Photographs by Peter Christopher. Back
Bay/Little, Brown, $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   This account of the last reigning Romanovs acknowledges their
political blunders and moral failings while emphasizing their
benevolent acts and abiding love for each other. In 1995, Francine
du Plessix Gray called the narrative ``amply documented and
compellingly written'' and the color photographs of Romanov sites
``as beautiful as any pictures I've seen of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOSCOW: GOVERNING THE SOCIALIST METROPOLIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy J. Colton. Belknap/Harvard University, $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   This book traces the history of the Russian capital and the
politics that shaped it. In 1996 our reviewer, Stephen Kotkin, said
the author succeeds in ``superbly demonstrating the depth of the
Soviet-era contribution to the ancient city's outer face and inner
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HORACE AFOOT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Frederick Reuss. Vintage Contemporaries, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of this novel is a monkish middle-aged oddball, living
in a small town, who succumbs to the tug of intimacy when he
befriends a dying librarian and a self-destructive woman. The
result is ``a sly satire of Midwestern life and a restrained
account of how a closed heart comes to be unlocked,'' David Sacks
wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER OF BETRAYAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Hong Ying. Translated by Martha Avery. Grove, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A young poet's life unravels after she gets swept up in the 1989
Tiananmen Square protests and later finds her lover in bed with
another woman. ``Hong Ying's prose ... is both sensuous and
lapidary, eloquently expressing the novel's wide emotional and
intellectual range,'' Philip Gambone wrote in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGERS31-COX     01-30 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGERS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Managers fighting to keep trial alive
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Illinois Republican Rep. Henry Hyde once compared
prosecuting the impeachment trial of President Clinton to walking
into the ``jaws of political death.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde and his prosecutors seem to be snatching life from
those jaws. Every time the first impeachment trial in 131 years
seems to be on the verge of dying, the House Republican prosecutors
find a way to revive it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was less than two months ago that Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) said he had ``no plans'' for a Senate
trial.
</P>
<P>
   When the House voted Dec. 19 to impeach the president, forcing
the Senate's hand to conduct a trial, Lott said the trial would be
quick, over in as little as five days.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the standoff with Hyde and his fellow prosecutors
over calling witnesses to bolster their case that the president
lied under oath and obstructed justice to conceal his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors let Lott know there would be no case unless they
present a full case with opening arguments, witnesses and closing
arguments. The Senate balked, but it did give the House managers a
piece of what they wanted: a full three days of opening remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Then the prosecutors applied pressure for witnesses. And much to
the chagrin of Senate Democrats, and even some Republicans, they
got another inch.
</P>
<P>
   They won the right to question three key witnesses under oath
and videotape sessions for possible use on the Senate floor. In the
end the witnesses may not be live, but they are allowed to be
questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans call it sheer persistence. Democrats say it is more
like a relentless obsession by ideologues.
</P>
<P>
   But the facts are these: The House prosecutors have won
incremental victories from the Senate. And none is as important as
the right to question Lewinsky once more under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Lewinsky has been heard only on audiotapes from
conversations she had with her former friend Linda Tripp. Her
depositions for independent counsel Kenneth Starr were recorded on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky will be questioned by Rep. Ed Bryant (R-Tenn.) on
Monday. Presidential confidant Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal then will be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan will be queried by Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.) about how
he helped Lewinsky with a job search in New York City and whether
that job search was to buy her silence about her affair with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal will answer questions from Rep. James Rogan
(R-Calif.) about what the president told him about his affair with
Lewinsky and whether Clinton lied about Lewinsky with the idea that
Blumenthal would pass along the false information to others.
</P>
<P>
   And while the House prosecutors say they have been told by the
Senate leadership that they will not be allowed to call the three
witnesses to testify in person, the procedure approved by the
Senate on Thursday does not preclude that from happening, and it
even allows for the possibility of a vote on additional witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the House prosecutors were able to put a foot in the
door to keep it open. Political scientists say it is rare for the
House to have extracted so much from the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House managers have carefully and gingerly gotten much of
what they want by understanding they can't push too far,'' said
William Connelly, professor of politics at Washington &AMP; Lee
University. ``They understood you have to settle for less than the
whole loaf.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the House prosecutors say they are ``deeply unsatisfied''
with accepting less than a full loaf. They say the Senate has let
down the country by not hearing the story about the president's
conduct from witnesses. Witnesses, they say, will tell what
documents and videotapes can not.
</P>
<P>
   Several prosecutors, including Reps. Bob Barr of Georgia and
Lindsey Graham of South Carolina, are so frustrated by the process
that they would now like to see the independent counsel statute
overhauled if not removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten a quarter of the loaf,'' Barr said about the
impeachment trial to date. ``The Senate has forced us to
dramatically and unfairly cut back the number of witnesses we
requested. They have apparently decided we will have no opportunity
to have live witnesses and they apparently will give the White
House time for witnesses, so there again, they get the last word.''
</P>
<P>
   The country has been ``shortchanged'' in Barr's view because
they have heard a story about partisan warfare, instead of a story
about how the president violated the rule of law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr is not alone in openly expressing his frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this process has resulted in an outcome that won't
be legitimized by our public institutions and the people of
America,'' said Rep. Christopher Cannon (R-Utah).
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, the chance that the House prosecutors will win
a single Democrat in the vote to oust the president is very slim.
But that does not stop the House from pushing on, refusing to give
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managers have succeeded in keeping it (the trial) alive,
but it is on life support and the patient chart is on the steady
downhill slide,'' said Larry Sabato, a professor of politics at the
University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said he was surprised that the Senate leadership has put
so much on the line in accommodating the House managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised that the 55 Republican senators are seemingly
more concerned about the health of House Republicans than they are
about Senate Republicans,'' Sabato said. ``They don't want to pull
the rug out from the House but in the process they may be
endangering the GOP majority in 2000 in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
