<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaw overcomes odds to be honored in Hall of Fame
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Two players whose brilliant careers have at times been
overshadowed by their off-field indiscretions withstood some of the
most intense scrutiny ever imposed by a board of 36 selectors here
Saturday to gain induction into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   But while linebacker Lawrence Taylor and tailback Eric Dickerson
will garner most of the headlines for the five-man Class of '99,
the honoree who might have overcome the longest odds was Billy
Shaw. A former Georgia Tech linebacker who went on to star at
offensive guard for the Buffalo Bills (1961-69), Shaw became the
first player ever to spend his entire career in the old AFL to gain
admission to the pro football shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Also selected for induction Aug. 7 in Canton, Ohio, were
offensive guard Tom Mack and tight end Ozzie Newsome.
</P>
<P>
   ''During this week, I've had some time to reflect on the years
of the AFL and all of the ridicule we put up with for being the
so-called `new guys' and the perseverence we had to have,'' Shaw
said Saturday afternoon from his home in Toccoa. ''A lot of great
players had to perform in obscurity until the league finally got
accepted. It's a humbling thing to represent those players, to
carry their banner into the Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was the nominee of the Hall of Fame's seniors committee,
which nominates one candidate a year.
</P>
<P>
   He was a two-platoon performer at Tech for coach Bobby Dodd, but
his physique and quickness made him a natural at guard. He played
in eight AFL all-star games, and was named to pro football's
all-decade team for the '60s. He was a captain on the Bills' two
AFL championship squads but retired before the league began playing
a merged schedule with the NFL in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were two outstanding offensive linemen in the (AFL), Ron
Mix and Billy Shaw,'' said Sports Illustrated football writer Paul
Zimmerman, who extensively covered the league. ``(Shaw) was a
better player even than Gene Upshaw.'' Bills owner Ralph Wilson
noted that Shaw was ''a great team leader who had a heart of
gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw awaited word on the Hall of Fame voting Saturday morning
with wife Patsy, and several of the couple's close friends. Shaw,
who earned the nickname ''Steady Eddie'' during his playing career,
conceded that the last few days were nervous ones for him. Shaw
knew, he said, that deliberations on the Hall voting began at 7:30
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''By about 10:30 or so,'' he said, ''I thought my heart was
going to stop I was so nervous. When the phone rang with the news .
. . that was quite a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The voting session took nearly four hours, believed to be the
longest discussion ever on the 15 candidates, and the debate on
Taylor took 34 minutes alone. Selectors described the presentation
of Taylor as even but intense. Although he redefined linebacker
play and rates inarguably as one of the greatest defenders in NFL
history, Taylor came under fire because of his well-documented drug
problems. Taylor currently is in a treatment program for cocaine
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate must receive 80 percent of the votes for induction
and it is believed that the decision on Taylor was a close one.
Several New York-area newspapers conducted polls of the selectors
last week and most confirmed there were at least seven voters
opposed to Taylor's induction.
</P>
<P>
   In a statment released through the New York Giants organization,
Taylor said: ''I feel like it is the ultimate reward for playing
the game that I've loved so much and gave so much to. I appreciate
the debate and the consideration that was given my nomination.
Utlimately, this honor has to do with how I played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, who still holds the single-season rushing record with
2,105 yards in 1984, is the third-leading rusher in league history.
Mack played 13 seasons for the Rams and played in 11 Pro Bowl
games. Newsome tops all NFL tight ends in receptins with 662.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson played one month of the '93 season with the Atlanta
Falcons but his name does not appear in the media guide. He was the
only one of the five honorees to be here for the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never made it to the Super Bowl, so this is my Super Bowl,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS OF 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the likely candidates for the Hall of Fame next
year:
</P>
<P>
   _ QB Joe Montana: Four Super Bowl titles make him a lock-in his
first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   _ S Ronnie Lott: A big hitter with range, finished brilliant
career with 63 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   _ QB Phil Simms: Didn't make it to finals this year, but support
for him will pick up.
</P>
<P>
   _ DE Howie Long: Played all four positions along defensive front
played them all well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Owner Dan Rooney: Steelers boss played key role in
establishing labor peace in NFL.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS OF 1999 PRO FOOTBALL HALL OF FAME BIOS
</P>
<P>
   ERIC DICKERSON, Running Back
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Rams (1983-87), Indianapolis Colts
</P>
<P>
   (1987-91), L.A. Raiders (1992),
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (1993)
</P>
<P>
   _ Ran for a record 2,105 yards with the Rams in 1984. He stands
third on the career rushing list with 13,259 yards, having rushed
for more than 1,000 yards seven times. Was the No. 1 pick by the
Rams and second player overall by the Rams in 1983. Named NFL
Player of the Year in 1984 and the NFL Offensive Player of the Year
</P>
<P>
   in 1986. Gained a playoff record 248 yards rushing in 1985
Divisional Playoff Game. In 1987 was traded to Indianapolis in a
blockbuster trade that involved the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   TOM MACK, Guard
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Rams (1966-78)
</P>
<P>
   _ Although he never made it to a Super Bowl, Mack was a frequent
postseason player. He was selected to play in Pro Bowls 11 times in
13 years. One reason was his durability; he never missed a game
because of injury. The No. 1 pick by the Rams in 1966 played in 184
straight games.
</P>
<P>
   OZZIE NEWSOME, Tight end
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns (1978-90)
</P>
<P>
   _ Tops all NFL tight ends in lifetime receptions. ``The Wizard
of Oz'' went 150 games with at least one reception and totaled 662
catches for 7,980 yards and 47 touchdowns in his 13 seasons. A
first-round pick out of Alabama, he had 89 catches in 1983 and
again in 1984. Caught 50 or more passes six seasons. Did not fumble
in last 557 carries. Had three or more receptions in 112 games.
Played in three AFC Championhip game and was a Pro Bowl choice
1982, 1985 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
   BILL SHAW, Guard
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bills (1961-1969)
</P>
<P>
   _ The driving force of the Bills' offensive unit that emphasized
the run. Was proficient in pass and run blocking. Named first-team
All-AFL 1962-66. Selected to play in eight AFL All-Star games.
Named to pro football's All-Decade Team of the 1960's and All-Time
AFL Team. The captain for eight seasons, played on the Bills'
</P>
<P>
   championship teams of 1964 and 1965.
</P>
<P>
   LAWRENCE TAYLOR, Linebacker
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants (1981-1993)
</P>
<P>
   _ A quick and athletic linebacker who redefined his position.
Anchored the Giants' defense in two Super Bowls wins (1987 and
1991). Named NFL Most Valuable Player in 1986 following a season in
which he record a career-high 20.5 sacks. Was the NFL Defensive
Player of the Year in 1981, 1982 and 1986. Selected to 10 Pro
Bowls. Recorded 132.5 sacks, which doesn't included the 9.5 sacks
in 1981 when the statistic wasn't official. Was selected to the
75th Anniversary All-Time Team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
