</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALL-FALCONS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves can take big leap toward Hall with Falcons win
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The events of Saturday did not bode well for the
eventual candidacy of Dan Reeves to the Hall of Fame, and the
Atlanta Falcons coach may need an upset victory in Super Bowl
XXXIII today to merit consideration for the pro football shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Among the '98 finalists rejected by Hall of Fame selectors on
Saturday were coaches Marv Levy and George Allen. Both men had
sparkling resumes but the one element that factored into the
voting, acknowledged several of the 36 selectors, was that neither
of them ever won a Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, of course, lost four Super Bowl games with the Buffalo
Bills. Despite a career winning percentage of .681, Allen was a
loser in his lone Super Bowl appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was a four-time Super Bowl loser with the Minnesota
Vikings, selectors inducted coach Bud Grant in 1994. But it took
several years for Grant to finally crack the Hall, and sentiment
Saturday seemed to indicate that any coach elected in the future
may need at least one Super Bowl triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is 0-3 in Super Bowl games, all during his tenure with
the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, Dan has to keep Atlanta on top to have a real shot,''
said longtime Buffalo News columnist Larry Felser, one of the Hall
of Fame selectors. ''The fact he has taken two different franchises
to Super Bowls gets him some attention but it probably doesn't get
him into (the Hall of Fame). Now if he takes a team like Atlanta,
which has had a miserable history, and wins the thing, that could
do it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no players, coaches or administrators with anything
more than flimsy ties to the Falcons in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta coach Norm Van Brocklin (1968-1974) was inducted
in 1971 for his contributions on the field, not the sideline. Wide
receiver Tommy McDonald, who went into the Hall last summer, spent
the 1968 season with the Falcons, but it came in the twilight of a
career most associated with the Philadelphia Eagles. Running back
Eric Dickerson, one of five men inducted Saturday, spent the first
month of the '93 season with the Falcons. While a Falcons helmet
appeared on the Dickerson press release that was distributed here
Saturday, the team doesn't even list him in its media guide as ever
having played for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 seasons, Reeves is seventh among winningest coaches
with 172 victories. Five of the six men ahead of him _ Don Shula,
George Halas, Reeves' mentor Tom Landry, Curly Lambeau and Chuck
Noll _ already are in the Hall of Fame but all of them have
championships on their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The only one of the six not enshrined at Canton is Chuck Knox,
and he rung up 193 wins in 22 years. Like Reeves, however, Knox
never won a Super Bowl and selectors seem unmoved by the fact he
resurrected three franchises. Knox has yet to be a finalist, and a
survey of selectors here last week indicated waning support for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think (Reeves) is a viable candidate unless he wins
the big game,'' said selector Jerry Magee of the San Diego
Union-Tribune. ''His career is reminiscent of Don Coryell's
coaching tenure. Great regular-season record but no trophies.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight men who coached teams since the 1970 merger are in the
Hall of Fame and they have an aggregate 17 Super Bowl victories.
All but Grant have at least one Super Bowl win and, of that group,
all but Weeb Ewbank of the New York Jets are multiple winners.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' winning percentage of .580 is superior to that of Ewbank
(.507) and Noll (.572). But it is far below those of Hall of Fame
coaches Vince Lombardi (.740), Joe Gibbs (.683), Shula (.665), Bill
Walsh (.617), Grant (.607) and Landry (.601).
</P>
<P>
   A victory today, though, would go a long way toward closing the
gap and there is some dissenting opinion among selectors that
Reeves' current record is good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has been three places now and won, and that deserves
consideration,'' said Boston Globe columnist and Hall of Fame
selector Will McDonough. ''I don't think he has to win a Super Bowl
for us to think seriously about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
