<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-DAVOS _ DAVOS, Switzerland _ The United States cannot run
huge trade deficits with its major trading partners indefinitely,
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned an international
conference of political and business leaders Saturday. (Glass, Cox
News Service). 15
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ONECHILD _ BEIJING _ There are hundreds of thousands of
``missing girls,'' in China every year. The result of abortion,
infanticide or abandonment, all happening at incredible rates
because Chinese parents can have only one or two kids. And they
still want sons, not daughters, so they dispose of the females.
This is reflected in China's increasingly skewed sex ratio, most
recently documented at a record 120 boys to every 100 girls.
(Natural rate is 105/100.) The more efficient Chinese birth control
cadres become at limiting births, the more girls go missing. And
the more difficult life will be for Chinese young men as they come
of age, lacking girls to marry. One woman related that many women
in their village respond to the government limitation on babies by
getting ultrasound examinations and then having abortions if they
discover the fetus is female. ``I know many people who do this,''
she said. ``Medically, it's very safe now.'' The American angle on
this is that thousands of abandoned baby girls have become
available for foreign adoption. More than 4,000 American families
took home Chinese girls last year. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS to be placed on the Cox Server. MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   w/CHINA-SCANNERS _ WASHINGTON _ An American company that helped
launch medical ultrasound machines in China two decades ago says it
cannot control now whether Chinese doctors use them for
sex-selection abortions. Hedberg said the ultrasound systems her
company sells in China are used for treating heart, vascular and
skeletal problems as well as fetal monitoring. ATL Ultrasound is
one of at least three American medical equipment companies whose
ultrasound technology is now in widespread use at Chinese hospitals
and clinics. Others include General Electric and Hewlett-Packard.
(Christie, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   POPULATION-DATA _ Population control data and chrono on Chinese
population control. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTO. MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   HONDURAS-DIGGINGOUT _ LA CEIBA, Honduras - Honduras is the
second poorest nation in the Americas (behind only Haiti), where
the average family earns $875 a year. Thanks to Hurricane Mitch,
Honduras is now $3.4 billion poorer. Thousands of homes, farms and
cattle were swept away by the mudslides and floods spawned by
Hurricane Mitch last fall. Hundreds of roads, bridges, water and
phone lines have been obliterated. More than 5,600 lives were lost.
This country, with the help of countless Americans like David
Swartz of Dayton, is still digging out from the storm that forever
changed their lives. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News). 100. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The story, at 100 inches, is long, but trimmable. Photos
posted Thursday in the International folder in a folder called
DDN-Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-HEALTH _ HAVANA, Cuba _ Cuba's socialist system has failed
in many respects. Store shelves are often empty. Houses are
dilapidated and scarce. But Cuban scientists have developed an
array of new vaccines and drugs that are at the leading edge of
biotech research around the world. Cuba's state-run biotechology
industry has always been much admired for the advances it's made.
But now health officials in Cuba say a new AIDS vaccine will be
ready for use within two to five years. Preliminary testing of the
new formula is scheduled to begin in early 1999. We take a look at
the biotech industry and its goals in coming years. (Emling,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   EDs: WITH PHOTO: International folder on the Cox Server.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECTIONS _ JERUSALEM _ If you believe that elections
tell you a lot more about a country than about the candidates,
Israel's May 17 prime ministerial showdown fits the theory. What we
have seen so far is a field with at least five prominent opponents
representing small factions and realigning the country's political
map. There has been little talk about issues, but already, Israel
has seen major players change parties, Watergate-styled break-ins
at campaign headquarters and accusations that slogans are being
used to incite violence. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   w/ISRAEL-GENERALS _ JERUSALEM _ If you want to be Israeli prime
minister, it helps if you're an army general. Its even better if
you personally snuffed out a couple terrorists. The Labor Party
candidate, former General Ehud Barak, did. In the 1980s, he dressed
like a woman, sneaked into a downtown Beirut apartment and shot
three PLO fighters. Also on the operation, but headed to a
different apartment block, was one of Barak's opponents, recently
retired Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, who won Israel's highest medal
for bravery on the mission. Former Gen. Moshe Arens is also running
with his own party and others are being courted to join the parties
in their campaigns. Current Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu never
got above captain (though he was in Barak's unit), but it does not
change the fact that a country on constant guard against security
threats has frequently turns to its military leaders for the top
political post. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS-BOX _ Thumbnails on the major contenders. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SECEDE _ IVANGOROD, Russia The grass wasn't always
greener on the other side of the border. But now it is, and the
residents of this depressed Russian border town want to secede and
become part of the neighboring country of Estonia. In Soviet times,
there was little difference between Ivangorod and the Estonian town
of Narva across the border. Now, Estonia's economy is booming while
Russia is in the grips of yet another economic crisis. Novogorod
has petitioned both Russia and Estonia to shift the border, but
neither government is much interested. Estonia is seeking NATO and
European Union membership; adding a border dispute would only
complicate issues with Russia. (Holmes, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: WITH PHOTO: International folder on the Cox Server.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS: Information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MANAGERS _ WASHINGTON _ Illinois Republican Rep. Henry Hyde once
compared prosecuting the impeachment trial of President Clinton to
walking into the ``jaws of political death.'' But Hyde and his
prosecutors seem to be snatching life from those jaws. Every time
the first impeachment trial in 131 years seems to be on the verge
of dying, the House Republican prosecutors find a way to revive it.
(Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-SPENDING _ WASHINGTON _ As both parties prepare to add
billions of dollars to defense spending to counter a decline in
combat readiness, watchdog groups say there is much wasteful
spending that could be eliminated. We will provide an examination
of up to 10 wasteful projects, including several boondoggles forced
on the Pentagon by Congress. Among the prime areas of waste: too
many military bases; weapons or airplanes such as the
Lockheed-Martin C-130s that exceed those requested by the Pentagon;
too many nuclear submarines, and wasteful handling of inventory.
(Malone, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   w/MILITARY-DATA _ Graphics material on budget trends. MOVED
TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Cox photos for this story will be placed in the National
folder on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-ETHICS _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, the
incoming chairman of the House ethics committee, talks about his
new job, generally considered one of the most thankless in
Congress. (Dart, Cox News Service 750). MOVED THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ It will be a year Jan. 30 since Eric Robert Rudolph
rented Kull the Conqueror from a video store and bought a few
groceries in Murphy, N.C., then disappeared as police descended on
his trailer, where the lights were still on. In Murphy and nearby
Andrews, Rudolph remains a topic of conversation _hero to some,
satan to others, a marvel to most. How, for instance, has he
survived two killer winters in the outdoors? Or is he outdoors? Or
in one of the old mines where he used to play? Or in somebody's
vacation cabin? Or in Missouri, or Colorado, or hanging with
neo-Nazis in Belgium or Germany? Or is he even still alive? We talk
to townsfolk, including the trekkers and trappers and hunters who
know the woods and hills, for the latest theories and speculations.
We also find out all we can about the official search by federal
agents and how they're adjusting to life among the mountain
natives. (Harmon/Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/RUDOLPH-FUGITIVE _ Looking at other fugitives who have eluded
law enforcement for long periods of time, particularly any still at
large. (Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH-BOMBTIME _ 1998 timeline on the bombing, the search and
charges against Rudolph. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The timeline is being posted in the National folder on the
Cox server as a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH-VIET _ It has now been a year since Atlanta and
Birmingham bombing suspect Eric Robert Rudolph slipped into the
heavily wooded mountains around Andrews, N.C., with federal law
enforcement agents only a few hours behind him. Despite the
closeness of the pursuit of Rudolph and fresh leads last year at
this time, the anti-government recluse and former airborne soldier
has managed to elude one of the most intensive and concentrated
manhunts in recent law enforcement history over the last 12 months.
Rudolph is threatening to become as enigmatic and as elusive a
target as fabled hijacker D.B. Cooper, who disappeared into the
Pacific Northwest on Thanksgiving Eve 1971 with $200,000 in
Northwest Airlines' money after parachuting from one of their
Mexico-bound jets. Rudolph's hunters appear no closer now to
tightening the noose on their quarry than they were when they first
showed up in Andrews. If anything, the feds have gotten bogged down
in a mission that has developed eerie similarities to the U.S.
military involvement in Vietnam. There may never be a satisfactory
conclusion to the Rudolph hunt, just as Vietnam ended without any
real resolution of the problem. (Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-DESIGN _ ST. LOUIS _ Amid a neighborhood of dilapidated
homes and crumbling factories lies the Gateway Elementary, Middle
and Michael school, an oasis of innovative modern design. As
politicians continue to debate federal support for school
construction and renovation, Gateway is one of several schools
across the country that are exploring what makes a stellar learning
environment for students. (Monroe, Cox News Service 600) MOVED
</P>
