   w/SCHOOL-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ In a move expected to spark a
new battle with Congress, President Clinton wants the federal
government to provide $22 billion in tax credits to groups that
loan money to build new schools and repair old ones. (Monroe, Cox
News Service) MOVED TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-GRAPHIC _ State-by-state snapshot of school facilities in
Georgia, Florida, Texas, North Carolina, Colorado and Ohio. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-FAIL _ ATLANTA _ We reported last month the first
results of student teacher failure rates on a tough new national
test Georgia has started requiring for new teachers _ called Praxis
II. Now we're getting an exclusive look at how that 21 percent
failure rate breaks out at each of the 15 public and 19 private
colleges with education programs. The results at historically black
colleges, we hear, are so bad that the agency that administers the
test, the Professional Standards Commission, has agreed with their
demands that scores be broken down by race at all 34 schools _ to
show, for example, that blacks at UGA and GSU did almost as bad as
students at Paine College or Fort Valley State. This tests
subject-matter knowledge, the area that needs strengthening but is
not something colleges of education have traditionally been
accountable for. Denying certificates to, say, 50 or 60 percent of
the graduates of a historically black college is a controversial
move _ threatening the college's very existence in the case of
Paine College in Augusta, and further depressing an already scarce
supply of minority teachers. PSC is giving us exclusive on stats
and we should be able to get react Wednesday. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TWO-CITIES _ ATLANTA _ Bad air, a mega-hub airport that wants to
grow even more, sprawl and endless traffic; a liberal city
surrounded by conservative suburbs that can't see eye-to-eye on
regional issues; skyrocketing property values; a large minority
population and growing numbers of immigrants; a redeveloping
downtown and a surrounding state that's mostly rural, and which
eyes the big city with suspicion. Atlanta? Yes, but also its Super
Bowl opponent _ Denver. A tale of two cities that are far apart,
yet very close. (Goldberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTARIANS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Two Libertarians discuss what
attracted them to the party, which they say is gaining popularity.
(Borths, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   DELPHI _ The unions that represent GM's Dayton-area workers have
agreed to promote the Delphi Automotive Systems spinoff to
potential investors in a stunning turnaround for GM-Union
relations. Nick Nichols, chief GM negotiator for the IUE, delivered
a speech late last year to about 600 GM executives and received a
standing ovation. Nichols' theme was that GM and its workers must
be partners in this spinoff if it's to succeed. In exchange for the
IUE's support, GM has agreed to extend the retirement benefits
cut-off date for IUE members until Oct. 1. IUE will also be
eligible for significant discounts on trucks and cars through 2000.
This contrasts to the heated battles that have characterized GM's
relations with the UAW, it's largest union. But there is some
evidence, at least here in the Miami Valley, that the frostiness
between GM and the local UAW membership is thawing. (Wagner, Dayton
Daily News). 30. WITH PHOTOS AND CHARTS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   IRS-VISIT _ If you live more than 40 miles from the nearest
Internal Revenue Service, the IRS may be coming for a neighborly
visit to help you file your 1998 income taxes. Don't panic. They're
not coming to your house but, beginning Monday, it will send vans
with to 24 cities in Georgia that are more than 40 miles from the
nearest IRS office. Monday, the vans will visit the first three
cities: Elberton, LaGrange and Tifton. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MICROTALK _ DAYTON, Ohio _ If you think you need a bit more than
a pager to keep in touch with family members but you don't want the
expense of equipping everybody with cellular telephones, Cobra
Electronics might have a solution for you. Cobra offers a whole
line of small, relatively inexpensive two-way radios that can be
clipped onto a belt like a pager. (Cumming, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
