<SLUG> BC-COMMUTATION-REACTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG REACTION TO GOVERNOR'S DECISION TO SPARE LIFE OF KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL AND KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Death penalty opponents were gleeful Friday over
Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan's decision to spare the life of a
condemned killer after Pope John Paul II made a personal plea for
the man's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous act of mercy, something you don't see from
politicians nowadays,'' said the Rev. Larry Rice of St. Louis. ``He
didn't wait until the last minute; he didn't cut corners. He's to
be commended.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice and others said they hoped Carnahan's action _ combined
with the pope's two-day visit and his pointed call for the
abolition of the death penalty _ would invigorate their movement.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's political opponents criticized his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said he changed Darrell Mease's death sentence to life
without parole out of respect for the pope and the pope's direct
request for mercy that came after a prayer service Wednesday in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Mease, 52, was convicted of the ambush slayings of his former
drug partner, the man's wife and their paraplegic grandson in
southwest Missouri in 1988. He was scheduled to be executed on Feb.
10.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, director of the New Life Evangelist Center, said he plans
to start a petition drive to abolish capital punishment. He said he
hopes to gather enough signatures to put the issue on the November
2000 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that public sentiment has
traditionally favored the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Early reaction to Carnahan's decision indicates that still may
be true. The governor's office received about 200 calls Friday,
many of them critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten more that I would characterize as supportive of
the death penalty than those who are against it,'' said Chris
Sifford, Carnahan's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Republicans said the decision could be an issue in next
year's Senate race between Democrat Carnahan and Republican U.S.
Sen. John Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Duwe, spokesman for the state GOP, said Mease ``was the
poster boy for the death penalty in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't execute Darrell Mease, who can we execute?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leader Delbert Scott's office received several
e-mails and telephone calls critical of Carnahan's decision, said
Scott Swain, Scott's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting some phone calls and they are not happy,''
Swain said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sifford said the governor's office was not surprised by the
reaction. He said Joe Bednar, Carnahan's legal counsel, planned to
contact the son of the couple killed by Mease to explain why the
governor spared the life of the man who killed his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Sifford said the governor's office was unsuccessful in reaching
the victims' family on Thursday and planned to apologize for the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less critical of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hill, executive director of the Missouri Baptist Convention,
said Baptists would have a wide range of views on the issue, but he
did not object to Carnahan's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a personal basis, I feel comfortable with the governor
responding to a plea for mercy,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Mike Schilling, a Springfield Democrat who has
introduced a bill to end the death penalty, said
government-sanctioned killing perpetuates a cycle of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continual churning of a vengeful attitude throughout
society,'' Schilling said. ``People are horrified by a really
gruesome murder and what's the first thing they ask? `Are you going
to seek the death penalty?' Politicians have demagogued this issue
so they look tough on crime. But it is vulgarizing our culture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
