<HEADLINE>
DISCOUNT DENVER IF THE MOON IS BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: This is the time of year when all the weird and
off-beat auguries start telling us whether it's going to be a good
year or bad year for stock players.
</P>
<P>
   The January Barometer, for instance, on Friday forecast an up
market for 1999. The barometer's custodian, Stock Trader's Almanac
publisher Yale Hirsch, says it has only registered three
significant bad calls since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   If the Standard &AMP; Poor's composite index ends January with a
gain, according to the barometer, things look rosy for the market.
Since the S&AMP;P 500 ended the trading month well on the plus side,
this is an encouraging sign. While the barometer gave significantly
false signals in 1966, 1968 and 1982, Hirsch says, it has never
been wrong in the years when a new Congress convened.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there's the Super Bowl Predictor, with which
nearly everyone in the stock market seems familiar. The other day a
colleague looked at the Denver-Atlanta match-up and said, ``Well,
it doesn't matter who wins this year, right?''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl Predictor, in case you haven't heard, is based on
the big game's history since 1967. When a National Conference team
wins, the market as measured by the Dow Jones Industrial Average is
usually up. It's also bullish when an American Conference team wins
if it was an NFL member before the NFL merged with the American
Football League. Conversely, when an American Conference team wins,
the average usually declines.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl Predictor has a success rate of nearly 90
percent, but Denver's participation throws an anomalous wrinkle
into this year's game, which prompted the colleague's observation.
Even though American Conference champ Denver won last year, the
stock market still had a spectacular year. Moreover, Denver was
involved two of the other three times the Super Bowl Predictor was
wrong. Even though NFL teams beat the Broncos in 1978 and 1990, the
Dow Jones lost ground both years.
</P>
<P>
   So, based on Denver's history, the team's penchant for throwing
the Super Bowl Predictor out of kilter makes it a highly
questionable indicator this year regardless of who wins.
</P>
<P>
   If these prognosticatory staples are too old hat, here's a new
toy to play with. It isn't geared to predicting the market's
full-year performance, but it sure is interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the ``Blue Moon Theory,'' and credit Market Logic with
the research into this weird bit of market lore. A ``blue moon,''
incidentally, is the second full moon to happen during a single
month. Although they usually occur only once every 2 years or so,
1999 will have two such occurrences. The first will be Sunday
night, and the second will be Wednesday, March 31.
</P>
<P>
   What Market Logic has discovered is that the S&AMP;P 500 has
better-than-average performances before and after blue moons.
Measurements since 1950 show the median change the days before a
blue moon was plus 0.30 percent and the average change was only
slightly less. The days after a blue moon, the median gain was 0.21
percent and the average gain more than double that. The daily
average over nearly 50 years has been only 0.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you can strike it rich with this bit of esoterica seems
doubtful, but isn't it fun to know?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
