<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-TIGER-MYSTERY-720&AMP;     01-30 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TIGER-MYSTERY-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY OF STRAY TIGER LEADS OFFICIALS TO A PRESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey wildlife agents continued Saturday to count tigers on
a private refuge in Ocean County, trying to confirm suspicions that
a 431-pound Bengal tiger shot to death as it wandered loose last
Wednesday had escaped from the compound. But there were no signs
that the mystery was nearing solution.
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson Township neighbors worried and wondered about the
world-class concentration of tigers in their midst, investigators
for the state Division of Fish, Game and Wildlife again scouted
craggy lairs and other hiding places in the dense winter woods of
the 12-acre reserve called Tigers Only Preservation, trying to
account for about 20 of the big cats.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor William Allmann of Jackson Township said the investigators
were probably on the right track. ``All indications are that the
tiger came from this property,'' he said, noting that Six Flags
Great Adventure Safari Park nearby had accounted for its nine
tigers. ``The only other possibility is that someone could have
dropped it off, but that's very far-fetched.''
</P>
<P>
   But the owner of Tigers Only, Joan Byron-Marasek, insisted
through a lawyer, Valter Must, that the wayward tiger had not come
from her property, that a 20-foot perimeter fence was intact, and
that the episode _ and the curiosity and suspicions it has aroused
_ had turned her quiet, private life upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client is beleaguered,'' Must said. ``She's a very private
person. It's been a circus out here, with law-enforcement and
animal-rights people, the press and people sneaking into the woods
to take her picture. She wants to accommodate the public's need to
feel safe, but she hopes this incident doesn't destroy what she has
worked for her entire life. She finds this whole thing very
intrusive and embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama began last Wednesday after residents on two nearby
roads spotted a tiger on the loose, triggering a seven-hour search.
Efforts to tranquilize and trap the animal failed _ the darts
missed _ and the police, fearing that someone might be hurt, shot
and killed the tiger in a driveway.
</P>
<P>
   The episode, which left some residents terrified and many
astonished to learn that dozens of tigers were harbored in the
area, prompted an extensive search for the tiger's owner. Samples
of the tiger's fur, and soil and other material from its paws, were
taken for analysis, which could take several days. An autopsy
revealed nothing in the tiger's stomach that might provide a clue.
</P>
<P>
   After the elimination of Six Flags, suspicion fell quickly on
Tigers Only. Exercising a search warrant on Friday, state wildlife
investigators went to the compound to take a census and examine
Mrs. Byron-Marasek's records, including her exotic-animal licenses
for a reserve she has owned for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But at the gate the investigators were confronted by 17 large,
dangerous-looking dogs, all of which, Allmann said, had no township
licenses. The mayor said Mrs. Byron-Marasek tried to round up and
pen the dogs, but was so long doing so that the investigators
decided to enter the property using cagelike movable steel tunnels
obtained from Six Flags Great Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Huljack, deputy chief of the wildlife division's
enforcement bureau, said the investigators tallied 17 tigers, but
were not satisfied that their count was complete. Mrs.
Byron-Marasek's state exotic-animal licensing paperwork suggested
that the reserve was home to 23 tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Byron-Marasek was quoted by officials as saying that none
of her tigers was missing, that several had died, while others _
ferocious but shy _ were just hiding from the unaccustomed hubbub
of cars coming and going, of helicopters chattering overhead and
strangers moving about their normally serene woods.
</P>
<P>
   While the search warrant expired on Friday, Mrs. Byron-Marasek
gave wildlife investigators permission Saturday to continue their
effort, Allmann said. He said that Mrs. Byron-Marasek was
cooperating and that reports to the contrary were incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said he had strengthened police patrols around
the compound, in part because of residents' fears, which were
heightened by a report of a breach in a perimeter fence. Officials
confirmed that part of an outer fence was down, but said that a
20-foot inner fence was still intact.
</P>
<P>
   And so the mystery _ and the fears _ remained.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This makes me very nervous, especially with the number of
tigers she has,'' Diane Dememmo, 31, a mother of two children, said
Saturday as she eyed the compound warily from her parked car.
``It's happened once. We don't want it to happen again. As a
mother, I'd like to see the preserve closed down, or at least more
security.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Gunther, a mother of six who has lived in the area for
21 years, said she was not worried. ``There's never been a
problem,'' she said. ``I didn't even know the preserve was there.
She has a responsibility to maintain proper fencing, but I think
having the preserve in the community is a wonderful thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
