<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 1/30/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MIAMI -- Jan. 30, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL, 1-30 -- Until
the kickoff, the Super Bowl is always a talk show. Not these days.
A young Miami Dolphins fan getting ready for Super Bowl XXXIII
Sunday, takes on a tackling bag at a National Football League theme
park in Miami Saturday. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 30, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SENATE-3, 1-30 --
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, left, confering with a fellow Republican
Sen., Paul Coverdell of Georgia, sees a need for witnesses in the
trial of President Clinton. Gramm, says he could comfortably vote
guilty or not guilty on the articles of impeachment without an iota
of additional information. ``Justice is not an outcome, it's a
process,'' says Gramm. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 30, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SENATE-2, 1-30 --
Sen. Gordon H. Smith of Oregon, left, shown meeting with the
British Ambassador, Sir Christopher Meyer, says he and a number of
Republican colleagues are leaning toward voting to acquit President
Clinton on perjury and to convict him of obstruction of justice.
Most of the senators interviewed would not signal how they intended
to vote; they said that would be inappropriate, given that they are
acting in part as jurors who have taken oaths of impartiality.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 30, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SENATE-1, 1-30 --
James Ziglar, front, the sergeant-at-arms during the trial of
President Bill Clinton, carries subpoenas past the Senate chamber
for delivery to the three witnesses Saturday. Ziglar is followed by
his executive advisor Ozzie Girard. It is a weekend of preparation
for all sides as depositions in the trial of the president are set
to start Sunday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HALLANDALE, Fla. -- Jan. 30, 1999 -- RAC-SMITH-JOCKEY,
1-29 -- Mike Smith, a jockey sidelined by two injuries for seven
months last year, does some brushing up Friday before a morning
workout at Gulfstream. He managed to hold his weight at 114 during
his latest absence by working out three or four hours a day -
crucial in a business in which jockeys have eaten their way into
oblivion. ``I feel great, but I realize it's always different
getting on a horse,'' he says. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- Jan. 30, 1999 -- WEALTHY-CEMETERY,
1-30 -- The graves of Steven J. Ross, the entrepreneur who built a
family funeral parlor business into Time Warner Inc., and his
parents at Green River Cemetery in East Hampton, on Long Island.
Today, Green River Cemetery, the most fashionable place to be dead
in the Hamptons is fully booked. When Steven J. Ross died of cancer
in 1992, Courtney Sale Ross, his widow bought 110 grave plots, at a
cost of $77,000, at the cemetery. Her expressed purpose: to provide
plots for generations of Rosses to come. (Vic Delucia/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) VLADIVOSTOK, Russia -- Jan. 30, 1999 --
RUSSIA-JOURNALIST, 1-30 -- Capt. Grigory Pasko, 37, a reporter for
Boyevaya Vakhta (Battle Watch), the newspaper of Russia's Pacific
Fleet, arriving for trial in Vladivostok. Pasko, accused of
reporting about the dumping of military waste at sea, has been
charged with disclosing some of the state's most sensitive secrets.
Pasko's wife, Galina Morozova, below, with a photo of the couple's
honeymoon in Egypt, has only seen him six times since his arrest.
If convicted, he could stay in jail for another 20 years. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
