<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5410 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERBOWL-LADY31-COX     01-30 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-LADY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    12 Super minutes
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PLAM BEACH, Fla. _ In a few short hours, this high-school
gridiron on the western edge of Miami will be transformed into a
field of dreams. But first, Maggi Rosenberg has to contend with a
fate worse than thunderclouds.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   No one had bothered to tell Rosenberg, rehearsal coordinator for
Super Bowl XXXIII's halftime show, that the field, otherwise home
to Dade Christian School's football team, was due for a scheduled
soaking. So when she arrives on the morning of the show's first
full-scale rehearsal _ with more than 1,000 performers, crew
members and production staff _ she discovers all her markings have
been washed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, we had a beautifully painted field,'' Rosenberg
sighs. ``Today, we have a beautifully watered field.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the business of show business when you're dealing with
the world's most-watched spectacle, seen by a live audience of
75,000 and worldwide television audience of close to a billion.
It's true there's a football game being played today at Pro Player
Stadium, but don't tell that to the people involved in the Super
Bowl halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   People like the 500-plus cheerleaders who have come to perform
from high schools throughout Martin, Palm Beach, Broward and
Miami-Dade counties. People like the entertainment executives from
New York's Radio City Music Hall, who are producing the whole
shebang.
</P>
<P>
   And people like Maggi Rosenberg _ Wellington resident,
well-known local children's entertainer (her stage name is ``Miss
Maggi'') and now one of the pivotal players in this 12-minute
production.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. All this for 12 minutes, give or take a few
seconds of banner-waving. Wouldn't it just be easier to let a band
march?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for the SUPER BOWL!'' replies Rosenberg, who came to the
job because of her work on a San Francisco 49ers halftime show a
few years ago promoting children's literacy.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Super Bowl halftime shows stretches all the way
to 1967, the event's first year. Back then, a marching band did
suffice as entertainment. Make that two marching bands _ from the
University of Arizona and University of Michigan _ who amused the
crowd at Los Angeles Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that followed, the show grew to slightly larger
proportions. Broadway veteran Carol Channing sang ``Hello, Dolly!''
from a giant float hoisted on to the field. The youth group Up With
People performed a couple of times. Disney produced a
silver-anniversary salute to the game, featuring New Kids on the
Block.
</P>
<P>
   But it took a little competition _ namely when the upstart Fox
network decided to air its hit comedy series, ``In Living Color,''
during halftime in 1992 _ for the NFL to get wise to the show's
real potential. The next year, working with Radio City Productions,
the league staged a blockbuster event featuring Michael Jackson,
who seemingly popped out of a giant video screen as part of his
dramatic entrance. The crowd went wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really took the show away from the traditional pom-pom
girls to a much more theatrically produced show,'' says Radio City
Vice President Michael Fiur, who has been in charge of six halftime
specials, including this year's.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ``the biggest challenge is how to top yourself,''
Fiur adds. In 1996, the show in Phoenix featured pop diva Diana
Ross departing by helicopter, a move that required the approval of
the Federal Aviation Administration. Last year's bash in San Diego
was billed as ``A Tribute to Motown's 40th Anniversary,'' starring
Boyz II Men, Queen Latifah, Smokey Robinson and Martha Reeves, who
sang her classic hit, ``Heat Wave,'' to the accompaniment of balls
of flame.
</P>
<P>
   As for this year's production, estimated to cost $2.5 million?
Organizers are careful not to reveal any of the special effects _
they wouldn't want to spoil the surprise _ but this much is clear:
The show is a little soul, a little swing and a lot of salsa. The
Miami Sound Machine herself, Gloria Estefan, is the headliner,
Stevie Wonder is her special guest and Big Bad Voodoo Daddy fill
out the bill to tie in with the current swing revival.
</P>
<P>
   But the stars, if anything, take a back seat to the volunteer
cast of hundreds. To see them rehearse at Dade Christian School _
after Rosenberg got the painting crew to come back, of course _ is
to witness a sight even an operatic great like Richard Wagner (or a
circus showman like P.T. Barnum) couldn't have envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers are waving flashlights to the bluesy beat of a Wonder
song. Teams of older swing dancers are pretending they're at the
world's biggest sock hop. Guys on stilts are actually attempting
gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   And all this is happening _ more or less _ at the same time,
thanks to a dozen or so production assistants scurrying across the
field and a petite woman _ staging director Judy Chabola _ barking
orders into a microphone as she stands on a platform high above the
action. A typical command to the color-coded groups of performers
might go something like this: ``Blue people with the spinners, can
you please go back?'' or ``Yellows, go get ready for the jump
ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, you're looking at a kaleidoscope whose edges
become more distinct as the rehearsal process continues,'' says the
show's creative director, Jeffrey Ernstoff, who jokes that his
biggest challenge is finding a role for his 86-year-old mother, a
Boca Raton resident. ``The trick is to combine the traditional
elements of pageantry with a hip twist.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a trick that necessitates a year of planning. This year's
halftime show got its start as soon as the clock ran out on last
year's Super Bowl. The process typically begins with picking the
right artists _ Estefan was a natural choice for Miami _ and then
selecting the music. After a score is created, a team of
choreographers gives the show its visual shape.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the work isn't done in a studio. Instead, it's laid out
on grids and charts _ like the battle plan for the invasion of a
small country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is war,'' says head choreographer Doug Jack, who like
most of his halftime colleagues stages stadium events throughout
the world. ``We've done shows in Singapore where we actually used
the military as our base of command.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 12 minutes seen around the world are just one part of the
equation, however. Equally important is the plan for bringing out
the 20-piece, 10-ton portable stage where the headliners perform.
While the average stadium rock show takes a day to assemble, the
NFL allots the halftime stage crew, featuring more than 150
volunteers, less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we can't dent a blade of grass in the process,'' says
Fiur, the executive producer. The secret? ``We use pneumatic
airplane tires,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the television aspect. The halftime show is really
two shows: one for the stadium audience, the other for home
viewers. The former can't see Estefan's expression as she sings,
but the latter can't feel the sonic boom of the fireworks (yes,
there will be plenty bursting in air).
</P>
<P>
   ``For the stadium audience ... you want to fill as much of the
field as possible. On television, that spectacle doesn't always
translate,'' says Paul Miller, the director for Fox, now the
broadcast network. ``My main focus is on the stars who are
performing.''
</P>
<P>
   And as far as set-up goes, the halftime TV crew gets about as
much time as the halftime stage crew, sometimes literally shoving
the network sports producers out of their spots. ``It's the
greatest get-out-of-the-way moment in show business,'' says
creative director Ernstoff.
</P>
<P>
   What's Rosenberg's role in this army of entertainers and
executives? She's a kind of behind-the-scenes drill sergeant,
responsible for everything from picking practice locations to
ordering the gallons of Gatorade the cast will consume to making
sure paramedics are on hand. (A bungee jumper was killed during a
rehearsal for the 1997 halftime show.)
</P>
<P>
   And during today's big game, it will be Rosenberg's job to
gather the 1,200 cast and crew members at an off-site location,
shuttle them on 30 buses to the stadium and get them back just
after halftime. And, oh yeah, feed them. What do you serve 1,200
people on their night of fame? Rosenberg has a two-word reply:
``Box lunches.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering, Rosenberg doesn't get to see the game.
Neither do most of the cast and crew, which makes it particularly
hard to recruit college athletes for some of the grunt work. But no
one else seems to care. At the show's makeshift headquarters in
suburban Miami, a bulletin board announces the details of each
rehearsal. It's only in tiny handwriting at the bottom that you'll
find the names of the teams, Denver vs. Atlanta, along with the
current odds.
</P>
<P>
   At least they're finally aware who's playing. ``I didn't even
know who was in the playoffs,'' Rosenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
