<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-JAMALAN     01-30 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-JAMALANDERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON SHOWS NO EVIDENCE OF NERVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Nothing bothered Jamal Anderson this past week, and if
that's still the case Sunday, nothing may bother the Atlanta
Falcons, either.
</P>
<P>
   For Anderson, the crush of Super Bowl week was merely the
extension of a life spent in the midst of celebrity. Media hordes
were nothing new to the 26-year-old running back. Questioners
coming from all angles were old hat, something he'd seen handled
with aplomb for most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   For a kid who grew up thinking of Sugar Ray Leonard as his
uncle, Muhammad Ali as his father's friend, Mike Tyson as his big
brother, and Donna Summer as his dance instructor, a few thousand
notebooks and cameras were no problem, because he long ago learned
that's what it's all about at the top.
</P>
<P>
   The way he sees it, the way he's always seen it, is that this is
how it's supposed to be. At least if you want to achieve athletic
success it is, because if you do, celebrity follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being at Eric Dickerson's house when I was like
10,'' Anderson recalled. ``I saw all these trophies and I was like,
`Oh, my God, he's the best ever.' That influence was invaluable.
Being around all those guys is where I learned about being
competitive. All they talked about was being the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was intensely competitive and he's recognized as one of
the top bodyguards in his business. He worked hard to be the best
in the business. All of us grew up with that attitude: `Why be
average?' ''
</P>
<P>
   For the last 25 years, James Anderson has made a living guarding
celebrities such as Ali, Michael Jackson, and Richard Pryor. His
son saw people like Summer at family barbecues and Pryor on the
living-room couch. He saw Leonard at press conferences and Ali
stopping traffic.
</P>
<P>
   As he grew up, they would take him aside, explain to him what
press conferences and interviews and fans were all about, and as he
listened, Jamal Anderson also grew. He grew into a 234-pound
battering ram of a back who this season finished second only to
Denver's Terrell Davis in rushing yards with 1,846, the ninth-best
total in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons he learned as a kid surrounded by celebrity came
into play all week, a week that has overwhelmed many a young NFL
star ill-prepared for the endless questioning that goes along with
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, we have a natural tendency that when we see people on
television, we put them on another level,'' Anderson said. ``For
some reason, people think they're not human. Not only are they
celebrities, they're held to a higher standard because they're on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's unfortunate because everybody's human.
Everybody errs. Everybody makes mistakes. We're all the same. We're
all going to eventually bleed, be afflicted with different diseases
or problems, die.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come up and ask for an autograph and I say, `My name on
a paper is no more valuable than your name on a paper.' If it
really means something to them, so be it, but we need to understand
that we're all the same people regardless of what we do. I'm no
more important than the guy who builds a car or the person who
keeps his kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who was around our house, we treated everybody
the same way. Believe me, Sugar Ray Leonard didn't get any more
special treatment than our neighbor who came over for a barbecue.
We threw them on the couch together. Ray didn't eat before anybody
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate enough to oftentimes be standing right next to
Muhammad or Sugar Ray in situations like this when I was young. I
would be thinking, `This is unbelievable,' watching how they
handled these situations. They looked forward to it. That's what
they were all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrying the load
</P>
<P>
   Now it's what Anderson is about as he awaits his arrival on the
biggest stage in professional football. When he gets there, he will
bring a powerful body, strong legs, and an ability to absorb and
deliver punishment that allowed him to carry the ball a record 410
times this season.
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson speaks of those carries, there is not a hint of
complaint, not a mention of being worn down by the kind of workload
normally reserved for the Budweiser Clydesdales. There is only a
sense that this is his game and he will play it out in the hopes
that it will transform him into the kind of athlete who needs
someone like his father around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't something I thought about a lot until it got to
about 370,'' Anderson said. ``Then I was like, `Wow.' Just to think
about the fact that nobody's carried that many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting pounded every year since I was 7, so I'm
used to it. I had 410 carries but I don't feel it. I don't want to
say it was easy. I don't really want to do it again, but I don't
feel like it was that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (coach) Dan (Reeves) thinks I feel good, he'll give it to
me as many times as it goes in the flow of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If things are flowing well for the Falcons, that is a lot of
times, because Atlanta is 20-2 when Anderson carries 20 or more
times, including 15-0 this season. Knowing that, the Broncos expect
to see a good deal of Atlanta's celebrity-in-waiting Sunday. More,
they expect, than they'd like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presents two or three huge problems,'' said Denver safety
Tyrone Braxton. ``First of all he's fast, so he can outrun you.
Second of all, he's quick so he can outmaneuver you. And three, he
has power. He can run over you. If any back has that, he's a great
back. The guy is a great back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of Earl Campbell. He's short, he's strong, he's
thick, and he's quick. He's a very difficult force to be reckoned
with.''
</P>
<P>
   That's only when he's on the field, however. Anyplace else,
Jamal Anderson is his father's son and his celebrity client's
protege. He is a glib kid with a ready smile and an answer for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal has been around a lot of greatness and I think it's
taught him humility,'' his father said several weeks ago while
working for Tyson in Las Vegas. ``If you see him bragging, he's
joking, having fun with the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got that from Ali and Ray. It helps him relax. He doesn't
want you uptight when you're talking to him. Jamal's effervescence
comes from his mother. He's always been one of our shiest children
but he grew into being outgoing. He's learning to be comfortable
with his own success now. Since the Falcons began having success,
he's become a more gregarious person.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming control
</P>
<P>
   It would have been difficult to imagine a more engaging athlete
to deal with during a week as tedious as this past one, but Sunday
no one expects to see that side of Anderson until his work is done
_ except for perhaps those moments when he dances the Dirty Bird,
the steps he uses to celebrate his touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson danced that dance 16 times this season and if he can do
it a couple more times Sunday, he will surely have the underdog
Falcons in position to unseat the defending Super Bowl champions
because it would likely mean Atlanta was running with authority and
running down the clock.
</P>
<P>
   That control of the game has been a big part of the Falcons'
success, and there is only one way to achieve it: Anderson must run
over people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not careful, if you don't have two guys there to
wrap him up and do a great job tackling him, he'll run over two
guys,'' said Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski. ``He'll run over
three guys. In film the last two weeks I've seen some amazing
things done by this man.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a ball-control team, and they're the best in the
league as far as that goes, so we have to stop him. But he can do
it all. He's a combination of Terrell Davis, who can make you miss,
and the power of Jerome Bettis. He's got the speed of some of the
best backs in the league. He's got the full package.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they've got a great system for him. They like to hold onto
the ball, and he seems like the key to the whole thing. If he gets
out on us, they'll give themselves a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If the former seventh-round draft choice from Utah gets out on
the Broncos, he'll also give himself a chance to become what he's
long dreamed of since he was a boy learning not to look wide-eyed
at guys named Ali and Leonard. He'll give himself a chance to shine
in front of the world, a chance to have his own time in the
celebrity's sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do picture yourself in those situations,'' Anderson
conceded. ``You picture yourself growing up to be Muhammad Ali. You
just try to imagine what it's like to be them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I enjoy the situation we're in right now. Playing in the
Super Bowl is great. There are no bad days for Jamal Anderson. This
is the greatest athletic stage there is and I'm happy to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself in a situation once where I was either unwanted
or overlooked (coming out of Utah), so this is the reward for all
late-round picks. When you start like that, you have to fight and
claw your way to where we are now. This is something I've worked
for my whole life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I thought coming out of the draft that I had more
ability than to have been picked in the seventh round, but for one
reason or another I was picked No. 201. That's a constant
motivator. People don't think players like myself or Terrell Davis
(a sixth-round pick in 1995) should be achieving these things.
That's always prominent in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at the Falcons the same way. We weren't supposed
to be here. That's why I believe we're going to do some things that
will impress a lot of people. We feel good about where we are as a
team. We're looking forward to the challenge. It's going to be a
lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jamal Anderson's approach to life and celebrity, what else
could it be?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
