<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CALHOUN FUMES, AND THE HUSKIES RESPOND 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis' team more than weathered the game-opening tornado,
but even with a 12-point lead three minutes into the second half,
he understood the forecast remained cloudy with a 90 percent chance
of a heavy Connecticut run. Beyond the youthful tendencies of his
own players in games against higher-ranked teams, he knew Jim
Calhoun wasn't going to just go away without a burst of hot air.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike with Jarvis, the bearded egghead in control of the
understated blend of urban talent that is St. John's, Connecticut's
top-ranked Huskies feed off the uncensored emotion of their kinetic
coach. So here they were Saturday, in sold-out Madison Square
Garden, suddenly down a dirty dozen, with Calhoun predictably
spinning like a twister in a corn field.
</P>
<P>
   His junior center, Jake Voskuhl, had earned his scorn and a seat
on the bench with an inbounds pass that turned into a Bootsy
Thornton 3-pointer. Calhoun yanked Albert Mouring off the bench by
his shirt _ the classic move of the Knight _ after his senior
guard, Ricky Moore, made another distasteful pass. Only Voskuhl,
appreciating the company in his moments of misery, stood up to
greet Moore, which motivated Calhoun to scream at him some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy thing, when someone's yelling at you like
that,'' Voskuhl said after UConn had ridden Calhoun's rage to a
78-74 victory. ``But you also know that he isn't really mad at you.
He's mad at the team.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that when Calhoun began to thunder, it had been a
team effort, both ways, which accounted for the 53-41 St. John's
lead. The stark reality Calhoun faced, from the point when his team
led by 16-3 after starting with a five-minute bolt of lightning,
was that the Red Storm had come back to dominate UConn as if the
Huskies had stepped up from the Patriot League. St. John's, in the
person of Lavor Postell, was killing UConn on the offensive boards.
Their two New York City recruits on the Brooklyn-Queens Expressway
to eventual draft lottery status, Ron Artest and Erick Barkley, had
settled in and were going about the day as if beating No. 1 was
simply what they had been brought to St. John's to do.
</P>
<P>
   Artest and Barkley were signed not by Jarvis, but Fran
Fraschilla, the human jumping bean whose two-year run ended with an
unceremonious and unexplained dismissal last spring. Though these
aren't his players _ to speak in the vernacular of the market _
Jarvis has managed in a short amount of time to mold them in his
more subdued manner. St. John's, when on its game, plays less like
a storm, more like the Red Calm. The chest-bumping, face-contorting
show ended with the careers of Felipe Lopez and Zendon Hamilton.
Wasted motion and emotion, like Fraschilla, were out. Execution and
efficiency were in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just really kicked our butts,'' Calhoun said, explaining
how he got to a time out, 17 minutes 9 seconds remaining, the
Garden rocking for a college game as it hasn't since, well, last
week against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the stoppage, Calhoun said almost nothing, which is
difficult for a man who talks as if he's getting paid by the word.
``Think what you're doing,'' he said, finally, raising the
likelihood of UConn's first defeat, the loss of its top ranking
and, worse, the loss of unchallenged supremacy in its own league.
He fumed for the remainder of the long television time out, waiting
for his players to inhale his wrath. Richard Hamilton soon spoke
up. Then Khalid El-Amin. Then the Huskies charged out with a
renewed passion, with a 10-0 run, with the apparent resolve of the
more experienced team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all stems from Coach Calhoun; we feed off him,'' said
Voskuhl, who wound up scoring two significant baskets as the
Huskies made their final, frantic, up-tempo push, rallying from a
4-point deficit with an 11-0 run and a lead of 72-65.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found an old friend, and that is our defense,'' Calhoun
said, launching into one of his high-speed monologues. Jarvis, in
contrast, later sat with his hands clasped, placidly explaining how
St. John's had failed to execute in the closing minutes, as it had
in other close calls in the Garden against Stanford, Purdue and
Duke. ``We're just not there yet,'' he said. ``We've been in a
position to beat every one of them. It's about being the last team
to make the last run.''
</P>
<P>
   Around Jarvis sat four of his sad-eyed players, including
Artest, who had tried to take control of the game against the
defense of Kevin Freeman, but couldn't, and Barkley, whose judgment
with the ball was uncharacteristically freshman-like as the game
slipped away. His forced jumper, with St. John's down by 4 inside
of 25 seconds, was the Storm's last chance, and it came in a crowd
and with Artest calling for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In one more unwitting testimonial to Calhoun's motivational
skills, Voshkul got the rebound, forcing St. John's to foul.
Artest, never shy about upbraiding a teammate in the heat of a
game, complained to Barkley, who told him, in no uncertain terms,
to mind his own business.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis' cool, calming effect was obviously, painfully, all
gone. The sun was down, the day was lost. St. John's, in the end
playing Jim Calhoun's game, was sucked into the teeth of an
emotional storm. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
