<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-HOUSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKE BOSTON, HOUSTON HAS ACT TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Bob McNair spent an interesting few days with Bob Kraft
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is the owner who couldn't find a home for his football
team in his hometown. McNair is the owner of a home for a football
team in his hometown who can't find a team to occupy it. Only in as
dysfunctional a place as the National Football League under Paul
Tagliabue could such a situation exist.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday and Thursday, McNair tried to convince Kraft and
the rest of the league's Finance Committee that Houston, the
nation's fourth-largest city, deserves the NFL's 32d franchise, an
expansion team likely to be awarded at the owners' meetings in
March.
</P>
<P>
   All McNair had to offer is deep pockets to pay the league's
exorbitant franchise fee, no rivals in his town trying to fight him
over ownership, and a voter-approved, signed, sealed, and delivered
$310 million stadium plan that guarantees the NFL the world's first
retractable-roofed, natural grass, 69,250-seat football facility
ready for occupancy in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While Kraft couldn't squeeze Massachusetts Speaker of the House
Tom Finneran for more than $57 million to build some off-ramps in
Foxborough, prompting Kraft to move the Patriots to Hartford,
McNair cobbled together a constituency that included Harris County
politicians, the Houston Sports Authority, the Metropolitan Transit
Authority, the Houston Livestock Show &AMP; Rodeo Association, the
mayor, the city council, and the city's voters; and he got them all
to agree to provide 74 percent of the financing ($230 million) for
the stadium that will adjoin the Astrodome and turn the entire area
into the world's largest trade-show facility.
</P>
<P>
   While McNair was working on his plan to return an NFL team to a
city the league abandoned in 1994, Kraft couldn't find two nickels
to rub together to keep his team in Massachusetts _ a team that was
in the Super Bowl just three years ago. Not surprisingly, Bob
McNair finds this surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some interesting conversations because of what he's
gone through,'' McNair said Thursday. ``He's had some awful
problems up there that I sure can't understand. But we've been
fortunate to have a united front in Houston. He asked me about how
I managed to accomplish that, because it's clear to everyone that
you need to develop public support.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Oilers left, it was a wakeup call for Houston. Most
people just thought these were only threats. They thought the team
would never leave. After that happened, the environment was
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense when Bud (Adams) owned the Oilers that we
didn't need to do anything to help them with a stadium. Now the
attitude is very different. Houston is my hometown, and I'm a
homer. I pull for anything that's Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen in Baltimore and St. Louis how the people started to
develop an inferiority complex about their city when they lost
their franchises. It happened in Houston. We have a vibrant economy
and a great city, but I'd travel around the world on business and
people would ask me, `What's wrong with Houston? Why'd you lose
your football team?' I got tired of having to defend Houston
instead of promoting it, so I got involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with what he has put togther, McNair is not a lock to
win league approval for a franchise. Also in the running are two
groups from Los Angeles, although neither has solid stadium
financing, voter approval, or the political landscape to get a
stadium built.
</P>
<P>
   One group, which has only about $20 million in government
backing, hopes to put a team back into a refurbished LA Coliseum
that would cost nearly $342 million. The other, led by former
Hollywood mogul Michael Ovitz, is pushing for a $350 million
stadium in Carson, Calif., but has about as much governmental
support as Kraft had in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the NFL and many owners continue to privately favor
Los Angeles, whispering that they do not want an entire generation
in the second-largest market in the country to go without the NFL.
That might sound logical to a league that has no team in LA or
Houston but approved franchises in Nashville, Jacksonville, and
Charlotte, but it makes little sense when the nation's
fourth-largest city appears eager and organized to embrace the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is the 11th-largest TV market in the country; LA is
second. Yet in 1994, the last year both cities had NFL teams,
Houston ranked ninth in NFL TV ratings, LA 15th.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, a year after the Oilers left for Tennessee, Houston's
NFL television ratings were still higher than 25 percent of the
cities with teams; and last year, its Super Bowl viewership was
higher than any city without an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting is that two NFL franchises, the Rams and the
Raiders, left Southern California because of lack of fan support,
while McNair argues that the Oilers left because of a lack of
stadium support. He seems to have numbers to back that up. In the
five years before their moves, Houston averaged 55,436 fans per
game in the outdated Astrodome, the Raiders were drawing an average
of 53,318 to the Coliseum, and the Rams were down to an average of
48,572 in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league knows they need to be in Houston and in Los
Angeles,'' McNair said. ``What they're in a quandary about is how
to do it. If the 32d franchise goes to Houston, will that close out
Los Angeles? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five or six teams that could move there without
paying the huge franchise fee for an expansion team, and that would
allow them more money to go toward solving the stadium problem out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, they have two groups vying for an expansion team
in Los Angeles and neither has enough public support. Is that a
reflection of the true level of support for bringing NFL football
to LA or is it a measure of their passion for football? I don't
know, but what's obvious to me is that we have the best plan, the
financing, and the public support. If Houston is awarded the next
franchise, we're ready to start building the stadium. The NFL knows
that's not the case in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   As one NFL owner put it last week, ``How we've run things lately
wouldn't be a case model for long-term planning, would it? I don't
think they'll be studying the franchise moves we've made at the
Harvard Business School.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL ends up with a franchise in troubled Los Angeles
while shutting out Houston and Bob McNair, it will be more evidence
that Paul Tagliabue knows how to make money but has no idea how to
run a football league.
</P>
<P>
   Tip of the cap
</P>
<P>
   NFL Players Association executive director Gene Upshaw said last
week the salary cap for 1999-2000 will increase about $5 million,
to $57.5 million per team . . . McNair once explored buying the
Miami Dolphins when Joe Robbie was looking to sell and has long
been involved in horse racing. His best horse was Touch Gold, who
won the Belmont a few years back . . . New Cleveland Browns coach
Chris Palmer, who has been going over the list of available
veterans in the upcoming draft, says he has found few people who
can help and a lot who are overpriced. There are also more than a
few players on the list who have already decided to retire. Green
Bay, for example, has Reggie White and Robert Brooks on its list.
White has already announced his retirement, and word is Brooks's
bad back may force him to give up the game . . . If you're still
wondering what happened with Dave McGinnis and the Chicago Bears'
head coaching job, here's the story of how it blew up in his face
from someone on the inside of the dealings. After interviewing with
Bears owner Michael McCaskey, McGinnis was told there would be
another meeting the following day. Driving out to the Bears complex
in Lake Forest, Ill., the next morning, McGinnis heard a radio
report that said he had been hired and a press conference would be
held that afternoon. That was news to him since he had not yet even
brought his agent into the negotiations. Enraged, he went to Bears
front office man Mark Hatley with heated words. He came out
insulted by an offer for a four-year deal worth $750,000, $800,000,
$850,000, and $900,000, plus $200,000 for a television show (the
going TV rate is $1 million a season, even for head coaches with no
experience). Worse, only the first two years were guaranteed, with
a buyout option for the team after that. McGinnis stormed out and
the deal collapsed. A day later, Dick Jauron was named the Bears
coach . . . If the Patriots intend to get into the free agency
sweepstakes for either 49er wide receivers Terrell Owens and J.J.
Stokes or Arizona's Rob Moore, they will be fighting more than the
likelihood that Owens and Moore could end up being named transition
or franchise players next month. Division rival Miami also is
interested. Coach Jimmy Johnson badly wants another target for Dan
Marino and fears Yatil Green may not be the deep threat he hoped
for after back-to-back season-ending knee injuries . . . The
Raiders have just over a week to decide whether to pay quarterback
Jeff George a $5 million bonus to buy back three more years on a
contract George was able to void at the end of this season, his
second in Oakland. Word out of Oakland is that owner Al Davis is
not convinced George is the man to build his team around, but head
coach Jon Gruden is pushing Davis to write the check . . . Unhappy
Vikings quarterback Brad Johnson has told his agent to ask
Minnesota to trade him because he does not want to back up Randall
Cunningham again next season. Minnesota is unlikely to comply with
that request, just as Buffalo has no intention of trading Rob
Johnson, regardless of whether he beats out Doug Flutie next
summer, because of the salary-cap hit . . . When the free agency
period begins in two weeks, Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin will be
looking to get into the market for top defensive players such as
Chiefs cornerback Dale Carter, Packers tackle Santana Dotson, and a
familiar face, Lions linebacker Stephen Boyd, whom Coughlin coached
at Boston College. . . . Apparently there are two sides to a
bizarre story out of New York last week. Dolphins linebacker Zach
Thomas claimed he was mugged near the Port Authority bus terminal
at 3:30 a.m. and had his wallet stolen. But a Port Authority
spokesman claims two of its police officers found Thomas
intoxicated and unable to remember whether he was assaulted, fell,
or was in a fight. Stay tuned . . . This was a week of revelations
and soul-searching at the Super Bowl. One day Cornelius Bennett is
talking about becoming a born-again Christian not long after he was
charged with sexual misconduct, then Atlanta receiver Terence
Mathis told a packed room of reporters how he almost ruined his
life with alcohol. Denver offensive line coach Alex Gibbs, who will
never be accused of being a touchy-feely kind of guy, then claimed
he nearly quit the team because he became depressed after learning
that All-Pro tackle Gary Zimmerman was retiring last spring. ``I
was so depressed that I didn't want to go to camp,'' said Gibbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
