</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS ON SOLID GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Eventually, somebody is going to run the football in
Sunday's 33d Super Bowl. Whoever does is going to win. Don't bet
against the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons had not upset the Vikings two weeks ago to win
the NFC Championship, Minnesota would be favored to beat the
defending Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos. Of that you can be
sure.
</P>
<P>
   So why shouldn't the team that beat the team that would have
been favored to beat the defending champions beat the defending
champions?
</P>
<P>
   The gambling constituency has made the Broncos a 7 1/2-point
favorite, but it is difficult to fathom why. Certainly Denver has
the game's leading running back in Terrell Davis and an offensive
line in front of him that is as nimble and adept at holding without
being penalized as any in the league. Together they have created
one of the more powerful forces in the football universe _ a
crushing running game that took Davis to 2,008 yards this season
and his team back to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday Davis is faced with a defense that was the
second-stingiest in the NFL against the run, a quick and agile
group that likes to penetrate into the backfield and hold its
ground, cutting off the cutback lanes runners like Davis search
for, and rallying to the ball with alarming swiftness.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have allowed only one runner to gain 100 yards since
they embarked on what is now a 22-4 streak, and that was on a day
when defensive tackle Travis Hall was out of the lineup and three
other starters left with injuries during the game.
</P>
<P>
   In their only shot at Davis, they limited him to 79 yards last
year in a one-touchdown loss, so they have no reason to look upon
controlling him in this game as an Olympian task. Even if they do
it, of course, the Falcons still have to cope with Shannon Sharpe,
Rod Smith, Ed McCaffrey, and future Hall of Fame quarterback John
Elway, but the fact is putting the ball in Elway's hands these days
is the best way to beat the Broncos because at 38 he is not the
force he once was.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if the game comes down to quarterbacks, Atlanta has the
superior one in Chris Chandler, although who knows if he will come
through in the biggest game of his life?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the key for each team will be containing the other's
running game, because that is what both have used to get this far.
Atlanta has the edge there, it would seem. Denver is strong on
defense, but the Falcons allowed just 75 yards rushing per game
this season, while controlling the clock better than any team in
football with a battering ram of a back named Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings were the highest-scoring team in NFL history this
season but they scored only 7 points in the final 2 1/2 quarters
against the Falcons because Anderson ran just enough to allow
Atlanta to control the clock. Then the Falcons were able to beat
Minnesota's secondary with their own set of explosive wide
receivers, Tony Martin and Terance Mathis. Those two allowed the
Falcons to quietly lead the NFL in yards per pass attempt, and they
were the second-most productive set of receivers in the game,
trailing only Minnesota's Randy Moss and Cris Carter in yardage
while finishing fourth as a duo in touchdown catches.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's strong point these days is running, not passing, and
Atlanta's strong point is stopping the run while pounding the ball
itself. Thus the critical stats may be these: The Broncos are 33-4
when Davis rushes for 100 yards or more, 6-0 in playoff games. The
Falcons are 20-2 when Anderson rushes 20 times or more, including
15-0 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Good as Davis is, and he's the best in the league, it's easier
to rush 20 times than it is to rush for 100 yards, so the edge,
slight though it may be, would seem to be with the Falcons' defense
not the Broncos' offense.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons can contain Davis and prevent him from making the
sharp cutbacks into an open defensive backfield, Atlanta can win as
long as Anderson is free to slam away enough to keep the clock _
and his offense _ moving.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is a back who wears defenses down, pounding, pounding,
pounding with his 234 pounds until they begin to lose their
resolve. The proof is that in first halves this season, he has
rushed for 713 yards and an average of 3.75 yards a carry, but in
second halves he has 1,133 yards, averaging 5.15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   So expect a game of clock management in which the Falcons will
try to control the ball for long stretches (which they did better
than any other team, averaging more than 33 minutes of offense a
game) and keep Davis on the sideline, where he can do no damage.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say Elway isn't capable of winning a game for the
Broncos, but the fact is in this game the Falcons have the better
quarterback and at least as good a defense, so the difference will
be which running game comes through.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if it's the one that belongs to Atlanta's
Dirty Birds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
