u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HALLOFFAME-TAYLOR     01-30 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALLOFFAME-TAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL TAYLOR REACHES HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With voters staying within the rules, Lawrence Taylor
rolled into the Pro Football Hall of Fame on his first try
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the controversial linebacker of the New York Giants,
created the most interest ever in a Hall of Fame vote when his
off-field life brought into question his fitness to be enshrined in
Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was one of five new members elected Saturday. He was
joined by Eric Dickerson, one of the greatest running backs of all
time; tight end Ozzie Newsome of the Cleveland Browns, now general
manager of the Baltimore Ravens; senior candidate Billy Shaw of the
Buffalo Bills, who played most of his career in the old American
Football League; and Tom Mack, an 11-time Pro Bowl guard for the
Los Angeles Rams who made it in his final year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Taylor became too much of the story; his brushes
with the law, which include two arrests on drug charges, led to a
debate about whether he should be inducted. The controversy
detracted from the other four players, who all had distinguished
careers.
</P>
<P>
   In statement handed to media, Taylor said he was ``humbled'' by
his election.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, who played with four teams but mostly the Rams and
Colts, called this the biggest thrill of his life. ``I never made
it to the Super Bowl, so this is my Super Bowl,'' said the man who
holds the single-season rushing record of 2,105 yards, set in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Players must be named on 80 percent of ballots cast to be
elected. With all 36 voters present, 29 were needed. There was no
announcement on the final tally.
</P>
<P>
   Boston native Howie Long made an impressive showing on his first
chance, finishing in the top seven. He and wide receiver Lynn Swann
of the Pittsburgh Steelers came up just short in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Long, the great defensive lineman of the Raiders, and Swann will
automatically be seeded into the final 15 next year, and will be
favorites for election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
