<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5420 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-BEANPOT-ADVANCE-B     01-30 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-BEANPOT-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL EVENT FEELS LIKE THE BIG TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The feeling was one of finality, arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grew up thinking, `That's the place to play _ the Garden,
in the Beanpot,' '' recalled Keith Tkachuk, the former Boston
University winger who these days scores his goals _ and lots of
them _ as the NHL's premier power forward with the Phoenix Coyotes.
``I just remember it was such a thrill to step on that ice. It was
sick. Just to skate over that Bruins `B' symbol and know, finally,
you're there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beanpot, which opens its 47th chapter Monday night on
Causeway Street, comes to center stage each February for what is
arguably the nation's biggest college hockey tournament. For many
players, it also serves as the ultimate proving ground, two nights
to show NHL scouts, personnel directors, even general managers that
they're getting closer to the day when they might be able to cull a
living out of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, Boston College, Northeastern, and BU, the four Beanpot
brothers, have sent upwards of 100 players on to the NHL. The
Beanpot is by no means a sure road to The Show, but a good couple
of nights on Causeway, where the Garden has segued to the
FleetCenter, can be the steppingstone to something big.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just what the scouts are looking for,'' said NU coach
Bruce Crowder, the former Bruin who played his college hockey at
the University of New Hampshire. ``They get to see these kids under
pressure, here in a big barn with 16,000, 17,000 people watching.
Are they watching the kid who can score a big goal, win a game, or
a kid who gets the seventh or eighth goal in a blowout _ goals that
don't mean anything? This is the place to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   The '91 Beanpot final, recalled BU coach Jack Parker, was
exactly that kind of showcase for former Terrier Tony Amonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a spectacular show,'' recalled Parker.
</P>
<P>
   The season began with Amonte, in his sophomore year, setting his
aim on 30 goals. As a freshman out of Thayer Academy, where he was
Jeremy Roenick's linemate, he banged in 25 with the Terriers. But
by January the Hingham sharpshooter had scored only nine times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the Beanpot comes, the final, and he gets knocked cold by
a BC defenseman,'' recalled Parker, who will be coaching his 26th
Beanpot these next two Mondays. ``His helmet went flying and he had
to be helped off the ice. It was a big hit. But he came back in the
third period and got a hat trick, and that started it for him _ he
went on a tear and got his 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Amonte was in the Rangers' training camp the following
September, barely six months later, and scored 35 goals in his
rookie season with the Blueshirts.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of success stories make the Beanpot, at the very
least, a convenient, tantalizing recruiting tool for all four
schools. You want to make it to The Show, kid? Look at Tkachuk and
Amonte. Or Don Sweeney and Ted Donato at Harvard. Chris Nilan at
Northeastern. Joey Mullen, Brian Leetch, and Steve Heinze at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' said Parker, ``it used to be an even
better recruiting tool. Recruits used to decide in April, May, and
June, and you'd have the Beanpot to entice them. Now they make up
their minds before the season begins.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case for Craig Adams, Harvard's senior captain
from Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in Western Canada,'' said Adams, ``I'd never heard
of the Beanpot. I'd given it little or no thought prior to that
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The night came during Adams's February '95 visit to Harvard. The
Crimson were in the Beanpot and Adams was in the Garden stands,
wondering whether someday he would be part of the dazzling tableau
that was playing out in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Harvard admissions officer found me in the stands,''
recalled Adams, ``and handed me my letter of acceptance.''
Finality. Arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his 11th season with the Bruins, Sweeney played in four
Beanpots ('85-88) with the Crimson. More than 700 games into his
NHL career, he still remembers the excitement of being in the
Garden and skating for the first time on an NHL rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about it, when you're there, there's no knowing if
you'll ever step on NHL ice again,'' he said. ``I was drafted
(166th overall in '84), but you don't know if you're ever going to
make it. No one ever knows. You've got to savor it. And to be 18
years old, standing there in the Garden, I think that would have a
dramatic impact on anybody. Seeing those banners in the rafters,
that's when it really sets in.''
</P>
<P>
   Updated traditions
</P>
<P>
   The first Beanpot opened the day after Christmas 1952 as the New
England Invitational Hockey Tournament at Boston Arena (now
Matthews Arena at Northeastern). It moved to the Garden in January
'54, where first-night attendance was only 711.
</P>
<P>
   Walter A. Brown, then the Garden president, soon charged Tony
Nota, the man in charge of the Garden's mail room, with the duty of
finding an appropriate trophy. The affable Nota, who also acted as
official timer for Bruins and Celtics games, settled on the
silver-plated pot that stands as the crowning cup of Boston
collegiate supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   For some 30 years, the tournament winner carried the Beanpot
back to campus, the victors proudly parading it through the halls
of academia. Lore has it that one of those tours led it to a
Harvard frat party, where it was unceremoniously treated as an
ashtray. Nowadays, it never leaves Causeway Street, where it
remains on permanent display under the aegis of the Sports Museum
of New England on the Fleet's fifth floor. The winners parade it
around the ice and promptly hand it back over for safe keeping.
Each school keeps a Beanpot plaque on campus, updating with
commemorative tags when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The trophy is the tournament tangible. The tournament itself is
so much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's about people,'' said Jack Grinold, NU's venerable
director of sports information, the Beanpot's longtime secretary.
``It's about the players, the coaches, even the referees _ all the
marvelous people who have worked and skated through the tournament,
through all the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's the atmosphere. You're in the Garden (now the Fleet),
where the mood of the place usually is all the Bruins fans against
those six other guys on the ice. But you go to the Beanpot, and you
can quarter the building, all four schools represented equally in
the course of a night. The bands are playing, the place is jumping
. . . just marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Fleet held its first Beanpot in '96, the bands weren't
nearly as much of the tournament's fabric as they were during the
Garden years. They took their customary places down low, near the
boards, but somehow their notes were muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a big space,'' noted Grinold. ``Not the same as skating
in the old closet.''
</P>
<P>
   The bands subsequently have been moved to the balconies, where
they can more openly exchange rhythmic blasts and Bronx cheers.
Some of the old hop is returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need is a BC-BU final,'' said Sweeney. ``It has to be
those two schools, and it also has to be a great game. Then it will
be equally as good in the new building as it was in the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, the Bruins winger, played in three Beanpots ('89-91)
with BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and lost every one of 'em,'' he said. ``But it was still
great. Everyone builds it up so much and, I don't know, maybe
that's why we didn't do so well. Harry Sinden (Bruins
president/general manager) is up there in his box, the scouts are
watching, and you have this feeling, `Hey, yeah, I'll show them
that I can play in this rink.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
