</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-TERRELLDAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS MAKES STRONG CASE FOR TITLE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Terrell Davis has a sign in his hotel room: ``Take your
medication.'' Terrell Davis will have a sign this Sunday on his
locker in Pro Player Stadium: ``Take your medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis will have friend after friend, teammate after
teammate, come by his locker this Sunday and remind him to take his
medication for migraine headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone on the team is going to be reminding him,'' said
Denver running back Vaughn Hebron. ``Believe me, there's no way
Terrell's going to forget this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos may have one of the more unusual game plans
of any Super Bowl team, based as it is on one premise far removed
from X's and O's: ``Terrell Davis first takes his medicine.'' Then,
and only then, can the schemes and strategems and football
chess-playing be implemented for Davis to run to his left _
seemingly always to his left _ and chew up the Atlanta Falcons'
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in charge of it this time,'' said Davis. ``I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Davis forgot to take his medication before last
year's Super Bowl in San Diego between the Broncos and Green Bay.
Like so many players before him, players who thought they might be
immune from the crushing pressure of a Super Bowl, Davis lost focus
in the hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not until after warmups and only 10 minutes before kickoff did
Davis remember the necessity for his playing well: taking
medication for the migraines that had bedeviled him since he was a
boy. For the medication to be effective, it must be taken an hour
or more before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the most famous headache in football history.
Davis was able to play in the first quarter against Green Bay and
was able to score a TD. But then he experienced the visual aura
that he knew all too well was the precursor of a migraine, and
terror overcame him on the sideline. He was forced to sit out the
second quarter as he prayed that a drug newly prescribed for him,
DHE, would be able to divert the migraine.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Davis returned in the second half and pulverized the
Packers as only he can, as only the best back in football running
behind football's best offensive line can.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has had only one migraine episode since then _ during
practice three months ago _ and he is confident that his nemesis is
under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a preventive medication I'm taking,'' he said.
``Anytime I work out or practice I take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Judy Lane, a Colorado neurologist and a world authority on
headaches _ not to mention a rabid Broncos fan _ was able to
instill confidence in Davis that his migraines could be diverted by
diagnosing them as ``exertion-induced.'' As long as Davis took the
medication before beginning his physical activity, the migraines _
and not Davis _ would be sidelined. So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Strong combination
</P>
<P>
   Davis doesn't seem to be fast and doesn't seem to be elusive,
but his low center of gravity, his ability to spot holes and lanes
in which to cut back against the grain, and his power all make him
the most effective back in the league. Add the blocking of the line
in front of him and the result is PowerBall; not a lottery, but a
guarantee of football riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Terrell is an unbelievable back,'' said Rich Brooks,
the defensive coordinator of the Falcons. ``He's a combination of
Jim Brown and Barry Sanders because he can both break tackles and
take it downhill. The thing about Terell, he's very decisive. Above
all, you don't want him to get into the secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Where, perceptions to the contrary, Davis is fast enough to run
away from defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that fast,'' countered Davis. ``In high school they
had me at linebacker and at fullback.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said it is not necessarily physical skills but psychology
that is behind his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, the one thing that scares me the most is failing,
especially at this level,'' he said. ``I think, `Someday, it's not
going to be there. I'm not going to be on top and I'm going to have
to deal with that.' But while I'm here, and while I'm having
success, I'm trying to do everything possible to stay on this
level. Whatever that means, or whatever I have to do, I'm doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When his career is done, said Davis, he wants to be known as one
of football's all-time great backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals are long-term rather than short-term,'' he said.
``I've always said that when I leave the game, I want to leave my
signature on it. By thinking like that, I can come back next year
and be the best I can be. That's just the way I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Key to the game
</P>
<P>
   There are no long-term goals Sunday. It will be most difficult
for the Broncos to win if Davis does not run well. It will be most
difficult for Atlanta to win if Davis is not contained. The game,
simply put, will be decided by whether Davis or the Atlanta defense
wins this battle.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be easy for Davis. The Falcons have one of the NFL's
best defenses against the run and, as Davis himself recognized, the
fact that linebackers Jessie Tuggle and Cornelius Bennett are so
experienced means he will not see much overpursuit that would allow
him to make his trademark cutback.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, the Falcons' defense seems to have energy
similar to Davis's, energy that usually allows him to run as well
in the fourth quarter as in the first quarter, if not better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of speed over there on that defense,'' said
Davis. ``They seem to have energy throughout the game, which is
kind of difficult to play against. They're not overly big players
over there, but they're very quick and fast, and very disciplined.
It's going to be a big challenge for us _ but I welcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   In studying film of the Atlanta defense, said Davis, he sees a
disciplined unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most times when you see a defense, you hope they get out of
their lanes,'' he said. ``They have assignments to do, obviously,
but when 'backers sometimes get anxious, they run out of their
lanes and it gives me an opportunity to cut back. Usually, if they
keep hitting the front side hard enough, they'll overpursue and you
can cut back on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the key to much of Denver's running success. The
trademark Denver play is for Davis to take a toss from quarterback
John Elway, head left and, with that superb vision of his, spot a
running lane formed either because of crisp blocking or
overpursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, with Atlanta, with Tuggle and Bennett, they seem to be
very patient with what they do,'' explained Davis. ``It's kind of
like they play gap control very well and it's the type of team I
hate to see. I like to see people more undisciplined than that.''
</P>
<P>
   On both sides of the ball, discipline. Davis, the most
disciplined of runners, and the Falcons with a disciplined defense.
It will be a matchup to savor.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, unlike Super Bowl XXXII, Terrell Davis should be
on the field for four quarters. He will take his medication, and
any headaches in Pro Player Stadium will be football headaches, the
pain felt by the loser of the Terrell Davis-Atlanta defense war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
