<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-30 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE TRADED DIAMONDS FOR A SUPER BOWL RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Guaranteed to happen sometime in Super Bowl XXXIII:
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will kick off. No. 86 will come flying downfield and
make the tackle. ``That was Ed Smith,'' Pat Summerall will say. And
somewhere in America a baseball player will come leaping off the
couch and shriek, ``Hey, I wonder if it's that Ed Smith?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' says Ed Smith, ``many of my teammates don't
know. They'll come up to me and say, `You used to play baseball?' I
get phone calls and messages all the time. They'll see me play on
TV and call. They'll say, `Is this the same Ed Smith I knew playing
in such-and-such?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Smith may have the freshest 29-year-old body in the NFL.
That's what happens when you skip college entirely to play nine
years of professional baseball. He doesn't much look like any third
baseman I've ever known, but he was indeed a third base prospect in
the White Sox, Cubs, and Indians organizations before quitting in
anger and frustration when, despite hitting .323 at the time, he
was demoted from Triple A to Double A to make way for what were
referred to as Cleveland's ``prospects'' in the summer of '96.
</P>
<P>
   And here he is, the most improbable participant imaginable in
the Super Bowl. Ed Smith has made himself into a valued member of
the Falcons' special teams. He had six solo tackles against the
Vikings two weeks ago, and in his profession that is a very good
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed is so athletically talented,'' says Atlanta special teams
coach Joe DeCamillis. ``And he keeps getting better, practice by
practice, and not just game to game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have written a better script for me,'' says
Smith. ``I'm still pinching myself to make sure it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   The path to Pro Player Stadium began when the 1987 Pemberton
(N.J.) High School graduate turned down a combination
football/baseball offer from North Carolina to sign with the White
Sox. When his baseball career stalled, he turned to his younger
brother Irv, the Notre Dame star who currently plays tight end for
the 49ers. Irv put him in touch with the right people, and the next
thing Ed knew he was playing for former Boston College great Ernie
Stautner with the Frankfurt Galaxy, attracting some attention with
a one-handed grab that was the ``Play of the Week'' on the ``George
Michael Sports Machine'' program.
</P>
<P>
   He spent time in both the Rams and Redskins organizations before
catching on with the Falcons in 1997. He is listed as a tight end,
but, for now, his calling is with the various special teams. And he
will tell you that not even the hottest grounder to third compares
with the things that go on when someone kicks off a football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like running through a minefield, or like running down
the middle of a street with someone shooting at you,'' he declares.
``Your head is on a swivel.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Smith brings an uncommon degree of latent athleticism to the
task. It is very difficult to imagine this huge man playing third
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I am very proud of manning the hot corner all
those years,'' he says. ``I made all the plays, diving plays and
everything else. Every year I'd come to camp and they'd talk about
putting me at first, but I'd always wind up at third.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he was a mere shrimp when he played baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played at 225, and never more than 230, when I played
baseball,'' says the 6-foot-4-inch Smith. ``Now I'm playing at
258.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine trying to turn yourself into a professional football
player when the last time you had put on a uniform was to perform
with a small New Jersey high school nine years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I put on the uniform it felt like a suit of
armor,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   And technique, what technique? He had never needed much in the
way of technique while terrorizing Pemberton's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Equally challenging was the adjustment he needed to make above
the neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big difference between a day-in, day-out sport and
one you play once a week,'' he reports. ``I've had those 5-for-50s
and those times you can't pick up a ground ball. Then you get on a
bus and you can't get it out of your mind. In baseball, you need to
stay calm, no matter what happens. In football, you find that
aggression is good. It's OK to be mean. That's what I like about
football. There is nothing like the excitement and adrenaline rush
I get on the day of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There isn't anything like the wear and tear of football, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being in the Marines,'' he says. ``There are a lot
of days you just don't want to do it. When I get out of bed some
days, you can hear the snap, crackle, and pop in my body. I don't
want to insult anybody in baseball, but there are plenty of times
you play the game, stay up all night, and then play another game.
In football, you need your rest. And people don't think about the
mental fatigue of needing to study a new game plan every week.''
</P>
<P>
   His feelings about baseball are guarded. He was, in fact, a
fallout victim of the baseball strike, having refused repeated
requests to become a replacement player and then, in the end,
winding up unappreciated by both parties. He doesn't follow teams;
he follows friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Phillies are on, I will wait to see Doug Glanville
bat,'' he says. ``Then I'll flip around until he comes up again.
But I don't watch games.''
</P>
<P>
   His thoughts now are concentrated exclusively on football, and,
for Ed Smith, Sunday's game has an extra meaning, over and above
the fact that it is the Super Bowl. He has spent many a day
watching little brother Irv play at Notre Dame and elsewhere. He
has even played against his brother five times professionally. But
Sunday will be the first time that his brother will be in the
stands watching him play professional football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can't describe how happy I am about that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Smith had the strangest resume of anyone in this game, but
there is no question he belongs. He says he was officially anointed
at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Daniel, our tight end coach, came up to me one day and
said, `You used to be a baseball player trying to play football,'
'' Smith says. `` `Now you're a football player who used to play
baseball.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Keep your eye on No. 86. I still can't picture him playing third
base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
