<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-EASTPREVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR NO-BULL EVALUATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, we know there's at least some suspense this year. Pat
Riley's observation that everyone would be playing for second as
long as Michael Jordan was around was eerily prophetic. Now Michael
is gone, his team has disassembled, and as many as six clubs in the
Eastern Conference probably think they have a legitimate shot to
make the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana starts out as the favorite, having re-signed key guys
and brought in Sam Perkins for one more paycheck, er, opportunity.
But New York, Miami, New Jersey, Atlanta, and a dark horse or two
could surface. By June, one team will have forgotten the
back-to-back-to-backers.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are ranked according to their predicted order of
finish, which, in years past, has been wholly imprecise. (The West
preview will run Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 55-27, first place. Lost in first round of
playoffs to New York.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Clarence Weatherspoon, Terry Porter, Mark
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Brent Barry, Latrell Sprewell, Eric Murdock.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``The Old Ways.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Riley played one too many hands of poker last
year. He got nothing for Ike Austin (Barry left without
compensation) and missed out on the Sprewell fire sale. But none of
the losses was really critical _ Barry wasn't even on the playoff
roster _ and his core group remains intact for yet another
thugfest. There's also the lingering question of Voshon Lenard's
stress fracture and _ yikes _ the admission by el presidente that
he could stomach reprobate Dennis Rodman under certain conditions.
(What do you think the over/under would be on the first time Alonzo
Mourning clocked Rodman in practice?) Still, with Zo, Tim Hardaway,
Jamal Mashburn, and P.J. Brown, this is as good as it gets in an
otherwise even but mediocre division.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 43-39, tiedfor second. Lost in second round to
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Latrell Sprewell, Marcus Camby, Dennis
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Charles Oakley, John Starks, Chris Mills, Buck
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Back 2 Good.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: This is, in many ways, a watershed season for the
Knicks. They've added Sprewell, maybe the best off-guard in the
game. But Mr. Warmth's presence won't help as much if Patrick
Ewing's knee, wrist, or karma is (still) bothersome. And who is
going to do the dirty work now that Oakley is in Toronto? The
Knicks weren't at it for a week before they were on Camby for his
Abdelnaby-ish work habits, and coach Jeff Van Gundy already is
worried about Ewing, not to mention Phil Jackson. The Knicks wisely
re-signed Chris Dudley, who should see plenty of action, especially
if the enigmatic Camby seems determined to become Elden Campbell
East.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 43-39, tied for second. Lost in first round to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Jim McIlvaine, Eric Murdock.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Sherman Douglas, Michael Cage.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``The Other Man's Grass Is Always Greener.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Do we believe the early stories out of camp that
Coach Cal is a kindler, gentler soul? He should be. The new owners
got Jayson Williams re-signed, McIlvaine and Rony Seikaly form an
interesting backup tandem, and there's talent at every position.
The only downers are the injuries to Kerry Kittles and Seikaly,
each of whom may miss a month or more. They were in the hunt last
year until injuries decimated them. They should be in it this year,
too, unless the ever-sensitive Cal implodes or the injury bug
strikes again.
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 41-41, fifth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Ike Austin, Michael Doleac, Matt Harpring.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Mark Price, Derek Harper.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Unable To Stay, Unable To Leave.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: We all know how far this team is going: as far as
Penny Hardaway takes it, or wants to take it, or is allowed to take
it. We also know that Chuck Daly may still be able to coach, but
that he's also back for the money, and that can be dicey if things
unravel again. (Remember the stories last year that the Prince of
Pessimism was through?) Hardaway not too long ago was one of the
best players in the game. But he has been invisible (and annoying
at times) the last two years _ coincidental, of course, with the
departure of Shaq. He's a free agent at the end of the season and
the Magic can't allow Hamlet Hardaway to control the agenda. Daly
may yearn for the days of Rodman, Salley, Mahorn, and Laimbeer if
he has another year like last year.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 36-46, sixth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Paul Pierce, Popeye Jones, Tony Battie.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Zan Tabak, Travis Knight, Tyus Edney, Michael
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``This Doesn't Have To Be Love.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: There is a wide range of possibilities here. If
Kenny Anderson gets hurt, we're talking cellar and another high
draft pick. If he stays healthy, we're talking possible playoffs.
The Celtics have young legs, which helps in a compacted season. But
young legs get tired, too, as we've seen already in camp. The
problems in the middle are not nearly as acute as last year in that
Battie can block shots, the workmanlike Jones can get rebounds and
keep-alives, and the mammoth Dwayne Schintzius can be an
intimidating presence who also will get his hands on the ball. This
team should again be fun to watch but not very much fun to play
against. They will score. Their problem will be stopping the other
guys.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 42-40, fourth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Mitch Richmond, Otis Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key loss: Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key undecided: Rod Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Substitute.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: This team has chaos written all over it. The
Wizards and arch-enemy David Falk are a scant $28 million apart
over Strickland, who merely was _ and is _ their best and most
valuable player. Chris Whitney just doesn't instill the same fear
(although he torched the Celtics last year in Game 82). Juwan
Howard may have overtaken Larry Johnson as the league's most
overrated player. Oh yes, and did we mention that the Celtics'
center spot looks omnipotent compared with that of Washington's?
Gheorge Muresan, at last check, was flirting with the Hornets, who
lost both their centers to free agency. But the really big guy
hasn't played in more than a year and is still not ready to go now.
Jahidi White, Terry Davis, and Thorpe are the by-committee
candidates at this writing. And what must the soon-to-be-free
Richmond be thinking as he sees Strickland jump through hoops? He
probably isn't thinking of hiring Falk.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 31-51, seventh. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Matt Geiger, Larry Hughes, George Lynch,
Harvey Grant, Nazr Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Joe Smith, Derrick Coleman, Brian Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``As Long As He Needs Me.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Larry Brown's record as talent procurer is a bit,
shall we say, mixed? He traded Keith Van Horn, essentially for Tim
Thomas and change. He signed Geiger and Theo Ratliff to deals
exceeding $50 million each. He passed by Paul Pierce to take Larry
Hughes in the draft, something that still might work for the 76ers.
For things to improve here, a lot of young guys have to make it
work. Thomas has to become a force at small forward and Hughes is
the shooting guard, or, at least, the other guard to Allen Iverson.
Brown did bring in some depth with Grant and Lynch, and Scott
Williams is still there to crack jokes because he can't play
anymore. Philly's fate ultimately will hinge on the talented but
still raw Iverson. Where's the rest of the scoring going to come
from? Is Geiger anything more than a backup elevated to starter
because of the dearth of centers and dilution of talent? Is Ratliff
the real deal? Too many questions, although Iverson, after all, has
a sneaker named The Answer. We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 58-24, second. Lost in conference finals to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key addition: Sam Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: None.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Closer To Fine.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: It's all here, ready and waiting, for the Pacers.
They have all their important people back and they know the drill.
So does Perkins, who has been a Western Conference mainstay and
understands what the postseason is all about. The Pacers aren't
used to being in the spotlight, however, and they are the
fashionable choice as the season begins. People are watching.
Expectations have never been higher. Indiana is one of a handful of
teams to have made it to a conference final but never the NBA
Finals. Everything is in place for that to end.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 50-32, fourth. Lost in first round to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Mark West, Anthony Johnson, still waiting
for a small forward (LaPhonso Ellis?), Roshown McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key loss: Christian Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key retention: Alan Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``I Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: This is still the best four-man team in the NBA,
even with the loss of Laettner. Henderson stepped up big-time last
year and now is being handsomely paid to do so this year and
beyond. He joins Dikembe Mutombo, Steve Smith, and Mookie Blaylock
in the starting four. They need a fifth, not to mention a sixth,
seventh, and eighth, too. The addition of someone like Ellis, who
is leaning toward Atlanta, would help immensely. There are some
other free agents out there (KJ, Jim Jackson) who theoretically
should be interested in joining a team that has a decent shot at
supplanting the Bulls. The one imponderable is why the Hawks seem
to have so much trouble getting those certain someones.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 47-35, fifth. Lost in first round to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key addition: Johnny Newman.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: none.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``My Heart Belongs To Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Well, Shawn Kemp doesn't belong in this category,
does he? Goodness knows what made him blow up during the lockout,
but he's going to have to lose it in a hurry. The Cavs were
arguably the surprise team of the league last year, getting a lot
of mileage out of four rookies and the newly arrived Kemp. They
have basically the same gang back this year _ their top nine
scorers, to be precise _ and that should mean more improvement. The
players know the league a little better, know each other a lot
better, and big man Zydrunas Ilgauskus is developing into a very
nice package in the middle. Much of the Cavs' success rests on the
ever-widening shoulders of Kemp. He led them in scoring and
rebounding last year, but his numbers were below what he had done
in Seattle. That may be a result of the Eastern Conference style as
much as anything, but he is still their most potent force.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 36-46, sixth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: George Karl, Robert Traylor, Donny Marshall,
Dell Curry, Vinny Del Negro.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key loss: Andrew Lang.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Which Way To The Top?''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Karl got himself a sweet deal here and now his
impressive record is on the line; the Bucks last made the playoffs
when Titanic was still afloat. Was Milwaukee underachieving last
year or is it just a good rotisserie team? Karl can't afford to
lose key personnel for extended periods, and that means Terrell
Brandon and Glen Robinson have to be healthy. Ray Allen is an
emerging star and we keep hearing that his name is on Chicago's
wish list for next season. Karl has a pretty full cupboard. Allen,
Brandon, Robinson, and Tyrone Hill are an excellent foursome. Karl
feuded with Ervin Johnson in Seattle, but Johnson is all he has in
the middle unless he goes small with Hill. Traylor should help
along with veteran Dell Curry and valuable reserve Michael Curry.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 37-45, sixth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Jud Buechler, Loy Vaught, Christian
Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Grant Long, Malik Sealy.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``I Hope, I Think, I Know.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: The best news to hit Detroit had to be Michael
Jordan's retirement. The Pistons almost never beat the Jordan
Bulls. But something is missing here. How can a team with this
roster win one more game than the Celtics? New coach Alvin Gentry
has the job basically because he's the anti-Collins and Grant Hill
likes him. How long will that last? He was 16-21 last year. The
Pistons can put together a nice starting five, have Jerry
Stackhouse, Buechler, Jerome Williams (and maybe Kevin Johnson) to
come off the bench, and should be a lock for the playoffs. Maybe
they will finally do it. But this team has not won a playoff series
since 1991. This might be a nice team to put some money on _ and
hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 51-31, third. Lost in second round to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Derrick Coleman, Chucky Brown, Ricky Davis,
Brad Miller, Master P.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Vlade Divac, Dell Curry, Matt Geiger.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``This Door Swings Both Ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments: It's too bad Charlotte didn't sign Olden Polynice and
Rodman. Then they'd have the four biggest knuckleheads in the
league. The Hornets have added the terminally underachieving
Coleman to an already iffy mix featuring the volcanic Anthony Mason
and have lost Glen Rice for a while with elbow surgery. Did someone
say implosion? Gone are both centers as well as Curry, who is not
what he used to be, but still was a career Hornet. Coach Dave
Cowens has to somehow preside over this wild kingdom, and it won't
be easy. Coleman says he's a changed man; how many times have we
heard that one? Maybe he is. He'd better be, for Charlotte's sake.
Without Rice, this team is going to have to get its work done
inside, and that's difficult without a reliable outside threat.
David Wesley has to step it up or Cowens could be in for a long
shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 16-66, eighth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Kevin Willis, Charles Oakley, Vince Carter,
Michael Stewart, Sean Marks.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Chauncey Billups, Oliver Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Frozen.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: It's hard to pick this team ahead of anyone, but
the dismantling of the Bulls makes that possible. The Raptors went
through 24 players last year, but now have what looks, on paper
anyway, to be a better team. Willis gives them an inside option,
although he has only one shot. Oakley, if he decides to play, can
add some toughness. Newcomer Vince Carter looks terrific and it's
up to Butch Carter to rehabilitate the rest of the team. He's got
some interesting names, from Doug Christie to Dee Brown to Tracy
McGrady. A modest upgrade may be all that's possible, however.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 62-20. Won NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Brent Barry, Mark Bryant, Corey Benjamin,
Andrew Lang, Tim Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Phil Jackson, Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen,
Dennis Rodman, Luc Longley, Steve Kerr, Jud Buechler. (Have I
forgotten anyone?)
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Nearer My God To Thee.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Can't wait to hear the introductions at the
United Center for the first home game. (``And now, from Oregon
State . . .'') Maybe the Bulls will surprise people and be a lot
better. That doesn't appear to be what they want, which means
they'll probably end up right here. Chicago is building for next
year, hoping to bag a free agent or two (Ray Allen, Vin Baker,
Penny Hardaway) as well as a high draft pick. Add those potentials
to Toni Kukoc and Barry and you have a nucleus at least. But, this
year, it's going to be downright ugly, and there could be more
changes before the season ends. How does a starting five of Bill
Wennington, Dickey Simpkins, Kukoc, Barry, and Ron Harper sound?
This could be the most overt tank job since the 1996-97 Celtics.
</P>
