<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DONNHANDICAP-CHARM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM ENDS UP OUT OF POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ A few minutes before Saturday's Donn
Handicap, trainer Bob Baffert was in the paddock waiting for his
entry, Silver Charm, to arrive and be saddled. Baffert was being
the usual Baffert _ relaxed and talkative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going for the Broncos,'' Baffert schmoozed. ``I
used to be for the underdog, but now that I've got the big horse,
I'm starting to like favorites. And when that guy on the Falcons
(Ray Buchanan) said Shannon Sharpe looked like Mr. Ed, that made it
for me. That was the deciding factor. I love Mr. Ed.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert stopped talking for an instant and looked around the
paddock. Business was at hand. A horse race was to be run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did the big gray go?'' Baffert asked.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, after Baffert's horse had been found and the Donn
Handicap had been run, the 21,325 fans at Gulfstream Park were
asking the same question: ``Where did the big gray go?''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, naively sent off as the 4-5 favorite by this
tourist-heavy crowd, ran a dull, plodding race, finishing a
well-beaten third behind Puerto Madero and Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time in 21 starts that Silver Charm
failed to finish first or second.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm had everything against him, starting on the far
outside in post position 12 on a track that favored inside speed,
and spotting his rivals at least 6 pounds and as much as 16. Silver
Charm would have had to have been overwhelming and dominating to
win, and ``overwhelming'' and ``dominating'' seldom have been
adjectives associated with his name. ``Courageous'' is the usual
description.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Puetro Madero, the Chile-bred horse that last May
finished second in the Massachusetts Handicap, had been training
crisply for Richard Mandella ``and he broke from the gate like a
quarterhorse,'' said jockey Kent Desormeaux. ``He won the race
coming out of the gate. His feet weren't even touching the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   When Puerto Madero ($10.40 to win) crossed the wire 2 3/4
lengths in front of Behrens and nearly 3 ahead of Silver Charm, who
barely beat out 129-1 shot Hanarsaan for third, Baffert rushed down
from the clubhouse to commiserate with Gary Stevens, Silver Charm's
jockey. The $500,000 Donn, the first race of the NTRA Champions
Series, was to be Silver Charm's first step this year toward
earning the $3.3 million he needs to top Cigar's all-time earnings
mark of $9.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to be on the inside today,'' Baffert said to Stevens,
who found it impossible to get inside from the far outside. ``And
then we had to go to Plan B.''
</P>
<P>
   Plan B?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping we could get a good spot from the gate,'' Baffert
explained. ``But it looked like all the outside horses went for the
lead from the start and we were left with Plan B _ just sitting
behind horses and go when we could.''
</P>
<P>
   All true, but Silver Charm never did ``go,'' falling 10 lengths
behind on the backstretch. Baffert blamed the track (``He never
took a hold of the sand'') and said the only consolation ``was that
he finished up well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, once Baffert learned he had drawn post 12 (``If I'd
known that before the race, I wouldn't have come''), it was clear
that neither he nor Stevens wanted to punish the horse, instead
prepping him for the Santa Anita Derby in five weeks and then the
Dubai World Cup in two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Gary that if you couldn't get over (to the inside)
right away,'' said the trainer, ``don't kill him in trying to get
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Puerto Madero had taken the lead at the top of the stretch,
Desormeaux said, ``I took a peek back and I thought I'd see
something gray coming after me. But nothing was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   So now it is Puerto Madero who may be the top handicap horse in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver Charm looked like he got shuffled back and maybe didn't
run his best race today,'' said Mandella. ``But my horse ran a big
race regardless of what happened to Silver Charm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
