<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SILVER-CHARM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM IS UPSET AND SO IS NEW RACING SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ Silver Charm, cast as the ``national
champion'' in a new series of races for senior horses, ran third as
the beaten favorite Saturday while the Chilean star Puerto Madero
won the $500,000 Donn Handicap at Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   The race inaugurated a series of 11 events grouped as a
championship series by the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association, with bonus money of $5 million based on a point system
designed to lure the country's best handicap horses. And the series
was built around the 5-year-old Silver Charm, winner of the
Kentucky Derby two years ago and winner of the Dubai World Cup last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But though he was the even-money favorite, Silver Charm could
not follow the script. He carried high weight of 126 pounds, giving
away 6 to Puerto Madero and 12 to Behrens, who finished second, and
he started on the far outside from the No. 12 post position. And
apparently both factors proved too much of a handicap. Instead,
Puerto Madero broke smartly, stalked the early pace for
three-quarters of a mile and then took dead aim on the lead as they
entered the homestretch. He pulled swiftly in front and, at the
finish, led Behrens by 2} lengths, with Silver Charm firing too
little and too late, 2{ lengths farther back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a cat out there,'' said Kent Desormeaux, who was
imported from California with Puerto Madero late last week. ``His
feet don't even touch the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won the race leaving the gate and, after 100 yards, he got
into an easy gallop. He sat behind two horses in front of him, and
the tank was full. He was asking, `When are you going to turn me
loose?' He did the rest. He's a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Life was not so rosy for Silver Charm and his celebrity team,
led by Bob and Beverly Lewis of Los Angeles, the owners, and Bob
Baffert, the blithe spirit who trains him. The marketing men who
designed the series apparently staked everything on Silver Charm,
coaxing Lewis to fly him from the West Coast and even arranging a
police escort from the airport to Gulfstream Park. But Silver Charm
could not overcome the burdens of weight and distance imposed on
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we gave up too much coming out of the gate,'' Lewis
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping we could get a good spot from the gate,'' Baffert
said. ``But it looked like all the outside horses went from the
start, and we were left with Plan B _ just sit behind horses and go
when we could.''
</P>
<P>
   From the viewpoint of a structured series of races for
thoroughbreds, the result might have created a quandary. Silver
Charm, the hero, ran third in the opener. And Puerto Madero, the
winner, probably will ship to the $5 million Dubai World Cup in
March and thereby compromise his appearances in the series for
``NTRA champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero is a 5-year-old bay who won eight straight races
in Chile before he was bought by Dwight Sutherland and R. D.
Hubbard, the owner of Hollywood Park Race Track, who also owns
Gentlemen, the retired champion from Argentina. Their new star won
the Native Diver at Hollywood Park in December in his fifth race
since arriving last April. He now has won 11 of 16 starts and has
run second three times.
</P>
<P>
   He covered the mile and one-eighth in the Donn in 1:48 1/5,
paying $10.40 for a $2 bet to win as the second choice. He also
earned $300,000 while Silver Charm had to be content with
third-place money of $50,000, which he will add to his career
earnings of $6.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mandella, who trained Gentlemen and now trains Puerto
Madero, reported that it took fine-tuning his horse's style to
adjust his speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got too good at coming off the pace,'' Mandella said.
``He'd give the field half a mile. But lately we've worked on that.
Silver Charm looked like he got shuffled back off the pace, and
maybe didn't have his best day. But the only way not to get beat is
to leave him home.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   JERRY BAILEY won five times on an expanded program of 12 races,
but finished fifth aboard Sir Bear in the Donn after his horse
showed early speed. Bailey will be back on Sunday when the
3-year-old colts take to the Triple Crown trail with a field of
seven starting in the Hutcheson Stakes at seven furlongs.  &UR;  &LR; . .
. &UR;  &LR; MIKE SMITH &UR;  &LR;  returning to racing five months after he broke two
vertebrae in his back in a spill at Saratoga, lost an allowance by
a nose in his return, and he rode the long shot Truluck to sixth in
the Donn Handicap. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
