<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURE IS COSTLY _ AND WORTH IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one wanted to part with a big name to acquire Pavel Bure.
Hard to figure, isn't it? The Russian Rocket potted six goals in
his first three games with the Panthers, his legs barely in gear,
looking every bit the darting, dazzling magician who connected for
back-to-back 60-goal seasons earlier in the '90s with Vancouver.
Imagine what he'll do when he hits his stride.
</P>
<P>
   Every team in the NHL wants to add an impact player. At least,
every team says that, while some give the standard cash caveat. The
frightening part is, there may be only a dozen true such players in
the game. Bure is one of them, a bona fide game-breaker, and there
is every reason to believe he will keep it up for at least 4-5
years. Pencil him in now for about, oh, 225-250 goals over his next
400 games.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Canucks had to settle for Ed Jovanovski, Dave
Gagner, and a couple of prospects _ including potential No. 1
goalie Kevin Weekes _ to grant Bure's wish and get him out of
Vancouver. Granted, Bure did himself no favors with his trade
demand, solidifying his reputation as a pouting, selfish player
concerned first and foremost about cash and caring little about the
color of his sweater.
</P>
<P>
   So, were the Flyers going to give up John LeClair or Eric
Lindros for Bure? Not in a Broad Street heartbeat. Would the Ducks
have parted with Paul Kariya? Forget it. And the Avalanche wouldn't
give up Peter Forsberg, the Ducks Teemu Selanne, the Senators
Alexei Yashin. None of those names ever entered the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But Bure is going to propel the Panthers into the
playoffs. In fact, as of Wednesday night, only 10 days after
Florida acquired his rights, Bure already had his new club holding
the No. 7 playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. That, folks, is
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Why were so few clubs willing to take Bure? Reputation was part
of it. Payroll was part of it. The Panthers will pay him $3 million
this year and may soon complete a deal that will pay him upwards of
$10 million a year (five years/$47 million is the rumored figure).
Not a lot of clubs _ as we know all too well here in Boston _ want
to take on that kind of debt, even if it could mean a true
opportunity to contend rather than simply compete.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of interest in Bure also shows that GMs and player
personnel directors around the league don't always know talent,
even when it's as obvious as the Bure on their nose. What, were
they afraid of breaking up team chemistry? Come on. Team chemistry
in '99, for the most part, is getting 18 skaters to buy into a
trap. Just makes the ice bubble, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Does Bure pout? Sure. Is he expensive? Absolutely. Does any of
that diminish his skill? Not one iota. But rest assured, the longer
Bure sat, the more he became a questionable commodity in the minds
of the men who make their living deciding who can and who can't
play.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a single thing to question about Bure, not by
today's standards of, shall we say, player imperfections. Take that
chemistry bunk and toss it under the Zamboni. Loads of clubs
already suffer fools with a lot less talent, figuring that, OK,
so-and-so isn't the best team guy, but he has the skill to win a
playoff round.
</P>
<P>
   Bure is a joy to watch, a rarity in today's humdrum game. No one
can equal his combined skating and stickhandling skills, and yet,
when he was there for the asking, the silence around the league was
haunting. Bill Torrey and Bryan Murray, No. 1 and No. 2 in the
Miami front office, knew enough to make the obvious move. The fact
that so few others made serious attempts to acquire Bure ought to
tell a few club owners that their on-ice woes can be traced
directly to their front-office faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of the Rock
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leaf Gardens bids adieu to its beloved Leafs in a couple
of weeks (Feb. 13 vs. Chicago), but the barn doors will remain open
for business. The Rock, Toronto's entry in the National Lacrosse
League, kicked off their home schedule there last weekend before a
crowd of some 11,000. ``You've got to see a game, it's just wild,''
said Bruins Hall of Famer Bobby Orr, reached last week in his
office at Woolf &AMP; Associates. Orr is part-owner of the Rock, along
with the likes of Leafs tough guy Tie Domi and ex-Bruin
coach/Canadian TV icon Don Cherry. Orr's longtime pal, Bill
Watters, assistant to Leafs president Ken Dryden, put together the
limited partners. ``I played it a little as a kid, but I never took
it too serious,'' said Orr. ``It's one great sport, especially when
it's played inside.'' . . . The Stars don't need toughness behind
the blue line, but don't be surprised to see them pursue Ulf
Samuelsson before the March 23 trade deadline. The value might not
be so much the addition in Dallas as the prevention in Detroit. The
Winged Wheels obviously need something to get going, and Dallas
will do everything it can to keep that from happening, including
siphoning off the dastardly Samuelsson . . . Word around Buffalo is
that the Sabres want a second-round pick for Derek Plante _ the
same compensation they got for sending Donald Audette to the Kings
. . . The Rangers lost out in the Bure hunt, ostensibly because
they wouldn't give up top prospect Manny Malhotra. What will it
take for the Blueshirts to land Theo Fleury? Answer: Todd Harvey.
The Russian Rocket would have guaranteed the Blueshirts a trip to
the playoffs, just as he will for the Panthers (perhaps at the
Bruins' expense?). He was worth Malhotra. But is Fleury worth
giving up Harvey? Answer: No. Remember, Bure will be 28 years old
in March, Fleury 31 in June . . . Surly Sabre Matthew Barnaby
hasn't displayed much of his edge lately. He and the
ever-underperforming Geoff Sanderson, ex- of the Forever .500s,
also have been mentioned in the Fleury swap rumors.
</P>
<P>
   What's up, Doc?
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruin equipment man Ken ``Doc'' Fleger, who left Causeway
Street last season for a job at the Coyotes' practice facility in
Scottsdale, Ariz., didn't find the career change to his liking. He
hopes to catch on with another NHL club for next season . . . When
Luc Robitaille notched his 500th goal at the start of this month,
his LA teammates presented him with a home entertainment system. He
returned the favor by presenting each of them with a bottle of Dom
Perignon. What, the local packie was out of Marcel Dionne? . . .
Former No. 1 pick Alexandre Daigle finally was traded Friday, from
Philadelphia to Tampa Bay via Edmonton. The Flyers had him swapped
at the All-Star break for the Oilers' Andrei Kovalenko, but the
deal crashed when Daigle snubbed a one-year, $1 million contract
extension offered by Edmonton boss Glen Sather. Another rumor, via
ESPN, had Daigle headed to the Kings for Steve Duchesne, who has
done little since returning to LaLa Land as a free agent from the
Blues. Daigle hopes to be an actor someday (someday?), and would
have preferred a swap to Anaheim or Los Angeles to pursue his
thespian aspirations (no, not something routinely treated in a
hyperbaric chamber) . . . Don't you think Bryan Smolinski would
look good again in a Bruins sweater? He's banking just shy of $1.8
million this season with the Islanders, playing on a third line.
His career has gone straight to nowhere, truly a disappointment
after his strong play in the World Cup. He's only 27, and if he's
not playing on a first or second line, his skills don't mean much .
. . NHL Players Association brotherhood update: Prior to the Devils
playing in San Jose a couple of weeks ago, New Jersey defenseman
Scott Stevens telephoned Brantt Myhres and apologized for calling
the Sharks tough guy ``a drunk'' when the clubs clashed just after
the New Year. Myhres graciously accepted the olive branch . . .
Tampa GM/coach Jacques Demers says it would be difficult to deal
Wendel Clark, but the truth is, he'll have no choice but to let him
go if somebody offers the Bolts a legit mid-20s forward or
defenseman who could contribute over the next 5-7 years. Now in
their seventh season, the Bolts will miss the playoffs for the
sixth time this April. Does it get any more basic than that? Either
they establish a franchise base, and soon, or there will be no fan
base to cultivate. Clark to Boston? Sure, nice fit. But what
mid-20s legit performer could the Bruins afford to send Tampa's
way?
</P>
<P>
   A good match
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you love to listen in on some of the conversations
between Brian Sutter and nutcase Andrei Nazarov, the 6-foot-5-inch
Russian Bear the Flames recently acquired from Tampa Bay for
Michael Nylander? Nazarov's infamous ``I even scare myself
sometimes'' line will follow him forever. And it's just that kind
of gonzo grittiness that Sutter loves. Nazarov has the oh-so-rare
good drool factor . . . From the Deep In The File Drawer Dept.:
Marc Crawford, hired last Sunday to replace Mike Keenan as coach in
Vancouver, was the Canucks winger who landed the last hit on
Normand Leveille the night of Oct. 14, 1982. Moments after the
thundering, head-banging check along the boards, Leveille was
wisked away for life-saving surgery to repair a cerebral
hemorrhage. Medical experts said it was a congenital malformation
that led to Leveille's injury and permanent paralysis. Wonder if
they ever compared their X-rays with the game film . . . USA Hockey
has notified NHL headquarters that it would like to know in the
next 6-8 weeks whether the league intends to send its best and
brightest to Salt Lake City for the 2002 Olympic Games. If not,
Colorado Springs has to begin shingling together an itinerary for a
pre-Olympic tour that would begin in the fall of 2001. The
player-selection process undoubtedly would begin during the 2000
offseason. The bet here: NHL commish Gary Bettman and his fellow
Lords of the Boards go to Olympus if they're guaranteed enough
prime-time TV exposure. It doesn't have to be a 2 1/2-hour time
slot, just, say, 45 quality minutes per night . . . You weren't
doing your hockey due diligence last week if you missed Pope John
Paul II, during his visit to St. Louis, turning his cane upside
down and pretending to use it as a hockey stick, drawing deafening
cheers from the crowd. What will happen first: the ESPN commercial,
with His Holiness doling out hip checks at Bristol headquarters, or
Nike issuing its new Papal Tiger skate line? Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
