<HEADLINE>
NATO GETS GO-AHEAD FOR KOSOVO AIRSTRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ Western powers, frustrated at the crumbling of a
cease-fire in Kosovo, cleared the way Saturday for a military
attack, authorizing the leader of NATO to call airstrikes if
hastily arranged peace negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, European nations agreed to send ground troops to
enforce the peace in the long-troubled Serbian province, an idea
being discussed within the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO stands ready to act,'' the alliance's Secretary General
Javier Solana told reporters Saturday in Brussels, after NATO voted
to authorize airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will take this decision in the light of both parties'
compliance with international commitments,'' he said. That comment
referred to concerns that earlier threats were directed only at
Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic, and not also at the Kosovo
Liberation Army, a guerrilla force made up of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these demands are not met,'' Solana said, ``NATO is ready
to take whatever actions are necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``Contact Group'' of six Western nations has
demanded that both the Serbs and the Albanians meet Saturday in
Rambouillet, France, to hammer out an agreement to give
``substantial autonomy'' to the southern Serbian province in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   France and Britain, meanwhile, offered ground troops to back up
any negotiated agreement. And German Defense Minister Rudolf
Scharping said Bonn was prepared to deploy around 3,000 troops in
Kosovo if needed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has floated the idea, but has not made a firm
commitment to providing ground troops, which many analysts regard
as critical to keeping a negotiated peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has made no decisions, and the foreign policy
team has made no recommendations,'' insisted David Leavy, the
spokesman for the National Security Council. The White House does
not want ground troops in a situation where there is combat, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's latest threat received a cool response in Belgrade, where
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook personally delivered the
ultimatum to Milosevic. The Yugoslav president, who has maintained
that he will not give autonomy to the 90 percent, ethnic Albanian
population of Kosovo, has a week to start negotiations, and three
weeks to come to an agreement, or face airstrikes, Cook told
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic refused to conduct the negotiations in the French
town, near Paris, saying that Kosovo is ``an integral part of
Serbia'' and that talks should be held in-country. But Cook said
Milosevic did not outright refuse the demand to hold talks
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not expect to get a `yes' on the spot,'' Cook told
reporters in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Cook then flew to Skopje, Macedonia, to meet with feuding
Albanian leaders. Divisions on the Albanian side represent another
stumbling block to peace, even though Albanians are united in
feeling wronged by the ruling Serbian regime.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian political leader Ibrahim Rugova has backed a nonviolent
solution. But he has no control over the KLA, which has waged a
guerrilla war against the Serb police and army for about a year,
and which refuses to accept anything less than independence for
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, for his part, refuses to give Kosovo independence.
His armed forces have waged an aggressive assault against KLA-held
territory in Kosovo, including civilian homes. About 2,000 people,
mainly Albanians, have died since the conflict began, and 250,000
have been forced to flee their homes to escape burning and looting
of ethnic Albanian villages.
</P>
<P>
   A critical question now is the KLA's commitment to peace talks.
Last October's cease-fire agreement was wrested from Milosevic, and
the KLA was not at the negotiating table. It is not clear whether a
KLA representative will be at the negotiating table in Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have complained that when they pull back their forces,
as specified in the October agreement, the KLA only moves in and
takes over the territory.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO airstrike against Milosevic, many fear, would only
buttress the KLA's position, provoke Milosevic anew, and escalate
the conflict. KLA members, in interviews, have said that they are
waiting for help via a NATO air assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one seems to know how to handle'' the KLA, said John
Mueller, a professor and Balkan specialist at the University of
Rochester. ``You can probably intimidate Milosevic into some kind
of deal, but it's not clear what's happening with the Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair reiterated Saturday that the
peace must be adhered to by both sides. ``We're not going to step
in to fight some kind of war on behalf of the UCK,'' he told CNN,
referring to the Albanian acronym for the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The West has been very sensitive recently about appearing to be
even-handed in the conflict. Milosevic has been the main target of
air assault threats, although the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe's Kosovo Verification Mission has accused
both the Serbs and the KLA of violating the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Both the violence and the tension came to a head two weeks ago,
when the verification mission discovered the bodies of 45 ethnic
Albanians, dressed in civilian clothes and dumped on a muddy, rural
hillside near Racak.
</P>
<P>
   Mission chief William Walker quickly accused the Serbs of
committing the massacre, a statement that nearly got him thrown out
of the country. Since the day of the discovery of the corpses,
there has been violence or a hostage situation nearly every day,
suggesting that the cease-fire has been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been more sharp-tongued since then in his criticism
of the KLA, referring to their taking of five Serbian hostages last
week as a ``terrorist act.'' It was the first time Walker used the
word ``terrorist,'' the word Serbs use to describe KLA rebels.
</P>
<P>
   A Serb civilian was killed and his wife was seriously injured
Saturday when a grenade exploded in their bedroom in northwestern
Kosovo, the Serbia Media Center reported. On Friday night, a
grenade exploded in a bar in the Kosovo capital of Pristina,
injuring six Serbs and one Albanian. The attack, a rare instance of
ethnic violence in relatively calm Pristina, came hours after 24
Albanians and one Serb policeman were killed in Rogovo, near the
Albanian border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
