<HEADER>
A5431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-HISTORY     01-30 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFORMANCE FOR THE AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those of us who relish golf history, we usually find it on
our bookshelves. We blow away the dust and learn of the magic
created by the likes of Old Tom Morris and Harry Vardon, Willie
Anderson and Walter Hagen, Francis Ouimet and Bobby Jones. Gene
Sarazen made a double eagle that put an everlasting smile on the
game and Byron Nelson was truly unbeatable one war-torn summer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us were not there that fateful Saturday in 1960 when
Arnold Palmer drove the first green at Cherry Hill and helped
invent professional golf as we know it. Nor were we there two
summers later when Jack Nicklaus stole The King's thunder and set
in motion a string of major successes that would redefine the way a
champion should play.
</P>
<P>
   History all of it, but most of us must trust the written words
because we weren't there for any of it. Which is why it was so
special to watch David Duval's round of 59 last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the game's greatest moments, and to be witness to
it _ albeit from in front of a TV set _ was a treat. There are
images of sports heroes that gently, and easily, come to mind when
greatness is recalled: Willie Mays settling under a fly ball, Bobby
Orr rushing the puck, Gale Sayers returning a kick, Bob Cousy
leading the break. Now add to that the graceful performance under
pressure by Duval.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to argue that Johnny Miller's 63 at Oakmont in 1973
and Ben Hogan's 67 at Oakland Hills in 1951 were more noteworthy
because they came in final rounds of US Opens on grueling layouts,
you will find plenty of support (and no argument here).
</P>
<P>
   But Duval's effort should not be dismissed; it should be
embraced, for it was as close to perfection as we shall ever see in
golf. This was not Al Geiberger shooting 59 in the second round
with the lift-clean-and-place rule in effect. This was not Chip
Beck shooting 59 on a Las Vegas course that was much too short by
PGA Tour standards. Wonderful, historic rounds they were, but they
were not final-day efforts, and they had chip-ins and long putts
that players don't think of holing.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Duval's round was beyond description, a string of
frozen ropes off the tee, one laser-beam iron on top of another,
with more deadly accuracy than has ever been shown in heated
competition. (Did his playing partners say anything to Duval, Jeff
Maggert was asked. ``We just kept saying, `Nice shot.' '') Only one
of Duval's 11 birdie putts came from 10 feet or more, and the eagle
that put the punctuation mark on the afternoon was from 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight should have stayed on Duval's historic
accomplishment, but it shifted to incidental matters such as the
world rankings. Duval is No. 2, behind Tiger Woods, but who cares?
It is only a piece of paper, spit out by a computer that is
programmed by people who probably can't comprehend the magnitude of
skill it took for Duval to scorch that 5-iron 218 yards, with the
tournament on the line, to set up his eagle at 18.
</P>
<P>
   Being No. 1 on some mindless list gives you a moment in the
spotlight. A 59 in the clutch gives you a spot in the history
books.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer the history, particularly when there's a view.
</P>
<P>
   A Hogan reminder
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday will mark the 50th anniversary of an event that had
nothing to do with golf but everything to do with the making of
arguably the game's most revered icon. It was in the early morning
of Feb. 2, 1949, that a car driven by Ben Hogan collided with a
Greyhound bus on a foggy road some 80 miles east of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan was returning to his home in Fort Worth from a tournament
in Phoenix, where he had lost in a playoff to Jimmy Demaret. At 36,
Hogan was in his prime, the best player in the game, owner of two
PGA Championships and the 1948 US Open. The accident probably would
have killed him had he not dived across the front seat to protect
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries were severe, from the broken bones _ pelvis,
collarbone, ribs, and ankle _ to the life-threatening blood clots
in his left leg. It was surgery to repair those clots that led to a
permanent circulatory problem that caused Hogan to limp.
</P>
<P>
   If he were a legend in the making before the crash (his 37th
professional victory had come at Pebble Beach the week before the
Phoenix tournament), the courageous comeback immortalized him. All
the polls and surveys and opinions that rate our greatest athletes
of the 20th century will mean nothing if William Ben Hogan is not
near the top.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Venturi may cherish his friendship with Hogan as much as he
does his 1964 US Open victory, and he knows very well that Hogan
was a man of few words _ and none when it came to that accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never brought it up,'' said Venturi. ``I never asked him
about it and I never heard him mention it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he started out in pro golf, Venturi made it a point to get
close to Hogan, to play practice rounds with him, to study
everything about him. That Hogan came back to win the US Open 16
months after the accident, then go on to win five more majors, all
while struggling to keep his stamina on a bad leg, is the stuff
Hollywood usually has to invent. But in Hogan's case, they had the
real-life script, which led to the movie, ``Follow the Sun,''
filmed in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironic that they made the movie thinking he couldn't come
back,'' said Venturi. ``But he proved them wrong _ as he always
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Kite's new role
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kite will again be part of the Ryder Cup scene when it
arrives at The Country Club in September, though in a far less
pressure-packed role _ and one more financially rewarding _ than he
had two years ago in Spain when he was US captain. Sources say Kite
will be part of the BankBoston corporate picture, socializing with
guests, and perhaps playing golf with clients at Charles River CC
in Newton . . . When the MGA holds its spring conference March 9 at
the Westin Copley Place in Boston, the theme will be ``A Salute to
the Ryder Cup.'' The event is usually attended by member club
directors, but it is open to the public this year and a silent
auction will be held. Among the items for sale: chances to play
golf at Worcester CC, site of the 1927 Ryder Cup, and The Country
Club. For information, call 781-449-3000 . . . Kirk Hanefeld, one
of the premier club professionals in New England, has left Salem CC
to become director of golf at the Ridge Club in Sandwich . . .
Another New Englander on the move is John Brown, the popular head
pro at the Woodlands in Falmouth, Maine. He'll be carrying on his
duties at the Brookside Club in Allentown, Pa. . . . Tracy West has
been named tournament director for the annual BankBoston Classic, a
staple on the Senior PGA Tour that will be at Nashawtuc CC in
Canton Aug. 20-22.
</P>
<P>
   Painful outing
</P>
<P>
   You would have to have a heart as cold as an Anchorage winter
day to not feel for Beck. Casual fans of the PGA Tour probably are
familiar with his struggles the past two years, and it's a mystery
where his game has gone. This is a man who was 6-2-1 in Ryder Cup
matches in 1991 and 1993, a player who once shot a 59 and was
renowned for his optimistic approach to the game. But he can't make
a cut anymore, and his opening round at the Phoenix Open Thursday
was a particularly sore thing to behold _ three doubles and eight
bogeys in a round of 83. He played his front side in 9 over,
recording one par, one double, and seven bogeys . . . They were the
first pair off the tee in the final round of the Naples LPGA
Memorial last Sunday, so Britons Mhairi McKay and Alison Nicholas
decided to have some fun. They often ran between shots and spent
little time over their balls in an attempt to play the quickest
round in Tour history. Alas, they fell 14 minutes shy of the mark,
which is 1 hour 50 minutes. One hour 50 minutes? That's about three
swings for Jose Maria Olazabal . . . Woods has committed to next
week's AT&AMP;T at Pebble Beach, again paired with Kevin Costner.
Wonder if there's any chance they'll be grouped with Woods's
Stanford teammate, Notah Begay, whose amateur partner will be
Hughes Norton, the IMG agent who helped make Woods a very rich
young man, then got fired last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
