<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY RETURNS TO D.C. FOR TRIAL TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The circus returned to town Saturday, as swarms of
reporters, paparazzi, and political activists converged for the
arrival of Monica S. Lewinsky for her high-stakes deposition Monday
in President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under a heavy police escort after a flight from Los Angeles,
Lewinsky rushed from a shiny sport utility vehicle to a downtown
hotel room and the uncertainty that awaits her. The former White
House intern will be questioned for the first time Monday by the
president's lawyers and a House member who is pushing for the 42d
president's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica, Monica,'' some spectators shouted, as others waved
placards emblazoned with anti-Clinton broadsides: ``Jail to the
Chief,'' ``Treason is the Reason,'' ``God Bless the Dress.''
</P>
<P>
   It was DNA evidence on Lewinsky's dress that purportedly
confirmed Clinton's sexual relationship with her. Clinton faces two
articles of impeachment charging him with perjury before a federal
grand jury and obstructing justice to try to conceal his affair
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With two senators presiding over the private deposition,
Lewinsky will be questioned for up to eight hours at the
Renaissance Mayflower Hotel, where she is staying, five blocks from
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On 22 previous occasions when she has testified under oath to
FBI investigators or a federal grand jury, Lewinsky has shown a
keen recollection for the details of her relationship with Clinton
and the circumstances stemming from their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Ed Bryant, a Tennessee Republican who will
question her for the House prosecution team, is expected to focus
largely on elements of the obstruction charge against Clinton. The
Senate prohibited the House team from asking Lewinsky about details
of her sexual relationship with the president, which directly
relate to the charge that he lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   A central issue in the deposition will be several grand-jury
statements that Lewinsky made about the alleged coverup. At one
point, she testified, ``No one ever asked me to lie, and I was
never promised a job for my silence.'' At another point, she said,
``The best way for me to explain how I feel what happened was, you
know, no one asked me or encouraged me to lie, but no one
discouraged me either.''
</P>
<P>
   The House team is trying to persuade the Senate that Clinton and
his friend, Vernon E. Jordan Jr., helped Lewinsky try to find her
``dream job'' in New York in exchange for her filing a false
affidavit about her relationship with the president in a sexual
harassment suit that Paula Corbin Jones filed against him and
settled last year for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also is expected to question Lewinsky about Clinton's
personal secretary, Betty Currie, hiding gifts that the president
had given Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers are expected to treat Lewinsky gently in the
hope she will support their position that no evidence directly
supports the House team's theory of Clinton's alleged obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's deposition will be videotaped. The House team is
expected to ask the Senate later this week to permit Lewinsky to
testify in person on the Senate floor. Should that request be
rejected, the House members are expected to request that portions
of the videotaped deposition be shown to the full Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
