<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     01-30 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE TAYLOR'S FINAL RIFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Lawrence Taylor was elected to the pro football Hall of
Fame Saturday. But far from being the no-brainer L.T. had
predicted, the vote was a wrenching moral wrestling match _ a match
that is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of news media members selected Taylor and four others
_ Eric Dickerson, Billy Shaw, Tom Mack and Ozzie Newsome. Long
after the vote was announced, members of the panel discussed,
defended and debated whether Taylor, plagued by drug problems for
years, deserved to be in the pro football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor transformed professional football the way Charlie Parker
transformed music; each made great innovations despite horrifying
drug addictions that ripped apart their lives and, in Bird's case,
took his life at the age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Parker are in their respective Halls of Fame. `Bird,'
as Parker was called, was elected virtually the instant he died;
Taylor was elected on the first ballot. But Taylor was elected amid
a heated debate among a distinguished panel of voters over whether
he truly belonged in the Hall. Consistent with the climate of
self-righteous indignation, the panel grappled with whether great
performance on the field is enough. Should off-field character
count? Ultimately the decision was no.
</P>
<P>
   L.T., despite being in the Miami area while working on a movie,
did not appear before news media members Saturday and declined to
speak to them by phone. He said through a spokesman that he didn't
want to go through the ordeal of justifying why he belongs in the
Hall of Fame. His performance speaks for itself. He said in a
statement that he appreciated the debate surrounding his selection.
``Ultimately, this honor has to do with how I played the game,'' he
said. ``Obviously the majority of the committee felt the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, L.T. The majority felt honor bound to the Hall of
Fame bylaws which mandate, quite simply, that on-field performance
is the only criterion. Despite the straightforward guidelines, the
panel of voters fiercely debated the efficacy of Taylor's election.
At the end of the selection process, they voted on a motion to
include character and conduct in the bylaws. The measure failed by
24-11 with one abstention. For now, the rule of the day is
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The players in the pro football Hall of Fame are connected by
how they performed when they left the locker room and walked onto
the field; not by what they did when they left the field for the
bars, bedrooms and brothels.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty I have with L.T. has nothing to do with whether
he is in or out of the Hall of Fame, but with whether he cherishes
the institution. He certainly respects the players in the Hall, but
maybe not the Hall itself. Clearly, he doesn't cherish his own
legacy. If he had, long ago, he might have thought about how he
might be remembered in history _ as well as the history his family
must live with.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Taylor's 17-year-old son found himself in the position
not of basking in his father's glory, but of defending his father's
continuing addiction. Right now L.T.'s on-field exploits are fresh
and powerful; 10 or 20 years from now they will be diminished by
time and the most graphic memories will be those of his off-field
exploits and excesses. When I think about Bobby Layne I think of a
swashbuckling drinker who showed up for games hung over. Taylor
never traduced the Xs and Os of the game and that is why he is in
the Hall of Fame. His play was superb, consistently intense.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling than whether L.T. is in the Hall is the role the
news media plays in putting him there _ or keeping him out. There
is an irresistible temptation on the part of the media to become
more actively involved in the game, to break out of the press box
and get involved in a world many of us love and respect. This
relationship between athletes and the news media is like being in a
great zoo. There are areas you'd like to visit, but there is a
reason why those bars are there, and we cross them at our peril.
Members of the media have to remove themselves from a voting
process in which they have no business being involved. Interpret
the news, lend perspective to the news. But don't make the news,
determine and manipulate history.
</P>
<P>
   Football writers would never submit to having their careers
judged by a panel of football players led by, say Keyshawn Johnson.
What gives the news media the right to not judge athletes on their
athletic abilities, but to judge morality? Or are we saying, in our
arrogance, that we are better equipped to judge them than they are
to judge us? It's as if the media, not the United States Senate,
were to vote on the president's guilt or innocence. That is not our
role; more than that, that is not our place. Our place is in the
press box, beyond the sidelines, reporting, analyzing, discovering
and uncovering news. Not determining.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Taylor is in the hall, where he belongs. Now the men
and women who have spent their lives building franchises, coaching
teams, playing and officiating must determine whether the Halls of
Fame will be sacred or common.
</P>
<P>
   Is the hall a temple or just another prison? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
