u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WITNESSES-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      01-30 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITNESSES-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MANAGERS HOPE TO MAKE LEWINSKY APPEAR SYMPATHETIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To tape or not to tape is not the question. It's
how the witnesses will play to the cameras that is making Democrats
on both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue quiver.
</P>
<P>
   Who will sweat? Who will fidget? What secrets will be uncovered
in the body language of the three witnesses as they testify before
House managers, White House lawyers, senators, and videocameras
this week?
</P>
<P>
   And, if the nation has a chance to see and hear Monica S.
Lewinsky, will the media caricature of the lovesick intern be
replaced by the image of a sympathetic, vulnerable,
three-dimensional young woman who was used and dumped by a cad in
the White House?
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest danger to the president is that Monica will come
off as a likable, star-struck little girl seduced by a powerful
male,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst at Claremont
Graduate University. ``It will be very difficult to overcome that
perception on the video. In politics, perception is reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Though conviction of Clinton still appears doubtful, Democrats
worry that unfavorable images from the videotapes could linger long
after the trial ends.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic senators fought last week against videotaping the
depositions of Lewinsky, Washington lawyer Vernon E. Jordan Jr.,
and presidential adviser Sidney Blumenthal. In particular, they
argued, it would exploit Lewinsky and dishonor the chamber to have
tapes about a sexual affair shown in the Senate chamber.
Republicans promised they would vote again before playing the
videotapes in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is 1999, we're about to go into the year 2000,'' said
Senate majority leader Trent Lott. ``To not have videotape
available for senators, and maybe beyond that, is not defensible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democratic leader Thomas A. Daschle of South Dakota
said he feared the videotapes would lead to to live witnesses. ``We
don't want the spectacle of Monica Lewinsky or anyone else. . . .
We don't need salacious material.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Rhode, a professor at Stanford University Law School,
was hired by House Judiciary Committee Democrats last year to be
their guide on gender issues, particularly on how to handle the
sensitive issue of Lewinsky. Rhode is skeptical that preserving the
former intern's reputation is what drives Democrats against the
videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit hard to take at face value these professed
concerns, that their opposition is to protect the dignity of Monica
Lewinsky,'' Rhode said. ``I would not say that has been a high
priority through the proceedings, and I am not convinced it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are concerned about is how this will play in Peoria,
and whether there is something that comes out in the visual
presentation that will poison people's views of President
Clinton,'' Rhode said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the president's aides went into high gear to
discredit Kathleen Willey, a former White House volunteer, after
she appeared on ``60 Minutes'' and said Clinton groped her outside
the Oval Office. Joseph diGenova, a Republican and a former federal
prosecutor, said the Lewinsky videotape could cause the same
negative public reaction to the president, and the same
``good-to-evil turn on Lewinsky'' from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they afraid of with the videotape?'' diGenova asked.
``For one thing, people might start to tell the truth. The other is
that the image of Monica Lewinsky _ youthful, naive _ is going to
get people rethinking this whole case.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the White House and Republican managers will handle
Lewinsky with care. They remember the harsh questioning of Anita
Hill during the confirmation hearings of Supreme Court Justice
Clarence Thomas, after Hill accused Thomas of sexually harassing
her. The questioning caused an angry political backlash that led to
the election of a record number of women to Congress in 1992 and
nearly cost some senators on the Judiciary Committee their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly to their benefit not to rile Lewinsky and send
her into some furor,'' Jeffe said. ``It is best not to make her
angry.''
</P>
<P>
   House managers are spending the weekend preparing for the
depositions. They hope that Lewinsky, Jordan, or Blumenthal will
deliver a bombshell, contradicting what they told the grand jury
based on a refreshed memory or a new fact. It has been reported,
for example, that when Lewinsky met with House managers last week,
she expressed surprise over the extent to which the president
portrayed her as a stalker. That could come up.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, though, House managers are looking for witnesses to
adjust their stories just enough, or leave such strong visual
impressions, that the Senate feels compelled to hear from the
witnesses in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Videotaped testimony is one step closer to live testimony, and
therefore it is viewed by the Republican side as a step in the
direction of prolonging the trial and, then, hoping something will
emerge that swings negative into positive votes,'' said Marvin
Kalb, director of the Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics,
and Public Policy at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Videotaping depositions has become quite common, particularly in
civil litigation, and it does change the dynamic when witnesses
testify before cameras, lawyers say. A witness's appearance and
demeanor become relevant; unlike transcripts, videotapes show how
long a witness takes to answer a question, as well as gestures and
body language.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosensteil, director for the Project for Excellence in
Journalism, a nonprofit group, said he does not expect a video
camera to rattle Lewinsky. ``She is probably one of the most
videotaped women in America already,'' he said, but, he added, it
could have some effect on the senators viewing the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can imagine a lot of senators scrolling the videos, checking
the instant replays, looking for mannerisms, sweaty palms, and
shifty eyes,'' said Rosensteil, the former media critic at the Los
Angeles Times. ``The cameras may not affect what anyone says in
their depositions, but it could cause senators to get fixated on
exactly the wrong things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
