<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DAVIS31-COX     01-30 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DAVIS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davis a headache for opponents
 &HT;    WITH ILLUSTRATION
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Terrell Davis is ready. He has one big sign for his
hotel room, another big sign for his locker at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The message: Take your Indocin.
</P>
<P>
   That is the drug that prevents his migraines, the one he forgot
to down until shortly before kickoff of Super Bowl XXXII last
January in San Diego, the one that almost left him alongside
Scottie Pippen in the Hall of Infamous Postseason Headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, of course, snapped out of the funk, regained his vision
and ran for 157 yards and three touchdowns to give Denver its first
Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   The headache is long gone. And now Davis is earning a reputation
not only as the NFL's best player of today _ he was named MVP for
the 1998 season _ but also as one of the best big-game athletes
ever.
</P>
<P>
   If Reggie Jackson was Mr. October, then Davis is starting to
look like Mr. January.
</P>
<P>
   In four seasons, he has played seven postseason games, scoring
at least one touchdown in each and averaging 145.2 rushing yards _
the best in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, he will be facing a defense that finished the
regular season ranked second in the NFL against the run, a defense
that for all its nice talk about Davis, believes it can stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no super-human players in this league,'' Atlanta
defensive end Chuck Smith said. ``Everybody can be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   But how?
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins did it in December. They held Davis to 29 yards in
a Monday Night meeting at Pro Player Stadium. Of course, three
weeks later in Denver, Davis took an injury-depleted Dophins'
defense and racked up 199 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He burned the Dolphins with what has become the Broncos'
bread-and-butter play: a pitch to Davis that allows him get the
ball deep in the backfield and look for a hole.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that makes Davis so effective is that once he
spots that hole, he makes it through. Not just most of the time.
Nearly all of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't second-guess himself and dance,'' Smith said.
``There's a lot of guys out there who like to dance and sit back
there and be cute. ... When he sees that crease, he's going to hit
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's Tom Jackson, a former Broncos' linebacker, said: ``If you
open it up 10 times, he's going to hit it nine times.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if he doesn't, that doesn't mean you have stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one in the league more physical than Terrell
Davis,'' Jackson said. ``He can run you over or he can take it
80.''
</P>
<P>
   Or both.
</P>
<P>
   The first strategical question for the Falcons is this: Do they
stick with their traditional seven-man front, which would seem like
a hanging curveball for Davis to hit? Or do they go with an
eight-man front?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' players gave different answer to that question this
week. Linebacker Jessie Tuggle said they plan to start with the
seven-man front. Safety Eugene Robinson said they will cut the to
chase, so to speak, and use eight-man fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``(To stop him) you have to try to cut out the running lanes and
play an eight-man front,'' he said. ``I know that puts a lot of
pressure on the pass defense. Ray Buchanan and our other
cornerbacks have got to come up big against John Elway, because we
(the other defenders) have to stop Terrell Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice the verb he uses. They (ITALICS) have to (END) stop
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the consensus. If the Falcons can't stop Davis,
or at least slow down his record-setting pace, they can't win this
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to attack him,'' Smith said. ``We are not going to
sit back there and stargaze.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But there is another problem. If you worry too much
about running to the place where Davis is, you can end up being
burned by his cut-backs. Just ask the Dolphins. Once he blew
through holes in their line, he left the field littered with
linebackers and safeties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be disciplined,'' Tuggle said. ``The second time
Miami played Denver, the linebackers overpursued a little bit. We
can't play that kind of game against Terrell.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. January can be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Just give him a migraine so bad that he can't even see.
</P>
<P>
   That did the trick for a half against the Packers. Then the
emergency nasal spray that Broncos trainer Steve Antonopulos gave
Davis, began to kick in. This year, it seems unlikely that will be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has the signs ready. And his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is going to be reminding him,'' fellow running back
Vaughn Hebron said. ``Believe me, there's no way Terrell's going to
forget this time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
