<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAMAL31-COX     01-30 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAMAL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backs stage to Anderson
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Atlanta Falcons and Denver Broncos present this gift
to football fans today: Runs in their stockings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key to the game is which running back is going to
establish his dominance,'' said former Broncos linebacker Tom
Jackson, of the backs which finished first and second in the NFL in
yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Will Terrell Davis' slashing burn Atlanta? Can Jamal Anderson
ramble downhill on Denver?
</P>
<P>
   Davis would enjoy watching this game, since he's a ''running
backs fan,'' who speaks of the ''friendly game of chess that
running backs play.'' He and Anderson move like queens, rooks,
bishops and knights all in one. Take them out, defensive coaches
and players say, and you ''check'' their offenses, by neutralizing
play-action passing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing is being able to run the football,
because then you can select when you want to throw it,'' Falcons
offensive coordinator George Sefcik said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can stop (Anderson), it would put the ball in (Chris)
Chandler's hands and they have to do it that way,'' said Broncos
linebacker Bill Romanowski.
</P>
<P>
   Davis rushed 392 times this season, for 2,008 yards, the
third-best total in history. Anderson gained 1,846 yards on a
league-record 410 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would rather face Terrell Davis any day instead of facing
Jamal Anderson,'' Falcons cornerback Michael Booker said. ''Jamal
will run to you just to run over you. Terrell is strong and he's
fast and all of those things, but we're going to put two or three
guys on him and hit him early.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, these early (dirty) birds may get the worm.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammed Ali was in the hospital the day Jamal Anderson was
born, waiting to see his bodyguard's son. Twenty-six years later,
James' baby boy Jamal is more bull than butterfly or bee, some say
in more ways than one: a big talker with a big ego, but also a big,
gifted back who presents enormous problems for a defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''First of all he's fast, so he can outrun you,'' Broncos safety
Tyrone Braxton said. ''Second of all, he's quick, so he can
outmaneuver you. He's got quick feet. I remember the Detroit game
he stopped on a dime and cut back against the linebackers. And
three is power. He can run you over. Growing up watching Earl
Campbell, that's who he reminds me most of. He's strong, he's
short, he's thick, he's quick and he's fast.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a complete football player,'' Sefcik said of the former
seventh-round pick. ''He'll step up against the best of them and
pick up blitzing linebackers. He'll block in the running game too,
if you ask him. He runs excellent routes and can make people
miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Microwaves are more complicated than Atlanta's offense. The
Falcons led the NFL in time of possession at 33:10, by bludgeoning
opponents with the 235-pound Anderson and then slipping a lithe
receiver deep. Atlanta was 14-0 this season when Anderson carried
the ball at least 20 times. He gained at least 100 yards in 12 of
16 regular-season games, scored 14 touchdowns and averaged 11.8
yards on 27 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to pound it until it works,'' Falcons fullback
Brian Kozlowski said. ''You're not going to make every tackle on
Jamal, and sooner or later he's going to break one on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Falcons guard Calvin Collins suggests, break your arm if
you get lazy and don't square up. The Broncos, who use safety Steve
Atwater as a fourth linebacker, are good tacklers and skilled at
plugging gaps. Greg Robinson's unit finished second in the league
in rush defense, and allowed 14 yards on 13 carries to both the
Dolphins and the Jets in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''They attack well,'' Anderson said. ''They hit the line of
scrimmage fast and they play off the blocks really well. The key
for us is being able to sustain blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says, ``I think we can run the ball against anybody.
No question.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What you try to do is eliminate as many big plays as you
possibly can,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ''He's going to
get his yardage. You have to gang-tackle him and slow him down.
He's consistent and durable, and I like his enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a combination of a Napolean Kaufman and Jerome Bettis
runner,'' Broncos linebacker John Mobley said. ''He's got the power
of Jerome and he's shifty enough like Kaufman.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes to use the stiff arm to fend off tacklers.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to somehow get that arm away from him, whether it be
grab it or go low on him, there's definitely ways to defend it,''
Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski said. ''If you have three guys
tackling him, a stiff arm doesn't do any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was hardly stiff this week, drawing on his experience
hanging out with his father's clients, people like Ali, Sugar Ray
Leonard and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always learned to relax in these situations and to enjoy
yourself, and if you do that, the atmosphere won't be a problem,''
he said. ''I'm not nervous in this setting. This is like a natural
environment for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The grass at Pro Player Stadium isn't, but Anderson prefers it.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me, I'm a little more confident in my football on grass,''
Anderson said. ''I can let it all hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Broncos hang on for dear life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
