<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-PREDATORS-     01-30 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PREDATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEVILS FAIL TO HOLD EARLY LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils scored the first two goals
Saturday against the expansion Nashville Predators, then lost in
overtime by 3-2, and afterward they were looking for answers for
their lackadaisical performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunham, Martin Brodeur's former backup with the Devils, had
27 saves for the Predators as they ended the Devils' season-high
four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Devils were overconfident and looked past Nashville
to Monday night's visit by the Detroit Red Wings, one of the
league's elite teams, Coach Robbie Ftorek said to ask the players.
</P>
<P>
   The players maintained that they had just been outworked by
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't hear anybody talk about Monday,'' Randy McKay said.
Lyle Odelein agreed, saying: ``Nobody talked about Detroit. This
was a must win for us and it is unacceptable. They outworked us in
our zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek, who usually praises his team's play regardless of its
performance, pointed to one reason for the Devils' losing a game
they should have put away after first-period goals by Odelein and
Denis Pederson gave them a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play together as a team, and if you don't do that,
you're not going to have success against anybody,'' Ftorek said.
``We just didn't play for 60 minutes and they played hard. They
made some mistakes but they covered up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik, the Devils' leading scorer and usually an objective
analyst of the team's performance, was closest to the reason for
the loss to one of the league's weaker teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the tape,'' Holik said, ``you won't see enough
white jerseys around the puck. That means we didn't work hard
enough to support the puck. We have to support each other and do
better as a team. When we turned it on, we were the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils did just fine in the first period. Odelein scored his
first goal of the season, on the power play, with 2 minutes 35
seconds left in the period after a pass by Holik, and Pederson
scored his seventh with 26.9 seconds left. But they never looked
forward after that and rarely threatened with any seriousness the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 2-0, maybe we thought it was going to be an offensive
fest,'' Brodeur said.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who registered his third shutout of the season and 35th
of his career on Thursday night in Boston, faced 23 shots Saturday
afternoon, including two in the overtime. He did not have any
spectacular saves and could take part of the blame for the goals.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Johnson's 11th of the season, 4:13 into the second period,
went in off Brodeur's left arm to cut the Devils' lead to 2-1.
Scott Walker's sixth, which tied the game with 8:25 left in
regulation, started when Brodeur's clearing attempt went to an
opponent in his zone.
</P>
<P>
   And Sebastien Bordeleau's winning goal, 2:43 into overtime, went
through Brodeur's pads to the disappointment of the Continental
Arena matinee crowd of 17,808.
</P>
<P>
   ``He surprised me when he took the shot,'' Brodeur said of
Bordeleau's seventh goal of the season. It gave the Predators
(18-26-4) their second consecutive victory and handed the Devils
(27-15-5) their first overtime loss in eight such games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a moral booster for us,'' said Tom Fitzgerald,
the captain of the Predators, who made the pass for Bordeleau's
winner. ``It's really huge for us because it came on top of winning
in Buffalo. This is one of the toughest teams in the conference,
but we stuck to our system and persevered.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's first goal, by GREG JOHNSON, was the first one
MARTIN BRODEUR allowed in 108 minutes 42 seconds, going back to the
second period of the victory in Los Angeles on Jan. 21. ... MIKE
DUNHAM, Brodeur's understudy last season, was the winning
goaltender in his first meeting against his former team. Dunham
faced 29 shots and improved his record to 12-11-1. ... SERGEI
BRYLIN was scratched for the second game in a row after playing 12
in a row with no goals. ... SHELDON SOURAY was the other healthy
scratch for the Devils, who sent SASHA LAKOVIC to Albany for
conditioning and now have one extra forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
