<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN     01-30 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 31-COX &HT;    Anderson, Davis grew up in different worlds, but arrive at same
destination: Greatness
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Donna Summer, the disco diva, taught him to dance.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali _ whom he simply called Uncle Muhammad _ taught him
magic tricks and later instilled in him the human touch when
dealing people of all persuasions. Sugar Ray Leonard _ at the time
champ of the world _ rode a bicycle to his grade school to say
hello and years later showed him, first-hand, how to handle a press
conference with a touch of class.
</P>
<P>
   Boyz II Men _ who fascinated him with stories of their ascension
from Philadelphia's street corners _ let him try to harmonize with
them. Arsenio Hall slept on the floor of his house. Magic Johnson
would stop by for backyard barbecues and Mike Tyson let him drive
his Mercedes, his Jaguar, the Lamborghini and the Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   This was part of growing up for Jamal Anderson, the star running
back of the Atlanta Falcons and the son of James Anderson, security
chief for dozens of big-name athletes and entertainers from Ali,
Michael Jackson, Diana Ross and Richard Pryor to his current
handling of Tyson
</P>
<P>
   When Jamal Anderson talks of reaching for the stars, he means
just that...literally.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, the record setting Denver Broncos ball carrier,
also knows about aiming high _ though his childhood was quite a bit
different than Anderson's.
</P>
<P>
   With Davis, Dad meant little security.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Davis' life too often was alcohol and drugs, and that led to
prison stints for robbery and grand theft, guns around the house,
scales for weighing cocaine and pot and plenty of frightening and
bizarre late-night scenes for young Terrell.
</P>
<P>
   One night in the fall of 1981, Joe _ fueled on malt liquor and
macho _ stumbled home with a taped-up and loaded .38 in his fist.
He woke up his four youngest sons _ Terrell was just nine _ and
said he wanted to find out how tough his kids were.
</P>
<P>
   He backed them against the wall and had them raise their hands.
Then he began shooting into the wall just above them. Plaster flew,
the kids quaked and, through the acrid smell of cordite, Terrell
claims to have felt the hot air of a bullet passing near his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't scared, Davis said. `` I knew he wasn't going to kill
us. He loved us too much.''
</P>
<P>
   This love-hurts style of parenting _ waking the boys at 2 a.m.,
telling them to scoop up their new puppies he suddenly didn't like
and walking the crying kids through the neighborhood as he made
them throw the animals over neighbors' fences _ didn't work. Joe
died young and then Mom took over.
</P>
<P>
   Kateree Davis was 16 when she quit school and married. She got
her GED, took college courses and received a nursing degree. She
worked two jobs, made monthly house payments and did the best to
keep her kids in line.
</P>
<P>
   And right from the start, she made sure Terrell, the youngest of
her six boys, was linked to celebrity. She named him after R&AMP;B
singer Tammi Terrell because she liked the words of her hit song:
Ain't nothing like the real thing, bay-bee. Ain't nothing like the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   So, when it comes to the security business, when it comes to the
real thing, you get a pair of running backs like Jamal Anderson and
Terrell Davis, whose championship match-up today in Miami is like
nothing else in the history of the Super Bowl
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, Davis rushed for an NFL best 2,008
yards and 21 touchdowns. Anderson, second best, ran for 1,846 yards
and 14 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Never before have the league's two biggest ground threats met in
the roman numeral championships. That both of their teams run the
ball with unparalleled vigor means that Super Bowl XXXIII could
give us a game of basic, physical, old-school football. None of the
trendy West Coast offenses. No run and shoot. These teams key their
attacks with a pair of workhorse, outta-my-way backs.
</P>
<P>
   Because of it, defensive linemen and linebackers step up to stop
the run. Pass defenders cheat toward the line to help out and then:
GOTCHA. Each team can and will knock you out with the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, at 210 pounds, is strong, has great vision and a
tremendous burst when he first touches the ball. He is, in the
newly birthed-vocabulary of the ever-talking Denver tight end
Shannon Sharpe, simply ``Terrellian.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpreted by Atlanta defensive coordinator: ``Terrell's a
combination-Jim Brown-Barry Sanders.'' And that comparison is not
as far-fetched as you may think. Davis' career average of 105.1
yards a game is tops all-time in the NFL, just ahead of Browns
104.3 and Sanders 99.8.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led the NFL this season with a dozen 100-yard games. He
weighs 234 pounds and most of the weigh seems to be in his legs,
which keep churning and make him difficult to bring down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal has had an outstanding year,'' said Atlanta coach Dan
Reeves. ``I've been around running backs like Tony Dorsett, Calvin
Hill and Walt Garrison and I don't know that anybody had as good a
year as Jamal had.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, Davis is the better known. He was the league's MVP
this season and last year was the MVP of Super Bowl XXXII when he
demolished Green Bay with 157 yards rushing yards and three
touchdowns. His autobiography _ TD: Dreams in Motion _ just came
out and a movie on his life is in the works. Last July, he signed
an eight-year contract extension worth $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons' brass say Anderson's contract is being reworked so it's
closer to Davis' dough. And that will be just one more thing that
makes them amazingly similar.
</P>
<P>
   Neither back is particularly fast or elusive and they both came
into the league with absolutely no fan fare. Both had
undistinguished college careers _ Anderson at Utah, Davis at Long
Beach State and then Georgia. Combined they ran for less than half
the yards of this year's Heisman hero, Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was a seventh round pick _ the 24th running back _
chosen in the 1994 NFL draft. Davis was selected in the sixth round
_ 21st running back _ in 1995. Each went to his first NFL camp as
the fifth-rated halfback on his team. Neither was supposed to make
the cut, much less carry a team to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal had the same situation I did, we came along late in the
draft and showed people you can't count someone out because of some
report on paper,'' Davis said. ``Knowing where we came from, maybe
it will bring people a lot of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said this Super Bowl is ``the reward for all late round
picks. I'm not unlike Terrell's situation. You have to fight and
claw your way to where we are now. It's something I've worked for
my entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   For Anderson _ as his dad relates _ it's a childhood dream come
true.
</P>
<P>
   James Anderson tells of sitting in front of the TV watching
Pittsburgh defeat the L.A. Rams in Super Bowl XIV and little Jamal
announcing: ``I'm going to be in that game!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's a good one, Jamal,'' said Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Still it was thanks to James that his boy learned his patented
stiff arm move. It almost got the kid banned from his Pop Warner
League, but it sure worked wonders in the playoffs when he used it
twice on 49ers safety Merton Hanks _ on the same play _ during a
34-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   As for Davis, it was his mom who kept him pointed in the right
direction even as violence took its toll on others around him. One
of his older brothers went to prison after shooting a pregnant
woman whose fetus died during a robbery. Then his best friend was
shot to death over a gambling debt.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of their childhoods shaped Anderson and Davis into
caring players of today. This Super Bowl week both were involved in
high-profile fund raising projects for the needy.
</P>
<P>
   Davis takes special care of his mother, whom he has moved out of
San Diego and built a home around the corner in his Aurora, Colo.,
neighborhood. Anderson is taking care of his offensive linemen with
ever-increasing gestures of appreciation. When he passed the
1,000-yard mark early in the season he ordered a truck load of
20-inch televisions for his blockers. Once he topped 1,800 yards,
he bought them 36-inch flat screen TVs that cost $2,700 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boxes are getting bigger,'' Falcon left tackle Bob
Whitfield said. ``When I saw this last one I just said, 'He's the
greatest running back ever.'''
</P>
<P>
   In turn the lineman take Anderson to lunch every Friday and they
pick up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says, 'Hey that's not the way it goes. The running
back is always supposed to reach for the check,''' Anderson said
with a laugh. ``I just tell 'em, 'Hey, it's the '90s. Just like
women asking guys out on dates and paying the bill. These are new
times. Those old notions are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ...Except on the football field, today.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta meets Denver, it's likely to be an old-school Super
Bowl, a game where guys don't just reach for the stars, they make
the defenders see them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
