<SLUG> BC-MARS-SPACECRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS GLOBAL SURVEYOR WILL BE MANEUVERED INTO FINAL ORBIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ A series of white-knuckle maneuvers over the
next few days will determine the fate of the Mars Global Surveyor
spacecraft, which has spent a year and a half slowly, gradually
spiraling closer to Mars. If all goes well, the craft will finally
be able _ exactly a year behind schedule _ to begin a two-year
program of mapping the red planet with unprecedented detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be going through some of the most critical events of the
mission,'' said Michael Malin, head of the mission's imaging team
and designer of its high-resolution camera, which will be able to
make out desk-sized objects on the Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvers to adjust the craft's orbit around Mars involve
``high risk activity,'' Malin said, comparable to what Mars
Observer was doing just before it was lost. In 1991, Mission
controllers lost contact with the $1.5 billion Mars Observer just
as it arrived at Mars and was supposed to fire its main engine to
propel it into orbit around the planet; it has not been heard from
since.
</P>
<P>
   If controllers lose radio contact with the Mars Global Surveyor
spacecraft during this critical period, the craft would crash into
the planet's surface within two days, dragged from orbit by
friction from the thin atmosphere of Mars. But if the maneuvers go
as planned, the craft will end the week close to its final orbit
high above the atmosphere, where it should remain safe and stable
for the two years it will take to complete its work.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in the most critical of the five planned
maneuvers, Global Surveyor is supposed to fire its main engine for
the first time in four months and lift its orbit out of the
atmosphere and into a near-circle instead of the long ellipse,
dipping in and out of the air, that it has been following since it
arrived at Mars in September 1997. The new orbit will keep it a
constant distance from the planet so it can map its entire surface
in a consistent way.
</P>
<P>
   If that engine burn works the way it's supposed to, ``then we'll
celebrate,'' said Joe Beerer, the spacecraft's operations manager.
``That's when we start to breathe easy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time coming, Beerer said in an interview last
week at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory, where the mission was designed and is
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Global Surveyor was supposed to have completed its innovative
aerobraking in March 1998, using the drag of the planet's
atmosphere to slow the craft and bring it into its intended orbit
without having to use heavy rocket fuel to do it. But that process
was hampered by a solar panel that was damaged shortly after
launch.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, it turns out, was cracked when it sprang open in
orbit after having been sent aloft tightly folded. A device that
was supposed to slow the spring-loaded opening failed, and the jolt
cracked part of the panel, which is working now, but has needed
extra care.
</P>
<P>
   That won't matter anymore if the craft reaches its intended
nearly circular orbit this week, which will keep it above the
atmosphere where the solar panel should be safe. But the engineers
worry that they could encounter a similar problem when they release
a spring-loaded antenna soon after the craft reaches its final
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be on the safe side, the craft is expected to complete
three weeks of mapping of the surface of Mars before the antenna is
released. In the meantime, the data will be sent back using a much
lower-speed link through another antenna.
</P>
<P>
   Once it is in full swing, Mars Global Surveyor's views of the
surface should begin to answer some important questions about that
planet, whose surface area equals that of the Earth's dry land. For
one thing, it should provide some long-awaited information for the
planners of the Mars Polar Lander, which was launched Jan. 4 and is
due to land on Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   That craft is not equipped with airbags to cushion its landing,
as the 1997 Mars Pathfinder was. It will instead control its
descent with rocket motors, like the Apollo lunar landers and the
Viking landers on Mars in 1976. But this means the final landing
site, close to the planet's southern polar ice cap, must be chosen
with great care so that the craft will end up safe and level on the
surface. Mission planners are eager to get their hands on the
Global Surveyor pictures and topographic maps as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Global Surveyor has already provided some tantalizing previews
of the kind of detailed pictures of Mars that it will routinely
send back once it reaches its precise final orbit in early March.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Malin said, its pictures have already provided the
first evidence that Mars, now drier than any earthly desert, once
had water over a sustained period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Some planetary scientists have argued that features on Mars that
have been interpreted as signs of an early history of abundant
water, with rivers, lakes, and maybe even oceans, are nothing more
than remnants of brief, sudden floods. But Malin said a Global
Surveyor image showing a narrow channel in the floor of a wide
canyon, much like the Colorado river's channel inside the Grand
Canyon, is a clear sign of sustained flow over a long period of
time.
</P>
<P>
   It shows ``a continuous flow of water rather than a catastrophic
flood,'' Malin said. Still, he said, there is no visible evidence
that it ever rained on Mars. No tiny branches of the tributaries in
terrestrial rivers can now be seen on Mars. Maybe such features
will be seen in the new images, he said, or perhaps they have been
buried under millions of years' accumulation of dust.
</P>
<P>
   In another surprise, Global Surveyor pictures show layers of
land that appear to have built up over time in distinct stair-step
fashion through some kind of long-term climate cycle, perhaps
something like Earth's ice ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
