<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSON LEARNED: GO WITH BRONCOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I blew the call last year. Like referee Phil
Luckett, I had a 50-50 chance of getting it right and I just plain
flubbed it.
</P>
<P>
   I picked Green Bay to beat Denver in Super Bowl XXXII and a
couple of you with memories longer than Jason Elam's field-goal
range haven't let me forget it.
</P>
<P>
   No Siree Bob . . . or is it John? David? Mark? I'm not quite
sure since you keep forgetting to include your names when you leave
those very pointed messages on my voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   I'd be willing to bet that the bookmakers in Vegas who installed
the Packers as 11{-point favorites last year didn't receive a voice
mail with time left on the Qualcomm Stadium clock from a smug
stranger telling them Denver's win was proof of why they should be
on the chorus line, not setting the line.
</P>
<P>
   But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say I learned my lesson. Never pick against a team
with John Elway, Terrell Davis and Bill Romanowski on it and a
pills-and-potions producing company called Experimental and Applied
Sciences behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine, Crockett and McCaffrey rock!
</P>
<P>
   No way do I want to be like Broncos defensive end Neil Smith and
have people calling for me to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, an 11-year veteran, will rise above the commonality of
his surname today against the Falcons at Miami's Pro Player
Stadium. He has predicted as much, though his words didn't command
anywhere near the attention that Atlanta cornerback Ray Buchanan's
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play well for our team,'' Smith said, ``but I also
need to play well to prove again that I can play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler is in for a long
day. Count on Smith and Romanowski to remind everybody why
Chandler, before he was being hailed as the best quarterback in
today's matchup, was nicknamed ``Crys-tal Chandelier.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeBerg best not misplace his helmet a la Thurman Thomas.
It wouldn't surprise me if the 45-year-old DeBerg, who was
supplanted as the Broncos' starter in Elway's first NFL game, winds
up a footnote in Elway's final one.
</P>
<P>
   That would be almost as apropos as the decisive score coming on
a pass from Elway to Ed McCaffrey, whom then-Giants coach Dan
Reeves released in July of 1994 when the wide receiver was three
games shy of qualifying for his NFL pension.
</P>
<P>
   It would be really fitting for Broncos coach Mike Shanahan to
hand Reeves, his ex-boss, his fourth Super Bowl loss as a coach. Or
are you the last one to hear how there's no love lost between the
two men?
</P>
<P>
   If Reeves were smart, he'd watch his head during pregame
warmups. Once, before an exhibition game against Oakland, Shanahan,
then an assistant coach in San Francisco, goaded 49ers quarterback
Elvis Grbac into throwing a tight spiral toward the Oakland
sideline that barely missed the noggin of another Shanahan nemesis,
Raiders owner Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Another guy who better watch his head is big-mouth Buchanan.
He's the one who boldly predicted a Falcons upset victory.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates have taken to calling him ``Broadway Ray'' after
Jets quarterback Joe Namath, who delivered on his victory guarantee
in Super Bowl III, which also was played in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe they should be calling him ``Hammer Ray'' after Fred
Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson was a Kansas City cornerback who spent the week
leading up to Super Bowl I bragging about how he was going to use
his ``hammer'' arm blows to nail Green Bay receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the game.
</P>
<P>
   Late in a resounding Packers victory, Williamson was knocked
unconscious and had to be carried off the field on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe Falcons defensive end Lester Archambeau, the
Broncos' stalwart offensive line has borrowed a few techniques from
ol' Freddie. Archambeau has accused Mark Schlereth and Co. of chop
blocking.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's what they were doing that day early last week at
Joe's Stone Crab restaurant, practicing their chopping technique on
the specialty of the house while ringing up a four-figure tab.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say those stone crabs made the lightest offensive
line in the NFL work harder than Archambeau, Travis Hall, Shane
Dronett and Chuck Smith will have to.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta running back Jamal Anderson will have to work extra hard
for his yards. The Broncos' defense against the rush has been
positively persnickety in the playoffs, holding the Dolphins and
Jets to a combined 28 yards on the ground. The Broncos' last four
opponents have run for fewer yards (98) than Anderson's
regular-season average (115.4).
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will be in deep swamp land if Anderson isn't able to
run with any more abandon than he did against the Vikings in the
NFC title game.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and the Falcons might as well pack their wading boots
along with their cleats. Because every Denver player who gets into
the game will have the kind of added motivation that no amount of
zeros in a playoff bonus check can buy.
</P>
<P>
   All they'll have to do is look at No. 7, who'll today dot the
``i'' in icon, which is what he has become since leaving Granada
Hills High for Stanford and then Denver.
</P>
<P>
   This is likely Elway's last game and there isn't a Bronco worth
saluting who wants to be responsible for the quarterback's Hall of
Fame career ending on a downer.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that when he's in the huddle and Elway says ``This is
you, Terrell,'' all he can think is ``Don't let that man down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why I say Davis dashes for more than 100 yards, his
backup Vaughn Hebron becomes the fourth player in Super Bowl
history to run a kickoff back for a touchdown, fullback Howard
Griffith catches a touchdown pass, the defense contains Anderson
and Elway becomes the oldest quarterback to win a Super Bowl and
only the sixth to guide his team to back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be Denver over Atlanta, 27-17. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
