<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA was in jeopardy a month ago, still may be a month from
now, and smells reasonably ripe for some serious questioning today.
</P>
<P>
   So we have decided to double the jeopardy. We also hope to
double the fun, while wondering if this game will be resurrected to
the level of fan-tastic. You should begin seeking questions,
because we think we have the answers:
</P>
<P>
   1. Answer: Suspect rebounding. Question: Why won't the Knicks
win the championship? And by suspect, we weren't referring to
Latrell Sprewell, who's a pretty mediocre rebounder - as a guard.
But Jeff Van Gundy has installed the squeezer at small forward, a
bold move when we point out that power forward Charles Oakley now
is unleashing his dirty tricks to further the cause of the Toronto
Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   How about playing Sprewell at off-guard? No, that's where Allen
Houston lives. Well, why is not having Oakley such a problem? Easy.
Marcus Camby, a twig, and Larry Johnson, a towering 6-foot-5
veteran with a questionable back, are the candidates at power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   2. Answer: Yes. Question: Will the Lakers be able to defeat Utah
in a playoff series? The reason could be Derek Harper, their
oldcomer at backup point guard. Even though Harper has been in the
league long enough to remember when Don Nelson was considered a
genius, he is willing and able to guard another playmaking
antiquity, John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm still in the league because of defense and my desire to win
a championship,` Harper said. `All I'm missing is a ring. That's my
purpose.`
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' committee approach to power forward should be enough
when factored with the expected maturity of Shaquille O'Neal, Eddie
Jones and Kobe `Jumpingbean'' Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   3. Answer: Not without a trade. Question: Will Dennis Rodman
pick up his sixth championship ring, giving him one more than he
has hanging from his nostrils and ears? The unemployed Worm's
current free-agent option is taking the $1 million exception from
Orlando, where he would re-enlist with old Pistons den leader Chuck
Daly.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuck is a bit short on good players. With Rodman at power
forward, the Magic could attempt moving Horace Grant and his
massive contract in exchange for help elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   4. Answer: Because they almost won it last season. Question: Why
will the Pacers win the Eastern Conference championship?
</P>
<P>
   5. Answer: `Just Chew It.` Question: What will Nike us as its
marketing slogan for a new shoe with a high-pressure air sole
designed for phat players who practiced the pick 'n' sweet roll
during the lockout?
</P>
<P>
   6. Answer: Anything else. Question: What will casual fans watch
when NBA games are telecast without Michael Jordan in the starring
role?
</P>
<P>
   subhead UCLA update
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, in part, to expanded rosters, three Bruins selected in
the second round of the 1998 draft figure to still be on NBA
rosters next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani McCoy, selected by Seattle with the 33rd pick, could earn
a musical chair along the Sonics' bench row. But wayward 6-10 high
school hotshot Rashard Lewis (No. 32) and 7-0 first-round choice
Vladimir Stepania (No. 14) could make McCoy's Seattle adventure a
brief one. Add to the frontcourt logjam another ex-Bruin, Don
MacLean, who's a probable keeper because of his shooting touch.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Bailey, the 45th pick by Phoenix, provides an aptitude for
defense and enough athletic intrigue for the Suns to temporarily
overlook his sporadic jumper.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Henderson, taken at 56 by Vancouver, has battled back from
an injury sustained during a tour of the CBA. But Henderson happens
to play the same position (small forward) as the Grizzlies' budding
superstar, Shareef Abdur-Rahim. A week or two at the Shawn Kemp
Buffet could make J.R. a power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O'Bannon reportedly cleared waivers and was re-signed
for a second season with the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead More cash for Nash
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Nash signed a six-year extension with Dallas last
week, the total haul was reported to be $18. Sounds like a bargain
for the point guard Nelson pried away from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it wasn't exactly a bargain because - according to agent
Bill Duffy - the number was off. How off?
</P>
<P>
   `Off by about 50 percent,` said Duffy, who listed the actual
retail cost of locking up Nash at $33 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   subhead Shot clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Percy Miller, known in hip-hop circles as rap superstar `Master
P,` has taken his CBA scoring average of 1.9 points-per-game to the
Charlotte Hornets' camp. It has been reported that Miller was a
scholarship player at the University of Houston until a knee injury
prevented him from making Cougar fans forget about Clyde Drexler.
According to Bob Bass, the Hornets' vice president of basketball
ops, `He's not a totally unskilled player.'' Good thing Bass isn't
his agent. ... Former Long Beach State ace James Cotton has started
his second season by scoring points with new Seattle coach Paul
Westphal... Second-year Utah point guard Jacque Vaughn says he
developed his open-court ballhandling skills by dribbling around
his mother's flower pots stationed at strategic points on the
driveway. ... Rookie guard Felipe Lopez, coverboy for `Sports
Illustrated` before he even played a game at St. John's, has been
impressive in the Vancouver camp. ... The Sixers look scary with
young talents Allen Iverson, Tim Thomas and rookie Larry Hughes,
but also provide flashback shudders with Benoit Benjamin and Stacey
King on their training camp roster. .. A knee injury to New Jersey
guard Kerry Kittles should mean big minutes for former Cleveland
High and Long Beach State star Lucious Harris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
