<HEADLINE>
CHALK THIS ONE UP: FALCONS WILL WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Here in South Florida, the just-off-the-airplane
tourists are strongly advised not to drive the streets in an
automobile with a ``Rent Me'' bumper sticker. In these parts, the
translation apparently reads ``Mug Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Also high on the list of local don't's would be the ``Viva
Fidel'' window decal. And while in Miami traffic, never cut off a
suspected Colombian drug lord, unless, of course, you paid extra at
Hertz for a bullet-proof Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   But on a personal note, I ain't scared of greater Miami ...
well, except for the waiting-list line at Joe's Stone Crab, or
trying to beat the chalk at Gulfstream Park. That's real fear.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, my only other concern after a week in Miami actually
amounts to nothing more than a nagging worry over a football
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   I keep thinking Atlanta wins today's Super Bowl XXXIII. Been
thinking that way for two weeks. Can't talk myself out of it. Don't
want to talk myself out of it. I feel strongly about it.
</P>
<P>
   As you will read this morning, Mr. LeBreton totally disagrees,
him being a strong backer of the Backstabbing Brothers, Elway and
Shanahan. Sure, they knifed Dan Reeves a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Gil takes Denver anyway. As you know, Denver is a rather
solid favorite, so consider this the easy way out for LeBreton, who
also bets nothing but the chalk at Gulfstream. Where's the thrill
in that, Gil? Loosen up. Live a little. Go to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, picking Atlanta to win this Super Bowl goes against all
end-of-January football logic.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs don't often win these games, which, of course, has nothing
to do with mutts, although point-spread underdogs usually end up as
Super Bowl Alpo. In 32 previous encounters, the favorite has won
24, more often than not in a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Shockingly enough, I have sound football reasons for liking the
Falcons today ... OK, sound might be stretching it. But here's what
I've got:
</P>
<P>
   An entertaining game breaks out today, and a good time will be
had by all observers, TV and live audience. Points will be scored
on a consistent basis. But once the Falcons have won _ make it
30-24 _ the reason will be defense.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, all-world running back for Denver and best
overall player in the NFL, fits into that category of ``you can't
stop him, you can only hope to contain him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have an obscure front four on defense, but this
Chuck Smith-Shane Dronett-Travis Hall-Lester Archambeau quartet
climbed into the spotlight two weeks ago in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with linebackers Jessie Tuggle and Cornelius Bennett,
they trashed a good Vikings running game. No, Robert Smith is not
Terrell Davis. But Minnesota's offensive line was much more highly
regarded than Denver's.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to drag a safety into run-stoppage due to the high-octane
Minnesota receivers, the Falcons went straight seven against the
run, and prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Give Davis his 100 yards rushing today. But if that's all the
Atlanta defense allows, give or take 10 yards, then the Falcons
spring the upset. Davis has to have a very large game because these
days he carries John Elway and the Denver offense.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what was seen in Minnesota, the theory from here is the
Falcons can put the ``contain'' on Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's one other thing that swings me over to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Spunk.
</P>
<P>
   It was a team repeatedly programmed for an el foldo throughout
the Minnesota game. The expected blowout win for the Vikings
appeared to be happening in the first half when offensive turnovers
and offensive ineptness hit the Falcons. But they hung in, got the
break on a fumble just before halftime, scored off it, and stayed
upright.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth quarter, the game again appeared to be over,
several times. Like the Vikings up by 10 and Atlanta going nowhere.
Like the Vikings up by seven and needing a gimme field goal to cap
the win. But the Falcons had the right combination of spunk and
luck (on Gary Anderson's missed field-goal attempt) to eventually
pull off the shocking upset in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Never underestimate spunk. Or, for that matter, Chris Chandler,
who for this season has been a better quarterback than Elway.
</P>
<P>
   I take my chances today with both Atlanta and a rental car on
Miami streets. If I'm wrong, mug me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
