<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS WILL DANCE TO VICTORY BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As I write this, from down on the street below, I can
hear the rhythms of a live band, playing a Brazilian samba.
</P>
<P>
   At a cafe two blocks further down, I can order filet of
crocodile with a robust tapa of chickpeas with sausage and ham.
</P>
<P>
   According to my Haitian cab driver last night, the problem in
Miami isn't that the area is a cultural melting pot _ on the
contrary, it's more of a simmering bouillabaisse. The lines between
the cultures are clearly drawn.
</P>
<P>
   So let's not confuse a silly dance like the Dirty Bird with a
true tango like the Denver Broncos, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons, who do the Dirty Bird, are one Chris
Chandler catastrophe from being nothing more than the funky
chickens _ without the sausage and ham. What I'm trying to say is,
just a few weeks ago John Elway and the Broncos were bulletproof
and 13-and-0.
</P>
<P>
   But some people forget. They have leaped onto the Falcons'
bandwagon. Do they think Tommy Nobis is still the middle
linebacker? Don't they realize that the Atlanta Falcons making the
Super Bowl is one of the signs of the apocalypse?
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the Broncos were being hailed as, perhaps, the
greatest NFL aggregation ever. The Cowboys' defense never did stop
them. They scored 74 points in two games on the Oakland Raiders.
They won at Kansas City, 30-7. Denver had two receivers who scored
at least 10 touchdowns and the league's best player this year,
running back Terrell Davis, reached the end zone 23 times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, thanks to one show-stealing afternoon in Minneapolis, the
Falcons have swayed a few foolish hearts _ like that of our new guy
here, Mr. Galloway's.
</P>
<P>
   My pick in Super Bowl XXXIII? Dull, granted. But dull and safe.
</P>
<P>
   In that NFC title game, Randy says he saw an underrated,
run-challenging defense that battled and eventually outplayed the
vaunted Vikings for 60 minutes-plus.
</P>
<P>
   I say the Vikings choked. It was one of the biggest choke jobs
in NFL playoff history since, well, the Broncos lost to
Jacksonville in the 1996 divisional round and the Colts lost to the
Jets in Super Bowl III. That big.
</P>
<P>
   So-called experts have suggested that the Broncos' inability to
sustain a pass rush without blitzing could be their undoing. With
time, they say, quarterback Chandler will pick apart the Denver
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Everybody blitzes. Chandler was sacked 45 times during the
regular season. The Broncos defense, as a group, had 47 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting: If Chandler gets shaken up and has to leave, which
can happen, Atlanta's quarterback becomes 45-year-old Steve DeBerg.
Quit laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of our defense is to stop the run,'' Denver
cornerback Ray Crockett said. ``When you try to stop the run,
sometimes you put your secondary in some uncompromising situations.
We know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're very aggressive. In our secondary, we may give up
some plays, but we're going to come up with some big plays
ourselves. Look at the turnovers we've had in the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   In beating the Dolphins and Jets to get to the Super Bowl, the
Broncos recovered five fumbles and stole four passes. Nine
turnovers to none by the opponents.
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos are in a slump, what are the Cowboys in?
</P>
<P>
   Denver manhandled Miami in its first playoff game, 38-3, making
Jimmy Johnson think he'd be better off unemployed. The Broncos
trailed New York at halftime the next week, but won, 23-10, in a
game where the icy winds made two very good teams look like less
than they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen these guys on film,'' Denver linebacker Bill
Romanowski said of the Falcons. ``We know how good they are. But we
know it's really not about them _ it's about us. It's about playing
our style of football and playing our best game on Sunday. If we do
that, we'll win the game and go back-to-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. There is another factor here as well. The Elway's
Last Game factor. If you're going to go with the Dirty Birds,
you're going to have to convince me that the football gods would
allow somebody to spoil Elway's last hurrah. I don't see it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Super Bowl, the best team almost always wins. It's dull.
It's not very thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   But it's like my guess _ Broncos 27, Falcons 21. Boring and
safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
