<HEADLINE>
MOORE PROVIDES SUBTLE SPARK FOR UNDEFEATED UCONN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Guys like Quinn Buckner, Scott May and Kent Benson
have been waiting for Connecticut to fall off the edge it has been
living on. Say this about the Huskies _ they've got a strong grip.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Connecticut overcame a 12-point deficit in the final
17 minutes to defeat No. 9 St. John's, 78-74, in a scintillating
Big East Conference game yesterday at Madison Square Garden. The
Huskies, who trailed at halftime for the fourth consecutive game,
are 19-0 and the nation's only unbeaten Division I team.
</P>
<P>
   That won't sit well with Hoosiers like Buckner, May and Benson,
key players on the last team to run the table. Indiana was 32-0 in
1976. Now, the pressure is too great, the sport too balanced, for a
team to be perfect from November to March. UNLV couldn't do it,
Duke couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut is undefeated _ for now _ and a serious national
championship contender because of players like Ricky Moore. The
Huskies' lone senior, Moore exerted a subtle, beyond-the-box score
influence on victory No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   His team trailing by eight in the second half, Moore was the
only defender on a 3-on-1 Red Storm fast break. He stole the ball,
sprinted back the other way, was fouled and made both free throws.
Four-point swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' junior forward Richard Hamilton (22 points) said in a
serious tone, ``was a huge play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later Moore broke St. John's press and bounce-passed
to junior center Jake Voskuhl. His slam gave the Huskies the lead
for good, 67-65 with 4:41 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a player play as hard all the time as Ricky
Moore,'' said Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun, whose team plays No.
17 Syracuse tomorrow and is at No. 3 Stanford on Saturday. ``This
is the happiest I've ever seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   He could be a sad or angry former point guard, a bad influence
on a young team. The point guard job became Khalid El-Amin's last
season. Moore is ``the other guard'' and is asked to play defense
first, everything else second.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at who he gets matched up with,'' Voskuhl said. ``He
shuts down the other team's best guys. He should be Big East
defensive player of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's defensive assignment was Bootsy Thornton, who had 40
against Duke and 61 in his past two games. Thornton finished with
15.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game fit for a facility that bills itself as ``the
world's most famous arena.'' The Garden was rocking, two-thirds Red
Storm, one-third Huskies. Connecticut blitzed to a 16-3 lead; St.
John's stormed the offensive boards to go up, 43-38, at halftime.
Then the lead reached 12 and the Huskies said, ``Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't won, we wouldn't have lost,'' Calhoun said in his
best Casey Stengel. ``We would have been beaten. That's what we
strive for. Make the other team beat you. St. John's has some
tremendous warriors. They're as good as anybody we'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's five losses have been to Stanford, Purdue, Miami
(Fla.), Duke and Connecticut by a total of 16 points. And the Red
Storm will get better when their best post player, Tyrone Grant,
returns from his broken wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, we didn't deliver the knockout punch,'' said St. John's
coach Mike Jarvis, whose team is 17-5. ``But our day is coming.
Soon.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's is a team with marvelous talent that plays zealously,
but has yet to learn how to win. What the Red Storm needs is a
player like Ricky Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down 12 and I wanted to win bad,'' Moore said. ``If we
go out and don't quit, we've got the talent and experience to win.
We showed a lot of heart today. Again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
