</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-CHANDLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YEARS OF REJECTION, CHANDLER FINDS A HOME IN ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It would be easy for Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler
to use his Super Bowl platform and yell out a hearty, ``Ha, I told
you so'' to the teams that gave up on him.
</P>
<P>
   First, he would probably run out of breath, as the list is
numerous _ namely the Colts, the Buccaneers, the Cardinals, the
Rams and the Oilers. None of the teams viewed Chandler as a
franchise quarterback that could take them to pro football's
greatest stage.
</P>
<P>
   However, Chandler, 33, the former castoff who is now a Pro Bowl
quarterback and who will lead the Atlanta Falcons into today's
Super Bowl XXXIII matchup with the Denver Broncos at Pro Player
Stadium, chooses to savor the moment rather than search for
vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here is satisfaction for sure,'' Chandler said. ``But I
don't feel I'm getting back at anybody. The teams that gave up on
me, I think it's proven they made a mistake. But I try not to look
in the past. I think the best way to deal with it is forget about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's satisfaction, the way my career has gone to be in a
situation like this, to be with a good team and to be in the Super
Bowl. But, sure, sometimes I think about, wow, it's been a real
strange trip for me.''
</P>
<P>
   What a trip it has been.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's 11-year career includes the dubious distinction of
having started for more teams (six) than any NFL quarterback since
the 1970 merger. The five teams before the Falcons all discarded
him for someone else, someone they thought had more potential.
</P>
<P>
   He was drafted by the Colts in 1988 and earned all-rookie
honors. The next year he was injured, and the Colts drafted Jeff
George in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win nine games my rookie year with the Colts and almost go
to the playoffs,'' Chandler said. ``I think I'm going to be in Indy
forever. But I hurt my knee the next year and they totally give up
on me. I was on the golf course when I found out about them
drafting George.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay traded for him, but made him the backup to Vinny
Testaverde for a year and half. The Cardinals were next. There he
met quarterbacks coach Jerry Rhome, whom Chandler credits with
teaching him how to play quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   However, what looked to be a breakthrough _ considering that
Chandler passed for a then-career high 2,832 yards and 15
touchdowns in 1992 _ was only a mirage. The Cardinals signed Steve
Beuerlein in the off-season and made him their quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a move by them to point the finger at me for the team
not winning games,'' Chandler said. ``We were in a lot of games and
lost a lot of close games. I thought we had a pretty good year,
considering the team we had. When they brought in Steve, it was a
big disappointment, then a year later I was going somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on to the Rams, until the Rams decided Chris Miller was
their man. The Oilers followed, but he was only a stop-gap move in
the grooming process for Steve McNair.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, the ninth of 10 children growing up in Everett, Wash.,
knows the meaning of waiting your turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team basically does kind of give up on you and decides
that maybe another direction would be better, it's disappointing,''
Chandler said. ``It's hard when you keep going through those
things. It's nice to finally be in a situation where I don't have
to worry about that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler found a home and a coach he could trust when Dan Reeves
joined the Falcons in 1997 and acquired him from the Oilers for two
low-round draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been with a few football teams, questions come to
your mind like `Can I do it?' '' Reeves said. ``We knew he was a
capable quarterback. His toughness has been tested. But he was a
good quarterback when he came here and he's as accurate as any
quarterback I've been around.''
</P>
<P>
   After fighting through injuries last season, Chandler rewarded
Reeves' faith with a Pro Bowl season in 1998. He passed for 3,154
yards and 25 touchdowns and was the league's fourth-ranked passer
with a quarterback rating of 106.1. No one was better in the fourth
quarter, when Chandler fashioned a league-best quarterback rating
of 121.8.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who was given a four-year, $25 million contract
extension, said the key for him is finally finding an organization
that believes in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a chance to be a leader of the team,'' Chandler
said. ``When you have belief from the head coach, the front office,
the players and the whole organization it makes your job easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Chandler is considered by many experts as the key to
the Falcons' reversal from a 3-13 squad in 1996 to a Super Bowl
team two years later. The Falcons are 22-4 when he has started at
quarterback the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good quarterback and we believe in him,'' Falcons
receiver Terance Mathis said. ``Chris Chandler being here is
probably the driving force for us being in the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy nobody wanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
