<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBERG THROWS HIMSELF BACK INTO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The envelope showed up empty, which is what most people
thought of Steve DeBerg's idea of making a comeback. Maybe that is
what made this most odd thing possible.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, a guy who was named the NFL's Comeback Player of the
Year nine years ago had the kind of idea guys too often have when
they hit their mid 40s. DeBerg decided he wanted to go back to the
future.
</P>
<P>
   With his future cloudy, his past fading, and his present on
hold, the former quarterback of the San Francisco 49ers, Denver
Broncos, Tampa Bay Buccaneers, Kansas City Chiefs, and Miami
Dolphins wanted to be a kid again before it was too late. His
friends thought he'd gone middle-age crazy, but not because he
bought a sports car or took up disco dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the usual middle-age ventures into temporary
insanity, DeBerg decided he'd play professional football _ five
years after he'd retired from the game and a year after he stopped
coaching with the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg did not come to this decision lightly. He tested himself
first. He went back to the wars, back under center _ although a bit
more gingerly than before. What he did was join a coed flag
football league in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   After success at that level, why not the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried like hell not to let people know who I was,'' said
DeBerg, who is now 45. ``Playing with girls really made me work on
my touch. That's really where this all started. I was throwing well
enough to realize I still had some skills.''
</P>
<P>
   After a divorce and a drunk-driving arrest refocused his life,
DeBerg was trying to decide whether he truly wanted to continue
making the kind of sacrifices NFL assistant coaches make,
sacrifices he tried for two seasons under Dan Reeves with the
Giants and hated.
</P>
<P>
   The long days and longer nights, the endless hours watching film
in stuffy rooms, the absence of free time even to exercise
convinced him this might not be the way he wanted to spend the rest
of his professional life. But now that he was alone, DeBerg was
looking for something, and football had always been the answer. So
why not one more time?
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was just trying to get back into shape,'' he said.
``I was a long way away from the game last year. I had seen what a
tremendous personal sacrifice it took to be an NFL coach, so I was
trying to figure out a way to stay in professional football without
those 16-hour days. What I came up with was as a backup
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what I did was throw footballs into nets to get back
in shape, and eventually, I got the idea I might possibly get
invited to a training camp this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   To facilitate that, DeBerg sent out letters to most NFL teams.
One landed on Reeves's desk in Atlanta last June. But when he
opened it to see what his former quarterback and assistant was up
to, the Falcons coach found nothing inside, so he picked up the
phone, and a resurrection had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan called and said, `Steve, what is this empty envelope?' ''
DeBerg recalled. ``I told him it was supposed to be a letter that I
was interested in restarting my career. I had no idea Dan was in a
predicament with his quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Serendipity? Perfect timing? Call it what you will, but DeBerg's
envelope arrived just as Reeves was learning that his newly signed
backup quarterback, Mark Rypien, was considering retirement because
his young son was seriously ill with a disease that proved fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing he needed someone and being familiar with DeBerg both
from when he coached him in Denver (1981-83) and had him on his
staff with the Giants (1995-96), Reeves decided to take a look at a
man who apparently wanted to become the George Foreman of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, he didn't expect much. But seeing would be believing,
and Reeves saw more than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer we got to training camp, with what we had and what
we were willing to spend _ which was nothing _ there were very few
people that had experience with our offense, so we gave him one of
the longest workouts ever,'' Reeves recalled. ``He just threw the
ball great. If a guy can do it, I don't care if he's 25 or 45.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing, because when Reeves's Falcons challenge the
defending champion Broncos at Pro Player Stadium Sunday in the
Super Bowl, Steve DeBerg will be one hard hit away from replacing
starter Chris Chandler and carrying the hopes of a team and a city
on his 45-year-old shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   To say this is remarkable is an understatement. To say it is
absurd is not far from the truth, either. To say it is fun for the
oldest quarterback in the NFL is as precise as any pass DeBerg has
ever thrown, because few people get a chance like this, and no one
understands that better than the man who has been given it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity of a lifetime to even be invited to a
training camp,'' DeBerg said. ``To earn a backup position and be as
involved as I've been, I feel like the luckiest person in the
world. Really. There's a great sense of personal achievement making
an NFL team this year. That was a Super Bowl for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a lot of letters and calls from people my age who are
really excited about what I'm doing. I'm satisfied to just help the
team from the sidelines, but I know I'm one hit away from
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   To find himself in this position is doubly odd because 16 years
ago, DeBerg was starting ahead of the now-aging quarterback of the
Broncos, John Elway. This week there has been much talk about
whether this game will be Elway's last even as DeBerg says he hopes
to come back next season. It's a turn of events Elway finds
remarkable, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' Elway said. ``He's got nine lives. To
play as long as he has, you have to do a great job taking care of
your body, and that's what he's done. He seemed old to me when I
first came into the league (DeBerg was 30). I thought he was
ancient. Now I feel ancient.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Steve has always had the physical and mental attributes to
do it, and I'm sure with his experience and his coaching experience
with the Giants under Dan and now coming back as a player, he's
like another coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right spot
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely how DeBerg sees his role. When he made the
decision in 1994 to retire, it was because he feared he could end
up in Miami or with the New York Jets in another role. Each was a
team DeBerg felt might need him to become a full-time starter
because Dan Marino was struggling to recover from a torn Achilles'
tendon and the Jets had no one to play the position. At 40, DeBerg
knew his body wanted no part of that, so he left the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When the decision was made to reverse that decision last summer,
DeBerg did not kid himself. He understood that starting in a coed
flag league in Tampa is not quite the same as starting even one
Sunday in the NFL. The latter he knew he could handle, just as he
believes he could handle replacing Chandler Sunday in the biggest
game of his career, if necessary. But he also understood the limits
of being a coach on the field, so he decided to try a comeback that
wouldn't exceed his grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there would have been a team that presented an opportunity
to do what I did with the Falcons this year in 1994, I probably
wouldn't have retired,'' DeBerg said. ``It was the physical part of
starting 16 games that I was worried about. I figured I was pushing
the envelope there.''
</P>
<P>
   So for five years, DeBerg left the NFL until the day an empty
envelope was pushed onto Reeves's desk and a football resurrection
began. Sunday it will culminate in Super Bowl XXXIII, a game that
won't be coed and won't be touch football but will be a crowning
moment for an old guy who's still young at heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next July, I plan to try to make a football team,'' DeBerg
said. ``I really think that my concept of coming into this
situation and believing that I could contribute to a football team
is valid. I'm like a quarterback tutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so much more fun than coaching, I'd like to try and
do it again. Chris had a quarterback coach and a quarterback tutor
this year. It was a tremendous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed that _ for the student and for the tutor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
