<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-PENGUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS REMAIN IN A FUNK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ He doesn't say much; never has. As a leader, Ray
Bourque has always preferred to let his play speak for itself, but
Saturday the Bruins captain felt that wasn't nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   So, Bourque called a rare players' meeting after the abysmal 5-2
loss to the Penguins at the Igloo. He implored his teammates to
wake up out of the funk they're in, pay attention to business, and
straighten out whatever it is that has caused the team to lose four
straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's aggravation has been growing. After the team's 4-1
loss to the Islanders in New York last Tuesday, Bourque, who
normally takes his time and is one of the last to leave the
dressing room, was among the first to exit, and his face was the
picture of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   It's even rarer to hear coach Pat Burns say he was out of things
to say, which is as startling as Microsoft chairman Bill Gates
saying he has run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' top line of Jason Allison, Dmitri Khristich, and
Sergei Samsonov continues to disappoint. The most damning statistic
with regard to the trio is that they totaled just one shot in the
first 40 minutes, despite the fact that the Bruins had four
power-play attempts. They are taking up a third of the available
ice time and doing nothing with it.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, if there was any, was the team shut down Jaromir
Jagr's line (ending Jagr's point streak at 13 games), but that
opened the floodgates for the line of Alexei Kovalev (two goals,
one assist), German Titov (one goal, two assists), and Robert Lang
(two assists).
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he is frustrated by the repeated mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old thing,'' he said. ``We played pretty well,
we had a couple of missed assignments, and we come in 2-2 after the
first, playing not bad. It's not good enough. We should've been
leading after the first. Same old thing. We keep making mistakes
that are costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Burns) keeps harping on it. He keeps telling us and there's
not much more (the coaches) can do. Guys in this room have to pay
attention a little more to what's going on out there. Until we take
care of the little details, things we go over every day, every day
. . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Burns is increasingly frustrated by the inertia that has set in
with his first line. He benched Allison, Khristich, and the left
wing du jour _ Steve Heinze _ in the third period against the
Islanders. Samsonov was reunited with his linemates Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what their problem is,'' said Burns. ``I just
talked about it in the room. Nobody's being too hard on them. I
don't think anybody should be nervous about anything. I think we
should settle down and play as a team instead of maybe playing as
individuals. I don't care, I'll play five or six of my best
forwards, the guys who want to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who you are, but you're going to have some kind
of commitment in what you want to do for the team. It could be a
little bit of the sophomore part, they think, `Hey, we're great.'
You're not great, you're not great at all right now. You're not
very good right now, so you'd better have a better look at
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Being benched) is a part of hockey. I've seen the greatest
players benched before. If that's what bugs you, you'd better
change occupations.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ferraro gave Boston a 1-0 lead at 4:31 of the first, but
Kovalev pulled the Penguuins even at 7:44. Joe Thornton made it 2-1
at 11:33, but Kovalev knotted it again at 14:24.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was scoreless and the third was a nightmare
for the Bruins, as they gave up an even-strength goal to defenseman
Kevin Hatcher at 2:29, a shorthanded goal to Martin Straka at 7:26,
and a final goal to Titov at 15:14.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time since November 1997 that they've lost four
consecutive games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
