<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FAMILY OF BLACK VICTIM SAYS THEY FORGIVE THREE WHITE MEN ACCUSED OF
KILLING HIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JAMIE STOCKWELL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Nearly eight months after a black man from East Texas
was chained to the back of a truck and dragged to his death,
members of his family said they have forgiven the three white men
accused of killing him.
</P>
<P>
   The family of James Byrd Jr., whose death sparked national and
international attention, said they are past the anger and animosity
and are now looking toward the potential positive effects Byrd's
violent death will have on a torn society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I hate in return?'' asked Byrd's 17-year-old
daughter, Jamie Byrd. ``That would be what the men who killed my
dad did and I'm not like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Byrd's family is hoping for passage of a new hate
crimes bill in the Legislature that would be named the ``James Byrd
Jr. Hate Crimes Act.'' The bill, sponsored by Sen. Rodney Ellis and
Rep. Senfronia Thompson, both Houston Democrats, was the focal
point of a rally Saturday afternoon on the steps of the Capitol
where Byrd's family and a slew of legislators, lobbyists and
anti-violence organizations gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Byrd said the deep anger she felt toward the accused
killers when her father's dismembered body was found June 7 on a
back road outside Jasper has subsided. Her hope is that no one else
will ever be victimized by such a crime again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first heard about it, I was seeing all this stuff in
my head. Of course I was mad and I just thought, `Let me take them
and drag them.' That's how I was feeling, but then I was thinking
about it and I was like, `God can do anything. God will take care
of it,' '' said the Lufkin High School student.
</P>
<P>
   Her father's death, she said, has made her more aware of
people's intentions and even more cautious of who she trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not racist or anything. But now I'm more aware of
everything and I can't tell who's a Klansman,'' she said. ``When I
go to school and I see the Confederate flags on trucks I picture my
dad and when he was on the back of the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a loss of innocence, perhaps, but not a loss of hope, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't see her father's death as a ``white people issue,''
but something caused by the hatred of a particular group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a best friend who's white and I walk around with her
and people are like, `How can she do that?' and I guess they think
I'm supposed to hate but she's been my best friend for years and
this could've happened to her dad, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's rally came at the end of the first week of jury
selection in the trial of one of the men accused of capital murder
in Byrd's death. John William ``Bill'' King, 24, of Jasper, who has
served time in prison for burglary, is the first to stand trial. He
has denied killing Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   The other two defendants are King's friends, Lawrence Russell
Brewer Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs and Shawn Berry, 23, of Jasper.
Trial dates have not been set for them.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's nephew, Darrell Verrett of Houston, said the tragedy has
united the family and he urged them to push for change in a state
that has often been resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal in supporting this bill is to show how we
retaliate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Previous efforts to clarify Texas' hate crimes law _ which
doesn't list specific groups that might be victims of a crime of
prejudice or violence _ died in the 1995 and 1997 legislative
sessions. Many legal and law enforcement officials believe that it
is difficult to enforce the current law, which was adopted in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill would change the definition so that any offense
motivated by race, disability, religion, or sexual orientation
could be prosecuted as a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister, Louvon Harris of Jasper, said her brother would
be proud to know that his sacrifice contributed to such positive
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is a good thing. It's very much needed in this
state,'' Harris said. ``I think my brother would be proud to have
his name associated with something this good.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Rally of Hope,'' which was organized by the Lesbian and
Gay Rights Lobby of Texas, attracted several anti-violence groups,
including the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People and the American Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 200 people, carrying posters bearing such phrases
as ``Who will they come for next?'' and ``Show some compassion,
George Bush,'' applauded the efforts of legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that his (Byrd) legislators let him down, I think that
his police let him down and that his neighbors, all of us let him
down and we can't let that happen again,'' said Gal Lahat of the
American Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Hardy-Garcia, the executive director for the Lesbian and
Gay Rights Lobby, said that 2,400 hate crimes were documented in
Texas between 1992 and 1997, and that the number of crimes would
increase unless the Legislature intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett, Byrd's nephew, said that his family will take turns
attending King's trial. He said ``the penalty should fit the
crime'' when asked whether he believed in the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has forgiven the ones who killed my uncle. There's no
use for us to show hatred back,'' Verrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said she wants people to remember her brother for the
kind and good man he was, not the black man whose body was found
along a road early one Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved people. He spent his life entertaining people and was
well-known in Jasper. His death is a loss to the town and he will
always be remembered for who he was and remains to be,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
