u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-ST.JOHNS-BO     01-30 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-ST.JOHNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN KEEPS STREAK ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The question still is ``when'', not ``if'', UConn
will lose, which is what you must deal with if you are the only
unbeaten team remaining in Division 1; are a No. 1 team more than a
few people think is not as good as once-beaten and No. 2 Duke; and
are a team many people thought would lose to No. 9 St. John's
Saturday at Madison Square Garden in what was billed as the most
signficant Big East game in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Think again. In a setting that had a tournament feel to it, with
the sellout crowd of 19,528 and a national television audience,
UConn did what it has done all season, posting a 78-74 victory that
should at end _ at least temporarily _ any question about the
Huskies' credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team,'' said coach Jim Calhoun with a mixture of pride
and awe, ``is not ready to let go of that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows St. John's, which is now 17-5 (8-2 in conference) and
getting better each game, tried to take it away. The Red Storm
tried as hard as anyone the Huskies have played in this storybook
season in which UConn's record now is 19-0, with games against No.
17 Syracuse Monday night and at No. 3 Stanford Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm surge was constant after a slow start in which
they fell behind, 16-3, in the first five minutes. By the half they
were ahead, 43-38. Three minutes into the second half they were up
12, and all the sages out there predicting a fall from the
mountaintop for the Huskies were nodding their heads, wearing their
I-told-you-so-looks.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun was so upset with what was happening that he called a
timeout. ``I very rarely take a full timeout (that early),'' said
Calhoun, who then used most of it letting his team think about
where it was _ or wasn't _ going. ``Khalid (El-Amin) said some
things. Ricky (Moore) said some things.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, as they have in their last three games, against Miami,
Seton Hall and Georgetown, when they found themselves trailing in
the second half, the Huskies found a way.
</P>
<P>
   This time help came in the form of Moore, the senior guard who
has changed roles the past two years and been shuffled behind
Richard Hamilton and El-Amin on the list of UConn's ``go-to'' guys.
</P>
<P>
   But in one five-minute stretch, Moore showed some vintage skills
on offense, defense, and in running a team. ``He simply took over
the game,'' said Calhoun, who watched Moore stop a three-on-one
fast break, block a shot, go end-to-end, get fouled, and make a
pair of free throws, and go end-to-end again, dumping off a pass to
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to speed the tempo up, get the game going the
way we wanted,'' said Moore, who only had 6 points but had six
assists and also shut down Bootsie Thornton (15 points, but only 3
in the second half when Moore was covering him).
</P>
<P>
   Moore provided the first UConn surge. From there, Hamilton (a
team-high 22 points, El-Amin (15), and Kevin Freeman (16) pushed it
to the point where the Huskies and Johnnies were matching baskets
and big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the game of basketball is about,'' said St.
John's coach Mike Jarvis, who has watched his team play its guts
out this week and still be saddled with losses to No. 1 UConn and
No. 2 Duke. ``It's about runs and who will be the last team to make
the last run.''
</P>
<P>
   That was UConn. The Huskies got a Jake Voskuhl dunk that made it
67-65 with 4:34 left and gave them their first lead in the second
half, and they went from there.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had a run left and St. John's didn't and that was
the difference in the game, the most anticipated Big East matchup
since a 1985 when the Johnnies knocked off No. 1 Georgetown, 66-65.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn is one of the most arrogant teams,'' said St. John's
forward Ron Artest, shaking his head at another disappointment (the
Johnnies have lost their five games by a total of 16 points). ``But
they always back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 19-0, and how many teams have done that in the Big
East,'' said Calhoun, knowing that the end of the streak could come
as quickly as Monday if the Huskies continue to play from behind.
``But we're not giving this one back and we're just not going to
just give teams a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
