<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS TO STANFORD HELPED UCLA'S GADZURIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While handing UCLA its most disappointing defeat of
the season, Stanford did the Bruins a favor they won't soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal angered Dan Gadzuric, and he's been a terror ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-10 freshman, Gadzuric cannot specify exactly what the
Cardinal did to invoke his wrath. But sometime early in the second
half, Gadzuric got mad. And when he got mad, he got aggressive. And
when he got aggressive, he became unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm establishing stronger position inside than I was earlier
in the season,'' Gadzuric said. ``During the Stanford game, it just
happened. It was a personal thing. A feeling took over me. I don't
know what it is. But I'm hanging with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronger position in the low post means Gadzuric is in better
position to receive passes from his teammates and better position
to score. He carved up the Cardinal for 15 points, his best game of
the season by far, and he has scored 47 points in his last 75
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After two months of passive positioning, Gadzuric now overpowers
defenders for real estate in the low post and foul lane. He has a
variety of rapidly improving moves, from a soft turnaround to a
fledgling hook. Sometimes, he'll be in good enough position to
simply catch and dunk. In the last three games, he's shooting 77
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the ankle he sprained at USC has slowed Gadzuric. He
missed the Louisville game, then scored 16 points in 21 minutes
Thursday in UCLA's lethargic win at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the real pluses,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin
said. ``I was struggling to find any positives to put on the
chalkboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric did not practice Saturday because of soreness in his
right ankle and knees. But he's expected to play today against his
biggest challenge of the season _ Washington's 7-foot senior, Todd
MacCulloch, who averages 18.3 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The ankle) is a concern going against MacCulloch,'' Lavin
said. ``He's so big. He's a mountain. Collectively, we have to have
an awareness of where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Gadzuric's recent rise, the Huskies probably will have an
eye on him, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lineup shuffle? Freshmen Matt Barnes and Ray Young practiced
with the starters Saturday in place of the injured Gadzuric and
slumping forward JaRon Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin indicated he might make a change today. Rush is the weak
link on offense _ 35 percent shooting, 21 percent from 3-point
range _ but his defense and rebounding are indispensable. He leads
the Bruins in rebounding in conference play and preserved
Thursday's win with two deflections in the final 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray gives us more perimeter shooting,'' Lavin said. ``JaRon
has played well when he's come off the bench. They all have. They
know they'll still play the equivalent of a starter's minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who is 6-8, may be used to offset Washington's 6-8 power
forward, Chris Walcott.
</P>
<P>
   Point of attack: MacCulloch, Deon Luton and Donald Watts
generate most of Washington's offense, but freshman point guard
Senque Carey is quickly becoming an impact player.
</P>
<P>
   Since replacing Dan Dickau (broken foot) six games ago, Carey
has averaged 13.8 points and run the offense capably. (He had 19
points and five assists Thursday against USC.) No doubt, he's high
on UCLA's priority list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has given Washington a different dimension,'' Lavin said.
``They're a more difficult matchup than when Dickau was in the
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
