<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      01-30 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'LL TAKE THE FALCONS PLUS 45 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway is a punk and a juvenile
delinquent and you'd know it if you got your first real
professional job the year Elvis died, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Laverne &AMP; Shirley was on TV (not in reruns). Star Wars was in
the theaters (not in reruns.) Jimmy Carter was president (he
re-ran, but lost).
</P>
<P>
   And a quarterback named Steve De- &QL; 
Berg got drafted into the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg signed a contract for $18,000 that year, about four times
the deal I negotiated for myself as a newly hired reporter with the
Burlington County Herald in Mount Holly, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg passed for 33,782 yards, 13th in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before this past season, the ``retired'' quarterback
(he'd been coaching since 1993) got a tryout with the Atlanta
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him one of the longest workouts ever,'' Coach Dan
Reeves said at the time, ``And he just threw the ball great. If a
guy can do it, I don't care if he's 25 or 45.'' &QL; 
INSPIRING, THRILLING
</P>
<P>
   There's something heartening, something inspiring, something
thrilling about a guy appearing in the Super Bowl at 45. At least
there is to guys like me, who are 44.
</P>
<P>
   The year Madame Curie turned 44, she won her second Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   At 44, Puccini composed the opera Madame Butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   At 44, Orwell wrote 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, in our country, none of that sissified highbrow stuff
matters.
</P>
<P>
   However, an American male does begin to reassess his life and
his accomplishments, to sense that he's slipped into middle-age,
when there's no longer anyone older than him playing professional
football or baseball or basketball.
</P>
<P>
   For us, for now, there's DeBerg.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all been a great experience for me,'' he told a
reporter recently. ``Some guys were asking me the other day if we
wore face masks when I first started playing.''
</P>
<P>
   I know how this goes.
</P>
<P>
   Young journalists, curious about how it was when I started,
sometimes ask me if newspapers provided reporters with supplies
back then, or if we had to buy our own chisels and stone tablets. &QL; 
DOING IT FOR LOVE
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg doesn't dwell on the old days. He says even the money
he's earning now doesn't mean as much to him as simply being in the
game, doing what he loves to do, having an impact.
</P>
<P>
   It's all that any man asks.
</P>
<P>
   Dostoyevsky published Crime and Punishment when he was 45.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne published The Scarlet Letter.
</P>
<P>
   Tolkien published The Hobbit.
</P>
<P>
   Men like this prove beyond any doubt that a viable, hard-working
intelligent individual, no matter what his age, can become a
pompous blowhard once he loses his ability to throw the ball
downfield or scramble out of the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Some fellows defy the odds and manage to set an example in
professions outside the world of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Berry recorded My Ding-a-Ling at the age of 45. Mark Twain
learned to ride a bicycle at 55. Ambrose Bierce wandered off in
Mexico, and disappeared, at 71.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's Pablo Picasso, whose common-law wife
left him after finding out that he'd been cheating on her _ at 82.
</P>
<P>
   Among quarterbacks, however, there's only DeBerg.
</P>
<P>
   When Broncos superstar John Elway first came into the league 16
years ago, he replaced an ``aging'' DeBerg in the Denver backfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was ancient then,'' Elway said recently of
DeBerg. ``Now, I feel ancient.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in this country when we'd have expected
something more deferential from a 38-year-old like Elway. Something
more respectful.
</P>
<P>
   But, whatta ya gonna do?
</P>
<P>
   Kids these days. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
