<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SYRACUSE-SETONHAL     01-30 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SYRACUSE-SETONHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETON HALL IS HUMBLED BY THE ORANGEMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In the opening minute of the second half
on Saturday night, Seton Hall point guard Shaheen Holloway raced up
the floor as a teammate dribbled up the middle on a fast break. As
he passed his bench, Holloway lost his footing, skidding past Coach
Tommy Amaker. When Holloway got back on his feet and hustled to the
other end, he found himself the victim of a 3-point play by his
counterpart, Syracuse's Jason Hart. Amaker mercifully pulled
Holloway out of the game. But if Holloway was enduring one of those
nights, his teammates were not faring much better against a
vengeful Syracuse squad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen led from start to finish, coasting past the
Pirates, 76-62, at the Continental Arena. While the teams had been
tied with 5-5 records in the Big East Conference entering the game,
they bore little in common on Saturday night as Syracuse (15-6,
6-5) handed Amaker his first loss to the Orangemen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holloway went head to head with Hart, the pair ranking No. 1 and
2, respectively, in the conference in assists. And Holloway clearly
got the worst of it. Actually, when Hart connected on a 3-point
field goal just 2 minutes 46 seconds into the game, he had gotten
the better of it.
</P>
<P>
   Hart finished with 24 points, matching his career high, while
Holloway (1 for 10 from the field) finished with just 3 points, his
only field goal coming on a lay-up with 1:17 remaining. He also had
six turnovers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At one point in these teams' rivalry, the Orangemen defeated the
Pirates 23 times in a row, a streak that ended in 1992. Before
Saturday, Seton Hall had won eight of the last 15 games, including
victories in the last two games. When Seton Hall defeated Syracuse
earlier this season, the Pirates were in the midst of a seven-game
winning streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they looked like a different team from the opening tip
Saturday, displaying the flaws that have contributed to losses in
their last three games. And Syracuse, which entered the game ranked
No.17 in the nation, bore little resemblance to the team that had
been embarrassed by the Pirates in the Carrier Dome on Dec. 12. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates fell behind by 12-2 in the opening minutes and never
seemed to recover. Seton Hall turned the ball over four times in
its first seven possessions, missed a layup, and had another shot
blocked.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes continued as the Pirates had three more turnovers
before the game was seven minutes old. At that point, the Pirates
started trying to beat the Orangemen with 1-on-1 moves, which did
not work, but may have seemed like a good idea since almost every
pass was either errant or deflected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, the Orangemen had built a 43-31 advantage and the
only thing that kept the Pirates that close was the unlikely
offensive production by Ramon Cespedes, and Syracuse's inability to
take advantage of the mistakes, missing 12 shots from within five
feet of the basket. Cespedes, who had attempted just two 3-point
field goals this season, hit a pair from behind the arc, and added
another jumper, scoring 8 points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hart had 12 points and three steals in the half for the
Orangemen. The usual scoring threats struggled for the Pirates _
Holloway was 0 for 5 with three turnovers in the half, Rimas
Kaukenas was 1 for 5 and Duane Jordan was 2 for 6. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall's struggles have coincided with a decidedly tougher
portion of its schedule. The three losses entering this game came
on the road, at Notre Dame, at No. 1 Connecticut and at No. 23
Miami. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 2236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
