</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZ-GOP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE GOP REJECTS PRIMARY DATE SOUGHT BY MCCAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX _ The Arizona Republican Party voted unanimously Saturday
to rec ommend leaving the state's presi dential party primary just
where it is, beating back a push to move it from mid-February to
March 14.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of the 400 Republican delegates believe the proposal to
hold a later primary was floated to help presidential aspirant John
Mc Cain avoid an early showdown with Steve Forbes in McCain's own
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get jerked around for the benefit of one person,''
Arizona Republican Caucus Chairwoman Becky Fenger, who advocated
keep ing the earlier primary, told the delegates to applause.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Forbes spent $2 million in political advertising in
Arizona and walked away with Arizona's delegates to the national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The voice vote was largely sym bolic, because the final decision
will be made by the state Legisla ture, but it will be difficult
for GOP lawmakers to ignore the wishes of their own state party
members.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was opening his presi dential campaign office in New
Hampshire on Saturday and was not available for comment following
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, McCain spokes woman Nancy Ives denied that the
proposal was being pushed by McCain, saying only that the Mc Cain
forces supported the idea because ``it is the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at the Civic Plaza in downtown Phoenix focused more
on national than on state issues.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with criticism from some Americans who say that Republi
cans have been too aggressive in their pursuit of Clinton and that
the GOP will suffer in 2000, speaker after speaker expressed
confidence that, in the end, Republicans would not be hurt by their
votes to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many said, they will likely benefit and be vindicated
for standing their ground in the face of poll data favoring
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz. ``But I believe in the end that if we do what's right,
we'll have nothing to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   The loudest ovations went to a speaker who was not even
originally on the program but who nonetheless twice brought
delegates to their feet. Former Vice President Dan Quayle dropped
in to the convention to say a few words about impeachment, Arizona
Republicans and his own presidential plans.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, a Paradise Valley resi dent, praised Republicans in Con
gress for casting their votes to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never witnessed such congressional courage as I did on
that day,'' Quayle said. ``And when you stand up for what's right,
you'll be vindicated. Maybe not in the short term, but in the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also told delegates to expect him to announce his own
presidential candidacy soon, perhaps as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In other business, Republicans also passed a resolution to
increase outreach efforts to minority voters, but only after
stripping it of most of its original language.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, proposed by Jesse Hernandez, chairman of the
Arizona Hispanic Republican Council, was attacked by some delegates
as a ``feel good'' measure that would weaken the party's base.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed only after more than half its language was
removed, including the last line: ``The Republican Party rejects
the forces of hatred and bigotry that would set us against one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez expressed disappoint ment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying: `This is our club, and we don't want anyone
else in it,' '' Hernandez said. ``Their attitude is, `We don't care
if the world is changing, we don't have to change.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In other business, delegates named Mike Minnaugh as state
Republican Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Other elected officials who ad dressed delegates included Gov.
Jane Hull and U.S. Reps. Matt Salmon, J.D. Hayworth and John
Shadegg. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-99 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
