<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-WINGS-NYT     01-30 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-WINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGER VICTORY OVER RED WINGS COMES AT PRICE AS GRETZKY IS HURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A late goal by Niklas Sundstrom gave the Rangers a 3-2
victory Saturday over the Detroit Red Wings, the two-time Stanley
Cup champions, and it gave the Rangers two victories in a
three-game road trip. This, normally, would be reason for
unmitigated happiness.
</P>
<P>
   But their joy was somewhat tempered by the loss of Wayne
Gretzky, who leads the team in points with 47. Gretzky aggravated a
muscle strain in his ribs and left the game midway through the
third period. It is not known if he will miss any games. The
Rangers have a light week coming up. They play at home on Monday
night against Washington and on Thursday night against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Sundstrom poked a loose puck from close range past goalie Chris
Osgood at 15 minutes 18 seconds of the third period. Petr Nedved
got the assist after his pass bounced off a Detroit player's skate.
Also starring for the Rangers was goalie Mike Richter. The Rangers
were outshot by 40-14.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky sustained a rib injury in the previous game, on Thursday
night, a 3-2 loss in overtime in Carolina. He said he was in some
pain on Friday but practiced with the team. In Saturday's game, he
played 11:43 of the first two periods, but missed a couple of
shifts midway through the third, with Manny Malhotra taking his
place. Gretzky then left the bench and walked down the corridor for
examination. In his three seasons with the Rangers, Gretzky has not
missed a game, but has played with various illnesses and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered Saturday's game with five defeats in their
previous six games.
</P>
<P>
   This was the third of a three-game road trip, and as is often
the case when the Rangers tour, Gretzky attracted great attention.
Nobody knows if this, his 20th season, will be his last, so there
was the usual fuss about him. The angle this time was worthy. With
a total of 1,070 goals _ in the World Hockey Association and in the
National Hockey League, in both regular season and in the playoffs
_ Gretzky came into the game one goal behind Gordie Howe in the
same compilation.
</P>
<P>
   Howe was a star for the Detroit Red Wings when Gretzky grew up
in Brantford, Ontario, about a four-hour drive from here. When
Gretzky was young, Howe was Gretzky's favorite player. Howe wore
No. 9; Gretzky wears No. 99. Howe starred at the old Olympia
Stadium, and Gretzky talked about that building during a television
interview between periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of the only guys that played in that building,''
Gretzky said, referring to current players. ``It's a special place,
Detroit, to play hockey.'' Gretzky's father, Walter Gretzky, drove
in for Saturday's game, and Gretzky said: ``He has always been a
big Detroit fan and for him to come down here, he loves coming down
here. He was telling the guys today about the old Olympia.'' The
building, which was about two miles from here, has been demolished.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky assisted on the second Ranger goal as the teams each
scored once in each of the first two periods and entered the third
in a 2-2 tie. Getting the first was Igor Larionov, the veteran Red
Wings center, who took a pass from Slava Kozlov on the power play
and beat Richter at 14:04. Nedved evened the score at 1-1 just 21
seconds later when he shot from behind the goal line and banked it
in off Osgood's skate. Brian Leetch got his first of two assists on
that play.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean gave the Rangers a 2-1 lead at 5:30 of the second
period when he finished off a two-on-one rush by taking a pass from
Leetch and drilling it past Osgood. The play formed at the other
end when Ulf Samuelsson, the Rangers defenseman, upended Sergei
Fedorov, the Detroit center.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov helped even the score at 2-2 at 12:34 when he dazzled
the Ranger defense by skating from right to left, drawing the
coverage toward him and setting up the wide-open Brendan Shanahan's
shot. It was Shanahan's first goal since Dec. 23, and his face
showed great relief as the fans cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The center matchups were interesting. Gretzky played a number of
shifts against Fedorov; Nedved was matched against Steve Yzerman.
Another subtheme was the play of Leetch, who came into the game
without a goal in his previous 21 games. In the first period,
Leetch took two minor penalties, which are rare for him. Later, he
wrestled with Tomas Holmstrom while play continued at the other
end. No penalty was called for that one.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   JOHAN WITEHALL made his Rangers debut. He was called up from the
Hartford farm club this week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
