<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLES-SENATORS-NY     01-30 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-SENATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS' ONSLAUGHT OVERWHELMS THE ISLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ Bill Stewart got the Islanders to play hard
for him in his first three games behind the bench. But he couldn't
keep the team's true colors from showing through against the Ottawa
Senators on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders fell behind early, and big, giving up seven goals
in the first two periods and losing to the Senators by 9-2 at the
sold-out Corel Center. The nine goals were the most ever by a
Senators team.
</P>
<P>
   For three games under Stewart, who replaced Mike Milbury as head
coach, there was false hope floating in the Islanders' locker room
of perhaps regaining some respectability, if not getting back into
the playoff chase. But Saturday's loss further proved that this
group of Islanders is going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Another shoddy performance in goal by Felix Potvin opened the
floodgates. Potvin, who started for the first time in three games,
allowed seven goals on 36 shots before being relieved by Tommy Salo
to start the third period. Ottawa is a good young team, but Potvin
made the Senators look like the Edmonton Oilers of the mid 1980s;
he made Radek Bonk look like Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Ten different Senators recorded at least two points. Shawn
McEachern and Aleksei Yashin each scored two goals, and Bonk,
Magnus Arvedson, Steve Martins, Shaun Van Allen and Marian Hossa
each scored once to hand the Islanders their first loss under
Stewart (2-1-1). Zigmund Palffy and Robert Reichel scored the
Islanders' goals.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassing loss must have left Stewart scratching his
head, coming a day after the Islanders' inspiring, come-from-behind
4-4 tie with the Phoenix Coyotes at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   While playing bits and pieces of 10 seasons in the National
Hockey League, Stewart had to work harder than his teammates on
practice days just to be considered for the lineup on game days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a fringe player who not only had to look good on the
ice, I had to look good getting on the plane,'' the 41-year-old
former defenseman said last week. ``If I had a bad day getting on
the plane, I might be sent back to the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years removed from playing the game, Stewart has not
changed his hard-nosed, hard-work philosophy. He demands that same
level of effort from all of his players, whether they are elite
scorers like Palffy or fourth-line grinders like Steve Webb. ``Put
out for me,'' Stewart says. ``I'll put out for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, like most coaches, can live with defeat, so long as his
team competes hard for the entire 60 minutes. That, obviously, was
not the case on Saturday. So it will be interesting to see how
Stewart deals with this weak effort.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Micheletti, the color commentator on Fox broadcasts of
Islanders games, was a teammate of Stewart's on the St. Louis Blues
in the early 1980s and recalled one incident that Micheletti said
personified Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Micheletti remembered a run-in Stewart had with the Boston
Bruins' tough guy Stan Jonathan. ``Stan Jonathan cross checked him
in the face,'' Micheletti said. ``Smack! Broke his nose. Stewie
went after Jonathan but couldn't get him the way he wanted to. So
Stewie waited until the next game. And on the first shift, he went
right after Jonathan. Stewie got him good.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's resolve will be tested on Long Island, where he faces
his toughest challenge yet. He inherits a team with as many holes
to fill on the ice as it has problems to resolve off the ice. The
Islanders are headed for their fifth straight season without making
the playoffs. There are also ownership problems, which last off
season affected player personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Milbury's best decision as general manager this season
could prove to be promoting Stewart, who guided the Islanders to
their first victory in 11 games in his debut. ``We hired Bill
Stewart over the summer knowing that he had been successful at
every level that he coached and that someday he might get the
opportunity here,'' said Milbury, who stepped down as coach on Jan.
21 but remained as general manager.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, that opportunity may not have looked so
attractive. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
