<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVVY-SHOPPERS-OVERSEAS-RESEND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING ABROAD? A VAT OF CASH AWAITS YOU  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Jan. 20)   (This user-friendly 750-word ``separate buy'' story is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``t'' travel news files.)  
  
 By RUDY MAXA  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the stronger U.S. dollar lures you abroad for some shopping,
don't be one of the two out of three Americans who forget to get a
hefty rebate on their purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Canada, and, to a lesser extent, Asia, a consumption
tax is built into the price of many goods and services. As a
visiting American, you're entitled to a refund on many of those
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Are we talking real money here? In some cases, yes. The rates
for consumption tax vary from country to country, from a relatively
modest 2.9 percent in Singapore to a whopping 20 percent in
Denmark, Italy and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Except in Ireland, you must spend a minimum amount to claim a
refund. The minimum amount also varies (as little as $45 in Denmark
and as much as $340 in Switzerland and Liechtenstein), but in most
countries, you can accumulate purchases over time in order to reach
the threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers may also be eligible for refunds on
business-related expenses, depending on the country. For example,
if you stay in a hotel in Germany for business, you (or your
company) can claim a refund on the 16 percent tax you pay.
</P>
<P>
   In the United Kingdom, a company not based there may claim a
refund of the 17.5 percent value-added tax its employees pay for
hotels, rental cars, meals, telephone calls, trade shows, and even
marketing consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is in knowing how to get your money back. Let's say
you're in Milan, and you have no choice but to spend $2,000 on a
fabulous dress. You're entitled to a VAT refund of $400.
</P>
<P>
   The store clerk will need your passport _ always carry it when
shopping _ when he or she fills out the refund form. Each purchase
you make will be listed on the form, which must be presented to a
tax official when you leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   You must also be prepared to show the goods you purchased to the
tax-refund agent at the airport when you're flying out of any
country that's a member of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where many Americans get tripped up. If you check
your luggage before you locate a tax-refund kiosk, you might be out
of luck. The tax man can't be certain you're not trying to claim a
refund on goods purchased for a friend in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The moral: Have the goods available for display. The refund
papers from the places of purchase will be stamped; simply mail
them in, and your charge card will be credited or you'll be sent a
check. Or you may even be handed a cash refund on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Things are a bit more complicated for the business traveler. The
rules differ widely from country to country.
</P>
<P>
   France, for example, will rebate only the 20.6 percent in VAT
paid for phone calls, marketing-consultant services, and trade-show
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The U.K., on the other hand, is relatively generous in rebating
taxes but won't do so for individuals _ only companies. And
companies can file only four times a year for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   There are firms such as EuroVAT (800-828-0609) and Fexco
(800-865-4561) that specialize in recapturing taxes due American
businesses. Their fee is generally 20 percent of the taxes
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But just as in the retail arena, the savings can be enormous.
Let's say the employees of an American-based company spend, in
total, 223 days a year in the U.K. on business.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose that these road warriors spend an average $150 a night
on hotels, $35 a day on rental cars and gasoline, and $35 a day on
meals _ all told, about $49,000 a year in travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.K. levies a 17.5 percent VAT, a company can obtain a
refund of about $8,500.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, Canada began honoring corporate claims for
refunds as well. The rates vary from province to province, but
Manitoba, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, Newfoundland, and Quebec will
refund not only the federal sales tax but also the provincial sales
tax, which alone can reach 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Japan says it rebates 5 percent on most business expenses, but
Karen Bostrom, a vice president of sales and marketing with
EuroVAT, says that in practice Japan generally refunds 5 percent
only on hotel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's 5 percent or 20 percent, that money is yours. Ask
for those pounds, francs, yen, or marks back. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Rudy Maxa is a frequent contributing writer for
WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 750-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
