<DOCNO> NYT19990130.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-30 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CLUB-SLAYING-420&AMP;A     01-30 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLUB-SLAYING-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CLEARED ON SOME COUNTS OF SLAYING AT STRIP CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A jury acquitted two brothers of several charges
Saturday in connection with two 1996 slayings at Scores, a strip
club on the Upper East Side. But the jurors continued to debate
more serious charges, signaling that they were wrestling with the
credibility of the main prosecution witness, a Mafia turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in state Supreme Court in Manhattan cleared one of the
brothers, Victor Dedaj, 39, in the death of one of the men, Michael
Greco 22. But the jurors remained deadlocked on a second-degree
murder charge against Dedaj in the death of Jonathan Segal, 25. And
they remained undecided on the most serious charges against Simon
Dedaj, 35, first-degree murder in both killings.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors from Westchester County are closely watching
the trial of the Dedaj brothers. Willie Marshall, 33, a Mafia
turncoat who was a key witness against the brothers, is also
considered a lead prosecution witness in the upcoming trial of John
A. Gotti, the son of imprisoned Mafia leader John J. Gotti. The
younger Gotti is scheduled to be tried later this year in
Westchester County on extortion and fraud charges
</P>
<P>
   The Dedaj brothers were accused of murdering the two men, a
bouncer and a waiter at the club on East 60th Street, after an
argument broke out at an early-morning birthday celebration.
Marshall and other prosecution witnesses testified that the
brothers shot Greco and Segal, but defense lawyers said that the
brothers acted in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, the jurors sent a note to the judge saying
that they had reached a verdict on some of the counts, but were
deadlocked on others. Justice Edwin Torres called the jurors to the
courtroom to hear the partial verdicts. The jury acquitted the two
brothers on several burglary and second-degree murder charges, but
said that they were deadlocked on nine other counts.
</P>
<P>
   Torres ordered the jurors to continue deliberations. At 7 p.m.,
after about two more hours of debate, the jurors, with Torres'
permission, ended their discussions for the evening. They are
scheduled to resume deliberations Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The family members and friends of the Dedaj brothers were
distraught Saturday morning as the jurors began their third full
day of deliberations. Simon Dedaj's girlfriend, Donna Kelly, wept,
and Marika Dedaj, the mother of the two men, prayed with other
family members. After the partial verdicts were read, they seemed
to find hope. ``It is reassuring to hear the not-guilty verdicts,''
said Robert P. Kelly, an lawyer for Victor Dedaj.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the trial, prosecutors and defense lawyers presented
starkly different versions of what happened. The prosecution said
that Simon Dedaj shot and killed Greco, a bouncer, and Segal, a
waiter. The defense contended that Victor Dedaj fired the gun, but
only in self-defense. The partial verdicts cast little light on
which version the jurors believed, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, a former bouncer and a former prison guard, was as
much the focus of the trial as the Dedaj brothers. Jurors faced a
complicated task in deciding whether they believed Marshall. As
part of his long history of criminal activities, Marshall testified
that he and his associates extorted money from the owners, disk
jockeys and strippers at Scores for the Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor in the Scores case, Daniel McGillycuddy,
urged the jurors to trust Marshall, noting that a FBI wiretap
recorded him giving his brother the same description of the
killings that he gave during his testimony in court. Saturday,
before the verdicts, the jurors took a break from their
deliberations to listen to several of the FBI tapes for a second
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
