<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WALSH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER `ARIZONA REPUBLIC' PUBLISHER WALSH DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mason Walsh, a former publisher of ``The Arizona Republic'' and
``The Phoenix'' ``Gazette'' known for his public-spirited
journalism, died Saturday at Scottsdale Healthcare Osborn of
complications from pneumonia. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, a music lover who once performed in the Dallas Symphony,
worked for the Phoenix newspapers for more than 20 years, retiring
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In his 46-year journalism career in Texas and Arizona, he
conducted newspaper campaigns against crime and for free medical
forums and polio immunization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mason Walsh was a great force for professionalism in his work
and for public good in the cities where he worked,'' said John F.
Oppedahl, president, publisher and chief executive officer of
Phoenix Newspapers Inc., which publishes ``The Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an effective editor and businessman in his several
roles at Phoenix Newspapers and helped lead the company into the
modern age. He aspired to high standards and met them.''
</P>
<P>
   And he worked tirelessly to make sure that the Valley of the Sun
grew wisely as well as quickly, former Phoenix Mayor Sam Mardian
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He exuded integrity and character,'' Mardian said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Mitchem, director of corporate relations for Northern
Arizona University, said Walsh was dedicated to the public good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a person who had the best interests of the city
and community at heart,'' Mitchem said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchem, who, like Walsh, was a charter member of the Phoenix 40
_ now known as Greater Phoenix Leadership _ said Walsh was
concerned more with the group's accomplishments than with its
image.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Moyer, who did stints as managing editor of ``The Gazette''
and ``The'' ``Republic,'' recalled Walsh as a calm force in the
news operation, a peacemaker who had a deep feeling for news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sort of a newsman's publisher,`` Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was born Nov. 27, 1912, in Dallas, into a newspapering
family. One of his great-grandfathers and two of his uncles were
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh got his first newspaper job at the age of 11, delivering
papers for the ``Dallas Times Herald.'' In 1929, he won a cub
reporter job with the ``Dallas'' ``Journal'' and used it to help
pay for his studies at Southern Methodist University.
</P>
<P>
   He majored in political science at SMU and wanted to go to work
for the State Department, but the tight job market caused by the
Depression quashed that plan after he graduated in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Walsh temporarily took up a music career, playing
violin, viola and violoncello in movie and vaudeville theaters, on
the radio, in dance bands, and with the Dallas Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, he returned to reporting, taking a job at the
``Journal.'' He later worked at the ``Dallas Dispatch-Journal,''
which was formed in the merger of two afternoon dailies.
</P>
<P>
   While news editor there, he rushed out an extra on the Dec. 7,
1941, Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, rounding up staffers at home
because the paper didn't normally put out a Sunday edition.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh later was employed by the ``Austin Tribune'' before going
to work with North American Aviation in Dallas, first in public
relations and then as head of employee services.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, he went to work for the ``Dallas Times Herald,'' where
he rose from city editor to managing editor before taking a job as
managing editor of ``The'' ``Gazette'' in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, when President Kennedy was assassinated in
Dallas, Walsh used his knowledge of the city to help a ``Gazette''
staff artist put together a map of the shooting site moments after
the story hit the wire services.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he became general manager of ``The Gazette/The
Republic,'' and in 1975 was given the additional job of assistant
publisher. He was named publisher of the papers in 1978, was made
publisher emeritus in 1980, and retired in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gazette'' was closed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was a past president of the Associated Press Managing
Editors organization, and a board member of the Phoenix Symphony
Association and of the Phoenix Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Anne; daughter, Peggy, a media
consultant; and sons, Timothy, an attorney, and Kevin, chief of the
Associated Press bureau in Miami, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements will be handled by Messinger Mortuary, 7601 E.
Indian School Road, Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The date and time of services have not been announced, but the
location will be St. Barnabas of the Desert, 6715 N. Mockingbird
Lane, Paradise Valley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
