<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAREHOLDER-GUERILLA-TACTICS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN UP, GOLIATH: HOW SMALL INVESTORS CAN BE HEARD  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors)   (This user-friendly 625-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance
story is from the January issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish
this article, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By DAVE CALIFANO  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dead-in-the-water stock investment is no fun. But when you own
more than 17 percent of the stock in question, at least you get to
punish somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, when it became clear that the aggressive growth
projections trumpeted by Sunbeam chief Albert Dunlap were just so
much balloon juice, money manager Michael Price demanded Dunlap's
swollen head. And Price's 17.5 million Sunbeam shares ensured that
he got it.
</P>
<P>
   But what about smaller investors? In absolute terms, they may
not have as much at stake as a major player like Price, but their
losses can be just as painful, if not more so.
</P>
<P>
   Do they stand a chance of making their voices heard when they
think one of their companies is being mismanaged?
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly enough, yes. Just ask Nell Minow, a principal in
Lens, an activist investment fund based in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, Lens was the extremely dissatisfied owner of a
tiny percentage of Sears, Roebuck stock. The source of Minow's
discontent: the Sears board, which essentially stood by while the
company frittered away its franchise as Middle America's retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up, Lens took out a full-page ad in The Wall Street Journal
accusing Sears's directors, by name, of being ``non-performing
assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days after the ad ran, Sears held its annual meeting, where
a stunningly large percentage of the company's normally docile
stockholders endorsed Minow's plan to return the Big Store to its
retailing roots.
</P>
<P>
   She proposed that the company jettison its Dean Witter
financial-services arm and its Coldwell Banker real-estate unit. In
1993, Sears did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Minow's tactics aren't usually so flashy or brash, but they all
are designed to send the same message. ``Everything I do is to let
the company know that it's being observed,'' says Minow. ``Once
this happens, it reacts differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Another principle of effective shareholder activism is that
frontal assaults are rarely successful. ``You have to go through
the back door,'' confirms Amy Domini of Domini Social Investments.
</P>
<P>
   One of her favorite tactics is to introduce resolutions for
shareholders to consider at a company's annual meeting. The best
resolutions are the ones that promise, if passed, to make
management's lives miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll file a resolution on a sensitive matter like management
compensation,'' says Domini, ``and only agree to withdraw it if the
company will speak to us about the issues we're really concerned
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite pressure tactic is what's called the 220 demand
letter. Many companies are incorporated in Delaware because of that
state's pro-management legal code. But one key part of the code is
actually a shareholder's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Under section 220 of Delaware General Corporation Law, investors
can, upon written request, inspect the books and records of any
company whose stock they own.
</P>
<P>
   Lens recently played the 220 card against Juno Lighting, a
company in which Lens holds 721,000 shares. Concerned about the
dearth of outsiders on the company's board, Lens had for months
pressed Juno to appoint several outside directors.
</P>
<P>
   Juno agreed, but the effort proceeded slowly until Minow fired
off a 220 letter demanding to see all records pertaining to the
company's search. Juno subsequently opened a line of communication
with Lens, but Minow hasn't let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management's credibility is questionable,'' she says, ``and I
am currently drafting a shareholder proposal and preparing for a
proxy fight in case they don't keep their promises. As Reagan said,
`Trust, but verify.'''
</P>
<P>
   Minow expects shareholders to become even more aggressive about
defending their interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing is not just about being smart in finding value
anymore,'' she says. ``It's also about being smart in creating
value.'' And if creating value means playing rough sometimes, hey,
that's business.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Dave Califano is a staff reporter at WORTH
Magazine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this useful 625-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
