<SLUG> BC-ADD-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following Arizona Republic stories have been added for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for Jan. 31, 1999. If you
have any questions, please contact the Republic News Desk at (602)
271-8108.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AZ-GOP (Phoenix) _ The Arizona Republican Party voted unanimously
Saturday to recommend leaving the state's presidential party
primary unchanged, rejecting a plan to move it from mid-February to
March 14. Many of the 400 delegates believe the proposal to hold a
later
</P>
<P>
   primary was floated to help presidential hopeful John McCain
avoid an early showdown with Steve Forbes in McCain's own state. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RIMSZA (Phoenix) _ Smiles, speeches, photos, handshakes _ they are
daily rituals for Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza. He reads The Three
Little Javelinas to first-graders, explains later how he saved the
name of the Phoenix Coyotes, then zips off to a reception with the
governor.Rimsza seems always on the go. But even his friends are
beginning to ask where he's headed _ whether he's more concerned
with stoking the city's image than taking on weighty problems. City
Council members and neighborhood leaders worry that he is standing
idly by while urban sprawl goes unchecked and the municipal transit
system remains one of the worst for a city its size in the country.
BY CHRIS FISCUS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WALSH (scottsdale) Mason Walsh, a former publisher of The
Arizona Republic and The Phoenix Gazette known for his
public-spirited journalism, died Saturday at Scottsdale Healthcare
Osborn of complications from pneumonia. He was 86. By CHUCK KELLY.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIGLEY (Higley, Ariz.) _ Frustrated with the red tape preventing
their protests from reaching Gilbert Town Council, Higley residents
on Saturday decided to think pink. Ed Welsh and about 35 of his
neighbors painted a 50-foot wall a shade of pink _ a hot color to
match their moods. They are fighting mad at a Shea Homes proposal
to turn 273 acres of farmland into 768 cookie-cutter homes, 3.7
homes per acre. By JAIMEE ROSE. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
