<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Taylor gets fitting spot among elite
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ Lawrence Taylor told the media he deserved to be elected to
the Pro Football Hall of Fame, and it seems they agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants linebacker was elected Saturday. Joining him
will be running back Eric Dickerson, also a first-year candidate,
tight end Ozzie Newsome, and offensive linemen Tom Mack and Bill
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor clearly deserved the election based on a 13-year career
that included one league Most Valuable Player honor, three
Defensive Player of the Year titles and 10 Pro Bowls. But his
actions off the field caused some to question whether he deserved
the honor. Taylor has been arrested twice since retirement,
including a drug possession charge last September. He was suspended
once during his career for violating the league's substance-abuse
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Another whose career was unequaled was Dickerson, a Sealy native
and former SMU running back who came into the NFL with the Los
Angeles Rams and also played with the Indianapolis Colts, the Los
Angeles Raiders and Atlanta Falcons. Dickerson set a single-season
rushing record of 2,105 yards in 1984. He ranks third on the career
rushing list with 13,259 yards in 11 years. His career was cut
short because of a neck injury in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   One of Dickerson's lasting memories is facing Taylor during his
rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing the Giants and they told me to cut Lawrence
Taylor,'' Dickerson said. ``And I said, `OK.' I didn't want to do
that, but it was my job. So I cut him, and when he got up, he said,
`Don't ever cut me again.' I went back to the sidelines and said,
`That man said don't ever cut me again.' They called the play
again, and I said, `Put some other guy in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson said he expects his records to fall, most likely to
Denver's Terrell Davis, who rushed for 2,008 yards this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, it seems someone gets closer and closer,'' he
said. ``If someone breaks my records, I'll be happy for him because
then you guys (media) will have to say something about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson was a No. 1 pick, second overall after John Elway in
the 1983 draft. He holds the rookie rushing record with 1,808 yards
and 18 touchdowns. Dickerson was the NFL Player of the Year in 1984
and Offensive Player of the Year in '86. He played in six Pro
Bowls, but never made it to a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my Super Bowl right here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's legal problems did not fall under any category of the
football bylaws, which contain no ``good citizenship'' clause.
Though there was plenty of debate, Taylor received the necessary 80
percent vote (of 36 voting members).
</P>
<P>
   And though he has granted interviews all week to lobby on his
behalf, Taylor was the only one of the five electees who was unable
to meet with the media. Taylor was in Florida for the filming of an
Oliver Stone movie and the shooting schedule didn't allow interview
time, Hall of Fame officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did release a written statement: ``I appreciate the
debate and the consideration that was given to my nomination.
Ultimately, this honor has to do with how I played the game.
Obviously, the majority of the committee felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsome holds a tight end receiving record with 662 catches for
7,980 yards and 47 touchdowns in 13 seasons with the Cleveland
Browns. Newsome, who retired in 1990, was a finalist last year, but
was not selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the longer it takes to get in, the more you appreciate
it,'' Newsome said. ``Not getting in in the first year, not even
making it into the final 15, I began to really appreciate just what
making it into the Hall of Fame means.''
</P>
<P>
   And making it this year is special for the lifetime Cleveland
Brown. The Browns will resume play this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the opportunity to go in when the Browns are going
back on the football field is a double whammy,'' he said. ``It
makes it more special for myself. I'm a Cleveland Brown. I wore
that orange helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack played 13 seasons as a guard with the Los Angeles Rams.
Selected to play in 11 Pro Bowls, Mack never missed a game to
injury, anchoring the Rams' offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, another guard, made the Hall of Fame as a senior candidate
in his final year of eligibility. Shaw was selected to play in
eight AFL All-Star Games and played on Bills championship teams in
1964 and '65.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates, defensive end Howie Long and wide receiver
Lynn Swann, were finalists but were not selected. They will
automatically be finalists next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
