 A&AMP;M-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A&AMP;M lets Oklahoma State off the hook
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
STILLWATER, Okla. _ Texas A&AMP;M had a chance to pull off its biggest
upset of the season Saturday at Oklahoma State, but that
opportunity vanished down the stretch when the Aggies failed to
score in the last 4{ minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys made up an 11-point halftime deficit and took
control in the final seconds to earn a 66-61 victory in front of
6,270 fans at Gallagher-Iba Arena.
</P>
<P>
   A dunk by center Joe White gave A&AMP;M a 61-60 lead with 4:31 to go
and left OSU without two of its starters. Desmond Mason, the Big
12's top scorer, fouled White for his fifth foul, and center Alex
Webber had fouled out three minutes earlier. But the Aggies
couldn't take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M (9-9 overall and 2-6 in Big 12 play) trailed 62-61 after OSU
forward Adrian Peterson made a one-handed jumper as he drove the
baseline with 2:15 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team would make another shot the rest of the way, but
the Aggies had a chance to take the lead when they got the ball
back with 24.2 second left, still trailing 62-61.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M called timeout to set up a play, hoping to get the ball
inside to Shanne Jones. But point guard Clifton Cook had to take a
difficult 10-foot jumper from the baseline that bounced off the
rim. A&AMP;M forward Michael Schmidt leaped in the lane and tried to
tip it in, but the ball rolled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure (the tip) was going in,'' Schmidt said.
``But the ball just rolled in and out over the hoop. When it came
out, it broke my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Montonati grabbed the rebound, his 10th of the half and
11th of the game, and was fouled by Cook with 3.3 seconds to go.
Montonati made both free throws to put OSU in front 64-61.
</P>
<P>
   White attempted to make a full-court pass on the inbounds play,
but the ball hit the scoreboard that hangs over midcourt, giving
OSU possession.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Adkins, who was the top scorer for the Cowboys with 18
points, was fouled on the inbounds play and made the last two free
throws for OSU (15-5, 6-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances, but we just couldn't close it out at the
end,'' said A&AMP;M coach Melvin Watkins. ``Oklahoma State picked up
their intensity in the second half and did what they had to do. We
hoped we could withstand their run, but we got a little careless
and had some turnovers that were unforced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies entered the game with a two-game winning streak, but
they had a season-high 30 turnovers, including 10 by Cook. But Cook
also had 23 points, eight rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, the basket just wouldn't cooperate for us,'' Cook
said. ``We didn't get those last couple of shots we needed. It's
real frustrating because we had them in the same situation at our
place (a 64-59 win by OSU). But we're confident now that we can win
against good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statistical quirk that would qualify for a ``Believe it or
Not'' book, the Aggies had 16 turnovers in the first half and still
led 40-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played
</P>
</TEXT>
