<HEADLINE>
HIGLEY STAGE PINK PROTEST TO FIGHT DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGLEY, Ariz. _ Frustrated with the red tape preventing their
protests from reaching Gilbert Town Council, Higley residents on
Saturday decided to think pink.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Welsh and about 35 of his neighbors painted a 50-foot wall a
shade of hot pink _ a color to match their moods.
</P>
<P>
   They are fighting mad at a Shea Homes proposal to turn 273 acres
of farmland into 768 cookie-cutter homes, 3.7 homes per acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our Boston Tea Party,'' said Jim Staples, a Higley
resident of 20 years who helped coat the wall with a pink paint
plea. ``We're not trying to stop progress, we just want it
controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh's decidedly pink wall faces the pasture in question.
</P>
<P>
   The bright block beacon conveys the group's opposition to the
proposed Gilbert annexation and rezoning case that would make
Higley a rural county island surrounded by dense development.
</P>
<P>
   Since the land is currently under Maricopa County jurisdiction
and zoned as rural residential, like Welsh's land, meaning
approximately one house per acre is allowed, Gilbert must annex and
rezone the land for Shea to begin construction.
</P>
<P>
   This move would triple the size of the Higley School District,
turn Welsh's residential road into a six-lane straightaway, and put
an end to the quiet life Higley homeowners enjoy, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are not official Gilbert citizens, Higley residents
have no voting power in deciding the future of their surrounding
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Staples said that the group would be appeased if the farmland
was built upon under the current, more rural zoning. He also thinks
that Higley residents deserve a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the town) is going to take this (land), they should take
us as well,'' he said. ``Nobody will stand up for the people out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gilbert Councilman Phil Long is ready to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to hear all sides,'' he said, ``and the fence
certainly would attract attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Welsh's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the colors on that wall are loud enough to be seen all
the way to the state Capitol,'' he said. ``Give us some respect.
Give us a voice.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
