<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS </SLUG>
 TECH-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cold front stalls over frostbitten Tech
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ A winter weather system brought subfreezing temperatures
and snow to this part of West Texas overnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, a different type of cold front blew through
the Lubbock Municipal Coliseum, bringing with it a fourth
consecutive defeat for Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Raiders made five of their first six shots to take a
quick 12-7 lead before suffering through a painful 12-minute
stretch during which they made just 1 of 15 shot attempts and had
nine turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma took advantage, outscoring Tech 25-3 over that time, en
route to ending its own four-game losing streak with a 72-54 Big 12
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tech cut the Sooners' lead, which ballooned to 22 points at one
point, down to nine midway through the second half, but Oklahoma
pulled away again to give the Red Raiders their worst home loss of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners' top three scorers matched the Red Raiders' total,
as again Tech struggled offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Tech, which was playing its third straight game without shooting
guard Stan Bonewitz, was only 9-for-31 from the field in the first
half (29 percent). The Red Raiders are averaging 54.5 points a game
during the losing streak, and have dropped below the .500 mark for
the first time this season to 10-11 overall and 2-6 in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really difficult for us to run our offense without him
because Stan creates so many problems for a defense, and we play so
well together,'' Tech point guard Rayford Young said of his
backcourt mate. ``But I'll take the (blame) for this loss. I missed
a big shot that could have broke the momentum in the first half and
then I missed some big free throws. I believe those were the big
turning points of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, Tech's leading scorer at 14.3 points a game, had another
poor night from the field (5-of-14). In the three games Bonewitz
has sat out after having hernia surgery, Young is shooting 37.8
percent from the floor (14-of-37).
</P>
<P>
   The 5-11 junior missed three 3-pointers during the fateful
first-half stretch, but he was far from the lone Red Raider to
struggle. Oklahoma switched from its man-to-man defense to a
trapping 1-3-1 zone, and the Red Raiders did not adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every time Tech did get a good look inside, Ryan Humphrey
was there to block the shot. The 6-8 sophomore scored 15 points on
5-of-6 shooting, but was an even bigger factor on defense with five
blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like he blocked about 15 shots,'' Oklahoma coach
Kelvin Sampson said. ``If he didn't block more than five, he
certainly altered a lot more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The more shots the Red Raiders missed, the more tentative they
became.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think really the problem was all five guys on the floor were
waiting for the other ones to take charge and get us a big
bucket,'' Tech forward Cliff Owens said. ``We really looked kind of
stagnant. I don't think we got the ball inside-out like we need to,
to get some open shots for the guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't execute, point blank. I don't think it was
anything Oklahoma did, although they played hard and are very good
defensively, but we just didn't execute on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech, which trailed 37-24 at the half, trailed 48-26 with about
15 minutes to play after Eric Martin hit one of his five
3-pointers. Martin led all scorers with 26 points on 9-of-14
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, Oklahoma's offense went into a
turnover-plagued, five-minute scoreless stretch, while Tech's got
into gear.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ellis, Owens and Mario Layne each scored consecutive
baskets and Jevon Banks hit two free throws to account for a 12-1
burst for the Red Raiders to cut the lead to 49-40 with 9:40
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Tech would get no closer. Oklahoma made nine straight free
throws down the stretch, while Tech misfired on the front end of
two one-and-one opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners, who closed with a 16-8 run, improved to 14-7 and
5-3 in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game we needed to win for a smorgasbord of
reasons,'' Sampson said, ``not just for getting back into the
conference race and not just for to get off that 13 number.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really practiced hard this week and this was an important
game. This game gives us some validation. Every time you lose at
home you need two road wins to replace that. So this does not
replace the loss to Texas (last Monday). We have to win at Baylor
on Wednesday to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
